Reasoning: Current lifecycle analyses show that modern U.S. corn-ethanol returns slightly more energy than is consumed in growing, harvesting, transporting and refining it (energy return on investment ≈1.2–1.5). Sugar-cane ethanol has a much higher positive balance. Therefore, it is not correct that ethanol universally requires more energy to make than it yields; it generally provides a net, though sometimes modest, energy gain.

The term “property tax” is generic and applies to all kinds of real property—land, commercial buildings, apartments, factories, etc. “House tax” is usually used more narrowly for the municipal tax levied specifically on residential houses. Thus, while a house tax is one form of property tax, the two terms are not strictly identical.

Individuals can indeed feel pain in body parts that are no longer present (phantom limb pain) or that are paralyzed, because the nervous system and brain regions responsible for processing pain signals may still fire despite the lack of input from the original tissues.

Harry Potter and the Escape from Gringotts at Universal Orlando uses a steel coaster track with launch sections and drops, blended with motion-base vehicles, 3-D projection, and dark-ride scenes. Because the ride system is fundamentally built on a roller-coaster track and is classified by the park and manufacturers as a steel roller coaster/dark-ride hybrid, it is considered a roller coaster ride (albeit one with additional show elements).

answer: Yes — the difference is the salt form (HCl vs pamoate), not the active drug effect.
Reasoning: Hydroxyzine comes in two salt forms: hydroxyzine hydrochloride (HCl) and hydroxyzine pamoate (PAM). The salts affect the physical formulation (tablets, capsules, syrup, injectable) and the milligram strength required to deliver an equivalent amount of hydroxyzine base (e.g., 25 mg HCl ≈ 30 mg PAM). Pharmacologically, once absorbed both release the same active drug, so therapeutic effects and side-effect profiles are essentially the same; the main differences are the salt, available dosage forms, and minor differences in absorption/onset.
Answer: Yes — the difference is the salt form (HCl vs pamoate), not the active drug effect.

Reasoning: Barq’s Root Beer is owned and distributed by The Coca-Cola Company, not PepsiCo. Therefore it is not a Pepsi product.
In English there are several accepted words in major dictionaries whose letter “q” is not followed by “u,” such as “qat,” “qi,” and “faqir.” Therefore, such words do exist.

All Canadian provinces and territories allow visitors to drive with a valid U.S. driver’s license for a limited period (usually up to 90 days to 6 months, depending on the province). For short-term travel, no additional Canadian license is required; you must simply carry your U.S. license and obey local laws. Long-term residents, however, must exchange their U.S. license for a provincial one after the allowed visitor period.

In the FIFA World Cup (men’s and women’s), the two teams that lose in the semi-finals meet in an additional match—commonly called the “third-place play-off” or “consolation final”—to determine who finishes third. This fixture has been a standard part of the tournament format for many decades.

The Netflix series "Bloodline" was created by Todd A. Kessler, Glenn Kessler, and Daniel Zelman as an original drama. While it draws on themes common to many real families—secrets, crime, and guilt—its characters, plot, and events are fictional and not adapted from any specific true story.

Shower gels are designed primarily to cleanse skin. They often contain stronger or different surfactant blends and lack the conditioning agents, anti-static polymers, and pH adjustments that shampoos include for hair and scalp health. Using shower gel on hair once in a while will usually not cause serious damage, but regular use can strip natural oils, leave hair dry or tangled, and potentially irritate the scalp. Therefore, it is generally considered a poor practice (i.e., ‘bad’) compared with using a product formulated as shampoo.

Although primarily associated with digestion and metabolism, the liver also removes toxic substances from the blood and excretes waste products such as bilirubin by secreting them into bile. Because of this waste-elimination function, many biology texts list the liver as one of the accessory organs of the human excretory system along with the kidneys, lungs, and skin.

Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them is set in 1926, roughly 70 years before the events of the main Harry Potter series, and explores earlier events in the Wizarding World. Because it takes place chronologically before the original story while existing within the same fictional universe, it is classified as a prequel.

The CW officially renewed The Vampire Diaries for an eighth season, which ultimately aired from October 2016 to March 2017. Therefore, relative to the question of whether a Season 8 would exist, the answer is yes—Season 8 was produced and released.

Writer-director Bryan Bertino has said he drew inspiration from several incidents—the Manson family murders, the 1981 Keddie Cabin murders, and his own childhood experience of strangers knocking at his door—but the plot and characters of the 2008 film “The Strangers” are products of fiction. It is marketed as “inspired by true events,” yet it is not a direct or faithful retelling of any single real crime, so it is not truly “based on a true story.”

The Russell Group is a consortium of 24 leading UK research-intensive universities. Durham University was among the institutions added when the group expanded in 2012, and it remains a full member today.

Fox’s medical drama ‘The Resident’ finished airing its Season 6 finale on January 17, 2023, and the network has since cancelled the series. Therefore the current season is already completed and no further episodes are scheduled.

Magnesium citrate is the magnesium salt of citric acid. In the compound, the acidic hydrogen atoms of citric acid have been replaced by magnesium ions, producing the citrate anion (C6H5O7​3–). Therefore, the finished product contains citrate, not free citric acid itself. Lay descriptions may mention that it is ‘made from citric acid,’ but chemically it no longer contains citric acid in its protonated form.

In a spark-ignition internal-combustion engine, the spark plug produces the electrical spark that ignites the air-fuel mixture in each cylinder every cycle. Continuous ignition is required for every power stroke, so if the spark plug stops firing the mixture will not ignite and the engine will stall. Therefore, functioning spark plugs are essential to keep such an engine running.

Although both are sleeveless outer garments worn over the shoulders, a cloak is typically full-length (often reaching below the knees and sometimes including a hood), while a cape is shorter and usually ends at or above the hips or mid-thigh. Because of these functional and stylistic differences, they are considered distinct garments rather than the same thing.

The U.S. Department of State imposes a mandatory processing fee for filing Form DS-4079 and taking the oath of renunciation. Since 2014 that fee has been set at $2,350 (with very limited grounds for a waiver), so renouncing U.S. citizenship is not free.

The Amazon Fire 7 is an inexpensive 7-inch color tablet that runs Fire OS and supports apps, video, web browsing, etc. The term “Kindle” normally refers to Amazon’s e-ink readers designed primarily for reading books. Although both are Amazon devices and you can read Kindle books on a Fire 7, they are built on different hardware platforms with different screens and purposes, so they are not the same device.

Wisconsin’s alcohol laws create an explicit exception to the 21-year-old drinking age: a person under 21 may legally possess and consume alcoholic beverages if they are with a parent, legal guardian, or spouse who is of legal drinking age and the alcohol-serving establishment (or private host) allows it. The supervising adult must give consent and be present the entire time. Outside those specific circumstances, under-21 drinking remains illegal.

In all birds, feathers are epidermal appendages that develop from follicle structures where the epidermis invaginates around a dermal papilla. Penguins, though specialized for an aquatic lifestyle, are still birds and their plumage follows the same developmental origin. Therefore, the feathers of penguins arise from the epidermis.

Most manufacturers still recommend a short break-in period (usually the first 500–1,000 miles) during which you avoid full-throttle acceleration, high sustained RPM, and heavy loads. This allows piston rings to seat properly, brake pads and rotors to mate, and other moving parts to wear in evenly. Although modern machining tolerances are tighter than in the past, following the maker’s guidelines can still improve long-term performance and longevity, so some form of break-in is advisable.

The Enchanted Forest theme park near Salem/Turner, Oregon temporarily closed during the height of the COVID-19 pandemic but reopened to the public in 2021. As of the latest available information (through late-2023), it continues to operate on its normal seasonal schedule (typically spring through Halloween, with a winter closure). There has been no announcement of a permanent shutdown.

The Indianapolis 500 is held at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, whose grounds include the Brickyard Crossing Golf Course (with several holes located inside the track). Therefore, a golf course is indeed present at the Indy 500 venue.

In the main Marvel comic continuity, Wade Wilson (Deadpool) discovers that he fathered a biological daughter, Eleanor Camacho, with Carmelita Camacho (first revealed around Deadpool Vol. 3 #31, 2014). This confirms that Deadpool does indeed have a child in the comics.

Benson & Hedges remains an active cigarette brand owned and manufactured by major tobacco companies (e.g., Philip Morris International, British American Tobacco, and Altria in the U.S.). Although distribution has shrunk in some markets and certain product lines have been discontinued, the brand is still produced and sold in various countries today.

Federal income tax and Social Security tax are two separate taxes. Federal income tax is a general tax on an individual’s taxable income that funds a wide range of federal government programs. Social Security tax (part of FICA payroll taxes) is specifically earmarked to fund the Social Security program, which provides retirement, disability, and survivors’ benefits. Because they are imposed under different laws, appear as distinct line items on paychecks, and finance different government purposes, they are not the same.

In modern engine-management terminology the device that supplies the ECU with the engine’s rotational speed signal is the crankshaft position sensor. Because it delivers both position and rpm information, service literature often calls it the “engine speed sensor.” Although some vehicles may use other sensors (e.g., transmission speed sensors) for different speed readings, when the term is applied to the engine itself it is referring to the crankshaft sensor.

Indiana Jones and the Temple of Doom is set in 1935, while Raiders of the Lost Ark (the first film released) is set in 1936. Because the events of Temple of Doom occur chronologically before Raiders, it is considered a prequel within the series.

answer: Yes – the sequel is Avengers: Endgame
Reasoning: Avengers: Infinity War (2018) was designed as the first half of a two-part story. The direct continuation is Avengers: Endgame, released in 2019, which resolves the cliff-hanger ending of Infinity War. Therefore, there is indeed a ‘next part’ that follows Infinity War.
Answer: Yes – the sequel is Avengers: Endgame

Reasoning: The Toyota Highlander is classified as a midsize crossover SUV that has always used a unibody (car-based) construction derived from Toyota’s passenger-car platforms (e.g., K-platform, GA-K). A truck frame would imply a body-on-frame design like Toyota’s 4Runner or Tacoma, which the Highlander does not use.

Under U.S. copyright law (and similarly in many other jurisdictions), it is legal to record and release a cover of a previously published song as long as the covering artist obtains the appropriate mechanical (or compulsory) license and pays the statutory royalties to the copyright holder. Live performances of covers are also generally permitted provided the venue or promoter has the necessary performance licenses from the performing-rights organizations (ASCAP, BMI, SESAC, etc.). Therefore, covering a song is lawful when the required licenses and royalty payments are in place.

The electronegativity difference between carbon (≈2.5) and hydrogen (≈2.1) is only about 0.4. Bonds with such a small difference are generally classified as non-polar covalent. While there is a very slight polarity (carbon is marginally more electronegative), it is not enough for the bond to be considered appreciably polar in most chemical contexts. Therefore, carbon–hydrogen bonds are typically treated as non-polar rather than polar covalent.

The 2007 film “The Golden Compass” was intended to launch a trilogy, but its disappointing U.S. box-office performance, coupled with controversy, caused the studio to cancel further films. Although the remaining books were later adapted as the BBC/HBO television series “His Dark Materials,” no direct movie sequel to “The Golden Compass” was ever produced or released.

Columbus Day is one of the holidays designated by Congress under 5 U.S.C. § 6103. Federal offices close and most federal employees receive the day off, making it an official federal (national) holiday, even though some states and localities choose not to observe it or call it by another name.

New Balance Athletics, Inc. and Nike, Inc. are two distinct, independently owned sports-footwear and apparel companies. They have separate corporate headquarters, leadership, and branding, and they compete with one another in the marketplace. Therefore, they are not the same company.

Yes. For example, Interstate 10 runs from Santa Monica, California on the Pacific Ocean to Jacksonville, Florida on the Atlantic Ocean, so at least one Interstate Highway truly spans from one U.S. coast to the other.

Tomato purée is usually just strained, lightly cooked tomatoes with little or no added seasoning and a thicker consistency. Tomato sauce is typically cooked longer, thinned with liquid, and often contains added salt, herbs, onions, or other seasonings. Because of these differences in preparation, flavor, and texture, they are not considered the same product.

In English there are several valid words that contain no traditional vowel letters (a, e, i, o, u). Examples include interjections and onomatopoeic words such as “shh,” “psst,” “hmm,” and the adjective “nth.” Therefore at least in English, words can exist without a vowel letter, so the answer is yes.
The turkey vulture (Cathartes aura) is a well-known species of New World vulture native to much of the Americas, so it definitely exists.

A hole-in-one on a par-5 (called a “condor”) is extraordinarily rare but a handful of verified instances have been recorded in golf history—for example Larry Bruce’s ace on a 480-yard par-5 in 1962 and several later ones. Therefore the correct response to whether anyone has done it is yes.
Both the NFL’s New York Jets and New York Giants play their home games at MetLife Stadium in East Rutherford, New Jersey, a facility they co-own and share.

The U.S. Women’s National Team qualified for and participated in the most recent FIFA Women’s World Cup (2023). They have qualified for every Women’s World Cup to date, so they are indeed in the tournament.

No rule or inherent limitation prevents an African national side from winning the FIFA World Cup. Although none has done so yet, several have reached the quarter-finals and African football quality continues to improve. Therefore, it is indeed possible for an African team to win the tournament in the future.
A hammer is a heavy, hard object designed for striking. Any such object can be employed to inflict harm intentionally, so it can function as a weapon even though that is not its primary purpose.

Traditional fox hunting – pursuing a live fox with a pack of hounds – was banned in England and Wales by the Hunting Act 2004 (in force since 2005). While many hunt clubs still ride out, they are supposed to follow scent-laid ‘trail’ hunts or use other legal exemptions, not hunt live foxes. Therefore, in the legal sense, fox hunts as they formerly existed are no longer permitted in England, though related activities continue in modified form.

In the Army Service Uniform (ASU) regulations (AR 670-1 and DA Pam 670-1), the service coat (“ASU jacket”) is only authorized to be worn with the long-sleeve white dress shirt and a black necktie/neck tab. The short-sleeve ASU shirt is part of the Class B configuration and may not be worn under the service coat. Therefore, combining a short-sleeve ASU shirt with the ASU jacket is not permitted.

In Season 3 of The Vampire Diaries Damon and Elena admit growing feelings and share a couple of kisses, but they do not officially start a romantic relationship until Season 4 (after Elena becomes a vampire). Therefore, if “get together” means beginning an actual relationship, the answer is no for Season 3.

Line-backer Shaquem Griffin, who was born with amniotic band syndrome and had his left hand amputated as a child, reached the NFL in 2018 with the Seattle Seahawks and later spent time with the Miami Dolphins. He is the best-known example of an NFL player missing a hand, so the answer is effectively yes (though he announced his retirement in 2022, he was an NFL player).

“The Other Boleyn Girl” is a historical novel by Philippa Gregory that belongs to her larger sequence of Tudor-era books, often marketed as the “Tudor Court” (or more broadly, the “Plantagenet and Tudor”) series. Other titles in the same sequence include “The Constant Princess,” “The Boleyn Inheritance,” “The Queen’s Fool,” etc. Therefore, it is indeed part of a series rather than a standalone work.

“The Five Heartbeats” is the name of an R&B vocal group featured in the 1991 movie of the same name. Although the group was originally fictional, the name is indeed used within popular culture to refer to that (fictional) group, and cast members have occasionally performed together under the same name. Therefore, there is (at least fictionally) a group called The Five Heartbeats.
Mount Everest is geographically located within the Himalayan mountain range on the border of Nepal and the Tibet Autonomous Region of China, making it part of the Himalayas.

Under the National EMS Scope of Practice Model and in most U.S. states, IV therapy (initiating an intravenous line) is outside the standard scope of practice for an EMT-Basic. That skill is typically reserved for Advanced EMTs, EMT-Intermediates, or Paramedics. A small number of states may allow an EMT-Basic with an additional IV endorsement to start an IV, but that is an exception, not the rule.
No. 1 Court originally had no roof, but a retractable roof was completed and first used in 2019. Therefore, at present No. 1 Court at Wimbledon does indeed have a roof.

In the entire history of the NBA Playoffs, no team has ever erased a 0-3 deficit to win a best-of-seven series. The closest in the NBA Finals was the 1951 New York Knicks, who trailed 0-3, tied the series 3-3, but lost Game 7. Therefore, no team has successfully completed a comeback from 3-0 down in the NBA Finals.

Radio waves are a form of electromagnetic radiation. All electromagnetic waves—whether radio, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, or gamma rays—propagate at the same fundamental speed c (~3×10^8 m/s) in a vacuum. Therefore, radio waves travel at the speed of light.

Yes. In fact, a significant portion of the 1980 U.S. Olympic ‘Miracle on Ice’ roster went on to NHL careers. Players such as Neal Broten (1,099 NHL games), Dave Christian (1,009 games), Mark Johnson, Ken Morrow, Mike Ramsey, Rob McClanahan, Bill Baker, Steve Christoff, Mark Pavelich and others all played in the National Hockey League after the Olympics.

The interior angles of any triangle sum to 180°.  If one angle is obtuse (> 90°), the other two must share the remaining < 90°, so each is individually < 90° (acute).  If one angle is right (90°), the remaining two angles must sum to 90° and each is again < 90°.  If all three are already < 90°, the statement is trivially satisfied.  Hence, every triangle necessarily contains at least two acute angles.

Baylor University is located in Waco, Texas, while the University of Mary Hardin–Baylor is in Belton, Texas. They are independent institutions with their own administrations, campuses, and athletic programs, although UMHB began historically as a female branch of Baylor before separating in the 19th century. Today they operate as two distinct universities.

In the United States, the Supreme Court decision in Roper v. Simmons (2005) held that imposing the death penalty for crimes committed while the offender was under 18 violates the Eighth Amendment’s prohibition on cruel and unusual punishment. While a few countries in the world have not formally barred such executions, they are extremely rare and widely condemned. Therefore, in the U.S.—and in almost every nation today—a person who was a minor at the time of the crime cannot legally be sentenced to death.

The Indian men’s national football team took part in the Asian qualification rounds for the 2018 FIFA World Cup but was eliminated early and therefore did not reach the final tournament held in Russia.
“T. rex” is simply the common abbreviated form of the full scientific name “Tyrannosaurus rex,” referring to the exact same dinosaur species.

The 1914-era locks (Gatún, Pedro Miguel and Miraflores) that made up the ‘old’ Panama Canal continue to operate alongside the newer, larger third-set locks that opened in 2016. The original locks are still used daily by Panamax-size vessels and smaller ships, so the old canal remains in active service.

Commercial cotton candy is made by spinning sugar that has been mixed with food coloring and a small amount of flavoring. The standard pink variety is flavored with a ‘pink vanilla’ or light strawberry-vanilla flavoring, while the standard blue variety is flavored with ‘blue raspberry.’ Because the flavorings are different, they do not taste the same, even though both are primarily just sweet spun sugar.

The 1962 film adaptation of “To Kill a Mockingbird” received eight Oscar nominations and went on to win three Academy Awards, including Best Actor for Gregory Peck. Therefore, the title did indeed win Academy Awards.

In nature, mats of vegetation, peat, and soil can detach from the shore and remain buoyant, forming ‘floating islands’ that drift on lakes or wetlands (e.g., the floating islands of Loktak Lake in India or the peat islands on Lake Titicaca). Humans have also built artificial floating islands from reeds or modern materials. Therefore, the phenomenon does exist.

Female ferrets (jills) are induced ovulators and will stay in heat until they are bred or hormonally taken out of estrus. Prolonged heat causes persistently high estrogen levels, which can lead to estrogen-induced aplastic anemia and other complications that are often fatal if not treated. While veterinary intervention (spaying or hormone injections) can prevent death, an unmated and untreated jill has a high likelihood of dying. Thus, in the common sense of the statement, it is effectively true that female ferrets can die if they don’t mate.

Xbox One supports Xbox 360 titles only through its backward-compatibility program. Microsoft had to individually adapt and license each game, so only a curated list (a bit over 600 titles) is playable. Many Xbox 360 games were never added to that list, meaning they will not run on an Xbox One.

In typical human anatomy, the aortic arch gives rise to only one brachiocephalic artery (also called the brachiocephalic trunk). This single vessel sits on the right side of the midline and then divides into the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries. On the left side, the left common carotid and left subclavian arteries arise separately and directly from the aortic arch. Therefore, there is no separate left brachiocephalic artery.

In the U.S. version of Survivor, the prize pool is tiered. The winner receives $1 million, while the runner-up (2nd place) is awarded about $100,000 (and 3rd place slightly less). All remaining finalists and even pre-jury boots receive smaller appearance stipends. Therefore, runners-up do indeed receive money even though they do not win the grand prize.

11.22.63 was produced and promoted by Hulu as a self-contained limited series adapting the entirety of Stephen King’s novel. Since its 2016 release there have been no announcements, renewals, or development reports indicating plans for more episodes, and the creative team has repeatedly stated the story is complete. Therefore the proposition that there will be a second season is almost certainly untrue.

The United States has operated commercial nuclear power reactors since the 1950s and currently has more than 90 reactors generating about 18–20 % of the nation’s electricity, so nuclear power plants definitely exist in the U.S.

Since 2022 Wimbledon follows the unified Grand-Slam rule: when the deciding set (third in women’s matches, fifth in men’s) reaches 6-6, a 10-point match-tiebreak is played. (From 2019–2021 Wimbledon already had a final-set tiebreak, but it began at 12-12.) Therefore, under the current rules there is indeed a tiebreaker in the final set at Wimbledon.

The term “Twin Towers” referred to World Trade Center buildings 1 and 2, the two iconic skyscrapers at the center of the World Trade Center complex in New York City. Although the entire complex contained several other buildings, in common usage the phrase “the World Trade Center” often meant those two towers themselves. Therefore, saying the Twin Towers were the World Trade Center is essentially correct, though they were technically the main part of a larger complex.

Deion Sanders did reach the World Series with the Atlanta Braves in 1992, but the Braves lost to the Toronto Blue Jays. He was never on a team that won the championship, so he never earned a World Series ring.

The term “Alsatian” was adopted in Britain after World War I for the dog breed originally called the German Shepherd, to avoid the word “German.” Over time both names have been used interchangeably, and they refer to the same dog breed.

Real frogs have nociceptors and a strong escape reflex. If suddenly dropped into near-boiling water they will experience extreme thermal pain and immediately try to leap out (though they may be injured or die quickly). Thus the statement that a frog jumps out of boiling water is largely correct, unlike the related myth about slowly heated water.

According to Einstein’s mass–energy equivalence (E = mc²), energy and mass are two forms of the same physical quantity. In high-energy processes—e.g., pair production in particle accelerators or near intense electromagnetic fields—pure energy (such as high-frequency photons) can be converted into massive particle–antiparticle pairs, provided conservation laws (momentum, charge, etc.) are satisfied. Therefore, the creation of mass from energy is physically allowed and experimentally observed.

Rotten Tomatoes aggregates reviews from approved critics and assigns a 'Tomatometer' score from 0-100%. A number of widely-panned films (e.g., ‘Ballistic: Ecks vs. Sever,’ ‘Jaws: The Revenge,’ ‘Mac and Me,’ ‘Gotti’ (2018) before later reviews, etc.) have received a 0% rating, meaning every counted critic review was negative at the time. Therefore, movies with a 0% score do exist.

The Jaguar S-Type (produced 1999–2007) was built on the Ford DEW98 platform, the same rear-wheel-drive architecture used for the Lincoln LS and Ford Thunderbird. All production versions of the S-Type sent power to the rear wheels (AWD was never offered). Therefore, it is a rear-wheel-drive car.

In standard flatware size hierarchy, a teaspoon is smallest (~5 mL), a dessert spoon is intermediate (~10 mL), and a tablespoon is largest (~15 mL). Therefore, a tablespoon holds more and is physically larger than a dessert spoon.

In U.S. context, “the president” is generally understood to mean the President of the United States, whose official residence and workplace is the White House. Presidents customarily live there while in office, so the statement is accurate.

The dorsal root ganglion contains the cell bodies of primary afferent (sensory) neurons whose axons bring information from peripheral receptors into the spinal cord, so it is involved in carrying sensory input.

The series is set on Prince Edward Island, but the production chose Ontario locations (e.g., Pickering, Caledon, Millbrook, Prince Edward County in Ontario) to stand in for PEI. Aside from possible stock or aerial establishing footage, principal photography was not done on Prince Edward Island.

Both quantities use the same units (radians per second) and are often denoted by the same symbol ω, but they describe slightly different things. Angular velocity is a vector that gives the rate of rotation AND the axis/direction of rotation. Angular frequency is usually treated as a scalar that gives only the rate (magnitude) of oscillation or rotation, with no directional information. Thus they are related but not literally the same physical quantity.

A bullet fired upward will eventually fall back to the ground. Even though it slows as it rises, it accelerates downward and can reach terminal velocities (often 90-150 m/s) that are still well above the threshold required to penetrate skin, skull, or vital organs. Numerous documented cases show people being injured or killed by falling bullets from celebratory gunfire. Therefore, death is possible from a bullet shot into the air.

“Biggest” is usually interpreted as the largest by population. According to the 2020 U.S. Census, Salt Lake City has the highest population of any city in Utah (~200 k), larger than the next-largest, West Valley City (~140 k). Therefore, Salt Lake City is indeed the largest city in Utah by population.

“Chasing Cars” was written by Snow Patrol’s Gary Lightbody for the band’s 2006 album “Eyes Open.” Although the song became widely known after being prominently featured in the season-two finale of Grey’s Anatomy, it had already been written and recorded for the album, not specifically commissioned for the television show.

In The Lost World: Jurassic Park (1997) – and in the Michael Crichton novel it’s based on – the young girl (Cathy Bowman in the film’s opening scene) is swarmed by Compsognathus dinosaurs but is rescued by her parents and later reported to be recovering. Characters later mention that she is ‘just fine,’ so she survives the attack. Thus, the girl does not die.

Yes. Breathing air with a much higher-than-normal oxygen concentration (e.g., prolonged use of 100 % O2 or hyperbaric oxygen) can raise the partial pressure of oxygen in the blood and tissues to toxic levels (hyperoxia). This can damage lung tissue, eyes, and the central nervous system, cause absorptive atelectasis, and generate excessive reactive oxygen species. The body has no mechanism to store large amounts of extra O2 safely, so excessive oxygen intake can indeed be harmful.

Great Britain is the name of the island containing England, Scotland, and Wales. Northern Ireland is located on the island of Ireland and, while it is part of the United Kingdom, it is not part of the island—or political entity—called Great Britain.

Historical records show that while Tampa Bay has not had a direct land-falling major hurricane in recent decades, the city has been struck in the past—most notably by the 1921 Tampa Bay hurricane and earlier 19th-century storms such as the 1848 Great Gale. Therefore, at least once in recorded history, Tampa has indeed been hit by a hurricane.

In Catholic teaching, the sacramental components commonly called “last rites” (Anointing of the Sick, confession/absolution, and Viaticum) can be validly administered only by a validly ordained priest (or bishop). In an emergency, if no priest is available, laypeople may pray with or for the dying person, but they cannot confer these sacraments. Therefore, it is not true that anyone can give last rites in an emergency.

During the American Revolutionary War (1775-1783) the Continental Congress never enacted a national conscription law; the Continental Army was filled by volunteers and short-term state militia levies. While several individual states occasionally drafted men into their own militias to meet troop quotas, there was no overarching, federal draft like those used in later U.S. wars. Therefore, in the usual sense of a national draft, the answer is no.

A letterman jacket is personal property earned during high school. There are no formal rules that restrict wearing it once you graduate; many alumni continue to wear theirs for sentimental or fashion reasons. Social acceptance may vary, but it is entirely permissible.

Under Australian tax law, gambling or lottery winnings received by individuals who gamble recreationally are considered windfalls and are not assessable income. Therefore they are not subject to income tax, and related losses are not deductible. The only exception would be if the person is carrying on a gambling business as a professional, in which case profits (and losses) could be treated as ordinary income. For the vast majority of casual bettors, no tax is payable on gambling winnings.

The original Starz series wrapped up with its third (chronologically fourth if the pre-quel ‘Gods of the Arena’ is counted) and final season, ‘War of the Damned,’ in 2013. Starz officially stated at that time that it concluded the story. While a separate sequel/spinoff project (‘Spartacus: House of Ashur’) has been reported in development, this is not considered a Season 5 of the original show. Therefore, a conventional ‘Season 5’ of Spartacus is not planned.

Scar was killed at the end of the first Lion King film. In The Lion King II: Simba’s Pride he is only referenced in dialogue and appears briefly as a vision in fire, but he is not physically alive in the sequel.

The famous dog in the original Little Rascals/Our Gang shorts was Pete the Pup (several dogs filled the role, notably Pal the Wonder Dog who died in 1930 and his successor Lucenay’s Peter who died in 1946). All of those dogs have long since passed away. Even the dog that portrayed Petey in the 1994 Little Rascals movie would be well past a normal canine lifespan today. Therefore, no dog identified as “the dog from Little Rascals” is still alive.

“Journey 2: The Mysterious Island” (2012) follows and continues the story world that began with the 2008 movie “Journey to the Center of the Earth,” making it the second installment in that franchise.

While the main North and South Islands observe New Zealand Standard Time (UTC+12, UTC+13 in summer), the Chatham Islands—part of New Zealand—observe Chatham Standard Time, which is 45 minutes ahead (UTC+12:45, UTC+13:45 in summer). Therefore not every part of New Zealand shares the same time zone.

Both terms refer to the dehydrated form of milk produced by removing water content, and in everyday usage they are interchangeable. While labeling regulations may distinguish between variations such as non-fat dry milk or whole milk powder, the phrase “powdered milk” is simply another way of saying “milk powder.”

In the United States, governmental power is constitutionally divided between a national (federal) government and the governments of the individual states. This division of authority, with each level having distinct powers that cannot be unilaterally removed by the other, defines a federal system.

The term “relative” generally encompasses both blood relations and relations created through marriage (in-laws). A father-in-law is related to you through the marriage to your spouse, so he is customarily regarded as a relative.

David Visentin, the co-host of HGTV’s ‘Love It or List It,’ worked for many years as a licensed real-estate agent in Ontario, Canada (e.g., at Country Living Realty in Barrie). His on-screen role as the person who tries to persuade homeowners to ‘list’ their property is based on his actual professional background, not solely acting. Therefore, he is indeed a real, licensed real-estate professional.

The Washington Capitals, founded in 1974, captured their first (and so far only) Stanley Cup in the 2017-2018 season by defeating the Vegas Golden Knights in the Finals. Therefore, they have indeed won the Stanley Cup at least once.
The European Union is a political and economic union of primarily European countries. The United States is a separate, sovereign nation located in North America and has never been a member of the EU.

For automobiles and other vehicles, a title is the legal document that establishes who owns the vehicle, whereas a registration is the record with the state that the vehicle has been licensed to operate on public roads (and usually results in license plates and a registration card or sticker). Because they serve different legal purposes—ownership versus permission to operate—they are not the same thing.

Both breeds originate in Switzerland and trace back to the large Molosser-type dogs that the Romans brought across the Alps. The St. Bernard was developed at the Great St. Bernard Pass hospice for rescue work, while the Bernese Mountain Dog is one of the four Swiss Sennenhund farm dogs. Although they are now distinct breeds with different roles and appearances, they share a distant common ancestry, so they are related in a broad historical sense.

Historically, two international passenger services—Samjhauta Express (Delhi–Attari–Lahore) and Thar Express (Jodhpur–Munabao–Khokhrapar–Karachi)—have linked the Indian and Pakistani rail networks. Although both have been suspended since 2019 due to political tensions, the physical railway links and the officially designated cross-border trains do exist, so one can say that there is (or has been) a train connection between India and Pakistan.

In economic terms the ‘private sector’ includes all organisations that are not owned or controlled by the government. A public limited company (PLC) is called ‘public’ merely because its shares can be offered to the general public and traded on a stock exchange; ownership and control remain in private hands rather than the state. Therefore, PLCs fall within the private sector.

The United States does not have a universal, government-funded health-care system that provides services at no direct cost to all residents. Most people obtain coverage through private insurance (often employer-sponsored) and pay premiums, deductibles, and copayments. Government programs such as Medicare, Medicaid, and the Veterans Health Administration cover specific populations, but even these can involve some out-of-pocket costs. Emergency departments must treat patients regardless of ability to pay, but bills are still issued. Therefore, health care overall is not free in the United States.

Historical and archaeological evidence indicates that while thousands perished in the A.D. 79 eruption of Mount Vesuvius, many inhabitants of Pompeii (and nearby towns) managed to flee during the hours when only ash and pumice were falling, before the lethal pyroclastic surges arrived. Estimates of Pompeii’s population are around 10–12 thousand, yet only about 1–2 thousand bodies have been recovered, implying a substantial number escaped and survived.

According to special relativity, any object with mass would require an infinite amount of energy to reach or exceed the speed of light in vacuum. Although science‐fiction concepts (wormholes, warp drives, tachyons) are sometimes discussed, none have been shown to allow actual super-luminal travel within our current, experimentally verified laws of physics.

answer: No, there are currently no plans for another Golden Compass movie.
Reasoning: The 2007 film “The Golden Compass” under-performed at the U.S. box office and faced controversy, so its planned sequels were shelved. Since then the story has been adapted instead as the BBC/HBO television series “His Dark Materials,” which completed its run in 2022. No studio has announced or is developing a new Golden Compass feature film, and industry reporting gives no indication that one is in the pipeline. Therefore, it is very unlikely another Golden Compass movie is forthcoming.
Answer: No, there are currently no plans for another Golden Compass movie.

Reasoning: The Republic of Ireland reached the UEFA play-offs but lost 5–1 on aggregate to Denmark, meaning they did not secure one of Europe’s qualification spots for the 2018 FIFA World Cup (Northern Ireland also failed to qualify). Therefore, Ireland was not present at the tournament.

Under current Florida law a private individual who is not ‘engaged in the business’ of dealing firearms may sell a gun to another Florida resident so long as the seller has no reason to believe the buyer is a prohibited person. There is no state-mandated background check or licensing requirement for ordinary private, face-to-face transfers conducted outside of a gun show, although the state and some counties impose waiting-period rules and age restrictions (21 for handguns and most long guns). Therefore a private sale is generally lawful if these conditions are met.

In the 2004 film “Man on Fire,” the young girl, Pita Ramos, is kidnapped and initially presumed dead after a botched ransom exchange. However, it is later revealed that she is still alive. In the climax, Creasy trades himself for Pita, and she is safely returned to her mother while Creasy later dies from his injuries. Therefore, the little girl does not die in the movie.

Latent heat of vaporization equals the enthalpy difference between saturated liquid and saturated vapour at a given pressure (temperature). As temperature increases toward the critical point that enthalpy difference becomes smaller, reaching zero at the critical temperature. Therefore the latent heat is not a constant; it varies (generally decreases) with temperature.

A Network Attached Storage (NAS) device is essentially a specialized file server that presents storage to users over the network. Many NAS units also run additional services (e.g., media streaming, web hosting, virtualization) much like a general-purpose server. Therefore, a NAS can indeed be used as a server—at minimum for file services and, in many cases, for other server functions as well.

In the TV series “My Name Is Earl,” the main character, Earl Hickey, works through a list of wrongs to right as part of his quest for karma. The show was cancelled after its fourth season with many items still left on the list. Therefore, within the aired episodes, Earl never completed the list.

answer: No, Powerball matches do not have to be in order.
Reasoning: In Powerball drawings, the five white balls are drawn without regard to position; any ticket that contains those same five numbers in any order is considered a match. The only separate position is the red Powerball number, which simply has to match that single drawn number. Therefore, the order of the numbers on the ticket does not matter for winning combinations.
Answer: No, Powerball matches do not have to be in order.

Reasoning: “The Fate of the Furious” (released in 2017) is the eighth installment in the Fast & Furious franchise. Since then, at least one more main-series film, “F9” (2021), has been released, and additional sequels (e.g., “Fast X” and an eleventh film) are planned. Therefore, it is not the last movie in the series.

Battlefield 1, released in 2016 by DICE/EA, features a single-player story mode called “War Stories,” consisting of several short campaigns set in different theaters of World War I. Therefore, the game does include a single-player campaign.

Upon its completion in 1973, the Sears Tower (now Willis Tower) surpassed the World Trade Center to become the world’s tallest building and held that title until 1998, when it was overtaken by the Petronas Towers. Therefore, at one point in time, it was indeed the tallest building in the world.

In the United States, the National Minimum Drinking Age Act of 1984 effectively required every state to set the legal drinking age to 21 in order to receive full federal highway funds. While individual states can allow limited exceptions (e.g., under-21 consumption on private property with parental consent, for religious ceremonies, etc.), the general legal purchase age for alcohol is 21 everywhere. Therefore, the drinking age is not different in every state.
Yes. A condition known as anosmia can be congenital (present from birth) or acquired through injury, infection, or other medical issues, leaving a person with no sense of smell.

The Port Mann Bridge in British Columbia charged tolls from its reopening in 2012 until September 2017. The provincial government removed those tolls, and none have been reinstated. Therefore, the statement that it is currently a toll bridge is incorrect.

Denatured alcohol is ethanol that has been rendered undrinkable by adding small amounts of toxic or bad-tasting substances (e.g., methanol, isopropanol, bitterants). Acetone, on the other hand, is an entirely different molecule (propanone, CH3-CO-CH3) and belongs to the ketone family. Although both are common solvents, their chemical structures, properties, and typical uses differ. Therefore they are not the same substance.

In Euclidean vector spaces, the dot product is defined as the sum of the products of corresponding components of two vectors, yielding a single real number (a magnitude, not another vector). Hence it is a scalar quantity.

Most people have one eye that their visual system prefers for tasks requiring precise positional information, such as aiming or sighting; this phenomenon is called ocular dominance or eye dominance. While both eyes contribute to vision, one is typically relied on slightly more than the other, so the concept of a ‘dominant eye’ is real in vision science.

The European Economic Area (EEA) consists of all EU member states plus Iceland, Liechtenstein and Norway. The Isle of Man is a self-governing British Crown Dependency; it is not part of the United Kingdom, the EU, or the EEA. Therefore it does not have EEA membership.

NCIS: New Orleans typically follows the traditional broadcast schedule, airing new episodes from the fall through late spring (roughly September–May). If the question is being asked anytime after the season finale in May and before the next season’s premiere in the fall, the series is indeed finished airing new episodes for that season and is on hiatus until the next one begins.

The term “navel” is the anatomical word for the scar left where the umbilical cord was attached; “belly button” is the common, informal name for the same structure. They refer to the same part of the body.

In ‘The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King,’ Sméagol (also called Gollum) struggles with Frodo at the Cracks of Doom, bites off the Ring, falls into the lava inside Mount Doom, and is destroyed. Therefore, Sméagol dies in the story.

The Australian sitcom “Here Come the Habibs!” aired two seasons (2016 and 2017) on the Nine Network. Since then, Nine has not commissioned or announced any further seasons, and key cast members have moved on to other projects. Industry reports and network schedules show no development plans for a third season, indicating the series was effectively ended after season 2.

In The Legend of Zelda: Majora’s Mask, the world operates on a repeating three-day (72 in-game hour) cycle. If the player does nothing, at the end of those three days the moon crashes and the game is over, effectively giving the player a time limit. The limit can be reset indefinitely by playing the Song of Time, but the constraint is still present each cycle.

Different writing systems have developed their own symbols for numerals: e.g., the Hindu-Arabic digits 0-9 used in most of the world, Chinese characters 一, 二, 三, etc., Devanagari ०–९, Arabic ٠–٩, and many others. Therefore, although the numerical concepts are universal, the written forms are not the same across languages.

Margaret Atwood’s novel “The Handmaid’s Tale” was adapted into a feature film released in 1990 (directed by Volker Schlöndorff and starring Natasha Richardson, Faye Dunaway, and Robert Duvall). Therefore, a movie version of The Handmaid’s Tale does exist.

Guillermo del Toro and Vanessa Taylor wrote The Shape of Water as an original screenplay. A novelization by del Toro and Daniel Kraus was published afterward, but the film was not adapted from a prior book.

India does not designate any language as its national language in the Constitution. Hindi (in Devanagari script) and English are designated as the official languages of the Union government, but neither is officially termed the national language.

While one company, Luxottica, manufactures and licenses a very large share of the eyewear brands people recognize (Ray-Ban, Oakley, many designer-label frames, etc.), there are still numerous independent manufacturers and smaller companies around the world that design and produce eyeglasses. Therefore, it is not true that every pair of eyeglasses comes from the same company—just that the market is highly concentrated.

Marvel and Netflix officially announced at San-Diego Comic-Con 2016 that Daredevil had been renewed, and Season 3 subsequently entered production and was released in October 2018. Therefore, a third season does (or in present-tense, will) exist.

Although the classical textbook definition of a tree is a woody plant with a single main stem (trunk), in practice many trees naturally or through cultivation develop two or more main stems that rise from the same root system or from a point near the ground. Examples include some species of birch, crepe myrtle, and certain oaks that are often intentionally trained as multi-trunk specimens. Therefore, while the single-trunk concept is typical, it is not an absolute rule.

In both the novel and film, the dog Bailey lives out a full life with Ethan and eventually dies of old age before being reincarnated into another body. Therefore, Bailey does indeed die within the story (though the dog’s consciousness continues in a new life).

The 1955 movie ‘The Night of the Hunter,’ directed by Charles Laughton, is frequently included in scholarly and popular lists of film-noir titles. Its chiaroscuro lighting, expressionistic visuals, morally ambiguous characters, crime-centered plot, and fatalistic tone align with key stylistic and thematic traits of film noir, even though it also overlaps with Southern Gothic and thriller genres.
“Ivory Coast” is the English translation of the French name “Côte d’Ivoire.” Both names refer to the same West-African country, officially called the Republic of Côte d’Ivoire.

The square root of 2 is an irrational number, meaning it cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers (a fraction). Centuries of mathematical proof, starting with the ancient Greeks, have established that no fraction a/b with integers a and b (and b ≠ 0) can equal √2 exactly.

The white tape plumbers wrap around male pipe threads is made of PTFE (polytetrafluoroethylene). DuPont’s trademark for PTFE is “Teflon,” so the same product is often called either “thread-seal tape,” “PTFE tape,” or “Teflon tape.” In everyday plumbing usage these names refer to the identical material and purpose.

“Dragon fruit” is the common market name for the fruit produced by several cactus species (mainly in the genera Hylocereus and Selenicereus). In Spanish-speaking regions the same fruit has long been called “pitaya” or “pitahaya.” Although botanists may sometimes use “pitaya” for a slightly different cactus genus (Stenocereus), in everyday usage the two words refer to the identical, brightly colored cactus fruit sold worldwide.

Nutritional guidelines (e.g., WHO, UK “5-a-day”) recommend a total of at least five portions of fruit and vegetables combined each day, not five of each. Therefore the statement that it should be 5 portions of fruit and 5 of vegetables (10 in total) is incorrect.

Across all eight seasons the signature opening music composed by Ramin Djawadi stayed the same melody and arrangement, even though the title-sequence visuals (and occasionally the length of the edit) were updated. No new theme song was introduced, so the theme essentially did not change.

Bumble bees (genus Bombus) are social, fuzzy-bodied bees that typically nest in the ground, whereas carpenter bees (mainly genus Xylocopa) are generally solitary and excavate tunnels in wood. They differ in taxonomy, behavior, and nesting habits, so they are not the same type of bee.

In men’s football, the FIFA World Cup has never been won by the Czech Republic. The team has not reached a final since becoming an independent nation in 1993, and its predecessor, Czechoslovakia, finished as runners-up in 1934 and 1962 but did not win. Therefore, the Czech Republic has never won the World Cup.

In U.S. banking, the 9-digit code printed on checks is formally called the ABA “routing transit number.” In everyday usage, people shorten this either to “routing number” or to “transit number.” They are simply different names for the same identifier, not two separate codes.

Geographically, the continent of Australia consists of mainland Australia, Tasmania, New Guinea, and nearby islands on the same continental shelf. New Zealand sits on a separate submerged continental mass often called Zealandia, so it is not considered part of the Australian continent, though both are grouped in the broader region of Oceania.

Disney has not released an official production-start or release date, but the studio has repeatedly confirmed that it is developing at least one more Pirates of the Caribbean movie (often referred to as “Pirates 6”) and has commissioned scripts. Because an active development process usually precedes eventual production in large franchises, the odds favor another installment being made, even though plans could still be cancelled.

The 2010 film "The Last Airbender" was originally envisioned as the first part of a trilogy, but its poor critical reception, mixed audience response, and modest box-office performance led Paramount and Nickelodeon to shelve any plans for direct sequels. Since then no production start, casting, or studio schedule for a movie titled "The Last Airbender 2" has ever been announced. While other Avatar-related projects exist (e.g., Netflix’s live-action series and animated films from Avatar Studios), none of them are a theatrical sequel to the 2010 movie. Therefore, there is currently no official release date for "The Last Airbender 2."

answer: No – there is no universal age limit; it is determined by each sport's governing body.
Reasoning: The International Olympic Committee does not impose a single, blanket age requirement. Instead, each sport’s International Federation sets its own minimum- or maximum-age rules (e.g., gymnastics has a minimum age of 16 in the Olympic year, while equestrian has no upper limit). Therefore, an athlete’s eligibility depends on the specific sport, not on an overall Olympic age rule.
Answer: No – there is no universal age limit; it is determined by each sport’s governing body.

Reasoning: Indian Motorcycle was founded in the United States in 1901 and, since its acquisition by Polaris Industries in 2011, final assembly of all current Indian motorcycles takes place at Polaris’ plant in Spirit Lake, Iowa. Although like most modern manufacturers it sources some components globally, the motorcycles themselves are manufactured/assembled within the United States.

The Russell Group comprises 24 UK research-intensive universities. In Scotland, only Edinburgh and Glasgow belong to it; the University of St Andrews is not a member. Therefore, St Andrews is not in the Russell Group.

The song “Eye of the Tiger,” written by the band Survivor, was commissioned by Sylvester Stallone specifically for the 1982 film Rocky III after he was unable to secure rights to use Queen’s “Another One Bites the Dust.” It debuted in that movie’s opening montage, so it was indeed written for a Rocky film.

U.S. Courts of Appeals are designed to review decisions of the U.S. District Courts and certain federal administrative agencies. They almost never serve as the first court to hear a case; that role rests with the district courts (trial courts) or, in a few specific situations, the U.S. Supreme Court’s limited original jurisdiction. While courts of appeals can entertain certain extraordinary writs (e.g., mandamus), these are not considered general original jurisdiction. Therefore, as a general legal principle, the Courts of Appeals do not possess original jurisdiction.

Capturing your opponent's queen gives a significant material advantage but the game is only won by checkmate, resignation, timeout, or other formal end-of-game conditions—not merely by taking the queen.

Whether the yolk of a fried egg is runny depends on how long and at what temperature it’s cooked. A fried egg can be cooked sunny-side up or over-easy so the yolk stays runny, but it can just as easily be cooked over-medium or over-hard so the yolk is set. Therefore, it is not inherently true that a fried egg has a runny yolk.

Boo, the Pomeranian known online as “the world’s cutest dog,” was reported by his owners to have passed away on January 18, 2019. Multiple reputable news outlets covered the announcement, confirming his death.

Laurie Forman, Eric’s older sister on That ’70s Show, was originally played by Lisa Robin Kelly (seasons 1–3, briefly in season 5). After Kelly left the series, the role was recast with Christina Moore, who played Laurie during several episodes of season 6 before the character was written out. Therefore, the actress portraying Laurie was indeed changed during the show’s run.

Lake Michigan is part of the Great Lakes, which are linked by navigable channels to the St. Lawrence Seaway. From Lake Michigan you pass through the Straits of Mackinac into Lake Huron, then via the other Great Lakes to the St. Lawrence River, which leads to the Atlantic Ocean. Commercial freighters and recreational vessels regularly make this trip, proving it is navigable end-to-end.

In men’s FIFA World Cup history, Scotland have qualified for the finals tournament eight times (1954-1998) but have never advanced past the group stage, let alone reached the championship match. Therefore they have never appeared in a World Cup final.

San Diego is one of the largest military hubs in the United States, hosting several major installations such as Naval Base San Diego, Marine Corps Air Station Miramar, and Naval Base Coronado, among others. Therefore, there is definitely at least one military base in San Diego.
The 1966 FIFA World Cup finals tournament was staged in England; England both hosted the competition and won it that year.

In U.S. high schools and colleges, a varsity letter is awarded each season or activity in which an athlete (or participant in activities such as band, debate, etc.) meets the team’s lettering criteria. Therefore, students commonly earn a letter every year they qualify and can also earn letters in multiple sports or activities. Consequently, accumulating more than one varsity letter is normal and expected for multi-year or multi-sport participants.

answer: Yes. New Hampshire is the only state without a seat-belt law for adults.
Reasoning: In the United States, 49 states and the District of Columbia have laws requiring adults to wear seat belts (either primary or secondary enforcement). The lone exception is New Hampshire, which has no mandatory seat-belt law for adults (although it does require restraints for occupants under 18). Therefore, at least one state—New Hampshire—does not have an adult seat-belt law.
Answer: Yes. New Hampshire is the only state without a seat-belt law for adults.

Reasoning: For the most familiar species—the worker honey bee—the stinger is barbed. When it is driven into the thick skin of a mammal, the stinger stays behind along with part of the bee’s abdomen and digestive tract. This fatal injury causes the bee to die shortly after stinging. Other types of bees (e.g., bumblebees, many solitary bees) have smoother stingers and can sting repeatedly without dying, but the common statement that ‘a bee dies after it loses its stinger’ is true for honey bees, which is what the question usually refers to.

The Tomb of the Unknown Soldier at Arlington National Cemetery (and similar monuments in other countries) was created specifically to house the remains of unidentified service members. In the U.S. tomb, the World War I, World War II, and Korean War crypts each still contain the remains of an unknown soldier. The Vietnam War remains were identified in 1998 and removed, leaving that particular crypt empty, but overall the monument still contains actual, unidentified human remains.

In the U.S., the word “pickle” usually refers to any cucumber that has been pickled, regardless of the cucumber variety or the pickling style. A “gherkin,” on the other hand, is a specific, small, bumpy variety of cucumber that is commonly pickled. Thus, every gherkin that has been preserved is a pickle, but not every pickle is a gherkin. Therefore the two terms are related but not interchangeable.

Top competitive typists and record holders have documented sustained speeds slightly above 200 words per minute on QWERTY or specialized keyboards (e.g., 212 wpm on Typeracer, over 200 wpm in Guinness records). While far beyond average capability, these demonstrations show that 200 wpm is attainable by a small number of highly skilled individuals.

The 2018 film “Rampage,” starring Dwayne Johnson, was explicitly marketed as an adaptation of the classic 1980s Midway arcade game series of the same name, featuring giant creatures attacking cities—an idea taken directly from the game’s premise.

Alligators typically seize large prey, drag it into the water, and hold it underwater until it drowns. Because they cannot chew, they may either consume parts immediately or cache the carcass underwater or under vegetation to soften before eating the rest later. This behavior matches the description in the question.

Multiple fossil specimens of Tyrannosaurus rex include well-preserved skulls (e.g., the famous specimens ‘Sue,’ ‘Stan,’ and ‘Scotty’). Therefore, at least one T. rex skull has definitely been discovered.

The question does not specify which band is being discussed, so I cannot determine with certainty whether all of its members are alive. In the absence of that crucial information, my best guess is that—in most well-known classic bands—at least one member has passed away. Therefore, I answer "False," but my confidence is low because the band in question is unknown.

Since February 2017 New Hampshire has been a “constitutional-carry” state. Anyone who may legally possess a firearm can carry it openly or concealed without obtaining a state pistol/revolver license. Licenses are still available for reciprocity in other states, but they are not required for carrying within New Hampshire itself.

The South Pole is a single geographic point located at the southernmost tip of Earth, while Antarctica is an entire continent that surrounds and contains that point. Thus, they are related but not the same thing.
Competitive inhibitors resemble the substrate and compete with it for binding to the enzyme’s active site; their defining feature is that they occupy the active site, blocking substrate access.

Several women have appeared in organized professional baseball below the major-league level. For example, Lizzie Arlington pitched an inning for the Reading Coal Heavers of the Class-A Atlantic League in 1898, and more recently Ila Borders pitched in independent minor-league circuits in the late 1990s. Therefore, at least one woman has indeed played minor-league baseball.

In many U.S. jurisdictions, unlawfully breaking into a motor vehicle with intent to commit a crime (often called auto burglary) is classified as a felony offense rather than a misdemeanor. While statutes vary by state, the general criminal-law principle is that ‘breaking and entering’—whether of a building or a vehicle—elevates the conduct to felony status.

Victoria Plum (formerly Victoria Plumb) and Victorian Plumbing are two separate UK bathroom-product retailers. They were founded at different times, have different ownership and branding, and operate independently, even though their names and market space are similar.

In both the novel and the film, Tess Carroll is thought to have perished in a sailing accident, but Charlie follows her spiritual presence, locates her still alive aboard her damaged boat, and rescues her. She survives, so she is not actually dead.

In the United States, the National Guard is organized at the state level. Every U.S. state (as well as Washington D.C., Puerto Rico, Guam, and other territories) has its own National Guard units—both Army National Guard and, in almost all cases, Air National Guard—that operate under the authority of the state’s governor unless they are federalized by the President.

Wind carries mineral-rich dust, especially from the Sahara’s Bodélé Depression, across the Atlantic Ocean. This dust deposits phosphorus and other nutrients onto Amazon Basin soils, partially compensating for nutrients lost to heavy rainfall and leaching. Multiple satellite and field studies confirm this nutrient transfer, so the Sahara Desert does aid the Amazon’s growth.

France observes Central European Time (UTC+1) and Central European Summer Time (UTC+2). The United Kingdom observes Greenwich Mean Time (UTC+0) and British Summer Time (UTC+1). Thus, France is consistently one hour ahead of the UK throughout the year, so they do not share the same time zone.

Head-lice and their eggs (nits) are vulnerable to sustained temperatures above roughly 130 °F / 55 °C. Experiments have shown that directing very hot air at close range for 20–30 seconds per small section of hair can kill most lice and a high proportion of eggs; specialised devices that essentially work like powerful hair dryers take advantage of this. A normal household hair dryer on its hottest setting can in principle reach those temperatures, so, used carefully and systematically, the heat can kill lice. However, ordinary, casual blow-drying (brief, at a distance) usually does not keep the scalp hot long enough, so it is not considered a dependable treatment on its own.

The European Economic Area (EEA) includes all EU member states plus Iceland, Liechtenstein, and Norway. Israel is not an EU member state and does not belong to the EEA, though it does have separate trade agreements with the EU.

A nursery rhyme is usually a short, rhyming verse for children (e.g., “Humpty Dumpty,” “Twinkle Twinkle Little Star”). “The Three Little Pigs” is a prose folk tale/fairy tale about three pigs building houses and a wolf who tries to blow them down. It is generally classified as a fairy tale, not a nursery rhyme, even though it is told to children.

In the 1991–1992 season of the sitcom “Murphy Brown,” the main character, played by Candice Bergen, became pregnant and, in a famous episode titled “Birth,” gave birth to a son named Avery. The storyline sparked national discussion at the time, confirming that the character indeed had a baby on the show.

What flows out of a maple tree when it is tapped is a watery sap that contains only a few percent sugar. To produce maple syrup, this sap must be collected and then boiled (or otherwise evaporated) to remove most of the water and concentrate the sugars. Therefore, the finished product called "maple syrup" is not obtained directly from the tree; it requires processing.

The DreamWorks/Netflix animated series "The Adventures of Puss in Boots" concluded with its sixth season, released in 2018. There has been no official renewal or announcement of a seventh season in the years since, and the production team has treated season 6 as the final installment. Therefore, it is highly unlikely a season 7 will be released.

All living cells, including animal cells, are bounded by a plasma (cell) membrane that encloses the cytoplasm and regulates transport. Although animal cells lack a rigid cell wall, they definitely possess a cell membrane.

answer: No, standalone liquor stores are not allowed to open on Memorial Day in Oklahoma.
Reasoning: Oklahoma law (Title 37A, Section 3-129) requires package liquor stores to remain closed on certain holidays, including Memorial Day. While grocery and convenience stores may sell beer and wine on that day, stand-alone liquor stores cannot open.
Answer: No, standalone liquor stores are not allowed to open on Memorial Day in Oklahoma.

Reasoning: The sitcom "The Parkers" features the characters Nikki and Kim Parker, who were first introduced in the series "Moesha." The show was developed as a direct continuation of their story, making it an official spin-off.

Air Canada is a founding member of the Star Alliance. It has never been a member of the Oneworld alliance, which includes airlines such as American Airlines, British Airways, and Qantas. Therefore, the statement that Air Canada is part of Oneworld is incorrect.

Need for Speed: Carbon (released in 2006) continues the narrative that began in Need for Speed: Most Wanted (2005). It features the same protagonist escaping from Rockport and arriving in Palmont City, directly picking up after the events of Most Wanted. Because of this direct story continuity and its placement in the release timeline, Carbon is considered a sequel to Most Wanted within the franchise.

Ingrown toenails are often caused by the natural curvature of the nail plate, genetics, improper trimming, or pressure from footwear. Even after surgical or partial removal, the nail matrix usually remains intact and continues to grow. If the underlying predisposing factors are not fully addressed, the regrowing nail can curve and penetrate the surrounding skin again, so recurrence is possible.

David Brooks has been an Op-Ed columnist for The New York Times since 2003 and continues to publish opinion columns there on a regular basis (his byline and recent articles still appear on the Times’ website). Therefore, he is still writing for the NYT.

The statement matches the definition of XML (Extensible Markup Language), which is explicitly intended for describing and transporting data rather than displaying it. Therefore, the statement is accurate.

Under U.S. (and most other) copyright law, creating and performing a cover version of a copyrighted song is generally allowed so long as you obtain the proper license. Live venues usually rely on blanket performance licenses from PROs (ASCAP, BMI, etc.), and anyone who wants to record/distribute the cover must secure a mechanical license (e.g., through the Harry Fox Agency in the U.S.). If you fail to obtain the required licenses before publicly distributing or monetizing the cover, you could be infringing, but the act of making a cover itself is not inherently illegal.

S. E. Hinton’s novel "The Outsiders" is a work of fiction. While Hinton drew inspiration from real-life rival social groups she observed in her Oklahoma high school, the specific events and characters in the book are invented. Therefore, the story itself is not a factual recounting of real events.
The Washington Capitals, an NHL team founded in 1974, won their first and only Stanley Cup championship in the 2017-2018 season, defeating the Vegas Golden Knights in the Final.

The gastrointestinal (GI) tract refers to the continuous hollow tube that food passes through: mouth, pharynx, esophagus, stomach, small intestine, and large intestine. The liver is an accessory digestive organ that produces bile and aids digestion, but it is not part of the hollow tract itself.

Despite the name, salt water taffy is not made with seawater, but traditional recipes do include a small amount of table salt (along with water, sugar, corn syrup, butter, etc.) to balance flavor. Therefore, it does contain salt.

All branches of the U.S. military, including the Navy, maintain a Delayed Entry Program (DEP). It allows enlistees to commit to service, complete processing, and then ship to boot camp at a later date—often several months out. The Navy specifically refers to this as the Future Sailor DEP.

A standard UK National Insurance (NI) number is issued in the format AA NN NN NN L – two prefix letters, six digits, and a final suffix letter (A, B, C, or D). While there used to be special ‘temporary’ reference numbers without the suffix, every officially issued personal NI number that people use today ends with one of those four letters.

Traditional penne alla vodka sauce is made with tomatoes, vodka, aromatics, and a significant amount of heavy cream (and often grated Parmesan or Pecorino). The cream—and sometimes the cheese—are both dairy products. While dairy-free adaptations exist, the classic preparation does include dairy.

The 2018 film “I Can Only Imagine” dramatizes the real-life experiences of Bart Millard, lead singer of the Christian band MercyMe, showing how his troubled relationship with his father inspired him to write the hit song of the same name. Because the movie closely follows these documented events, it is considered to be based on a true story.
Season 4 of Better Call Saul premiered on August 6 2018 and all of its episodes have already aired, so it is indeed available (‘out’).

Whether an 18-year-old may legally have sex with a 15-year-old depends on the age-of-consent law where they live. In most U.S. states and many other jurisdictions, the age of consent is 16–18, so sexual activity with a 15-year-old would be illegal and could lead to statutory-rape charges. A few places (e.g., some European countries) set the age of consent at 15, or have close-in-age (‘Romeo and Juliet’) exceptions that might cover an 18/15 pairing. Therefore, while it could be legal in certain jurisdictions, it is illegal in many others; one cannot simply assume it is allowed.

answer: True (usually allowed, if no sign prohibits it and after stopping/yielding)
Reasoning: In most jurisdictions in the United States—and in many other countries—you are permitted to turn right when facing a steady red signal, provided you come to a complete stop first and yield to all cross-traffic and pedestrians. This maneuver is prohibited only when a sign specifically says “No Right on Red,” when the intersection is controlled by a red right-arrow, or in certain special locations such as most intersections in New York City. Because the question is general and does not specify a jurisdiction, the best general answer is that a right turn on red is usually allowed, subject to those conditions.
Answer: True (usually allowed, if no sign prohibits it and after stopping/yielding)

Reasoning: In standard poker hand rankings, a straight is defined as five cards in consecutive rank regardless of their suits. The requirement that all five cards share the same suit applies only to a straight flush (or royal flush). Therefore, a normal straight does not have to be the same suit.

answer: No, there is no difference; the terms are interchangeable.
Reasoning: In engine terminology, “two-stroke” (2-stroke) and “two-cycle” (2-cycle) are alternative names for the same type of internal-combustion engine. Both describe an engine that completes its full intake-compression-power-exhaust sequence in only two piston strokes (one crankshaft revolution). Although the words “stroke” and “cycle” emphasize different aspects (piston motion vs. thermodynamic cycle), in common usage they denote exactly the same engine design, so there is no practical difference.
Answer: No, there is no difference; the terms are interchangeable.

Reasoning: In the 2018 film “A Quiet Place,” Beau Abbott—the youngest son—activates a noisy toy rocket while the family is walking home. The sound draws one of the creatures, and Beau is killed in the opening sequence. Therefore, he does indeed die in the movie.

Yes. A total of 19 U.S. service members have received the Medal of Honor twice (no one has received it three times). These ‘double recipients’ earned their awards in separate actions, mostly during the Civil War and the early 20th-century era when regulations still allowed a second award for a different act of heroism.

The Walking Dead and Fear the Walking Dead are two separate television series. Fear the Walking Dead is a companion/spin-off that takes place in the same fictional universe but follows different characters, locations, and storylines. Therefore, they are not the same show.

The 1994 song “All I Want for Christmas Is You” was composed by Mariah Carey together with producer Walter Afanasieff. Because she is officially credited as a co-writer, it is accurate to say that Mariah Carey wrote (co-wrote) the song, though she did not write it entirely by herself.

In bighorn sheep (Ovis canadensis), horns are permanent structures present in both sexes. Rams develop large, massive, tightly curved horns, while ewes grow smaller, more slender horns with only a slight curve. Because horns are not shed annually and both males and females grow them, the correct statement is that both sexes have horns.

St. Louis once had a historic Chinese enclave (“Hop Alley”) in the late-19th/early-20th centuries, but it was razed during urban renewal in the 1950s–60s. No officially recognized or sizable Chinatown exists in St. Louis today; Asian businesses are scattered in various suburbs rather than concentrated in a defined district.

The original run of the BBC sitcom “Bad Education” consisted of three series (2012-2014). However, the BBC later commissioned a revival: a one-off 10-year-anniversary special and a new fourth series, which premiered in January 2023 with a largely new cast alongside some returning characters. Therefore, a season/series 4 does exist.

Under NFL and NCAA rules, a team may attempt only ONE forward pass on a given down, and that pass must be thrown from behind the line of scrimmage. Any second forward pass (or a forward pass thrown after the ball has crossed the line of scrimmage) is illegal. While the offense may execute any number of backward or lateral passes on a play, the question is generally interpreted as asking about forward passes, which are the primary kind of ‘pass’ in football. Therefore you cannot legally pass (forward) the ball more than once on a single play.

Yann Martel presents two mutually exclusive narratives: one with a Bengal tiger named Richard Parker on the lifeboat, and a second, more plausible human-only account that Pi offers to the investigators. The novel/film never settles the issue, but the evidence (lack of physical proof of a tiger, the parallel human characters, and the investigators ultimately filing the pragmatic version) implies the tiger is a metaphorical construct representing Pi’s instinct for survival rather than an actual animal. Therefore, in a literal sense, the tiger was probably not physically on the boat.

The best-known recent usage of the title is the 2017 Kevin Sorbo faith-based drama.
