That plot about an outspoken atheist who has a near-death experience and converts is a work of fiction written for the screen, not a dramatization of documented real-life events. Therefore it is not a true story (aside from any general inspiration the writers may have drawn from real conversions).

The cheetah is the fastest land mammal, reaching about 70 mph (112 km/h) in short sprints. Several birds, most notably the peregrine falcon in its hunting stoop (dive), have been measured at speeds well over 200 mph (320 km/h), which is far faster than a cheetah’s top speed. Therefore, at least in terms of maximum recorded speed, there are birds faster than a cheetah.

In an ant colony the single reproductive female (the queen) lays all of the eggs. Whether a female egg develops into a new queen or into a worker depends on factors such as genetics, diet (especially richer larval feeding), and colony pheromones. Thus the existing queen can and does produce eggs that become future queens, especially during seasons when colonies prepare for nuptial flights.

Father’s Day (Vaderdag) is observed in many Western countries, including the Netherlands, where it is traditionally celebrated on the third Sunday in June. It is commonly marked by giving small gifts, breakfast in bed, or family activities, similar to how Mother’s Day (Moederdag) is celebrated.

The 2003 “Lizzie McGuire Movie” is set in Rome and the production actually shot many scenes on location at well-known Roman landmarks such as the Trevi Fountain, the Spanish Steps, and the Coliseum (with additional studio work done elsewhere). Therefore it was indeed filmed in Rome.

Metal Gear Rising: Revengeance is a spin-off in the overall Metal Gear franchise, taking place chronologically after Metal Gear Solid 4 and using characters (e.g., Raiden) and plot elements established in the Metal Gear Solid series. Thus it is directly related, even though its gameplay and subtitle differ.

Under Article I, Section 3 of the U.S. Constitution, the vice president of the United States is designated as the presiding officer of the Senate, formally titled the President of the Senate. Therefore, by definition, the vice president is the president of the Senate.

The United Kingdom formally left the European Union on 31 January 2020 and completed its transition period on 31 December 2020, ending EU membership. Therefore, Britain is no longer a member of the EU.

In Marvel comics and canon, the Human Torch (most commonly Johnny Storm, and originally the android Jim Hammond) and Captain America (Steve Rogers) are entirely separate fictional characters with different origins, powers, and histories. The confusion arises because actor Chris Evans portrayed Johnny Storm in the early-2000s Fantastic Four movies and later portrayed Steve Rogers/Captain America in the Marvel Cinematic Universe, but the characters themselves are distinct.

Although most glass breakage is caused by an external impact, windows can also fracture without any direct force. Temperature gradients across the pane, residual stresses from manufacturing, nickel-sulfide inclusions in tempered glass, edge chips, or gradual frame movement can all create internal stresses that eventually exceed the strength of the glass and cause it to shatter spontaneously.

Wisconsin state law does not prohibit Sunday alcohol sales. Both on-premises (bars/restaurants) and off-premises (stores) may sell on Sundays, subject to the normal statewide hours (generally 6 a.m.–9 p.m. for liquor in stores) and any stricter local ordinances. Therefore, in most places in WI you can legally purchase alcohol on Sunday, just not outside the allowed hours or where a municipality has chosen to restrict it.

The Power of One is a novel (and later a film) written by Bryce Courtenay. Although Courtenay drew on some memories of his own adolescence in South Africa, the plot, characters (e.g., Peekay, Doc, Geel Piet), and many events are fictional creations rather than documented historical facts. Therefore it is not a literal true story, but a work of historical fiction inspired in part by the author’s experiences.

Both the 1949 original and the 1998 remake of “Mighty Joe Young” created the giant gorilla through special-effects techniques (stop-motion animation in 1949; a full-body animatronic suit combined with CGI in 1998). No live gorilla was used for the main character.

The Barber of Seville originated as a comedic play by Pierre-Augustin Caron de Beaumarchais (1775) and was later adapted into Rossini’s famous opera (1816). The characters and events—Figaro, Count Almaviva’s disguises, Dr. Bartolo’s guardianship of Rosina—are fictional inventions intended for satire and entertainment, not a dramatization of real historical events or people.

A real image is formed where actual light rays converge. Because light physically comes to focus at that location, a surface placed there (e.g., a screen) will intercept those rays and show the image. This is in contrast to a virtual image, where rays only appear to diverge from a point, so nothing can be caught on a screen.

In the United States, the Department of Defense (established 1947) is the executive department that oversees all branches of the U.S. Armed Forces, including the Department of the Army, which administers the U.S. Army. Therefore, the Army is organizationally subordinate to the Department of Defense.
The RMS Titanic struck an iceberg and sank on April 15, 1912, during its very first trans-Atlantic crossing from Southampton to New York, which was its maiden voyage.

St. Augustine was founded by the Spanish in 1565 and has been continuously inhabited since then, making it the earliest European-established, continuously occupied settlement in what is now the United States. No other city in Florida predates it in European colonial history, so it is widely recognized as the oldest city in Florida.

In the 2017 film (and its novelization) “The Book of Henry,” the central character, Henry Carpenter, is diagnosed with an inoperable brain tumor and dies part-way through the story. Therefore, the boy (Henry) does indeed die.
Many well-known titles—e.g., Fortnite, Minecraft, Rocket League—allow players on different hardware (PC, PlayStation, Xbox, Switch, mobile) to play together, so cross-platform games definitely exist.

AGM (Absorbent Glass Mat) batteries are a subtype of VRLA (valve-regulated lead-acid) batteries in which the electrolyte is absorbed in a fiberglass mat. VRLA batteries are often referred to as “sealed lead-acid” because they are maintenance-free and do not require topping up with water. Therefore, all AGM batteries fall under the broader category of sealed lead-acid batteries (though not all sealed lead-acid batteries are AGM; some are gel-type).

The Commonwealth of Nations is a voluntary association mainly composed of former territories of the British Empire that chose to maintain formal ties after gaining independence. Although the United States was once a group of British colonies, it gained independence long before the Commonwealth was formed and never sought or gained membership. Therefore, the United States is not a member of the Commonwealth of Nations.

Since the National Minimum Drinking Age Act of 1984, every U.S. state has set the minimum age to purchase alcoholic beverages at 21 in order to avoid losing federal highway funds. Although some states allow limited under-21 consumption (e.g., with parental consent or on private property), no state currently allows 18-year-olds to legally purchase alcohol.

In the context of statistical modeling and experimental design, the variable that researchers try to explain or predict is commonly called the dependent variable. Another common term for the same concept—especially in biomedical and social-science literature—is the outcome variable. Both labels refer to the response being influenced by independent/predictor variables.

The Taconic State Parkway, like most New York State parkways, was designed with low bridge clearances and is legally restricted to passenger automobiles. Commercial vehicles, including all trucks, are expressly prohibited for safety and design reasons.

The George Washington Bridge assesses a toll only for vehicles traveling eastbound into New York (Manhattan). Westbound traffic into New Jersey is toll-free. Therefore, drivers do not pay in both directions.

Yes. While adequate hydration is essential, consuming water far in excess of the kidneys’ ability to excrete it (roughly ≥0.8-1.0 L per hour) can dilute blood sodium levels, leading to hyponatremia or ‘water intoxication.’ This condition can cause neurological symptoms and, in severe cases, be life-threatening. Therefore, ‘over-drinking’ water is possible.

The Houston Astros played in the National League from their inaugural season in 1962 through the 2012 season before moving to the American League in 2013. Therefore, they indeed used to be in the National League.

answer: Yes – Mark Stone is the captain of the Vegas Golden Knights.
Reasoning: The Vegas Golden Knights did not name a captain in their first few NHL seasons, but on January 13, 2021 they appointed forward Mark Stone as the first captain in franchise history. Therefore, at present the team does have a captain.
Answer: Yes – Mark Stone is the captain of the Vegas Golden Knights.

Reasoning: In the U.S. version of The Office, Michael Scott and Pam Beesly are close coworkers and friends, but the show never depicts them entering a romantic relationship or formally dating. Michael’s romantic storylines involve characters such as Jan, Carol, and Holly, while Pam’s involve Roy and later Jim. Although there are a few awkward moments (e.g., Michael giving Pam a peck in the ‘Diwali’ episode), these are played for comedy and do not constitute a dating relationship.

If the question is about the FIFA men’s World Cup (the competition most commonly meant by “World Cup soccer”), the United States has never won it. The U.S. women’s national team has won the FIFA Women’s World Cup several times (1991, 1999, 2015, 2019), but the men’s team has not, and the default reference for “World Cup” is usually the men’s tournament.

Blue Cross Blue Shield plans mainly operate as health maintenance organizations (HMOs), preferred provider organizations (PPOs), and other network-based plans that fall under the umbrella of managed care. Although individual BCBS companies may also offer some traditional fee-for-service products, the brand overall is widely classified as a managed care organization.

Psychiatry recognizes several conditions in which a person can become pathologically preoccupied with another individual, e.g., the erotomanic type of delusional disorder (also called De Clérambault’s syndrome) and presentations on the obsessive-compulsive spectrum sometimes informally labeled “obsessive love disorder.” While the latter is not an official DSM-5 diagnosis, the former is, so a bona-fide mental disorder that involves being obsessed with someone does exist.

Yes. The same wrongful conduct can give rise to both civil liability (a tort) and criminal liability (a crime). For example, an assault may be prosecuted by the state as a crime and, at the same time, give the victim a right to sue for damages in tort. The two proceedings address different purposes—punishment/protection of society versus compensation of the victim—so they can coexist.

Enameled cast-iron cookware is coated with a glass-like vitreous enamel layer that forms a non-reactive barrier between the iron core and the food. Because the food never contacts bare metal, appreciable amounts of iron are not released during normal cooking. Only if the enamel is chipped or badly worn could some iron leach at the exposed spots.

In That ’70s Show, Eric and Donna become engaged in Season 6, but they call off the wedding after realizing they aren’t ready. By the series finale they reunite as a couple, yet no on-screen or canonical marriage takes place. Therefore, they do not end up getting married within the events of the show.

Administrative Law Judges (ALJs) preside over administrative hearings, take evidence, make findings of fact and conclusions of law, and issue decisions that are binding within their agency—functions that constitute judging. Although they are not Article III judges (they are part of the executive branch rather than the judicial branch and do not have life tenure), they are still legally recognized adjudicators with judicial authority in their limited sphere.

Under NFL, NCAA, and most high-school rules the receiving team may signal for and be awarded a fair catch on any free kick, which includes a kickoff, provided the ball has not yet touched the ground or another player. (In fact, recent rule changes give the receiving team the option to take the ball at the 25-yard line after a fair catch on a kickoff.) Therefore, it is legal to call a fair catch on a kickoff.

In the United Kingdom both 12-hour and 24-hour formats are in everyday use. Spoken language and informal writing often use the 12-hour clock (e.g., ‘3 pm’), but official contexts such as railway and airline timetables, the military, medical notes, and most digital devices normally employ the 24-hour clock (e.g., ‘15:00’). Therefore, it is accurate to say that the UK does use a 24-hour clock, even though it is not the only system used.

Under the U.S. Constitution, a person nominated to the Supreme Court by the President cannot take office until the U.S. Senate gives its 'advice and consent' through a confirmation vote. Therefore, confirmation is a mandatory step in the appointment process.

In The Vampire Diaries, Elena Gilbert experiences several near-deaths and becomes a vampire, but she is never permanently dead. At the end of season 6 she is placed under a magical sleeping spell linked to Bonnie’s life, and in the series finale she awakens, is shown to live a long human life, and reunites with her loved ones in the afterlife. Therefore, she does not die for good.

The Channel 4 drama series "Indian Summers" was produced for two seasons, first aired in 2015 and second in 2016. After the second season the network announced the show was cancelled, so a third season was never made.

The 2011 film ‘I Am Number Four’ under-performed at the box office and DreamWorks/Disney let the planned series stall. For more than a decade there have been no green-lit sequels or reboots announced by the studio or rights-holders. While anything could change in the future, there is currently no development or production underway, so it is most accurate to say no further films are planned.

Under the Laws of the Game and FIFA World Cup regulations, every knockout-stage match—including the final—must produce a winner. If the score is still level after 90 minutes of regular time and 30 minutes of extra time, the match is decided by a penalty shoot-out. This has happened in past World Cup finals (e.g., 1994, 2006), confirming that the final can indeed be settled on penalties.

Australian Sign Language (Auslan) developed primarily from British Sign Language, whereas American Sign Language (ASL) descends mainly from French Sign Language and has a different lexicon and grammar. They are not mutually intelligible and are considered separate languages.

Scientifically, both ‘dove’ and ‘pigeon’ refer to birds in the same family, Columbidae. Ornithologists do not draw a strict taxonomic line between the two; the choice of common name is mostly traditional and size-based (smaller species often called doves, larger ones pigeons). Therefore, in a biological sense there is no consistent difference.

As of now, Hunter × Hunter is an ongoing series—its story has not formally concluded, and no official follow-up (sequel) series has been announced or released. There are films, OVAs, and video games, but these are side projects or adaptations rather than a chronologically later sequel.

‘Medici: Masters of Florence’ was followed by a second season, released in 2018 in Italy (and later on Netflix) under the title ‘Medici: The Magnificent.’ Although branded with a new subtitle, it is officially the show’s Season 2, continuing the story of the Medici family two decades later.

The term “gauge” is used for both sheet metal thickness and wire diameter, but the numerical scales are derived from different historical standards. American Wire Gauge (AWG) applies to round electrical conductors, whereas sheet-metal gauge (e.g., the Manufacturers’ Standard Gauge or Birmingham Gauge) specifies the thickness of flat metal sheets. Because the reference tables differ, the same gauge number does not correspond to the same physical thickness, so the two gauges are not interchangeable.

Amy’s Baking Company, the Scottsdale restaurant made famous by the TV show “Kitchen Nightmares,” permanently closed in 2015 (after a brief attempt to relocate to Glendale). Therefore, it is no longer in operation.

The CW officially renewed the television series 'The 100' for a fifth season in March 2017, and production has already been scheduled, with episodes expected to premiere in 2018. Therefore, a season 5 is confirmed.

The Berlin Wall was a physical barrier erected by East Germany in 1961 to prevent movement between East and West Berlin, lasting until 1989. The Berlin Blockade occurred earlier (1948-1949) when the Soviet Union cut off ground access to West Berlin, prompting the Western Allies’ Berlin Airlift. These are two distinct historical events with different dates, causes, and characteristics.

In most karate styles the black belt marks the first level of mastery, but higher ranks (advanced dan grades) are often represented by special belts such as a red-and-white paneled belt or a solid red belt for 9th-10th dan. These ranks sit above the standard black-belt levels, so there is indeed a belt regarded as higher than black in many karate organizations.

In the Season 8 plane-crash finale of Grey’s Anatomy, Dr. Arizona Robbins is severely injured but ultimately survives. She later appears alive (with an amputated leg) in Season 9, confirming she did not die in Season 8.

England and Scotland are two separate constituent countries within the United Kingdom that meet along a well-defined land boundary of roughly 96 miles, stretching from the Solway Firth in the west to the River Tweed in the east. Therefore, a border does exist between them.

After independence, many Indian states were reorganised along linguistic lines (States Reorganisation Act, 1956). However, other considerations such as historical identity, culture, geography, administrative convenience, economic viability and political factors have also been used (e.g., Himachal Pradesh, Uttarakhand, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand, Telangana). Therefore, language is not the sole criterion for classifying or creating states in India.

Grey’s Anatomy uses exterior shots of real buildings in Seattle to establish the setting, but the actual filming of almost all interior hospital scenes takes place on purpose-built sets at Prospect Studios in Los Angeles (earlier seasons also used a decommissioned VA facility). It is therefore not filmed in a functioning, real hospital.

Both 29-inch mountain bike wheels and 700c road/trekking wheels use the same ISO bead-seat diameter of 622 mm, which means the tire bead will fit the rim. As long as the tire width is suitable for the rim’s internal width and there is enough frame/fork clearance, a 700c-marked tire can be mounted on a 29er wheel.

In nearly all U.S. states (and in many other countries), statutes prohibit anyone under the legal drinking age from possessing alcoholic beverages except in narrowly defined exceptions (e.g., religious ceremonies, presence of a parent/guardian in some states). Therefore, as a general legal rule, a minor’s possession of alcohol is unlawful.

Ground coriander and cumin come from two different plants—coriander seeds of the cilantro plant (Coriandrum sativum) and cumin seeds of Cuminum cyminum. Although their ground forms may look similar and are sometimes used together in recipes, they have distinct botanical origins and flavor profiles, so they are not the same spice.

All contestants who appear on the TV show Survivor receive some form of payment. The winner gets the $1 million grand prize, runners-up receive decreasing amounts (e.g., ~$100 k for second place, ~$85 k for third), and every other castaway typically gets a stipend for participating—often around $10 k–$15 k depending on how long they last. Therefore, yes, participants are paid to be on Survivor.

“Wiener dog” (or “weiner dog”) is just a colloquial nickname for the dachshund, referring to its long, sausage-like body shape. They are not different breeds; the nickname and the formal breed name describe the same type of dog.

In English, adjectives most commonly precede the noun (attributive position), e.g., ‘a red car.’ However, they can also follow the noun in predicative position (‘the car is red’) or in certain fixed expressions (‘attorney general,’ ‘something interesting’). Therefore, it is not a rule that adjectives must always come before the noun.

Saint Kitts and Nevis is an independent sovereign country in the Caribbean. It was formerly a British colony and became fully independent in 1983. It has no political status as a U.S. territory (such as Puerto Rico, Guam, etc.). Therefore, it is not a U.S. territory.

The original book “Cheaper by the Dozen” (1948) was written by two of the real Gilbreth children and recounts the actual experiences of their family of twelve and their parents, the pioneering time-and-motion-study experts Frank and Lillian Gilbreth. Although later film adaptations take liberties, the source material itself is autobiographical, so it is indeed based on a true story.

A regulation American football field (120×53⅓ yd incl. end zones) fits well within the size range allowed for a regulation soccer pitch (100-130 yd long × 50-100 yd wide). Although the markings differ, the physical space and surface are sufficient, so in principle soccer can be played there once the correct lines/goals are set up.

In quiet and even most forced inspiration, the diaphragm and external intercostals are the primary muscles that contract to elevate the ribs. The internal intercostal muscles (except for their inter-cartilaginous portion) are primarily expiratory muscles; they generally remain relaxed during inspiration and contract during forced expiration to depress the ribs.

Scientific studies suggest a genetic component, but they also show that perfect (absolute) pitch can be acquired when a child receives intensive, structured exposure to pitch labels in the first few years of life. A small number of adults have also demonstrated partial acquisition through focused training, indicating it is not strictly innate. Therefore, one does not have to be born with it; early (or in rare cases later) learning can develop the ability.

In standard poker hand rankings, a straight consists of five cards in consecutive rank order. Ace can be treated as either the highest rank (above King) or the lowest rank (below 2). Therefore the sequence A-2-3-4-5 is considered a valid straight, commonly called the “wheel” or “five-high straight.”
The CW announced that The Originals would conclude with its fifth season, and the final episode of season 5 served as the series finale. No additional seasons were produced afterward.

answer: Yes—Bobby Jones achieved the (original) Grand Slam in 1930; no one has done it with the modern majors.
Reasoning: Golf defines a ‘Grand Slam’ as winning all four recognized majors in the same season. In the modern professional era those majors are the Masters, U.S. Open, Open Championship and PGA Championship, and no one has captured all four in one calendar year (Tiger Woods held all four consecutively over two seasons, the “Tiger Slam,” but not in one year). However, the only person ever to win what was considered the Grand Slam at the time was amateur Bobby Jones in 1930, when the four majors were the U.S. Open, The Open Championship, U.S. Amateur and British Amateur. Thus, if the question asks whether anyone has *ever* achieved a Grand Slam in golf, the answer is yes—Bobby Jones. If it refers specifically to the modern professional majors, the answer would be no.
Answer: Yes—Bobby Jones achieved the (original) Grand Slam in 1930; no one has done it with the modern majors.

Reasoning: Under current U.S. Senate rules (changed in April 2017 via the so-called “nuclear option”), debate (and any attempted filibuster) on Supreme Court nominations can be cut off by a simple-majority vote. Because the same simple majority is then sufficient to confirm the nominee, a minority party cannot use a filibuster to block a Supreme Court nominee anymore. (Before 2017, 60 votes were required for cloture, so a filibuster could have stopped a nominee.)

The City of Industry is an incorporated city located within the boundaries of Los Angeles County, California. It was incorporated in 1957 and is well-known for being an industrial suburb east of downtown Los Angeles.

In the Bible the book originally titled in Hebrew 'Shir Ha-Shirim' literally means 'Song of Songs.' Because the opening verse attributes the song to King Solomon (“The Song of Songs, which is Solomon’s”), many English traditions call the book 'Song of Solomon.' Thus the two titles refer to the exact same biblical book; they are simply alternate names.
Disneyland’s Pirates of the Caribbean opened in 1967, while the first film in the franchise was released much later in 2003. Therefore, the attraction predates the movies.

Ethiopia uses the Ethiopian calendar, which divides the year into twelve months of 30 days each plus a small 13th month, Pagume, of 5 days (6 in a leap year). Hence, in the context of its traditional calendar, Ethiopia is said to have 13 months in a year.

The Wizarding World of Harry Potter has two areas at Universal Orlando Resort: Hogsmeade, which is located inside Universal’s Islands of Adventure, and Diagon Alley, which is in Universal Studios Florida. Therefore, part of the Wizarding World is indeed in Islands of Adventure.

HBO officially produced six seasons of The Sopranos. The sixth season was split into two parts (often informally referred to as 6A and 6B), which can lead to confusion and some people casually calling the second half “season 7,” but in the network’s count and in all official releases, there are only six seasons.
A yard is defined as 36 inches, which is exactly 0.9144 meters—slightly shorter than a meter. Therefore, the two units are not the same length.

The Sun, along with the rest of the Solar System, moves in a roughly circular orbit around the center of the Milky Way galaxy once every ~225–250 million years. Therefore, it is accurate to say that the Sun orbits the Milky Way.

The white outer layer on Brie is a rind formed by the mold Penicillium camemberti. This mold is intentionally added during production, is safe to eat, and is traditionally consumed along with the soft interior of the cheese.

In classical mechanics, the wheel and axle is listed alongside the lever, pulley, inclined plane, wedge, and screw as one of the six simple machines that transform applied force. Therefore, it is indeed classified as a simple machine.

Paramount Pictures has confirmed development of a sequel to the original 2012 film, with Tom Cruise expected to return and the script based on Lee Child’s novel “Never Go Back.” While release dates can always change, the studio’s announcement makes it clear that a second Jack Reacher movie is planned.

.22 WMR stands for .22 Winchester Magnum Rimfire, which is commonly referred to simply as “.22 Magnum.” They are two names for the identical cartridge—there is no dimensional or performance difference between the two designations.
The 2012 film "Wrath of the Titans" was produced and marketed as the follow-up to the 2010 remake "Clash of the Titans," continuing the story of Perseus. Therefore, it is indeed a sequel.

A spin-off is directly derived from or set in the same fictional universe as the original show and is usually produced by the same creators or rights-holders. Z Nation was developed by The Asylum for Syfy and has no narrative or production connection to AMC’s The Walking Dead universe; it is simply another, separate zombie-apocalypse series.

answer: No, there is essentially no difference; Muay Thai and Thai boxing are the same martial art.

While some gyms or promoters may market slightly modified rules under the English label “Thai boxing,” the core art and rule-set are identical, so in practice there is no real distinction.
Answer: No, there is essentially no difference; Muay Thai and Thai boxing are the same martial art.

Reasoning: In Australia the Queen’s Birthday holiday is officially observed as a public holiday in every state and territory except Western Australia (which has a different date). Victoria observes it on the second Monday in June each year, so in Victoria it is indeed a designated public holiday.

Fear the Walking Dead is a companion/spin-off series that takes place in the same fictional universe as The Walking Dead, created by the same producers and based on the same source material. Characters and storylines occasionally overlap, confirming the two shows are narratively connected.

Canada’s border officers normally require a passport (or other WHTI-compliant document such as a passport card or NEXUS card) from U.S. citizens. A U.S. military ID by itself is accepted only for members of the U.S. Armed Forces who are on active duty and are entering Canada on official military travel orders. For personal or recreational travel, a military ID alone is not sufficient—you would still need a passport or other approved travel document.

In Gaston Leroux’s original novel and in the 1986 Andrew Lloyd Webber stage musical, Christine and the Phantom do not have a child. However, in Lloyd Webber’s 2010 sequel musical “Love Never Dies,” Christine’s son Gustave is revealed to have been fathered by the Phantom. Because the question is usually asked in reference to the current Lloyd Webber canon, the sequel establishes that they did indeed have a son.

The speed at which sound waves propagate depends on the medium’s elastic and inertial properties (e.g., bulk modulus and density). Because these properties differ from one substance to another—and can even change with temperature or pressure within the same substance—the speed of sound varies between materials (e.g., ≈343 m/s in air at 20 °C, ≈1 500 m/s in water, ≈5 100 m/s in steel). Therefore it is not a universal constant across all materials.

In the U.S. government, the executive branch is headed by the President but also includes the Vice President, the Cabinet, executive departments, and numerous federal agencies and officials. Therefore, the President is not the only member of the executive branch.

Humans can develop a limited tolerance to very small, gradually increased doses of arsenic (historically observed in ‘arsenophagists’), but this does not constitute true immunity. The element still accumulates in the body, causes cellular damage, and produces serious long-term health effects. Even individuals who tolerate small doses will be poisoned by larger or sustained exposures. Therefore one cannot genuinely become immune to arsenic.

The lead singer of Blur is Damon Albarn. Albarn co-created the virtual band Gorillaz with artist Jamie Hewlett and performs the majority of Gorillaz’s vocals and songwriting. Therefore, the singer from Blur is indeed in Gorillaz.

Several operational helicopters existed during World War II, including the German Flettner Fl 282 and Fa 223, and the American Sikorsky R-4, which was used for rescue and liaison missions in the China-Burma-India theater. Although limited in number and roles, helicopters were indeed present and saw service before the war ended.

The NCAA Women’s College World Series starts with eight teams divided into two brackets that are played in double-elimination format; only after two teams remain does the event switch to a best-of-three championship series. Because the core of the tournament uses double elimination, it is generally described as a double-elimination event.

Skunks are not on the UK Dangerous Wild Animals Act schedule, so no special licence is required to keep one. They are also not on the EU/UK invasive-alien species ‘Union list’, so they are not banned outright. Therefore private individuals may legally keep a skunk, provided they meet general animal-welfare requirements and do not release the animal into the wild. (De-scenting surgery for convenience is prohibited under the Animal Welfare Act.) Hence it is legally possible to own a skunk in the UK.

“Brain freeze” is the common name for the brief, sharp headache (medically called sphenopalatine ganglioneuralgia) that can occur when something very cold touches the roof of the mouth and rapidly cools the blood vessels there. The sudden temperature change triggers pain signals that people experience as a quick, intense headache. Because this phenomenon is well-documented and has a medical explanation, it is real.

answer: Yes – she had one sister, Princess Margaret.
Reasoning: The question likely refers to Queen Elizabeth II, who is often simply called “the Queen.” Elizabeth II had one sibling: her younger sister, Princess Margaret. She had no brothers. Therefore, the correct response is that she did have a sibling (a sister).
Answer: Yes – she had one sister, Princess Margaret.

Reasoning: Both the original 1997 Norwegian film "Insomnia" and its 2002 American remake were developed from an original screenplay (by Nikolaj Frobenius and Erik Skjoldbjærg for the 1997 version). There is no prior novel or non-fiction book on which the story was based; any novelizations came after the movie.

Under the Laws of the Game (Law 15 – The Throw-in), a goal cannot be scored directly from a throw-in. The ball must touch another player before it can count as a goal; if it enters the opponents’ goal untouched, play restarts with a goal kick, and if it enters the thrower’s own goal untouched, a corner kick is awarded.

The musical and subsequent films are adapted from the novel “Anna and the King of Siam,” which itself was drawn from the memoirs of Anna Leonowens, an English governess who actually taught the children of King Mongkut of Siam in the 1860s. Although the dramatizations take many liberties, the premise originates from real historical people and events.

If the question is asking whether the entire cast of the original 2008 film “Mamma Mia!” returned unchanged for the 2018 sequel “Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again” (or for later stage productions), then the answer is no: while most principal actors reprise their roles, Meryl Streep appears only briefly, and several new performers (e.g., Lily James, Jeremy Irvine, Hugh Skinner, Jessica Keenan Wynn) join the sequel to play younger versions of the characters. Therefore the cast is not exactly the same.

In the United States and many other countries, Father’s Day is observed on the third Sunday in June. Because it is tied to a weekday-of-month rule rather than a fixed calendar date, the numerical date changes each year (e.g., June 17 one year, June 21 another). Therefore, it does not fall on the exact same calendar day every year.

The original TV series 'Pretty Little Liars' concluded with season 7 in 2017. No official season 9 exists; subsequent content in the franchise consists of spin-offs and reboots rather than additional seasons of the original show.

The American Community Survey is conducted by the U.S. Census Bureau under Title 13 of the U.S. Code. That statute makes participation mandatory for every address that is selected. Although fines for non-response are rarely enforced, the legal obligation still exists and the Census Bureau sends multiple follow-ups stressing that requirement.

The Ivy League is an athletic conference comprising eight specific universities: Brown, Columbia, Cornell, Dartmouth, Harvard, Penn, Princeton, and Yale. George Washington University, located in Washington, D.C., is not a member of this group, so it is not considered an Ivy League institution.

On the game show "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?", a contestant may choose to stop playing at any time after a question is revealed but before locking in a final answer. If the contestant chooses to stop, they leave with the amount of money they have currently accumulated (subject to the last guaranteed safe-haven level). This option is colloquially referred to as "taking the money." Therefore, the correct response is that, yes, a contestant can take the money.

Son of Beast, the wooden roller coaster at Kings Island, was permanently closed in 2009 after a series of incidents and remained standing but not operating until it was demolished in 2012-2013. Therefore it is no longer at the park.

MLB has restricted smokeless (chewing) tobacco use: since the 2016 collective-bargaining agreement all newly-joining players are prohibited from using it during games, and many ballparks are in cities that ban it on the field. However, veteran players who were already in the majors before 2016 may still use it, so chewing tobacco is not completely banned across all of Major League Baseball.

The 2016 song and album “Death of a Bachelor” by Panic! at the Disco list Brendon Urie as a songwriter (along with several co-writers on the title track). Because he is officially credited, it is correct to say that Brendon Urie wrote “Death of a Bachelor.”
Avengers: Infinity War contains a single post-credits scene (after the full credits) in which Nick Fury pages Captain Marvel, confirming that a post-credits scene does exist.

In human anatomy, the abdominal and pelvic cavities form a single continuous space (the abdominopelvic cavity). Although the pelvic brim/superior pelvic aperture is used as an anatomical landmark to distinguish ‘abdominal’ from ‘pelvic’ regions, it is not a physical partition like a diaphragm or membrane. Therefore, no true structure separates the two cavities.

Alice Walker’s novel “The Color Purple,” and the subsequent film and stage adaptations, are works of fiction. While the story reflects real historical conditions experienced by many African-American women in the rural American South during the early 20th century, the characters and plot are not drawn from a single documented, true account. Therefore, it is not ‘based on a true story’ in the literal sense.

Petroleum is formed from the remains of ancient marine organisms that were subjected to heat and pressure over millions of years, fitting the definition of a fossil fuel (energy sources derived from long-buried organic material).

The current Las Vegas Monorail runs from the MGM Grand to the Sahara along the east side of the Strip. It has no station at Harry Reid International Airport (formerly McCarran). Although extensions to the airport have been proposed, they have not been built, so passengers must use other transport (shuttle, taxi, rideshare, etc.) to reach the airport.

National Car Rental and Enterprise Rent-A-Car operate as distinct rental brands with separate service counters, pricing structures, and loyalty programs. However, both brands are owned by the same parent corporation, Enterprise Holdings. Therefore, they are not literally the same company, but sister companies under a single corporate owner.

The Ottoman Empire conquered Egypt in 1517 and, despite varying degrees of autonomy (especially under Muhammad Ali and his successors), Egypt remained formally within the Ottoman Empire’s domain until World War I. Therefore, Egypt was indeed a part of the Ottoman Empire.

The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA) introduced the NC-17 rating in 1990, replacing the X rating. Since then, numerous films—such as "Showgirls" (1995), "Blue Valentine" (2010, initially), and "Shame" (2011)—have been officially released with an NC-17 rating. Therefore, at least one movie has indeed carried this rating.

Metro Manila (the National Capital Region) is composed of 16 cities and 1 municipality, all of which lie within its own administrative region. San Pedro is a city in the province of Laguna, belonging to the CALABARZON Region (Region IV-A), immediately south of Metro Manila but not administratively included in it.
Boston Terriers typically weigh between about 12–25 lb (5–11 kg) and stand around 15–17 in (38–43 cm) tall, which places them in the small-breed range by most canine size classifications.

The term 'cortex' in the central nervous system refers to an outer layer composed mainly of neuronal cell bodies, dendrites, and synapses, which constitutes gray matter. The outer layer of the cerebellum—called the cerebellar cortex—contains Purkinje cells, granule cells, and other neurons, fitting the definition of gray matter.

RMS Titanic departed Southampton on 10 April 1912 for her first scheduled trans-Atlantic crossing. On the same voyage, she struck an iceberg and sank in the North Atlantic early on 15 April 1912. Therefore, the sinking occurred during her maiden voyage.

New England Baptist Hospital in Boston is an orthopedic specialty hospital that serves as a clinical teaching site for medical students and residents, notably through its affiliation with Tufts University School of Medicine and various orthopedic residency and fellowship programs. Hospitals that provide such formal clinical education are classified as teaching hospitals.

The Rocky Mountain chain runs south-north through the eastern portion of Utah, including major ranges such as the Wasatch and Uinta Mountains. While Utah also contains other ranges (e.g., in the Basin and Range Province) that are not part of the Rockies, the prominent mountain systems most people refer to in Utah are indeed extensions of the Rocky Mountains. Therefore, saying that the mountains in Utah are part of the Rockies is generally correct.

Lionsgate has officially kept the franchise alive since 2016, repeatedly announcing that “Now You See Me 3” is in active development. In 2020 the studio hired Eric Warren Singer to revise the script, and in 2022 Ruben Fleischer (Venom, Zombieland) was attached to direct with core cast members (Jesse Eisenberg, Woody Harrelson, etc.) expected to return. While the movie has not yet begun filming and has no confirmed release date, the studio has not cancelled the project; the current status is ‘in development,’ which in Hollywood terms means another installment is planned but not guaranteed until production starts.
Answer: Yes—“Now You See Me 3” is planned and in development, though it has not yet been shot or given a release date.

This confirms that school shootings have indeed taken place at private schools.

For the FIFA Men’s and Women’s World Cups, the host nation (or nations, if co-hosting) is automatically given a place in the final tournament. This has been the established practice for many decades (with the only exception being Italy in 1934, when all teams had to play qualifiers). Therefore, in modern World Cups, hosting guarantees qualification.

North Carolina generally allows open carry of a handgun without any permit, except in a handful of specifically prohibited places (schools, certain government buildings, premises that are posted “no guns,” etc.). Possessing a North Carolina Concealed Handgun Permit (CHP) does not revoke or limit that ability—​it simply adds the option to carry the gun concealed. Therefore, if you hold a CHP you may still choose to carry the handgun openly anywhere that open carry is otherwise lawful.

Brussels is known to have an area of window prostitution concentrated near Gare du Nord (Rue d’Aerschot, Quai de Willebroek and surrounding streets), commonly referred to as the city’s red-light district. Therefore, such a district does exist.

Density is an intrinsic (intensive) property of matter defined as mass per unit volume. Different substances have different atomic or molecular masses and different ways their particles pack together, so at the same temperature and pressure each material characteristically has its own density. Therefore density does depend on the type of material.

An ounce (oz) in ordinary usage refers to a unit of mass/weight (≈ 28.35 grams). A fluid ounce (fl oz) is a unit of volume (≈ 29.57 mL in the U.S., ≈ 28.41 mL in the U.K.). Because one measures mass and the other measures volume, they are not inherently equivalent; only for substances with a specific density (such as water at a particular temperature) would the numerical values happen to be close. Therefore, treating them as the same unit is incorrect.
The CW series “Crazy Ex-Girlfriend” ran for four seasons from 2015 to 2019, with its fourth and final season airing in 2018-2019. Therefore, a season 4 exists.

The New Zealand crime drama ‘The Brokenwood Mysteries’ was renewed beyond its fourth season. A fifth series was produced and first screened in New Zealand in 2019 (and later in other countries/streaming services). Therefore, the answer is Yes.

Assuming the question refers to the television series “Star Trek: Discovery,” the show was renewed for a second season shortly after its first-season debut, and that second season already aired (it premiered in January 2019 on CBS All Access/Paramount+). Therefore, the answer is yes—a second season exists.

answer: False – the basic measurement does not depend on gauge size
Reasoning: Rainfall is expressed as a depth (e.g., millimetres) that would cover a flat surface uniformly. Because that depth is independent of the collecting area, two properly calibrated gauges of different mouth sizes will register the same rainfall amount. A larger gauge can reduce random error (more water collected, better resolution) and lessen losses from splashing or evaporation, but these effects are secondary; the fundamental measurement principle is unaffected by diameter. Thus, within normal design limits, the size of the rain-gauge opening does not inherently change the rainfall reading.
Answer: False – the basic measurement does not depend on gauge size

Reasoning: Europe is one of the seven continents and is geographically, politically, and historically distinct from the United States, which is a country located primarily in North America. Therefore, Europe is not a part of the United States.

Under Law 15 of the IFAB Laws of the Game, a goal cannot be scored directly from a throw-in. If the ball enters the opponents’ goal without touching another player, a goal-kick is awarded; if it enters the thrower’s own goal, a corner kick is awarded. A goal is only valid if another player touches the ball after the throw-in.

New Jersey is one of the 50 U.S. states, encompassing large cities, rural areas, shore communities, and some commuter suburbs of New York City. Although portions of northern New Jersey function as suburbs of NYC, the state as a whole is not accurately described as a suburb.

In general accounting terminology, the terms “profit and loss account,” “profit and loss statement,” and “income statement” are used interchangeably to describe the financial report that summarizes revenues, expenses, and net profit or loss for a period. Although some expanded formats of an income statement may include additional sections (e.g., other comprehensive income), the core report—showing revenues minus expenses—remains the same. Therefore, in common usage they are considered the same statement.

Brown rice is rice that has had only the inedible husk removed, leaving the bran and germ intact; it is therefore a whole-grain form of rice. “Whole wheat” refers to wheat kernels (not rice) that retain their bran and germ. Because wheat and rice are entirely different grains, something called “whole wheat rice” would be a misnomer. Thus, whole wheat (even if cooked like rice) is not the same food as brown rice.

Under UK law, only monogamous marriages are legally recognized. Polygamy (being married to more than one person at the same time) is prohibited; entering into a second marriage while still legally married to someone else constitutes bigamy, which is a criminal offence. Therefore a person cannot legally have more than one wife in the UK.

The New York Post, founded in 1801, continues to publish both its daily print edition and an active digital news site. It regularly releases articles, breaking news, opinion pieces, and maintains a significant presence on social media, indicating it is still operating as a functioning media company.

Puerto Rico is classified by U.S. law as an unincorporated territory of the United States. A protectorate is a distinct sovereign entity that is under the protection and partial control of another state, whereas Puerto Rico does not have separate sovereignty; it is subject to U.S. Congress under the Territorial Clause. Therefore, it is not accurate to describe Puerto Rico as a U.S. protectorate.

The Netherlands and Belgium are two distinct sovereign states in Western Europe. They have separate governments, capitals (Amsterdam/The Hague for the Netherlands and Brussels for Belgium), languages and histories, though they share a border and were once united (1815-1830) before Belgium gained independence.

A traditional California roll is made with cucumber, avocado, and crab (usually imitation crab/surimi) rather than tuna, salmon, or other fin-fish. While imitation crab is seafood, it is made to resemble crab; the roll is generally described as containing no raw fish.

France gifted the Statue of Liberty to the United States in 1886. Today it is administered by the U.S. National Park Service as part of the Statue of Liberty National Monument, making it property of the United States government.

Reasoning: U.S. immigration law (8 U.S.C. § 1158) states that any non-citizen who is physically present in, or who arrives at, the United States has the statutory right to apply for asylum. While approval of the application is discretionary and subject to legal standards, the ability to seek asylum itself is a legally protected right under U.S. law.

Revenge of the Mummy is the name of an indoor launched roller-coaster/dark-ride attraction found at several Universal Studios parks (e.g., Orlando, Hollywood, Singapore). It is manufactured by Premier Rides, has coaster track, launches, drops, and qualifies as a roller coaster.

Since Mike Shanahan’s arrival in 2010, Washington’s base front has been the 3-4. Subsequent coordinators (Jim Haslett, Joe Barry, Greg Manusky) all kept the 3-4 scheme through the years when the team was still called the Redskins. Therefore, the Redskins did in fact employ a 3-4 defense during that era.

The Miami Dolphins NFL team does not keep a live dolphin at Hard Rock Stadium today. Although a trained dolphin named “Flipper” briefly appeared in a tank at some home games in the team’s inaugural 1966 season in the old Orange Bowl, the practice was discontinued decades ago and has never been revived in their current stadium.

The Xbox One includes a backward-compatibility feature that allows it to run many, but not all, Xbox 360 titles. If a 360 game is on Microsoft’s official compatibility list, an Xbox One can play it (disc owners insert the disc and download a compatible version; digital owners redownload the game). Games not on that list cannot be played. Therefore it is possible to use Xbox 360 games on an Xbox One, but only for the supported subset.

Courage the Cowardly Dog ended its original production run on Cartoon Network in 2002. While reruns may appear occasionally on Boomerang or streaming platforms, the series is not part of Cartoon Network’s current lineup and no new episodes are being broadcast on regular TV schedules. Therefore, it is not ‘still on TV’ in the sense of ongoing or regular broadcast.

Nickelodeon officially cancelled Game Shakers after its third season in 2019 following creator Dan Schneider’s departure from the network. No plans for a fourth season have been announced since, and production on the series has ended.

The 2017 film “The Mountain Between Us,” starring Idris Elba and Kate Winslet, is an adaptation of Charles Martin’s novel of the same name. Both the book and the screenplay are works of fiction and are not based on any documented real-life incident. Therefore, the movie is not a true story.

While the field is usually drawn from that year’s All-Star rosters, MLB rules do not require it. On several occasions (e.g., Yoenis Céspedes in 2013, Joc Pederson in 2015), players who were not selected as All-Stars were nonetheless invited and competed in the Home Run Derby. Therefore being an All-Star is not mandatory.

Yes. A rare meteorological phenomenon known as “thundersnow” occurs when strong upward motion in a cold atmosphere produces convection, generating lightning and thunder while the precipitation reaching the ground is snow rather than rain.

George Harrison invited his friend Eric Clapton to play the lead-guitar solo on the Beatles’ 1968 recording of “While My Guitar Gently Weeps,” and Clapton’s contribution appears on the released track.

Although red velvet cake does contain cocoa powder, it uses far less cocoa than a typical chocolate cake and relies on buttermilk, vinegar, and (often) red food coloring to create its characteristic color, tang, and tender crumb. Therefore, it is a distinct style of cake rather than simply chocolate cake dyed red.

For the Golden Boot (or equivalent top-scorer awards) only goals scored during normal time or extra time are included. Penalties taken during a post-match shoot-out are not considered part of the match’s official goal tally and therefore are excluded from Golden Boot calculations.

The original Adventure Time series concluded in 2018 with its tenth-season finale. Since then, only limited follow-up content (the 2020–2021 Distant Lands specials and the 2023 spin-off Adventure Time: Fionna and Cake) has been produced. Regular episodes of the original show are no longer being made, so in the sense of the main series, new episodes are not still being produced.

The 2014 film “50 to 1” dramatizes the real-life story of the racehorse Mine That Bird and his unexpected victory in the 2009 Kentucky Derby at odds of 50-1. Because the plot follows actual events and real people connected with the horse, the movie is indeed based on a true story.

Under Law 12 of the IFAB Laws of the Game, a goalkeeper is not allowed to handle (pick up) the ball when it has been received directly from a throw-in taken by one of their OWN team-mates. Doing so results in an indirect free-kick to the opponents. (If the throw-in were taken by an opponent, the goalkeeper may handle it.) Because the common interpretation of the question is whether they can legally pick up a team-mate’s throw-in, the correct answer is no.

The Barber of Seville is Figaro, a clever match-making barber from an 18th-century French play (and Rossini’s opera). Sweeney Todd is a 19th-century fictional barber who murders his customers in Victorian London (penny-dreadful tale, later Sondheim musical). They come from completely different stories, eras, and personalities, so they are not the same character.

Both are pressed from the seeds of the flax plant (Linum usitatissimum), but the term “flax (or flaxseed) oil” is used for food-grade oil that is cold-pressed and purified for human consumption, whereas “linseed oil” usually refers to industrial-grade oil that is often solvent-extracted, sometimes boiled or polymerized, and is intended for use in paints, wood finishes, etc. Because the processing, purity standards, and intended uses differ, they are not considered the same product even though they share the same botanical source.

The Banaue Rice Terraces are occasionally nick-named the “Eighth Wonder of the World,” but they are not included in either the traditional Seven Wonders of the Ancient World or the officially declared New7Wonders of the World list announced in 2007. Therefore, calling them one of the 7 Wonders is incorrect.

Canada is an independent sovereign state that remains a member of the modern Commonwealth of Nations (often informally referred to as the British Commonwealth). It recognizes the British monarch as head of state and fully participates in Commonwealth institutions, so it is indeed part of that organization.

Central Bank of India was among the 14 major commercial banks taken over by the Government of India in the first round of bank nationalisations on 19 July 1969. Being government-owned and part of that 1969 nationalisation makes it a nationalised (public-sector) bank.

The Canadian TV series “Private Eyes,” starring Jason Priestley and Cindy Sampson, was officially renewed by Global for a third season in mid-2018, and those Season 3 episodes subsequently aired in 2019. Therefore, the answer to whether it will be renewed for Season 3 is yes.

The Xbox One can play only those original Xbox and Xbox 360 titles that Microsoft has specifically made backward-compatible through software updates. Many games from earlier Xbox generations were never added to this list, so they will not run on an Xbox One.

If the question is about FIFA World Cups in soccer/football, the United States men’s team has never won. However, the United States women’s national team has won the FIFA Women’s World Cup four times (1991, 1999, 2015, 2019). Because the question does not specify men’s or women’s competition and simply asks whether the U.S. has ever won “a” World Cup, the truthful answer is yes—through the women’s team.

While the phrase “broken heart” is often used metaphorically, modern cardiology recognizes ‘stress-induced (takotsubo) cardiomyopathy,’ sometimes nicknamed “broken-heart syndrome.” Severe emotional stress can temporarily weaken the heart muscle, producing chest pain and ECG/enzyme changes that mimic a heart attack. Most patients recover, but the condition is real and clinically documented, so a “broken heart” does exist in a literal medical sense.

The lunar phase cycle (29.5 days) runs independently of the solar year. Because of this mismatch, the Moon’s phase on the date of the summer solstice drifts from year to year; it may be new, first quarter, full, etc. A full-moon solstice alignment is rare (e.g., it happened in June 2016) but certainly not annual. Therefore the statement is incorrect.

The Canadian television series "Heartland" premiered in 2007 and has continued releasing new seasons well past season 9; as of 2023 it is in its 17th season. Therefore, the total number of seasons is indeed greater than 9.

Interpreting the question in a historical sense (i.e., have the Milwaukee Brewers ever reached the World Series), the answer is yes: they appeared once, in 1982, losing to the St. Louis Cardinals. If the question were about the most recent season, the answer would be no, but absent a specified year the safest reading is whether they have ever made it.

Yes. A breed known as the Myotonic or “fainting” goat has a hereditary condition (myotonia congenita) that causes its muscles to stiffen when the animal is startled. The brief stiffness can make the goat fall over, giving the appearance that it has fainted. This trait is well-documented in livestock science and farm practice.

The Chinese-American dish called “shrimp with lobster sauce” is so named because the sauce is prepared in the style traditionally used for lobster in Cantonese cooking (garlic, fermented black beans, egg, etc.). In most restaurants and recipes the dish contains shrimp but no actual lobster meat.

In occupational and environmental health literature, the primary routes of lead entry into the body are inhalation of airborne lead particles and ingestion of lead-contaminated dust or materials. Inorganic lead compounds are not readily absorbed through intact skin or the ocular surface; eye contact can cause irritation, but systemic uptake through the conjunctiva is considered negligible. Therefore, lead dust is not regarded as being absorbed through the eyes in any meaningful amount.

In U.S. culinary terminology, ‘powdered sugar’ and ‘confectioners’ sugar’ are two names for the same product—granulated sugar that has been ground to a fine powder and mixed with a small amount of anti-caking agent (usually cornstarch). Although the grind can vary (6X, 10X, etc.), both terms refer to the same category of sugar used for icings and dusting.

Many U.S. high schools schedule what is commonly called a “free period” or “study hall,” during which students are not assigned a specific class and can do homework, meet with teachers, or take a break. While policies vary by school and district—meaning not every high school offers one—in general it is accurate to say that free periods exist in high school settings.

Commercial and backyard olive cultivation exists in several U.S. states—most notably California (which produces the vast majority of domestic olives), as well as parts of Arizona, Texas, Georgia, and Florida—where Mediterranean-type climates with mild, wet winters and hot, dry summers occur. Therefore, olives can indeed be grown in suitable regions of the United States.

answer: Yes – a membership is normally required to shop at Bi-Mart.
Reasoning: Bi-Mart is structured as a membership discount store similar to a small warehouse club. Traditionally, shoppers must buy a low-cost lifetime membership (about $5) and present the membership card to make purchases. Therefore, to shop at Bi-Mart you generally do need to hold a membership, aside from rare promotional events that may allow guests.
Answer: Yes – a membership is normally required to shop at Bi-Mart.

Reasoning: Panama’s senior men’s national team reached its first and so far only FIFA World Cup finals in 2018 (Russia). They had never qualified prior to that, but because they did reach the 2018 tournament, the correct response to whether they have ever qualified is yes.

Jefferson Airplane are widely recognized as an influential rock band of the 1960s San Francisco scene. They were officially inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1996, a fact documented by the Hall itself and numerous reputable music references.

The phrase comes from the song “Every Breath You Take” by The Police, whose lyrics (“Every breath you take, every move you make, every step you take, I’ll be watching you”) are written from the viewpoint of an obsessive, controlling ex-lover. The songwriter Sting has confirmed that it is intended to convey possessiveness and surveillance—essentially the mindset of a stalker rather than a romantic admirer.

The blood–brain barrier is formed by endothelial cells with tight junctions that prevent passive diffusion of large, water-soluble molecules. While a few specific proteins (e.g., insulin, transferrin) can cross via specialized receptor-mediated transport, in general intact proteins cannot freely pass through the barrier. Therefore, for most proteins the answer is no.

The Pirates of the Caribbean film series was conceived as a cinematic expansion of Disney’s ‘Pirates of the Caribbean’ theme-park ride, not as an adaptation of any pre-existing novels. Novelizations and tie-in books were published only after the movies were produced, so the films are not based on books.

Belgium’s men’s national team has reached the semi-finals twice (1986 and 2018). Their best finish was third place in 2018 after losing the semi-final to France and winning the third-place play-off. They have never played in the final match of a FIFA World Cup.

Every U.S. state’s marriage statutes list full-blood and half-blood siblings among the prohibited degrees of consanguinity, and all states criminalize sibling incest. While a handful of states allow first-cousin marriages, no state issues marriage licenses to siblings, so such a marriage cannot be legally contracted anywhere in the United States.

The Houston Texans recorded their first postseason victory during the 2011 season (January 7, 2012) against the Cincinnati Bengals in the AFC Wild Card round and have added several additional playoff wins since then. Therefore, they have indeed won at least one playoff game.

Since Polaris Industries bought and relaunched the Indian brand in 2011–2013, all full-size Indian motorcycles have been assembled at Polaris’ plant in Spirit Lake, Iowa, with engines machined in Osceola, Wisconsin. Although some components are sourced globally, the motorcycles themselves are built in the United States, so they are considered ‘made in America.’

Both terms refer to cucumbers that have been preserved in brine or vinegar, but they are not interchangeable. “Pickle” is a broad term (especially in the U.S.) for any cucumber that has been pickled, regardless of size or variety. A “gherkin” is a specific variety of small, bumpy cucumber that is typically picked when very young and then pickled. Therefore, every gherkin is a pickle, but not every pickle is a gherkin.

GDP per capita is calculated by dividing a country’s gross domestic product—the total market value of all final goods and services produced within its borders—by its population. Income per capita (often GNI or personal income per capita) measures the average income earned by residents and adjusts GDP for net income from abroad, depreciation, and certain transfers. Because of these adjustments, the two figures can diverge, so they are not strictly the same even though they tend to be correlated.

The BBC has confirmed that The Apprentice (UK) has been renewed and will return with a new series (Series 18) scheduled to air in 2024. Lord Sugar has signed on to continue as host, and casting for candidates has already taken place. Therefore, another series is planned.

Because the two DNA strands are complementary, the RNA sequence produced depends on which strand is used as the template. For any given gene, only one of the two strands contains the correct information in the right 5’→3’ orientation to produce a functional mRNA (and thus the correct protein). Transcribing the opposite strand would yield an RNA that is the reverse-complement and would generally not encode the intended protein (and might not be translated at all). Therefore, for proper gene expression it definitely matters which strand is transcribed.

The black spheres in bubble tea are tapioca pearls (often called boba). They’re made from cassava starch, boiled, and sweetened specifically to be chewed and swallowed along with the drink, so they are completely edible for most people (barring allergies or other medical restrictions).

For most humans, the distance from fingertip to fingertip when the arms are fully out-stretched (arm span) is very close to their standing height. This 1:1 ratio is a well-known anthropometric rule of thumb (e.g., Leonardo da Vinci’s Vitruvian Man). There is, however, natural individual variation of a few centimetres, so it is not an exact rule for every single person, but as a general statement it is considered correct.

When the series originally aired it was licensed for exclusive streaming by Amazon Prime Video through its agreement with Fuji TV’s Noitamina block. As of the latest publicly-available catalog information (through 2023), Kabaneri of the Iron Fortress has not been added to Crunchyroll’s library, while it remains on Amazon Prime Video. Therefore the statement that it is on Crunchyroll is incorrect.

Many states exhibit hybrid or combined governmental structures—for example, the United Kingdom is both a constitutional monarchy and a parliamentary democracy, and the United States is simultaneously a federal republic and a presidential democracy. These overlapping classifications show that a single country can indeed embody more than one type of government at the same time.

FIFA removed the golden-goal rule after the 2002 World Cup. Since then, including the 2018 World Cup, knockout matches use two full 15-minute extra-time periods regardless of goals scored, followed by a penalty shoot-out if still tied. Therefore golden goal was not in effect in 2018.

The U.S. National Guard consists of the Army National Guard and Air National Guard and falls under the Department of the Army and Department of the Air Force (and under state governors unless federally mobilized). The U.S. Coast Guard is a separate military service under the Department of Homeland Security (or the Navy during wartime). Therefore, the National Guard is not part of the Coast Guard.

While the modern nation-state of Turkey did not exist in antiquity, nearly all of the territory that makes up present-day Turkey (Asia Minor/Anatolia and Thrace) was conquered by Rome between the 2nd century BCE and the 1st century CE and remained within the Roman (and later Eastern Roman/Byzantine) Empire for many centuries. Therefore, the region corresponding to modern Turkey was indeed part of the Roman Empire.

A birth certificate is the original vital record (or a state-issued certified copy of that record) that is kept on file by a vital records office. A “certification of birth” (often titled Certificate of Live Birth, Certification of Birth Abroad, etc.) is a document that only attests that the birth is recorded in the vital-records system and summarizes key facts. It is derived from, but not identical to, the actual birth certificate; some agencies do not accept a certification in situations where a full certified birth certificate is required. Therefore the two documents are related but not the same.

In-N-Out Burger began in California, but over the past two decades it has expanded into several other U.S. states, including Nevada, Arizona, Utah, Texas, Oregon and Colorado (with more planned). Therefore it is not exclusive to California.

There are well-documented accumulations of marine debris, chiefly plastics, concentrated by ocean gyres—most famously the Great Pacific Garbage Patch—so the statement that there is a floating mass of garbage in the ocean is correct.

Brown sugar is essentially refined white sugar that still contains, or has had re-added, a portion of the cane molasses. Dark brown sugar specifically has a higher percentage of molasses than light brown sugar (roughly 6–7% by weight). Therefore, by definition, dark brown sugar contains molasses.

People are not allergic to pure H₂O in the classic immune-mediated sense, but several rare conditions (e.g., aquagenic urticaria, aquagenic pruritus, cold urticaria) cause hive-like or itching reactions whenever skin contacts water, including rain. In addition, rainwater can carry pollen, mold spores, or pollutants that can provoke true allergic reactions. Therefore, while extremely uncommon, reactions that amount to an ‘allergy’ to rainwater can occur.

Babies "R" Us is not an entirely separate corporation; it is a brand/chain that operates under the same corporate parent as Toys "R" Us. Both were divisions of Toys "R" Us, Inc. (later Tru Kids, Inc.). Therefore they fall under the same company umbrella, even though they target different customer segments.

According to the song’s producer Walter Afanasieff and composer James Horner, Celine Dion agreed to try a quick demo of “My Heart Will Go On.” She sang the full song once, and that single pass was so strong that they kept it; no later full-vocal re-record was done for the released version (only subtle mixing and editing). Therefore, the commercially released vocal was effectively recorded in one take.

In the United States the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) does not give pre-market “approval” to multivitamins or other dietary supplements such as Bayer’s One A Day Women’s multivitamin. The agency can take action if a supplement is found unsafe or mislabeled, and it sets manufacturing and labeling regulations, but it does not formally approve the product itself. Therefore, Women’s One A Day is regulated by the FDA but it is not FDA-approved.

The Australian Imperial Force participated in several major actions within the 1916 Somme offensive, most notably the battles for Pozières and Mouquet Farm. These engagements were integral parts of the overall Battle of the Somme, so Australia was indeed involved.

The University of Arkansas (the Arkansas Razorbacks) has captured numerous NCAA team titles, most notably in men’s indoor and outdoor track & field and cross-country, and also claims the 1964 football national championship as recognized by the AP and UPI polls. Therefore, Arkansas has indeed won national championships in multiple sports.

The term “Air Force One” is a call-sign used only when the sitting President of the United States is aboard a U.S. Air Force aircraft. Former presidents can, on occasion, be transported on the same type of aircraft (even the exact VC-25A jets normally used by the president), but once the current president is not on board the flight’s call-sign changes to “Special Air Mission” followed by a number. Therefore, while ex-presidents may ride on the physical aircraft, they do not fly on an aircraft bearing the call-sign Air Force One.

Both the 2009 original release and the 2022 reboot of Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2 include competitive and cooperative online modes in addition to a single-player campaign, so the title is indeed a multiplayer game.

Several pig breeds—e.g., Göttingen, Yucatan, and Juliana—have been selectively bred to be much smaller than standard farm hogs and are commonly referred to as miniature or ‘mini’ pigs. Although they still grow larger than many people expect (often 70–150 lb), they are genetically distinct and consistently smaller than conventional domestic pigs, so miniature pigs do exist.

The Articles of Confederation were America’s first national governing document, but they were replaced when the U.S. Constitution was ratified and took effect in 1789. Since then, the United States has operated under the Constitution, not the Articles. Thus, we no longer follow the Articles of Confederation except as a historical reference.

Honey bees have barbed stingers that lodge in thick mammalian skin and tear from the bee’s body, killing it. Bumble bees, however, have smoother, relatively unbarbed stingers that they can withdraw and use again. Therefore, a bumble bee generally survives after stinging and can sting multiple times.

The CBS reboot of Hawaii Five-0 concluded after its 10th season, with the series finale airing on April 3, 2020. No new episodes have been produced since then, though reruns may still air in syndication. Therefore, as an ongoing, actively-produced series, it is no longer on TV.

Despite the name, traditional salt water taffy is not made with seawater. It typically contains sugar, corn syrup, water, butter, flavorings, and a small amount of table salt. Thus, while both salt and water are ingredients, actual ‘salt water’ from the ocean is not used.

In mammals, lactation is hormonally triggered by pregnancy and birth. Dairy cows must first become pregnant and give birth (calve) to initiate milk production. After calving, they can be milked for many months, but eventually they must become pregnant again to start another lactation cycle.

The United States Postal Service (USPS) is designated by statute as an independent establishment of the executive branch of the U.S. federal government. Although it operates with a high degree of operational autonomy and is self-funded through postage and services rather than annual congressional appropriations, it was created by Congress and its employees are federal employees. Therefore, it is indeed part of the federal government.

Commercial dessert bananas such as the Cavendish are triploid and develop without fertile seeds. The edible part you buy contains only tiny, non-viable seed traces, so planting a peeled banana or pieces of it will not germinate. Banana plants are normally propagated by tissue culture or by separating the underground suckers (pups) from an existing plant. Only certain wild banana species that still have full seeds could, in principle, be grown from those seeds—not from the fruit pulp sold in stores.

In the United States and several other jurisdictions, a couple can be considered legally married without a formal ceremony or marriage license if they meet certain requirements (e.g., cohabiting for a requisite period, intending to be married, and holding themselves out to the community as spouses). Although not every state or country recognizes it, the concept of common-law marriage does exist in law where it is expressly provided for.

The Far Cry series is designed largely as a set of standalone stories that share gameplay mechanics and thematic elements rather than a single, continuous narrative universe. While there are a few explicit links—e.g., Far Cry New Dawn is a sequel to Far Cry 5 and there are Easter-egg references among various entries—most installments (Far Cry 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, Blood Dragon, Primal, etc.) feature separate settings, timelines, and characters. Therefore the games are not all connected in one cohesive storyline.

Georgia (the country in the Caucasus) allows U.S. passport-holders to enter visa-free for stays of up to one year. Therefore an American citizen does not have to obtain a visa in advance for normal tourism or business visits within that period.

Both condiments are tomato-based and seasoned with chiles, but they are formulated and used differently. Picante sauce is essentially a spicy, chunky salsa made from diced tomatoes, onions, peppers and spices; it has noticeable pieces of vegetables. Taco sauce is usually cooked longer, then strained or puréed to produce a smooth, pourable, ketchup-like consistency and is often milder in heat. Because of these texture, flavor and usage differences, they are considered distinct products rather than the same thing.

Belgium’s men’s national football team has participated in many FIFA World Cups, with their best finish being 3rd place in 2018 after losing the semifinal to France and winning the third-place match against England. They have never progressed to the championship (final) match of a FIFA World Cup tournament.

The Australian TV series “Love Child” is set against real historical circumstances—namely the treatment of unwed mothers and forced adoptions in 1960s-70s Sydney—but the specific characters and plotlines are fictional creations. Therefore it is inspired by true events rather than literally based on one true story.

In evolutionary biology, ‘fitness’ refers to an organism’s genetic contribution to the next generation – i.e., its reproductive success relative to others in the population. Although surviving long enough can contribute to higher fitness, survival is only one component; an organism that survives but leaves no offspring has low evolutionary fitness, while one that reproduces successfully but lives a shorter time can have high fitness. Therefore, the terms are not synonymous.

“See You Again,” performed by Wiz Khalifa and Charlie Puth, was specifically commissioned for the Furious 7 soundtrack as a tribute to the late actor Paul Walker. It was written and released in conjunction with the film.

The most recent film in the franchise, “Halloween Ends,” was released in 2022 and wrapped up the David Gordon Green / Blumhouse trilogy. Since then, the underlying rights have reverted to Malek Akkad’s Trancas International, and reports indicate Miramax has been shopping the franchise rights for new film or television projects. However, as of now no studio has officially green-lit or announced a new Halloween movie with a title, cast, director, or release date. Given the brand’s value it is very likely a new film will eventually happen, but there is currently no confirmed production.
