“Bayern Munich” is the standard English rendering of the German name “Bayern München.” Both refer to the same football club, FC Bayern München, based in Munich, Germany.

Article III, Section 15 of the Florida Constitution lists the qualifications for state legislators and explicitly states that each legislator must be at least 21 years old. Therefore, the constitution does specify a minimum age requirement.

Puerto Rico is a U.S. territory, not a state, and it has no electoral votes in the Electoral College. Therefore, residents of Puerto Rico cannot cast ballots that count in the U.S. general presidential election, though they may participate in party primaries. To vote for president in the general election, they would need to establish voting residency in one of the 50 states or the District of Columbia.

In almost every jurisdiction tattooing is regulated. Typically you must be 18 or older; if you are younger, most places either prohibit it outright or require a parent/guardian’s written consent. Therefore, you cannot simply get a tattoo at any age.

Comcast Corporation and Time Warner Cable (and its former parent Time Warner Inc.) have always been separate, independently incorporated companies. Although Comcast attempted to acquire Time Warner Cable in 2014, the deal was abandoned in 2015, and the two firms never merged. Therefore, they remain distinct entities, not the same company.

King snakes regularly prey on rattlesnakes and possess a strong physiological resistance to rattlesnake venom, which allows them to survive bites that would kill most other animals. However, scientific studies show that their resistance is not absolute—very large doses or repeated bites can still harm or kill a king snake. Therefore, they are resistant rather than completely immune.
Universal Studios Hollywood opened "The Wizarding World of Harry Potter" in April 2016, so the park does include a Harry Potter–themed area.

In drywall work, the term “mud” is simply a trades-person’s slang for joint compound. Both refer to the premixed (or setting-type) compound that is applied over seams and fasteners before sanding and painting. Although joint compound comes in different formulations (all-purpose, topping, setting), the generic term “drywall mud” encompasses them all, so they are considered the same thing.

“Brain on Fire” is based on journalist Susannah Cahalan’s real-life illness with anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis. In both the memoir and the film adaptation, she receives treatment and ultimately recovers; she does not die.

The 22nd Amendment to the U.S. Constitution limits any person to being elected president no more than twice. Even a president who assumes office mid-term (e.g., after a predecessor dies) may serve at most ten years total: if they serve more than two years of someone else’s term, they may be elected only once more. Therefore, an American president cannot legally run for and be elected to a third full term.

The term “AR-15” refers to the civilian, semi-automatic version of the rifle originally developed by ArmaLite. Modern armed forces, including the U.S. military, issue selective-fire variants such as the M16 and M4, which are capable of burst or full-automatic fire and are produced to military specifications. While these rifles share a common design lineage with the AR-15, the semi-automatic AR-15 itself is not standard-issue and is generally not used by military forces.

The FIFA World Cup winners have always been nations such as Brazil, Germany, Italy, Argentina, France, Uruguay, Spain, and England. The Republic of Ireland has qualified for the World Cup finals a few times (e.g., 1990, 1994, 2002) but has never progressed beyond the quarter-final stage and has never lifted the trophy.

The Washington Capitals reached the Stanley Cup Final in 1998 (losing to Detroit) and again in 2018 (defeating Vegas to win the championship). Therefore, they have indeed appeared in a Stanley Cup Final.

Microsoft Visio is a diagramming and vector-graphics application used to create flowcharts, network diagrams, org charts, etc., whereas Microsoft Visual Studio is an integrated development environment (IDE) for writing, debugging, and managing software code. They serve different purposes and are distinct products.

Under the equitable doctrine of part performance (used to avoid the Statute of Frauds for land contracts), courts require acts that are ‘unequivocally referable’ to the alleged agreement. Merely paying, or agreeing to pay, the purchase price does not meet that standard because it is compatible with many other relationships (e.g., a loan or deposit). Consequently, common-law jurisdictions such as England, most U.S. states, Canada, Australia and others hold that payment of the price by itself is insufficient proof of part performance. No jurisdiction is generally recognized as treating payment alone as adequate part performance.

There is a 2008 live-action film titled “Far Cry,” directed by Uwe Boll, which was produced as an adaptation of Ubisoft/Crytek’s 2004 video game “Far Cry.” Although the plot diverges in places, the movie is explicitly marketed as being based on the game franchise.

In most U.S. jurisdictions you may seek a restraining/protective order against any individual—including a landlord—if you can show they have engaged in harassment, threats, stalking, assault, or other behavior that meets the legal standard for a protective order. Merely being a difficult or neglectful landlord is not enough; a court will require evidence of specific wrongful conduct that endangers your safety or peace. Therefore, it is possible to obtain a restraining order against a landlord, but only if the statutory criteria are satisfied and you can present supporting evidence.

Both terms refer to sheep, but they describe different categories. A ram is an adult male sheep, whereas a lamb is a young sheep of either sex (typically under one year old). Because they denote different age/sex classes, they are not the same thing.

answer: Yes (she adopts a baby, Noah, and raises him as her son).
Reasoning: The question likely refers to Olivia Benson, the main character on “Law & Order: Special Victims Unit.” Within the series, Olivia never becomes pregnant or gives birth, but she does legally adopt a baby boy named Noah Porter-Benson, whom she raises as her son. Therefore, while she does not have a biological child, she does become a mother through adoption.
Answer: Yes (she adopts a baby, Noah, and raises him as her son).

Reasoning: In the U.S. federal government, the Department of Justice is an executive-branch agency headed by the Attorney General and overseen by the President. The judicial branch consists of the courts (e.g., Supreme Court, appellate and district courts), not executive agencies. Therefore, the Justice Department is not part of the judicial branch.

Unfortunately, shootings have occurred in hospitals on numerous occasions (e.g., the 2022 shooting at Saint Francis Hospital in Tulsa, Oklahoma, and earlier incidents such as the 2015 Brigham and Women’s Hospital shooting in Boston). Therefore the correct answer to whether there has ever been a hospital shooting is yes.

In the Marvel Cinematic Universe release order, Captain America: The Winter Soldier was released in 2014, and Avengers: Age of Ultron was released in 2015. Therefore, Age of Ultron comes after Winter Soldier both in release chronology and within the MCU storyline.

There is a popular legend that when European explorers asked the local Aboriginal people the name of the animal, the reply sounded like “kangaroo” but supposedly meant “I don’t know.” Linguists who have examined the historical record have shown this story to be a myth. The word actually comes from the Guugu Yimithirr language (“gangurru”), referring to a particular species of large kangaroo. Hence the claim that it means “I don’t know” is false.

Hornets, like other wasps, have smooth stingers without barbs, so they do not lose the stinger after stinging and can inject venom repeatedly. Therefore a single hornet can sting the same or different targets multiple times.

Like all mammals, cows only begin lactating after giving birth. A dairy cow must therefore first become pregnant, carry the calf to term, and calve before she will produce milk. After a lactation cycle ends, she is typically bred again to start another cycle. Thus breeding (impregnation) is necessary for milk production.
In-N-Out Burger operates in several western states, and Nevada is one of them; there are multiple locations in cities such as Las Vegas, Reno, and Henderson.

The rock band Queen scored multiple number-one singles on major charts, such as “Bohemian Rhapsody” and “Under Pressure” topping the UK Singles Chart and “Crazy Little Thing Called Love” and “Another One Bites the Dust” reaching #1 on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100. Therefore, they definitely have had number-one hits.

The Canadian dollar (CAD) and the American/U.S. dollar (USD) are separate national currencies issued by different central banks (Bank of Canada and U.S. Federal Reserve). They have different exchange rates and are not interchangeable at par value, so they are not the same currency.

HeLa cells are derived from a cervical cancer and, like most cancer cells, are highly aneuploid. They typically contain far more than the normal human diploid number of 46 chromosomes (often 70-80 or more) with numerous structural abnormalities. Therefore, they do not have a normal chromosome number.

Atlantic City, New Jersey is served by the Atlantic City Rail Terminal, which is the eastern terminus of NJ Transit’s Atlantic City Line, providing passenger rail service to and from Philadelphia. Therefore, a train station does exist in Atlantic City.

The phrase “legally blonde” substitutes the word “blonde” for “blind” in the familiar legal/medical expression “legally blind.”  This wordplay highlights both the protagonist’s hair color and the legal setting of the story, so the title functions as a deliberate pun on “legally blind.”

Tolkien’s writings mention several other dragons besides Smaug, such as Glaurung, Ancalagon the Black, Scatha, and others that lived in earlier ages; Smaug is merely the last great dragon known in the Third Age, not the only one ever to exist in Middle-earth.

Brain-computer interfaces already exist at research and early commercial stages (e.g., implanted electrode arrays such as Utah arrays, non-invasive EEG caps, cochlear implants). They allow neural signals to be recorded and, in some cases, stimulation to be delivered, enabling control of cursors, prosthetic limbs, and sensory restoration. While current connections are limited in bandwidth and sophistication, they demonstrate that a functional link between the brain and a computer is indeed achievable.

Disneytoon Studios, the division that produced the six direct-to-video CG Tinker Bell films released between 2008 and 2015, was shut down in 2018 and the seventh planned installment was cancelled years earlier. Since then, Disney has not announced any new entries in the standalone Tinker Bell animated series. While the character may still appear in other Peter Pan–related projects (e.g., 2023’s live-action ‘Peter Pan & Wendy’), there is no indication that Disney intends to revive or continue the dedicated Tinker Bell movie line in the foreseeable future.

The U.S. National Guard normally serves under state authority for domestic missions such as disaster relief or civil support, so much of its time is spent in the United States. However, when ‘federalized’ by the President, National Guard units can and do deploy overseas; they have served in every major U.S. conflict since World War II, including Iraq and Afghanistan. Therefore, it is not true that the National Guard always stays in the U.S.

During the Republic of Texas era, the capital moved several times. From 1837 to 1839 the seat of government was in the city of Houston before it was relocated to Austin. Therefore, Houston was indeed once the capital of Texas.

Thanos has a brief but significant appearance in the 2014 film “Guardians of the Galaxy,” where he meets with Ronan the Accuser and speaks to Gamora and Nebula. Therefore, he is indeed in the first Guardians movie.

answer: Yes – a caution can be given without the person being arrested.
Reasoning: In England and Wales a police caution is an ‘out-of-court disposal’ that can be given when a person admits a minor offence and agrees to accept the warning. The suspect is often arrested and interviewed first, but this is not a legal requirement. Officers may deal with someone voluntarily (e.g., by inviting them to the station or by issuing a street/simple caution on the spot) and, provided the person admits the offence and meets the other criteria, the caution can be administered without a formal arrest having taken place.
Answer: Yes – a caution can be given without the person being arrested.

Reasoning: After Germany invaded the USSR in June 1941, the Soviet Union joined forces with the United States, the United Kingdom, and other nations as part of the Allies, fighting against the Axis powers for the remainder of World War II.

In recent seasons of America’s Got Talent, the four judges each get one Golden Buzzer, and the show also gives one additional Golden Buzzer to the host (e.g., Terry Crews has used it on several acts). Therefore, the host does have a Golden Buzzer to use once per season.

The franchise known as the Milwaukee Braves (1953-1965) captured the World Series championship in 1957, defeating the New York Yankees in seven games. Therefore, they did indeed win a World Series during their time in Milwaukee.

Tea tree oil is the common name for the essential oil distilled from the leaves of the Australian plant Melaleuca alternifolia. In everyday usage, “melaleuca oil” or simply “melaleuca” refers to this same oil. While the word Melaleuca can also denote the broader genus of plants, when talking about essential oils the two terms are synonymous.

Author Dav Pilkey has stated in multiple interviews (e.g., around the 2015 release of Book 12, “Captain Underpants and the Sensational Saga of Sir Stinks-A-Lot”) that the twelfth book would conclude the main Captain Underpants series. Since then he has focused on Dog Man and other projects, and no official announcement of a 13th Captain Underpants novel has been made. Therefore, on the basis of currently available information, a 13th book is not planned.

Braveheart (1995) received several Academy Awards. Mel Gibson was the film’s director and one of its producers. At the 68th Academy Awards he personally won the Oscar for Best Director and, as a credited producer, shared the Oscar for Best Picture. Therefore, he did win an Oscar for Braveheart.

Trinity Forest Golf Club in Dallas, Texas was built as a private, membership-only facility (though it occasionally hosts professional events). Because it is not generally open to the public for daily-fee play, it is considered a private, not public, course.

Just Cause 3 is an open-world sandbox game, but it still contains a structured main campaign that follows protagonist Rico Rodriguez as he attempts to overthrow the dictator General Di Ravello in the fictional nation of Medici. Therefore, the game does indeed have a storyline, even though players can also ignore it and focus on free-form exploration.

The Ivy League is an athletic conference that comprises eight private universities in the northeastern United States (Harvard, Yale, Princeton, Columbia, Brown, Dartmouth, Cornell, and the University of Pennsylvania). The College of William & Mary, while a highly respected public university founded in 1693 and located in Virginia, is not part of that group.

The Brooklyn–Battery Tunnel (officially the Hugh L. Carey Tunnel) connecting Manhattan and Brooklyn is operated by the MTA’s Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority and requires all motor vehicles to pay a toll (now collected via E-ZPass or tolls-by-mail). Therefore, a toll is indeed charged to use the tunnel.

The 2004 film “The Terminal,” while heavily fictionalized, was inspired by the real‐life case of Mehran Karimi Nasseri, an Iranian refugee who lived for years in Paris’s Charles de Gaulle Airport. Because the movie’s premise comes from this real incident (even though details were changed), it can be said to be based—albeit loosely—on a true story.

A bowl is a general term for a round, open-topped container (or, in smoking contexts, the part of a pipe or bong that holds material). A pipe is a distinct tool or implement—often with a stem and mouthpiece—used to convey fluids, gases, or smoke; it merely contains a bowl as one of its parts. Hence, while a pipe may include a bowl, they are not identical objects.

In Major League Baseball, games that are stopped by weather, darkness, curfew, or other circumstances before becoming official (or before a winner is determined) have historically been declared "tie games." While such games are replayed in full and do not count in the standings, they are nonetheless recorded in the record books as ties. More than a thousand tie games have occurred in MLB history; the practice effectively ended in 2007 when the rules changed to make most halted games "suspended" rather than ties. Therefore, at various times in baseball history, there have indeed been tie games.
“oz” (ounce) is a unit of weight/mass, while “fl oz” (fluid ounce) is a unit of volume. They measure different physical quantities, so they are not the same, even though their names are similar.

answer: No, you are generally not allowed to have your phone in prison.
Reasoning: In most jurisdictions, cell phones are classified as contraband because they allow unmonitored communication; inmates are typically restricted to monitored landline calls. Although a few low-security or work-release programs may grant limited supervised access, the general rule in prisons is that personal phones are not permitted.
Answer: No, you are generally not allowed to have your phone in prison.

Reasoning: In a general parallelogram only the opposite angles are equal, while adjacent angles are supplementary (add to 180°). Therefore, unless the parallelogram is a special case such as a rectangle or square, not all four angles are equal.

Artificial selection describes the process in which humans consciously choose which individuals of a species reproduce in order to enhance desired traits. The practical way this is carried out is through selective breeding—mating those chosen individuals. In common usage, the two terms are used interchangeably, with selective breeding being the method and artificial selection the underlying concept, so they are effectively the same thing.

Both terms refer to systems for dividing geographic areas to aid in mail delivery, but “ZIP Code” is the specific name for the United States’ system run by the USPS, while “postal code” is the general term used internationally for equivalent systems in other countries. Thus, they are related concepts but not literally the same entity.

The 2018 film ‘Deep Blue Sea 2’ was released direct-to-video (on DVD/Blu-ray and digital platforms) by Warner Bros. Home Entertainment. It did not receive a theatrical release; only the original 1999 ‘Deep Blue Sea’ played in theaters.

Rivers are classified as freshwater bodies because they originate from precipitation, groundwater, and melt-water rather than the ocean. The Amazon River, flowing from the Andes across the rainforest to the Atlantic, therefore carries freshwater along virtually its entire course, only becoming brackish where it mixes with seawater near its mouth.

The title "Doctor" traditionally applies to anyone who has earned a doctoral-level degree. A PhD (Doctor of Philosophy) is precisely such a doctorate, so its holders are entitled to be addressed as “Doctor.”

Fauda’s creators and the Israeli broadcaster Yes confirmed and produced a third season, which premiered in Israel in late 2019 and was later released internationally on Netflix in 2020. Therefore, the statement that there is going to be (or already is) a third season is correct.

The University of Tampa (UT) fielded an NCAA football team from 1933 to 1974, but the program was discontinued after the 1974 season for financial reasons. Since then UT has never reinstated varsity football, and it currently sponsors no intercollegiate football team.

The Australian/New Zealand series “The New Legends of Monkey” was officially renewed by the ABC, TVNZ and Netflix. The eight-episode second season was filmed in 2019 and released internationally on Netflix on 7 August 2020. Therefore, not only was a Season 2 confirmed; it has already been produced and made available.

New Mexico maintains reciprocity with several states whose training and eligibility requirements meet its standards. Texas meets those standards, and New Mexico’s current reciprocity list includes Texas. Therefore, a valid Texas License to Carry (LTC/CHL) held by a Texas resident is honored in New Mexico, provided the holder follows all New Mexico carry laws and location restrictions.

Croatia has participated in several FIFA World Cups and achieved notable finishes (2nd place in 2018 and 3rd place in 1998 and 2022), but it has never won the tournament. Only a limited set of nations such as Brazil, Germany, Italy, France, Argentina, Uruguay, Spain and England have lifted the trophy.

The story 'A Little Princess' (and adaptations titled 'The Little Princess') originates from Frances Hodgson Burnett’s 1905 children’s novel. The novel was a work of fiction and not drawn from real-life events or specific historical figures, so film or television versions derived from it are likewise fictional.
Batting average = Hits / At-bats. Since a walk (base on balls) is not scored as an at-bat, walks are excluded from the batting-average calculation.

A bacterial species is typically described by a characteristic shape (e.g., rods, cocci, spirals), but individual cells can vary because of growth phase, nutrient or stress conditions, mutations, and phenomena such as pleomorphism. Therefore, not every cell in a species is guaranteed to have exactly the same morphology.

The U.S. Visa Waiver Program (VWP) currently includes 40 countries. While Croatia joined in 2021, Romania (along with Bulgaria and Cyprus) has not yet met all required criteria and is therefore not part of the VWP at this time.

Michael Mann’s 1995 film “Heat” originated from his own screenplay, which he had previously used (in shorter form) for the 1989 TV movie “L.A. Takedown.” It was inspired by real-life detective–criminal encounters, not adapted from a published novel or non-fiction book.

The NBA operates with a ‘soft’ salary cap—teams can exceed it through numerous exceptions (e.g., Bird rights, mid-level exception). A true hard cap would prohibit any spending above the set ceiling under all circumstances. Although certain transactions (such as using the non-taxpayer mid-level exception or acquiring a player via sign-and-trade) can trigger a separate hard-cap limit at the tax-apron level, the salary cap itself is not hard by default.

The 1964 film adaptation of the stage musical “My Fair Lady” remains the definitive screen version. While several studios have announced plans over the years (e.g., Columbia Pictures in the 2010s) to produce a new film adaptation, none of those projects has actually been completed or released. Therefore, as of now, no finished, released remake of “My Fair Lady” exists.

Despite the word “bleu,” the dish’s name refers to the French term for “blue ribbon,” not to blue cheese. Traditional chicken cordon bleu is a chicken breast rolled or stuffed with ham and Swiss‐type cheese (e.g., Gruyère or Emmental), then breaded and cooked. Blue cheese is not used.

A legislator is anyone who serves in a law-making body (e.g., congressperson, assembly member, senator). A senator is a specific kind of legislator who serves in a senate. Therefore, while every senator is a legislator, not every legislator is a senator, so the two terms are not identical.

The Mediterranean Sea is connected to the Black Sea via the Turkish Straits system: a vessel can sail from the Aegean Sea through the Dardanelles into the Sea of Marmara, then through the Bosporus into the Black Sea. Therefore travel between the two seas is possible.

In standard Chicken Foot (Chickenfoot) domino rules, a player’s final tile may NOT be a double. If your last remaining tile is a double you must also be able to immediately play an additional tile on some open end in the same turn; otherwise you must draw and keep playing. This prevents the round from ending with an unresolved double that would block further play. Therefore, you cannot legally go out on a double alone.

Both crewed submersibles (e.g., Trieste in 1960, James Cameron’s Deepsea Challenger in 2012, and subsequent expeditions) and remotely operated/automated vehicles with cameras have reached Challenger Deep, the deepest point of the Mariana Trench, and recorded visual observations. Therefore humans have indeed seen (directly and via cameras) the Trench’s bottom.

JPMorgan Chase & Co. is the parent financial holding company.  “Chase Bank” (formally JPMorgan Chase Bank, N.A.) is the consumer- and commercial-banking subsidiary/brand of that parent. Therefore they are closely related but not technically the same entity; Chase Bank is just one part of JPMorgan Chase.

Peter Gabriel was a founding member of Genesis (1967) and remained the lead singer until he left in 1975. Phil Collins joined Genesis as the drummer (and backing vocalist) in 1970, five years before Gabriel’s departure. Therefore, from 1970–1975 both Collins and Gabriel were concurrently in the band.

The “roar of the sea” heard when you hold a seashell (or even an empty cup) to your ear is not sound coming from the distant ocean. The curved cavity of the shell acts like a resonant chamber that amplifies and filters ambient background noise—airflow around your ear, blood moving in your head, and any environmental sounds—so it resembles a whooshing surf-like sound. If you go to a perfectly quiet, anechoic room, the sound disappears, demonstrating it does not originate from the real ocean.

In the Blue Jay species (Cyanocitta cristata), both sexes share the same blue, white, and black plumage pattern. Any sexual dimorphism is minimal—males average only slightly larger than females—so to the human eye they look virtually identical.
In U.S. dry measure, one bushel equals four pecks. Therefore, a peck is only one-quarter of a bushel, so the two units are not the same.

If the question is referring to the FIFA World Cup tournaments, the United States (“America”) does field national teams. The U.S. Men’s National Team qualified for and played in the most recent 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar, and the U.S. Women’s National Team is a regular participant in the FIFA Women’s World Cup (including the 2023 edition). Therefore, America does have a team in World Cup competition.

In U.S. meat-cutting terminology, the section of ribs that comes from the upper (dorsal) part of the pig, next to the loin, is officially called “loin back ribs” or simply “back ribs.” In retail and restaurant marketing these very same ribs are often labeled “baby back ribs,” the word “baby” just indicating that the bones are shorter and curved compared with spare ribs, not that they come from a younger animal. Therefore, ‘pork back ribs,’ ‘loin back ribs,’ and ‘baby back ribs’ all refer to the same cut.

The Bill of Rights consists of the first ten amendments to the U.S. Constitution. The First Amendment—protecting freedoms of speech, press, religion, assembly, and petition—is literally the opening amendment within that set. Therefore, it is unequivocally part of the Bill of Rights.

In modern rugby league the scrum is intended to be largely uncontested and stable. Laws prohibit either pack from pushing more than a minimal distance; the ball is fed and won without a shove. Therefore deliberate pushing to gain an advantage is not permitted.
Cedar Cove aired on the Hallmark Channel from 2013–2015 and was cancelled after its third season. No fourth season was produced or aired.

Every U.S. state has compulsory‐education laws that require children—usually starting between ages 5-7 and continuing until 16-18—to be educated. Families can choose public school, private school, or approved home schooling, but some form of schooling is legally mandatory.

Boost Mobile and Virgin Mobile were both prepaid wireless brands once owned by Sprint in the United States, but they have always operated as separate, distinct brands with their own plans, pricing, and marketing. Internationally, Boost Mobile (Australia, for example) is owned by a different entity and has no connection to Virgin Mobile. Therefore, they are not the same company or service, even though they have at times shared a corporate parent.

Under NBA, FIBA, and NCAA rules, goaltending after a backboard touch is only called if the ball has already contacted the backboard and is completely above the rim on a try for goal. If the ball strikes the backboard below rim level, a defender may still legally block or touch it (provided it is not on its downward flight and other basket-interference conditions are not met). Therefore, merely hitting the backboard below the rim does not constitute goaltending.
Berlin Station, the Epix espionage drama, released three seasons in total. After Season 1 in 2016 and Season 2 in 2017, a third season premiered on December 2, 2018. Therefore, a 3rd season exists.
Copa Airlines joined Star Alliance in 2012 and remains an active member, offering reciprocal benefits with the other Star Alliance carriers.
The ABC Family sitcom "Melissa & Joey" was produced and broadcast for four seasons (2010–2015). The network cancelled the show after its fourth season, and no fifth season was ever produced or aired.

Since 1974 the original FIFA World Cup Trophy stays in FIFA’s possession; the winning team is awarded it on the pitch but must return it before the next tournament and receives a gold-plated replica to keep. Only the old Jules Rimet Cup could be kept permanently (e.g., by Brazil after 1970). Therefore, modern champions do not keep the real trophy.

Honey-bee stingers are barbed and lodge in the skin, staying attached to a venom sac that continues to pump venom. They do not drop out quickly or cleanly by themselves; instead they usually remain embedded until they are manually scraped or pulled out.

Since the 2016-17 season, the Ivy League has held a men’s and women’s postseason conference tournament (often called “Ivy Madness”) among the top four regular-season teams to award the league’s automatic NCAA bid. Before 2017 the Ivy League did not stage such a tournament, but it does now.

C# is the programming language itself—its syntax, semantics, and compiler specification. “Visual C#” is Microsoft’s branding for the C# development tools and IDE support that ship with Visual Studio. When you write code in “Visual C#” you are still writing standard C#, but the term refers to the Visual Studio environment rather than to a different language. Therefore they are not literally the same thing, even though they involve the same underlying language.

In the United States Constitution, the vice president is designated as the President of the Senate, serving as its presiding officer and casting tie-breaking votes. Although day-to-day proceedings are usually handled by a president pro tempore or other senators, the vice president is formally the head of the Senate.

A tax-free savings account (e.g., Canada’s TFSA) is a registered account that can hold various investments such as stocks, bonds, mutual funds or cash. The account itself is a legal wrapper that provides tax advantages; the underlying holdings are the actual investments. Therefore, the TFSA is not, in and of itself, an investment.

Julian Barnes’s novel (and the later television adaptation) “Arthur & George” recounts the real‐life 1903–1907 case of George Edalji, a Midlands solicitor wrongly convicted of animal mutilation, and Sir Arthur Conan Doyle’s subsequent campaign to clear his name. The characters, events and legal case are historical, though dramatized in the retelling, so the work is indeed based on a true story.

In World War II, the Allied Powers (also called the Allies) were the coalition that opposed the Axis Powers. Core members included the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Soviet Union, along with many other nations. The USSR played a central military role against Nazi Germany after being invaded in 1941, so it is universally recognized as one of the principal Allied Powers.

In Orson Scott Card’s Ender universe, the novel “Ender’s Game” was followed by several direct sequels, beginning with “Speaker for the Dead.” Therefore, at least one sequel to the original book definitely exists.

“The Seven Ages of Man” is the popular name for Jaques’s monologue that begins “All the world’s a stage” in Shakespeare’s play ‘As You Like It’. It is a 28-line speech written in blank verse, not a 14-line poem with a fixed rhyme scheme. Therefore it is not a sonnet.

Brigham Young University is owned by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and most students are LDS, but the school does admit non-LDS students. Applicants of any (or no) faith may be admitted as long as they agree to follow BYU’s Honor Code; non-LDS students pay higher tuition but are otherwise eligible.

The term “cold fire” sounds contradictory, but chemists do recognise ‘cool’ or ‘cold’ flames: weak, pale, sometimes invisible flames that occur in certain low-temperature oxidation reactions (e.g., some hydrocarbon–air mixtures). Their temperatures (≈150 – 400 °C) are far below ordinary flames (≈1 000 + °C), and they can sometimes be touched briefly without burning skin. Thus, while not literally at room temperature, a genuine, much-cooler form of flame does exist, so the concept is real in a scientific sense.

Both O-ring and X-ring chains use elastomer seals to keep lubricant in and dirt out. An X-ring has a more complex cross-section that creates two sealing lips instead of one, so it generally retains grease better and, because the seal contacts the side plates over a smaller area, it produces slightly less friction. Tests by several manufacturers and user experience show X-ring chains lasting longer and running more efficiently than comparable O-ring chains, albeit at a somewhat higher cost. Therefore, if the criterion is durability and efficiency, an X-ring chain is usually considered the better option.
Both “cougar” and “mountain lion” are common names for the same species, Puma concolor. They are simply regional synonyms, so asking whether they are the same refers to the same animal.

In the 1990 film “Mo’ Better Blues,” Denzel Washington portrays jazz trumpeter Bleek Gilliam. Washington took lessons so his fingering and embouchure would look convincing on-screen, but the actual trumpet music heard in the movie was performed and dubbed by jazz trumpeter Terence Blanchard. Therefore, Washington did not truly play the trumpet parts used in the film’s soundtrack.

The United States already operates higher-speed rail (e.g., Amtrak’s Acela topping out around 150 mph), and multiple true high-speed rail projects—California High-Speed Rail (planned 220 mph), Brightline West (Las Vegas–Southern CA, 186 mph), and the Texas High-Speed Rail (Houston–Dallas, 200+ mph)—are in various stages of construction, permitting, or financing. While political, legal, and funding challenges could delay or cancel individual projects, it is unlikely that every effort over the coming decades will fail. Given ongoing construction in California and Nevada, the probability that at least one line meeting international high-speed standards (≈ 186 mph or higher) eventually opens is better than even.

Popcorn kernels do grow on an ear (a cob), but they come from a special variety of maize called popcorn, not from the sweet-corn variety commonly eaten as ‘corn on the cob.’ Therefore, if the question is asking whether the familiar sweet corn on the cob can be used to make popcorn, the correct response is no.

The U.S. Constitution does not specify how many justices must sit on the Supreme Court. Congress sets the number by statute and has changed it several times in history (ranging from 5 to 10). It has remained at nine since 1869, but that figure is not permanently fixed and could be altered by legislation.

answer: Yes, provided the cold-water bath is sufficiently cold (≈10–15 °C); colder ice baths do not add meaningful extra benefit.
Reasoning: The physiological effect that athletes seek from an ice bath is simply to lower tissue temperature enough to reduce inflammation, pain-signalling and perceived soreness. Research shows that water in the 10–15 °C (50–59 °F) range produces virtually the same reductions in muscle-skin temperature and post-exercise soreness as water near the freezing point with floating ice. Dropping the temperature lower with bags of ice mainly increases discomfort and the risk of cold injury, without demonstrating extra recovery benefits in controlled studies. Therefore, if the ‘cold-water bath’ is cool enough (≈10–15 °C) and the immersion time is similar (10–15 min), it is essentially as effective as an “ice bath.” If the water is only tap-cold in a warm climate (e.g., >18 °C), the effect will be smaller.
Answer: Yes, provided the cold-water bath is sufficiently cold (≈10–15 °C); colder ice baths do not add meaningful extra benefit.

Reasoning: Rice noodles are made primarily from rice flour (and sometimes tapioca or corn starch for texture). Glass noodles—also called cellophane or bean-thread noodles—are typically made from mung-bean starch, sweet-potato starch, or other starches that turn translucent when cooked. Because they differ in main ingredients, appearance, and cooking properties, they are not the same product.

In cooking and household contexts, “bicarb soda,” “bicarbonate of soda,” and “baking soda” are all common names for the same chemical compound: sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO₃). Different English-speaking regions favor different terms (e.g., ‘bicarb’ in Australia/UK, ‘baking soda’ in the US), but the substance is identical.

France and England’s senior men’s national football teams have faced each other in the FIFA World Cup on multiple occasions: group stage matches in 1966 and 1982, and a quarter-final in 2022. Therefore, they have indeed met in the World Cup.

“Dying Light: The Following – Enhanced Edition” is marketed as a complete bundle that repackages the base game of Dying Light together with the large ‘The Following’ expansion and all previously released DLC/updates. Therefore, purchasing the Enhanced Edition automatically provides you with the original game content.
Texas has an area of about 695,000 km² (268,600 sq mi), whereas Germany’s area is about 357,000 km² (138,000 sq mi). Therefore, Texas covers a larger land area than Germany.

Yes. The United Nations intervened in the first Indo-Pakistani war over Kashmir (1947-48), passing Security Council resolutions, arranging a cease-fire, and establishing the UN Military Observer Group in India and Pakistan (UNMOGIP) in 1949. This is a clear example of UN involvement in a conflict that included Pakistan.

When you request cash back while making a debit‐card purchase at most large retailers or grocery stores, the store typically does not impose a separate fee; it is simply added to the purchase total. (Using a credit card for cash back is treated as a cash advance and would incur fees, but that is not what ‘cash back’ at checkout generally refers to.) Therefore, in the common debit‐card checkout context, getting cash back does not cost extra money.

The term “Tommy gun” is a nickname for the Thompson, a weapon that fires pistol-caliber (.45 ACP) cartridges on full-automatic from a compact platform—features that define a submachine gun. It has been described in both historical and modern references explicitly as the Thompson submachine gun.

The George Washington Bridge charges drivers only when traveling eastbound from New Jersey into Manhattan; westbound travel into New Jersey is toll-free. Therefore, the toll is collected in one direction only, making it a one-way toll.

The How to Train Your Dragon film series consists of three main installments. The third movie, titled "How to Train Your Dragon: The Hidden World," was produced by DreamWorks Animation and released in early 2019 in many territories. Therefore, a third film does in fact exist.

Primary plant cell walls are composed mainly of cellulose microfibrils embedded in a matrix of hemicellulose and pectins. They contain numerous microscopic pores that make the wall highly porous to water and small solutes. Thus, water can move freely through the cell wall (apoplast) and the wall does not act as a barrier to water entry; regulation of water movement occurs mainly at the plasma membrane, not the wall.

Skyline Drive is a scenic road that runs the length of Shenandoah National Park in Virginia. At its southern end (Rockfish Gap) it connects directly to the northern terminus of the Blue Ridge Parkway, but the Parkway itself is a separate National Park Service unit that continues south through Virginia and North Carolina. Because they are distinct roads managed under different park units, Skyline Drive is not considered part of the Blue Ridge Parkway, even though they link together.

answer: Yes, provided you are a citizen of a Commonwealth realm; otherwise, no.
Reasoning: The style “Sir” is attached to a substantive knighthood granted by the British monarch. To use it, the recipient must be a citizen of the United Kingdom or of another Commonwealth realm that recognises the monarch as head of state (e.g., Australia, Canada, New Zealand, Jamaica, etc.). Citizens of those countries are therefore eligible to be called “Sir,” even though they are not British in the narrow sense of being UK nationals. People from countries outside the Commonwealth realms (e.g., the United States, France, Japan) can receive only an honorary knighthood and may not prefix their name with “Sir.”
Answer: Yes, provided you are a citizen of a Commonwealth realm; otherwise, no.

Reasoning: Allergies are immune responses to foreign substances. Pure H2O is essential to life and is already inside our bodies, so the immune system normally cannot treat it as a foreign antigen. There is a very rare condition called aquagenic urticaria in which contact with water triggers hives, but research suggests it is not a true immunoglobulin-E–mediated allergy to water itself; rather, it is likely a reaction to substances dissolved in the water or to a by-product created on the skin. Therefore, in the strict sense of an allergy to water, the answer is no.

The American Civil War effectively ended with Lee’s surrender in April 1865. The 13th Amendment, although passed by Congress in January 1865, was not ratified and added to the Constitution until December 6, 1865—several months after the war’s end. Therefore, in terms of becoming law, the amendment came after the Civil War.

"Under honorable conditions" is the formal wording for a General discharge (General Discharge Under Honorable Conditions). An "Honorable discharge" is a separate, higher characterization. Both are better than "Other Than Honorable," Bad-Conduct, or Dishonorable discharges, but they are not the same: an Honorable discharge confers the fullest benefits and indicates the highest standard of service, whereas a General discharge indicates satisfactory but not exemplary service.

Memorial Day is a federal holiday in the United States. The U.S. Postal Service observes all federal holidays, which means post office retail counters are closed and regular mail is not delivered (aside from limited Priority Mail Express). Therefore, the post office does not ‘run’ in the usual sense on Memorial Day.

The Jeep Commander was specifically designed to be Jeep’s seven-passenger SUV and was marketed with standard or available third-row seating. This third row is one of the model’s key distinguishing features compared with the two-row Grand Cherokee on which it is based.

Under Article II, Section 4 of the U.S. Constitution, all federal civil officers — which includes Supreme Court justices — may be removed from office through impeachment by the House of Representatives and conviction in the Senate. Historical precedent exists: Justice Samuel Chase was impeached by the House in 1804, although the Senate did not convict him. Therefore, a Supreme Court justice is subject to the impeachment process.

NOW (formerly NOW TV) gets most DreamWorks/Universal titles through its Sky Cinema library, and the How to Train Your Dragon films frequently appear there. At present listings, the original film is included in the Sky Cinema catalogue on NOW, so it should be streamable with a Cinema membership. Because availability changes often, this could have rotated out, so certainty is limited.

The informal “½-ton” label is normally applied to full-size 1500-series pickups such as the Ram 1500, Ford F-150, and Chevrolet 1500. The Dodge Dakota, meanwhile, is marketed and engineered as a mid-size pickup (smaller than those full-size models). Although its actual payload capacity can exceed 1,000 lb, it is not classified or commonly referred to as a half-ton truck.

California law prohibits carrying a loaded firearm openly in public and also bans most forms of unloaded open-carry. Concealed carry is only lawful if the person has been issued a valid Concealed Carry Weapon (CCW) permit by the local sheriff or police chief. Therefore, an average person cannot simply carry a gun on their person in California without meeting specific exemptions (e.g., law enforcement, CCW permit). In the general sense, the answer to whether you can carry a gun on you in California is no, unless you possess the required permit or fall under a legal exemption.

In chroma-key compositing, any uniformly lit background color that contrasts strongly with the subjects can be used. Green is most common because digital cameras are sensitive to it and it differs from most skin tones, but blue, red, magenta, or even bright yellow backdrops can work if wardrobe and lighting are controlled. Therefore the statement that other colors can be used instead of green is correct.

By definition, a rhombus is a quadrilateral with all four sides congruent and opposite sides parallel. Since opposite sides are parallel, there are two distinct pairs of parallel sides in every rhombus.

While most of the world’s prominent and accessible summits have been reached, there are still numerous unclimbed peaks—especially smaller, remote, or legally restricted mountains in the Himalaya, Bhutan, Tibet, and parts of Antarctica. The highest unclimbed mountain, Gangkhar Puensum in Bhutan, remains off-limits for religious reasons. Therefore, it is not correct that every mountain has been climbed.

FIFA rules require that a player hold the nationality of the country they wish to represent, but it does not have to be the one in which they were born or grew up. Players can represent a country through parents, grandparents, or naturalization, provided they meet eligibility criteria and have not played a competitive senior match for another nation. Therefore, they do not necessarily have to play for their birth-country or ‘home’ country.

Breaking Bad formally concluded with its fifth season in 2013. Creator Vince Gilligan and AMC have repeatedly confirmed the series is finished; subsequent content has come only in the form of the sequel film “El Camino” and the spinoff series “Better Call Saul,” not a sixth season. There have been no credible announcements or plans for a season six.

DreamWorks Animation officially announced Kung Fu Panda 4, which is scheduled for theatrical release on March 8 2024 (date already locked on studio slate and publicized in press releases). Therefore, a new Kung Fu Panda movie is indeed on the way.

Traffic codes in virtually every U.S. state (and in most countries) explicitly require drivers to yield the right-of-way—usually by pulling to the right and stopping—when an emergency vehicle approaches with activated lights and siren. Failure to do so can result in citations or more serious penalties. Therefore, it is indeed a legal requirement, not merely a courtesy.

Hundreds of distinct sign languages are used worldwide (e.g., British Sign Language, French Sign Language, Japanese Sign Language). American Sign Language is just one of many and is not mutually intelligible with most others.

Even on a single-core CPU, multiple threads can improve program structure and responsiveness. While they cannot run in parallel, the operating system can quickly switch between threads, allowing a program to keep its UI responsive while waiting for I/O, hide latency by overlapping computation with blocking operations, and simplify design through concurrent abstractions.

By definition a nation-state is a sovereign political entity; sovereignty implies the existence of a central authority that claims and exercises governing power over the territory. While some states may have weak or failed administrations at times, the concept of a nation-state includes having (at least in principle) a national government.

By definition, evergreen trees retain their foliage year-round. While individual needles or leaves are replaced periodically, evergreens do not shed all of their leaves at once during winter the way deciduous trees do.

In microbiology a single medium can contain components that inhibit the growth of some groups of organisms (making it selective) while also containing indicators that allow visible distinctions among the organisms that do grow (making it differential). Classic examples include MacConkey agar, EMB agar, and Mannitol Salt agar, which simultaneously select for certain bacteria and differentiate them based on biochemical properties.
New York City is comprised of five administrative divisions: Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, The Bronx, and Staten Island. Therefore, saying that New York City includes the 5 boroughs is correct.

A rational number can be expressed as the ratio of two integers with a non-zero denominator. A classical proof by contradiction (similar to the one for √2) shows that if √3 were rational, 3 would have to divide both numerator and denominator in lowest terms, which is impossible. Therefore, √3 cannot be expressed as a ratio of integers; it is irrational.

The Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) was passed by the U.S. Congress and signed into law by the President in 1993, and it applies nationwide. Therefore, it is a federal statute rather than a state or local measure.

In common culinary terminology, “spare ribs” refers to pork ribs taken from the lower portion of a pig’s rib cage, while “beef short ribs” come from the lower portion of a cow’s rib cage (either the chuck or plate). They are from different animals and are cut differently, so they are not the same.

A hiatal hernia generally causes gastro-oesophageal reflux and chest discomfort, but a sufficiently large hernia can protrude into the thoracic cavity, press on the left atrium, or irritate the vagus nerve. These mechanical or autonomic effects have been documented to trigger palpitations and atrial arrhythmias in some patients, although this is uncommon compared with typical GI symptoms.
Ricardo Kaká was selected for Brazil’s squad at the 2002 FIFA World Cup and appeared as a late substitute in the group-stage match against Costa Rica, meaning he officially played in the tournament.

After ball four, the ball remains live; the batter becomes a runner and may attempt to advance beyond first, and other runners may advance as well. Therefore, a walk does not create a dead-ball situation.

Designated Survivor premiered on ABC in 2016. The network ordered and aired a second season consisting of 22 episodes from September 2017 to May 2018. Therefore, a Season 2 definitely exists (and there is even a Season 3 that was later produced by Netflix).

In every men’s and women’s FIFA World Cup to date, the host nation has automatically qualified for the final tournament without taking part in the regional qualifying process. This is an established rule in the tournament regulations.

Both the 2018 and 2019 bouts between KSI and Logan Paul were distributed on a pay-per-view basis (YouTube PPV for the first fight; DAZN subscription/PPV and Sky Box Office PPV for the rematch). Therefore, viewers had to pay specifically to watch the events live.

LensCrafters and Pearle Vision operate as separate retail chains with their own branding, store networks, and management structures. However, both brands are subsidiaries of the same parent corporation (Luxottica, now part of EssilorLuxottica). Therefore, they are not the same company, even though they share common ownership.
Just Cause 3 was only released for PlayStation 4, Xbox One, and Windows PC. No Xbox 360 version was ever produced or made backward-compatible, so it cannot be played on an Xbox 360.

Since 2014 several teams around the world (e.g., Sweden, United States, Brazil) have performed successful uterus transplants from both living and deceased donors, with multiple babies born from transplanted uteri. Although still considered experimental and available only in limited clinical trials, the procedure has been proven technically feasible and can result in live births.

In the FIFA World Cup (football/soccer), knockout-round matches that remain tied after 90 minutes of regular time and 30 minutes of extra time are decided by a penalty shoot-out. Group-stage matches can end in a draw without a shoot-out, but a shoot-out procedure is definitely part of the tournament regulations for the elimination rounds.

The Xbox One is not universally backward-compatible with every Xbox 360 game. Microsoft selectively enables compatibility for specific titles; if a 360 game has not been added to the approved list, its disc will not run on an Xbox One. Therefore, only supported discs work, not all.
The CW officially renewed the TV series “The 100” for a fifth season back in March 2017, and that season was produced and aired in 2018. Therefore, a Season 5 does (and did) exist.

Red-eared sliders are freshwater turtles adapted to ponds, lakes, and slow-moving rivers. Their physiology cannot handle full-strength seawater for extended periods; high salinity disrupts their osmoregulation, leading to dehydration and organ stress. Although they may survive brief exposure to brackish or marine environments, they cannot establish or thrive long-term in the ocean.

The first mass-produced modern drinking straws, patented by Marvin Stone in the late 19th century, were rolled from paper and coated with paraffin. Paper straws remained common until plastic varieties became dominant in the mid-20th century, so historically straws indeed used to be made of paper.

The human body possesses an endocannabinoid system, which includes endogenous ligands (e.g., anandamide), receptors (CB1, CB2), and enzymes responsible for synthesis and degradation. This system plays roles in pain modulation, appetite, mood, immune function, and other physiological processes.

Kansas reinstated capital punishment in 1994 and still maintains statutes providing for the death penalty. Although no executions have been carried out since 1965, the death penalty remains legally in force and inmates are on death row.

The syndicated morning talk-show ‘Live with Kelly and Ryan’ ended its run when Ryan Seacrest departed in April 2023. The program continues under the new title ‘Live with Kelly and Mark,’ but the version branded ‘Kelly and Ryan’ is no longer broadcast.

The first season of Star Trek: Discovery aired in 2017. CBS All Access (now Paramount+) officially renewed the series, and the second season premiered in January 2019. Therefore, the show did receive a second season.

The Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) was adopted by a vote of the UN General Assembly in 1948; there was no formal ‘signing’ process. Member states either voted in favor, against, abstained, or were absent. Saudi Arabia was one of eight countries that abstained from the vote and therefore did not endorse the declaration. Consequently, it has not ‘signed’ or formally adopted the UDHR.

Stephen “tWitch” Boss was the resident DJ and later a co-executive producer on The Ellen DeGeneres Show, but the show ended its final season in May 2022 and tWitch is therefore no longer appearing on it (he also passed away in December 2022).

NBC aired only one season of “A.D. The Bible Continues” in 2015 and announced later that year it would not be ordering a second season. Although the producers expressed interest in continuing the story elsewhere, no network or streaming service has commissioned another season, and no production is underway. Therefore, barring new, currently unannounced developments, another season is not expected.

Bar soap, dish soap, or liquid hand soap are not intended for ingestion or prolonged contact with the delicate mucous membranes inside the mouth. Even ‘non-toxic’ soaps contain surfactants that can cause irritation, vomiting, diarrhea, or, if aspirated, chemical pneumonitis. Swallowing larger amounts can lead to more serious poisoning. Pediatricians and poison-control centers advise against this practice; safer, evidence-based disciplinary methods should be used instead.

The question refers to the 2004 film “Crash.” In the key scene the Persian shop-owner fires his gun at the locksmith, hitting the locksmith’s young daughter instead. However, the gun is loaded with blanks, so the bullet causes no injury. The girl is shocked but completely unharmed. Therefore, she does not die.

Unlike patents or copyrights, trade secrets are not protected for a fixed statutory term. Protection lasts for as long as the information remains secret, provides economic value from that secrecy, and the owner exercises reasonable efforts to maintain its confidentiality. Once the secret becomes public or those conditions are not met, protection ends. Therefore, there is no predetermined time limit.

In common chemical nomenclature, ‘boric acid’ usually refers specifically to the compound H₃BO₃, whose systematic (IUPAC-preferred) name is orthoboric acid. Other boron oxy-acids such as metaboric (HBO₂) and tetraboric (H₂B₄O₇) acids exist, but when no prefix is given, chemists mean orthoboric acid. Thus, the two names denote the same substance.

Both are religious talks, but a homily is a specific kind of sermon—usually a brief scriptural reflection delivered within a liturgical service (e.g., Catholic Mass). A sermon can be longer, delivered in or outside a service, and need not follow the set lectionary readings. Thus the terms overlap but are not strictly identical.

The blue whale (Balaenoptera musculus) is larger, in terms of both length and mass, than any other known animal, living or extinct, including the largest dinosaurs documented by paleontology. No credible evidence exists of a larger species.

The original and current World Trade Center complexes are located in Lower Manhattan on and around Greenwich Street. This area is considered part of Manhattan’s Financial District, adjacent to Wall Street and other financial institutions. Therefore, the World Trade Center is indeed situated within the Financial District.

Nigeria has participated in several FIFA World Cup tournaments (first appearance in 1994) but has never progressed beyond the Round of 16, let alone won the tournament. Historical records list only eight countries (Brazil, Germany, Italy, Argentina, France, Uruguay, Spain, and England) as World Cup winners, and Nigeria is not among them.

Edinburgh Castle sits on Castle Rock, which is the eroded volcanic plug of an extinct volcano that last erupted over 300 million years ago. Therefore, the castle is indeed built on the remains of a volcano.

Sacred Games Season 1 ended with 8 episodes. Although Netflix later released a separate Season 2 (also 8 episodes), the original first-season run did not and will not receive a ninth episode, and Netflix has not announced any further seasons or episodes since. Therefore, in the sense of a direct “episode 9,” none is planned.

In the 1997 film "Life Is Beautiful," the young boy, Giosuè, survives the concentration camp. His father, Guido, is killed, but the boy lives to be reunited with his mother at the end, riding on an American tank. Therefore, the little boy does not die.

In Disney’s 2017 live-action Beauty and the Beast, Dan Stevens (who plays the Beast) performs his own vocals, most notably on the new song “Evermore” as well as parts of “Something There” and “Days in the Sun.” Therefore, he does sing in the film.

answer: No, a stamp is not needed when posting to a Freepost address from within the same country.
Reasoning: In the UK a “Freepost” address is a licensed service where the organisation named on the envelope pays the postage. When posting from within the UK you simply write the Freepost address (or use the pre-printed envelope) and put it in a post box; you do not add a stamp. A stamp would only be required if you were mailing from outside the UK or wanted to pay for an upgraded service yourself.
Answer: No, a stamp is not needed when posting to a Freepost address from within the same country.

Reasoning: A hydrometer is an instrument that measures the relative density (specific gravity) of liquids. A lactometer, which is simply a hydrometer calibrated for the typical density range of milk, is routinely used in dairy practice. Therefore, a hydrometer (especially a lactometer type) can indeed be used to measure the density of milk.

The 2017 film “Molly’s Game,” written and directed by Aaron Sorkin, adapts the 2014 memoir also titled “Molly’s Game,” written by Molly Bloom about her real-life experiences running high-stakes poker games. Because the movie is drawn directly from this published memoir, it is indeed based on a book.

The rock band ZZ Top made a cameo appearance in the 1990 film ‘Back to the Future Part III’; they portray the 1885 Hill Valley festival band and perform an acoustic version of their song “Doubleback.” Therefore, they did play in the movie.

The phrase references the song "She's Like the Wind," which was co-written and sung by Patrick Swayze and appears on the soundtrack of the 1987 film Dirty Dancing. Therefore, yes—the song is indeed associated with (and featured in) Dirty Dancing.

New Hampshire is unique among U.S. states: it does not require adults to wear seat belts. Only occupants under 18 are mandated to buckle up. Therefore, in the sense of a universal seat-belt requirement for all drivers and adult passengers, New Hampshire has no such law.

Google Drive is not unlimited. Personal (free) Google accounts include 15 GB of shared storage across Drive, Gmail, and Photos. Additional capacity can be purchased through Google One subscriptions, and Workspace (business/education) tiers each have specified per-user limits. Therefore a storage limit definitely exists.
Greece participated in the UEFA qualification play-offs for the 2018 FIFA World Cup but lost to Croatia (4-1 on aggregate). Therefore, they did not reach the final tournament.

The title of largest grocery retailer in the world—measured by total sales—belongs to Walmart. Although the privately-held Aldi group (Aldi Süd and Aldi Nord combined) is one of the world’s biggest discount grocery chains with thousands of stores, its global grocery revenue is well below that of Walmart and also below a few other multinational retailers such as Costco and Carrefour. Therefore Aldi is not the largest grocer in the world.

In cell biology, the term “plasma membrane” refers to the thin, selectively-permeable lipid bilayer that encloses the cytoplasm of every living cell. The phrase “cell membrane” is an informal synonym that biologists use interchangeably with “plasma membrane.” Although plant, fungal and bacterial cells possess an additional outer structure called the cell wall, the membrane directly surrounding the cytoplasm is still the plasma (cell) membrane. Therefore, in standard usage the two terms denote the same structure.

The Kentucky Derby is traditionally scheduled for the first Saturday in May, a practice followed almost every year since 1931. However, there have been exceptions—most notably in 1945 (moved to June because of WWII) and in 2020 (moved to September due to COVID-19). Because these exceptions exist, it is not accurate to say the Derby is *always* held on the first weekend in May.

The Caribbean island of Saint Martin is geographically one landmass, but it is split into two separate political entities: the northern French Collectivity of Saint-Martin and the southern Dutch constituent country of Sint Maarten. Because the question asks whether 'St Maarten and St Martin' are the same, the correct interpretation is political/administrative identity, not merely geographic location. Politically they are different, so they are not the same.

The famed Mughal Peacock Throne was carried off to Persia by Nader Shah in 1739, and after his assassination pieces were likely dismantled, melted down, or dispersed. No verified, intact throne survives today, and historians agree its present whereabouts (if any part still exists) are unknown.
Wayne Gretzky played for the Edmonton Oilers and was a member of their Stanley Cup–winning teams in 1984, 1985, 1987, and 1988. Therefore, he did win the Stanley Cup (in fact, four times).
The CW officially renewed Crazy Ex-Girlfriend for a fourth and final season in April 2018, and the season subsequently aired beginning in October 2018.

While the $100 bill is currently the highest-denomination note in regular circulation in the United States, the U.S. Treasury has issued larger-denomination notes in the past, including $500, $1,000, $5,000, $10,000 and even a $100,000 gold certificate (used only between banks). Therefore, bills higher than $100 do exist historically, even if they are no longer printed for public use.

The Space Race was a competition in space exploration primarily between the United States and the Soviet Union during roughly 1957-1975. It was motivated by geopolitical rivalry, technological prestige, and military implications characteristic of the broader Cold War struggle between the two superpowers.

In elementary number theory, a perfect square is defined as an integer that is the square of another integer. Because squaring any integer (or any real number) always yields a non-negative result, no negative integer can equal n² for any integer n. Hence a negative number cannot be a perfect square in the usual sense.
Panama’s men’s national team qualified for the FIFA World Cup for the first time in 2018 (Russia). Therefore Panama has indeed appeared in a World Cup before.

In the Gregorian calendar (and the older Julian calendar), the year sequence goes directly from 1 BC (also written 1 BCE) to AD 1 (CE 1) with no intervening year 0. The concept of a year 0 is used in astronomical year numbering and some computational systems, but it is not part of the civil Gregorian calendar.

Guitar Center acquired Musician’s Friend in 1999, and today Musician’s Friend operates as an online/catalog division wholly owned by Guitar Center Holdings. Although the two brands keep separate storefronts and marketing, they are part of the same corporate entity, sharing inventory systems, warehouses, and ownership.
Several wasp species have a metallic-blue or steel-blue body coloration, e.g., the Blue Mud Dauber (Chalybion californicum) and other Chalybion species. Therefore, blue-colored wasps do exist.

In cattle, lactation is triggered by the hormonal changes that occur during late pregnancy and calving. A cow will not naturally begin to secrete milk unless she has gone through pregnancy (or is given an artificial hormone regimen that mimics those changes, which is rare in commercial practice). Once lactation has been initiated by giving birth, the cow can keep producing milk for many months as long as she is milked regularly, even though she is no longer pregnant at that moment. Thus, pregnancy (and calving) is required to start lactation, although it is not required to remain pregnant while lactating.

The term “veterinary medicine” usually refers to the clinical practice of diagnosing, treating and preventing disease in animals, whereas “veterinary science” is broader and includes all research and scientific study related to animal health, biology and medicine (e.g., pathology, epidemiology, pharmacology). Thus, while veterinary medicine is a part of veterinary science, the two are not strictly the same.

The fourth installment of the Shrek series has already been produced and released. It is titled “Shrek Forever After” (sometimes marketed as “Shrek: The Final Chapter”) and premiered in 2010. Therefore, a movie commonly referred to as “Shrek 4” already exists; future plans involve a potential “Shrek 5,” not a still-unmade fourth film.
Answer: Yes — it was released in 2010 under the title “Shrek Forever After.”

Reasoning: Avengers: Infinity War was conceived as the first half of a two-part story. The direct continuation of that story was released in 2019 under the title ‘Avengers: Endgame,’ which resolves the events and cliff-hangers set up in Infinity War.

In the film 'Get Him to the Greek', Russell Brand reprises his role as rock star Aldous Snow and performs the character’s songs. The vocals on the soundtrack are sung by Russell Brand himself (often with collaborations such as with Infant Sorrow’s fictional band members and guest artists), rather than being dubbed by another singer.
Based on 2020 U.S. Census population figures, New York City ranks first, Los Angeles second, and Chicago third, making Chicago the third-largest city in the United States by population.

The plot of the 2018 film “Forever My Girl” opens with the funeral of Liam’s best friend, Mason, who has recently been killed in a car accident. Although the accident itself is not shown on-screen, a character’s death is central to the story, so at least one person does die in the movie’s narrative.

The original State of Decay (including the Year-One Survival Edition available on Xbox One) is strictly single-player. Cooperative multiplayer was only added in the later sequel, State of Decay 2. Therefore the statement that State of Decay is co-op on Xbox One is incorrect.

Night of the Living Dead is a 1968 horror film by George A. Romero. Its plot about re-animated corpses (zombies) attacking the living is entirely fictional and not based on real events, so it is not a true story.
The 2015 title ‘Guitar Hero Live’ was officially released on several platforms, including the Xbox One. Therefore, a version of Guitar Hero exists and is playable on Xbox One hardware.

Number 10 Downing Street is the official residence of the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, and the position is commonly said to “live at Number 10.” In practice, some recent prime ministers have chosen to sleep in the larger flat above Number 11, but Number 10 remains their official residence and working home.

Marvel Studios had already announced and produced the direct follow-up, ‘Avengers: Endgame,’ which was released in 2019 as the sequel to 2018’s ‘Avengers: Infinity War.’ Therefore, the answer to whether there will be a sequel is yes.

Carmelo Anthony’s Denver Nuggets reached the 2009 NBA Western Conference Finals, where they lost to the Los Angeles Lakers. That is the only time in his career he has advanced that far in the Western Conference playoffs.

The CW officially renewed the television series ‘The Flash’ for a fourth season in early 2017, and that season subsequently aired during the 2017-2018 broadcast year. Therefore, the question can be answered affirmatively.

The 2000 film “Pay It Forward” was adapted from Catherine Ryan Hyde’s novel of the same name. Both the novel and the screenplay are works of fiction that explore the idea of doing good deeds for others, not a dramatization of real events or specific historical figures.
Croatia reached the final match of the FIFA World Cup in 2018, where they were runners-up to France. This confirms that Croatia has indeed made it to a World Cup final at least once.
Egg drop soup is made by drizzling beaten eggs into boiling or near-boiling broth. The heat cooks the thin streams of egg almost instantly, so the finished soup contains cooked egg, not raw egg.

Lake Erie drains into Lake Ontario via the Niagara River, but Niagara Falls makes the river itself unnavigable. However, the Welland Canal—part of the St. Lawrence Seaway—provides a lock system that bypasses the falls and allows vessels (from pleasure craft to large freighters) to transit between Lake Erie and Lake Ontario. Therefore, boating between the two lakes is indeed possible via this canal.

In U.S. usage, the term “secondary education” or “secondary school” normally covers all schooling after elementary/primary school and before college—typically grades 7-12 (middle/junior high plus high school). “High school,” however, usually refers only to the upper portion, grades 9-12. Thus high school is part of secondary school, but the two terms are not strictly identical.

The International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) and the International Development Association (IDA), which together are commonly referred to as the World Bank, have been granted the status of specialized agencies within the United Nations system through formal agreements. While operationally autonomous, this legal status constitutes an institutional affiliation with the UN.

The Paris Convention for the Protection of Industrial Property is administered by WIPO and open only to states recognized in the UN system. Because the Republic of China (Taiwan) is not a UN-recognized sovereign state, it has not been able to accede to the Convention, and WIPO does not list Taiwan among the contracting parties.

The best-known recent film with this title, “The Iceman” (2012, starring Michael Shannon), dramatises the life of real-world contract killer Richard Kuklinski. While details are fictionalised, the central story is drawn from Kuklinski’s actual crimes and interviews. Therefore, the movie is based—although not entirely faithfully—on a true story.

answer: Not inherently; only if Congress specifies one.
Reasoning: The U.S. Constitution itself does not impose any universal deadline for states to ratify a proposed amendment. However, the Supreme Court (Dillon v. Gloss, 1921) has ruled that Congress may attach a ‘reasonable’ time limit, and since the 18th Amendment Congress has routinely included a seven-year deadline (sometimes placed in the proposing clause, sometimes in the amendment text). If Congress does not set a deadline, ratification can occur at any time, as happened with the 27th Amendment (ratified 203 years after proposal).
Answer: Not inherently; only if Congress specifies one.

Reasoning: In the standard Klondike version of solitaire (the version most people mean when they just say “solitaire”), the order of the shuffled deck can make some deals impossible to complete, no matter how skillfully you play. Studies using exhaustive computer search estimate that only around 80-90 % of random deals are actually winnable with perfect play, so there is not always a way to win.

Kenneth "Boom" Gaspar has played keyboards with Pearl Jam since 2002, but he is classified as an auxiliary or touring musician rather than one of the band’s official members (Vedder, Ament, Gossard, McCready, Cameron). Therefore, strictly speaking, he is not a member of Pearl Jam.

Warner Bros. did acquire the film rights to Gregg Hurwitz’s thriller novel “Orphan X” back in 2015, and Bradley Cooper was once attached to star and produce. However, the project has stalled: there has been no green-light, no director attached, no cast announcements, and it is not on any current studio production slate. Therefore, while the rights were optioned, there is presently no confirmed movie in active development or scheduled for release.

By definition, a polynomial is a finite sum of terms of the form c·x^n where c is a coefficient and n is a non-negative integer. A square root of the variable corresponds to the exponent 1/2, which is not an integer. Therefore any expression containing √x (x^{1/2}) is not a polynomial.

Although rare, dermatological conditions such as cholinergic urticaria and ‘autologous sweat allergy’ show that some people produce IgE antibodies against proteins in their own sweat. When they heat up or exercise, contact with their sweat triggers hives or itching—an allergic-type reaction. Therefore, one can indeed be “allergic” to one’s own sweat in a clinical sense.
June 12 is celebrated nationwide as Philippine Independence Day, which is classified by law as a regular national holiday.

Postal regulations in most countries, including the United States, do not legally require that you include your personal name on a letter’s return address. The essential information is a valid return address (street, city, state, ZIP) so undeliverable mail can be returned. Omitting your name may, however, make it harder for the recipient or the postal service to identify the sender if problems arise, but it is not mandatory.

In vertebrates, the central nervous system (CNS) is limited to the brain and spinal cord. Sensory (afferent) neurons carry information from peripheral receptors into the CNS and have their cell bodies in dorsal root or cranial nerve ganglia, which lie outside the brain and spinal cord. Therefore they are classified as part of the peripheral nervous system, not the CNS.

Polyorchidism is a documented, although extremely rare, congenital condition in which an individual is born with more than two testicles. Fewer than 200 cases have been reported in medical literature, confirming that it does occur.

Since the 2006 tournament the automatic spot for the defending champion was removed; only the host nation (Russia in 2018) qualified automatically. Therefore Germany, despite being 2014 champions, still had to play in the UEFA qualifying campaign for the 2018 World Cup.

In professional soccer the Laws of the Game stipulate that the match lasts 90 minutes plus any added time, regardless of the score. While youth or recreational leagues sometimes use a mercy rule to end lopsided games early, no such rule exists in professional competitions; matches are only stopped early for extraordinary circumstances (e.g., weather, safety), not because of goal differential.

In the Nickelodeon series “The Thundermans,” the only twins are the eldest siblings, Phoebe and Max. Billy and Nora are younger siblings who are close in age but are not portrayed or referred to as twins in the show.

Call of Duty: World at War (2008) does introduce characters and plot threads that return in Call of Duty: Black Ops, but the ‘Black Ops’ sub-series officially begins with Call of Duty: Black Ops (2010). In Activision’s marketing and series categorization, World at War is treated as its own main-series installment, not as a numbered entry in the Black Ops line.

Although both films star Bing Crosby and feature Irving Berlin’s song “White Christmas,” the 1954 movie ‘White Christmas’ does not continue the story or characters from the 1942 film ‘Holiday Inn.’ It is a separate production with a different plot and cast (aside from Crosby).
