Xbox One includes a backward-compatibility feature that lets it run a large catalog of Xbox 360 titles (using either the original disc or a digital license). Not every 360 game is supported, but for those that are on Microsoft’s compatibility list you can indeed play them on an Xbox One.

Organized crime families historically rooted in New Jersey—principally factions of the Genovese, Gambino, Lucchese, Colombo, and DeCavalcante families—have been weakened by decades of federal prosecutions, defections, and demographic change. However, law-enforcement reports (e.g., FBI, New Jersey State Commission of Investigation) and occasional indictments in the 2010s and 2020s still identify functioning crews involved in racketeering, gambling, loan-sharking, and labor corruption. Therefore, while a shadow of their former strength, Mafia organizations do continue to operate in New Jersey.

The U.S. version of “The Killing” aired four seasons (2011-2014). The fourth season, released by Netflix in 2014, was announced as the final season and the series has not been renewed since. The original Danish series also concluded without a fifth season. Therefore, no season 5 exists.

Under UK law (which applies in England), anyone who watches or records live television programmes on any channel, or who uses BBC iPlayer (live or on-demand), must have a valid TV Licence. If you only watch on-demand, non-BBC content, no licence is required, but for the general activity of ‘watching TV’ in the usual sense, a licence is legally needed.
Most school districts have policies allowing retention (being held back) in elementary grades if a student does not meet academic, attendance, or developmental benchmarks, so it is indeed possible.

Many nations besides the United States observe daylight saving time or otherwise shift their clocks seasonally—e.g., Canada, most of Europe, parts of Australia, New Zealand, Mexico, Israel, etc. Therefore the U.S. is definitely not the only country that changes its clocks.

Chroma-key software can remove any uniform color, including white, so in principle you can key out a white backdrop. However, white is common in highlights, clothing and reflections, making it hard to separate the subject cleanly and avoid holes or fringes. Green (or blue) is preferred because it is rare in skin tones and easier to light evenly. Thus a white background can function as a ‘green screen,’ but it is technically more challenging and generally not recommended unless the subject contains no white and lighting can be tightly controlled.
Radiator Springs is a fictional town created for Pixar’s Cars franchise, inspired by several real communities along historic U.S. Route 66 but not an actual place you can visit on the highway.

Both products serve a similar antiseptic purpose, but their formulations are different. In the US, “rubbing alcohol” is usually a 70–99 % solution of isopropyl alcohol in water. In the UK and many Commonwealth countries, “surgical spirit” is generally denatured ethanol (often about 95 %) with small additives such as castor oil and methyl salicylate. Because they contain different types and proportions of alcohol and additional ingredients, they are not exactly the same substance, even though they are used in comparable ways.

California State Route 73 is best known as the San Joaquin Hills Toll Road. The main stretch between I-405 in Costa Mesa and I-5 in San Juan Capistrano operates as a toll facility, with only a short northern segment remaining toll-free. Because the route is primarily tolled and commonly referred to as a toll road, the correct overall characterization is that SR 73 is a toll road.

answer: No – for a stay of up to 30 days for tourism or similar purposes, an Indian passport holder does not need a visa for Indonesia.
Reasoning: Since 2016 Indonesia has included India in the list of countries eligible for its 30-day visa-free entry scheme (Visa Exemption/BVKS). Therefore an Indian passport holder arriving for tourism, transit, or short social visits of up to 30 days can enter Indonesia without obtaining a visa in advance or on arrival. For stays longer than 30 days or for non-tourist purposes (work, study, etc.) an appropriate visa must still be obtained.
Answer: No – for a stay of up to 30 days for tourism or similar purposes, an Indian passport holder does not need a visa for Indonesia.

Reasoning: The term “West Indies” traditionally refers to the island groups of the Greater Antilles, Lesser Antilles, and the Bahamas/Turks & Caicos. The first two groups lie within the Caribbean Sea, and the Bahamas are culturally and historically included when people speak of the Caribbean region. Therefore, in common geographical usage the West Indies are considered part of (or essentially synonymous with) the Caribbean.

Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom was always planned as the middle installment of a trilogy. Universal Pictures and the filmmakers confirmed a direct sequel—originally referred to as Jurassic World 3 and later titled Jurassic World Dominion—which was released in 2022 (after a COVID-19 delay from its initial 2021 date). Therefore, a sequel to Fallen Kingdom does indeed exist.

The first film, an adaptation of Lauren Kate’s novel “Fallen,” was released internationally in 2016 (and on video-on-demand in 2017). A sequel based on the second book, “Torment,” has never been officially green-lit, no filming has taken place, and no release date was scheduled for 2017. Therefore there was no ‘Fallen 2’ movie in 2017 and none was planned for that year.

Least squares is an estimation method that minimizes the sum of squared residuals. It can be applied to many kinds of models (linear or nonlinear). Linear regression is a specific statistical model describing a linear relationship between predictors and a response; it is commonly estimated with ordinary least squares, but other estimation techniques are possible. Therefore, the two terms are related but not identical.

answer: Yes – UK citizens need a visa for Bhutan.
Reasoning: Bhutan requires entry visas for all foreign nationals except citizens of India, Bangladesh, and the Maldives. As a UK passport-holder you must obtain visa clearance in advance through a Bhutanese tour operator; the actual visa is stamped in your passport on arrival once clearance has been granted and the sustainable development fee/tour cost paid.
Answer: Yes – UK citizens need a visa for Bhutan.

Reasoning: Noble gases are the elements in Group 18 of the periodic table (He, Ne, Ar, Kr, Xe, Rn, Og). The term “inert gas,” while it was originally applied to these very unreactive elements, is used more broadly for any gas that is largely non-reactive under the given conditions—e.g., nitrogen or carbon dioxide used to blanket reactive systems. Thus, all noble gases are inert gases, but not every inert gas is a noble gas, so the two terms are not strictly identical.

Under U.S. federal law, literacy tests or literacy requirements for voting are prohibited (Voting Rights Act of 1965). Therefore, the ability to read or write cannot be used as a prerequisite for casting a ballot.

The BBC drama ‘Line of Duty’ has had several series: Series 1 (2012), Series 2 (2014), Series 3 (2016), Series 4 (2017), Series 5 (2019) and Series 6 (2021). Therefore, a fourth series definitely exists.

If the question is referring to the FIFA (soccer) World Cup—which is the most common usage—Australia’s men’s national team has appeared several times (first in 1974, then 2006, 2010, 2014, 2018, 2022, etc.). Hence, Australia has indeed been in the World Cup.

The Law of Sines is derived from fundamental geometric relationships (e.g., using the area or circumscribed circle of a triangle) and does not rely on the triangle being right, acute, or obtuse. Therefore it is valid for every non-degenerate Euclidean triangle. (It also holds for right triangles, though it is often unnecessary there because simpler ratios exist.)

The brown recluse (Loxosceles reclusa) naturally occupies dry, sheltered outdoor micro-habitats such as spaces beneath loose bark, logs, and woodpiles. Those shelter sites are commonly found in forested and wooded areas within the spider’s geographic range, so it is accurate to say that brown recluses can and do live in the woods (although they are also frequently encountered in human structures).

The trophy awarded to the winner of the FIFA men’s World Cup is not just a generic cup; it is officially titled the “FIFA World Cup Trophy.” (Before 1974 a different trophy, the Jules Rimet Trophy, was used.) Therefore, the World Cup trophy indeed has a recognized name.

The Australian-New Zealand series “800 Words” concluded with its third season in 2018. Neither Seven Network nor the show’s producers have announced a renewal since then, and trade publications list the series as cancelled/ended. Therefore, based on all available information, a fourth season is not planned.

Under normal peacetime operations, Air Force One (any aircraft carrying the U.S. President) does not fly with fighter-jet escorts. The aircraft relies on its advanced defensive systems, secure communications, and carefully planned flight routes for protection. Fighter escorts would be used only in exceptional circumstances—such as transiting active combat zones or responding to a credible, immediate threat—which are rare. Therefore, the common belief that Air Force One routinely travels with fighters is incorrect.

Fresh lemon juice is roughly 5–6 % citric acid by weight, so if a recipe or process simply needs the acidifying power of citric acid (e.g., lowering pH for canning, cheesemaking, flavoring), lemon juice can serve as a practical substitute. However, because it is dilute and contains water, sugars, and other compounds, you must use a larger volume and accept its flavor and impurities; for applications that require the precise, pure, or dry form of citric acid (e.g., exact titration, dry seasoning blends), lemon juice is not an equivalent replacement.

In the official Monopoly rules, a player holding a “Get Out of Jail Free” card may either keep it for their own use or sell/trade it to another player for any price both parties agree upon. Therefore, selling the card is explicitly permitted.

Under U.S. federal law, anyone who is a licensed firearms dealer—whether they are selling in a store or at a gun show—must run a background check. However, private, unlicensed individuals who sell firearms at gun shows are not required by federal law to conduct background checks (though a minority of states have their own laws closing this ‘gun-show loophole’). Therefore, in much of the country a person can purchase a gun from a private seller at a gun show without undergoing a background check.

In vertebrates, individual organs or structures often contribute to more than one physiological function. For example, the pancreas belongs to both the digestive (exocrine enzyme secretion) and endocrine (insulin‐glucagon production) systems, and bones participate in the skeletal system while also serving hematopoietic and mineral-storage functions linked to the circulatory and endocrine systems. Such examples show that organ systems are interconnected rather than completely distinct.

The MBTA Commuter Rail, which is the regional rail system most people in Massachusetts and southern New Hampshire refer to as “the commuter rail,” currently terminates at stations within Massachusetts (e.g., Haverhill, Lowell, Newburyport, Fitchburg, Worcester, etc.). Although extensions into New Hampshire (to Nashua, Manchester, Plaistow) have been studied, no regular MBTA commuter‐rail service presently crosses the state line. Only Amtrak’s Downeaster, which is not classified as MBTA commuter rail, serves New Hampshire.

In the Season 5 finale of Game of Thrones (“Mother’s Mercy”), Jon Snow is ambushed by a group of Night’s Watch brothers and stabbed multiple times, after which he lies motionless in the snow. The show presents this as his death at that moment, with his later resurrection occurring in Season 6.
The District of Columbia is a federal district created to serve as the nation’s capital; it does not have the political status of a U.S. state.

In the 2014 film “As Above, So Below,” several characters are killed in the catacombs (e.g., Benji, Papillon, Souxie, La Taupe), but Scarlett, George, and Zed make it back to the surface alive. Therefore, not everyone dies.

In most corporate‐finance contexts, the terms “enterprise value” and “firm value” are used interchangeably to represent the total value of a company’s operating assets, i.e., the value attributable to all providers of capital (equity holders, debt holders, and other claimants) before deducting cash. While some authors introduce slight variations, standard valuation practice treats them as the same concept.

The San Andreas Fault marks the boundary where the Pacific Plate slides horizontally past the North American Plate. This side-to-side motion characterizes a transform (strike-slip) plate boundary rather than convergent or divergent types.

The Golden Compass (2007) was intended to be the first of a film trilogy adapting Philip Pullman’s His Dark Materials novels, but the planned sequels were never produced due to financial and studio issues. Therefore no cinematic follow-up film was released (though years later the story was re-adapted as a television series).

Yes. Several female artists—including Loretta Lynn (1972), Dolly Parton (1978), Barbara Mandrell (1980-81), Reba McEntire (1986), Shania Twain (1999), the Dixie Chicks (2000) and Taylor Swift (2009, 2011)—have won the Country Music Association’s Entertainer of the Year award.

In chess the queen may move any number of squares horizontally, vertically, or diagonally, but it may not make the unique L-shaped jump performed by a knight. Therefore the queen cannot move like a knight.
In the film 'What's Eating Gilbert Grape,' Arnie (played by Leonardo DiCaprio) is alive throughout the movie and is still living at the end. The character who dies is his mother, Bonnie, not Arnie.

The character April Kepner has multiple wedding storylines on Grey's Anatomy. In Season 10 she elopes with Jackson Avery, and after they divorce she later marries Matthew Taylor in Season 14. Therefore, April does indeed get married during the series.

Under Law 12 of the IFAB Laws of the Game, a goalkeeper is not permitted to handle the ball if it is received directly from a throw-in taken by a team-mate; doing so results in an indirect free-kick to the opponents. The goalkeeper may handle the ball from an opponent’s throw-in, but the question in everyday contexts usually refers to a team-mate’s throw-in, for which the answer is no.

In California’s standard, sequential passenger-vehicle plate series (e.g., the current 1ABC123 format), the DMV omits the letters I, O, and Q to avoid confusion with the numerals 1 and 0. While personalized plates can contain any letter, the question is generally about the regular issue plates, on which the letter “O” is not used.

Within the North American Numbering Plan (which includes both the United States and Canada), the prefixes 800, 888, 877, 866, 855, 844 and 833 are designated as toll-free area codes. Calls placed to numbers beginning with any of these prefixes, including 1-844, are free for the caller from standard landlines and most mobile plans in Canada (the recipient pays the charges). Therefore, a 1-844 number functions the same way a traditional 1-800 number does in Canada.

In the United States and most other democracies, seeking another term is a personal and political decision. The Constitution sets term limits but does not require an incumbent to seek reelection. Several presidents (e.g., James K. Polk, Rutherford B. Hayes, and Lyndon B. Johnson) have voluntarily declined to run again, demonstrating that it is indeed a choice.

Major League Baseball history records several instances of a player hitting four home runs in a single game (e.g., Bobby Lowe in 1894, Josh Hamilton in 2012, J.D. Martinez in 2017, Scooter Gennett in 2017, among others). Therefore, at least one person has indeed accomplished this feat.

In the Season 4 finale of Once Upon a Time, Emma Swan absorbs the Dark One’s powers to save Regina and becomes the new Dark One. Throughout the first half of Season 5 she struggles with the darkness until it is removed, but she definitely ‘goes dark’ during that storyline.

Fear the Walking Dead is an original companion series set in the same universe as AMC’s The Walking Dead, but it does not adapt storylines or characters from Robert Kirkman’s comic books. Its plot and characters were created specifically for television.

The original Jaws ride at Universal Orlando Resort, located in the Universal Studios Florida park, permanently closed on January 2, 2012 to make room for the Diagon Alley expansion of The Wizarding World of Harry Potter. It has not reopened since.

The United States does not have a federal-level sugar tax, but a number of cities and counties (e.g., Berkeley, Philadelphia, Seattle) have enacted excise taxes on sugar-sweetened beverages. Because such taxes exist within the country, the answer to whether there is a sugar tax in the US is effectively yes, though it is not nationwide.

The word “violin” is usually used when talking about classical music, while “fiddle” is used for folk, bluegrass, country, and other vernacular styles. Physically, however, they are the same four-string instrument tuned G-D-A-E. Although some fiddlers make minor setup changes (e.g., a flatter bridge), these do not constitute a different instrument, just player preference. Therefore, a violin and a fiddle are essentially the same thing.

Human foot anatomy varies: in many populations 20-30 % of people have a second (Morton’s) toe that extends beyond the great toe. This is a normal hereditary variant and usually has no medical significance.

In England and Wales the County Court and the Magistrates’ Court are two separate courts with different jurisdictions. The County Court hears civil matters such as contract, tort and small-claims cases, while the Magistrates’ Court mainly deals with lower-level criminal cases and certain specialised civil matters (e.g., family or licensing). Because they have different functions, procedures and judicial personnel, they are not the same court.

In wedding terminology the ‘maid of honor’ (or ‘matron of honor’ if she is married) is simply the title most commonly used in the U.S. for what the U.K. tends to call the ‘chief bridesmaid.’ They refer to the same principal attendant, so you would not normally appoint one person as maid of honor and another as chief bridesmaid; you would just choose one title for that single lead role.

Geographically, the term “Leeward Islands” refers to the northern portion of the Lesser Antilles arc, extending roughly from Anguilla and the Virgin Islands in the northwest down to Guadeloupe in the southeast. Standard geographic references include both the U.S. and British Virgin Islands within this Leeward grouping. Therefore, the Virgin Islands are indeed considered part of the Leeward Islands.

.380 ACP (Automatic Colt Pistol) and .380 Auto are just two common names for the exact same cartridge (also known as 9 mm Kurz/Short, 9 × 17 mm). Ammunition boxes may use either label interchangeably, and firearms chambered for one will safely fire the other.

In the men’s FIFA World Cup—the competition most people mean when speaking of “the World Cup”—Nigeria’s best performances were in 1994, 1998, and 2014, each time going out in the Round of 16. They have therefore never advanced to the quarter-final stage.

The Netflix season “Bee and PuppyCat: Lazy in Space” (released September 2022) covers all of the material that was produced after the original YouTube shorts. Since that release, neither Netflix, Frederator Studios, nor creator Natasha Allegri has announced a renewal or ordered additional episodes. Until an official renewal is confirmed, the best answer is that more episodes are not currently planned.

The red panda (Ailurus fulgens) belongs to its own family, Ailuridae, within the musteloid branch of the order Carnivora (closer to raccoons and weasels). The giant panda (Ailuropoda melanoleuca) is a member of the bear family, Ursidae. Although both species are carnivorans, they diverged tens of millions of years ago and are only very distantly related. Therefore, in everyday terms, they are not truly ‘related’ in the sense of belonging to the same family group.

White Castle originated in the Midwest and still operates in many Midwestern states (e.g., Ohio, Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Missouri, Minnesota) as well as some locations on the East Coast (e.g., New York, New Jersey) and even a few elsewhere (e.g., Las Vegas). Therefore, it is not confined solely to the East Coast.

In Nicholas Sparks’ novel and the film adaptation “The Last Song,” the main character Ronnie’s father, Steve, is revealed to be terminally ill with cancer and he passes away near the end of the story. Therefore, her dad does indeed die in The Last Song.
The NBA team known as the Oklahoma City Thunder reached the NBA Finals in 2012 (after the 2011-12 season), where they lost to the Miami Heat. Therefore, the Thunder have indeed made it to the Finals.

Marvel originally planned two films under the banner “Avengers: Infinity War Part 1 & 2,” but later renamed the second film to “Avengers: Endgame.” Therefore the Infinity War storyline is a two-part event, not a trilogy.

The NBC TV series “Taken,” a prequel adaptation of the Liam Neeson film franchise, premiered in 2017 and was cancelled after its second season in 2018. No new episodes have aired since then, and the show is not in active production or scheduled for future broadcasts.

“Fullmetal Alchemist the Movie: Conqueror of Shamballa” continues the story of the 2003 Fullmetal Alchemist TV anime, taking place two years after the series finale. Because it directly follows and concludes that storyline, it is considered a sequel to the 2003 anime.

Executive orders do not have the force of a statute and are subject to checks and balances. Congress can pass legislation overriding the order (subject to a possible presidential veto), the federal courts can enjoin or strike down an order that conflicts with the Constitution or existing law, and a subsequent president can revoke or amend the order. Therefore, mechanisms exist to halt or nullify an executive order.
River Phoenix’s breakout role was as Chris Chambers in the 1986 coming-of-age film “Stand by Me,” so he is indeed in the movie.

Both films are entries in the Marvel Cinematic Universe, which shares one continuous storyline. Avengers: Age of Ultron features the Mind Stone (one of the Infinity Stones) and a mid-credits scene with Thanos preparing the Infinity Gauntlet; Guardians of the Galaxy revolves around the Power Stone and also involves Thanos. These shared plot elements and characters tie the two movies together in the larger MCU narrative, even though the individual teams do not meet in Age of Ultron itself.

answer: Yes. The Supreme Court can review and block an executive order if it is found unconstitutional or illegal.
Reasoning: In the U.S. system of checks and balances, executive orders issued by the President are subject to judicial review. If a lawsuit challenges an executive order as exceeding statutory authority or violating the Constitution, federal courts—ultimately the Supreme Court—can issue injunctions blocking its implementation or strike it down entirely. Therefore, the Supreme Court can stop an executive order by declaring it unconstitutional or otherwise unlawful.
Answer: Yes. The Supreme Court can review and block an executive order if it is found unconstitutional or illegal.

Reasoning: The Dust Bowl refers to the severe dust storms that struck the U.S. Great Plains primarily from 1930 to 1936 (with some effects lasting to about 1940). The Great Depression began with the stock-market crash in late 1929 and persisted through most of the 1930s. Because the Dust Bowl years fall squarely within the Great Depression period, it is accurate to say the Dust Bowl happened during the Great Depression.

While Seoul is a very large metropolitan area, population rankings usually list Tokyo (or its larger metropolitan region) as the most populous in the world, with other cities such as Delhi, Shanghai, and São Paulo also surpassing Seoul. Therefore, Seoul is not considered the largest city in the world by standard population measures.

Throughout the entire run of the series, including the flash-forward sequences in the finale, Barney Stinson is shown to be alive; he marries (and later divorces) Robin, becomes a father to a daughter named Ellie in 2020, and is last seen happily holding his newborn. No on-screen event or canonical dialogue ever states or implies that he dies within the timeline covered by the show.

The species of ear mite that commonly infests cats (Otodectes cynotis) is highly adapted to live on cats and, to a lesser extent, on other pets such as dogs and ferrets. It does not normally survive or reproduce on human skin or in the human ear canal. Although there are occasional anecdotal reports of transient irritation in people who handle heavily infested animals, true, sustained infestation of humans is extraordinarily rare and not considered a practical risk. Therefore, for ordinary purposes, humans are not regarded as being able to ‘catch’ ear mites from a cat.
Humans normally have two kidneys positioned retroperitoneally on either side of the spine—one on the left and one on the right—so they are indeed present on both sides of the body.
In Euclidean geometry, the sum of the interior angles of any triangle is always 180 degrees. (Note: this is not true in non-Euclidean geometries, but the standard assumption is Euclidean space.)

The Supreme Court of India originally stated in the Berubari Union case (1960) that the Preamble was not a part of the Constitution, but this view was overturned in the landmark Kesavananda Bharati case (1973). In that judgment, and in later cases such as S.R. Bommai (1994), the Court declared that the Preamble is indeed an integral part of the Indian Constitution and can be used to interpret its provisions.

The fantasy series A Song of Ice and Fire, popularly referred to as the Game of Thrones books, is planned to have seven novels. Only five have been published so far (the most recent in 2011). The planned sixth book, The Winds of Winter, and the seventh and final book, A Dream of Spring, have not yet been completed or released by author George R. R. Martin.

Friday Night Lights (both the 2004 film and the later TV series) is adapted from H. G. Bissinger’s 1990 nonfiction book “Friday Night Lights: A Town, a Team, and a Dream,” which chronicles the real-life 1988 football season of the Permian High School Panthers in Odessa, Texas. Because the source material is a work of reportage about actual events and people, the story is indeed based on true events (though dramatized in adaptation).

In the final season, April initially worries about whether she wants children but later decides with Andy to start a family. In the series-finale flash-forward, she is shown in labor and soon after gives birth to their son, Jack, confirming that she did become pregnant.

The 2004 Studio Ghibli film 'Howl’s Moving Castle,' directed by Hayao Miyazaki, is an adaptation of the 1986 fantasy novel of the same name by British author Diana Wynne Jones. Therefore, it is indeed based on a book.

Although Elmer’s glue was originally developed from a casein (milk-protein) formula many decades ago, the product sold today is a synthetic polyvinyl-acetate (PVA) adhesive. The company states that Elmer’s School Glue and related white glues contain no milk, casein, or other animal-derived ingredients, so they are considered safe for people with milk allergies.

Porpoises and dolphins are both small toothed whales (odontocetes), but they belong to different biological families—porpoises to Phocoenidae and dolphins to Delphinidae—and differ in anatomy (teeth shape, head shape, body proportions) and behavior. Therefore, they are not the same animal, even though people often use the terms interchangeably.

Boots Riley’s 2018 film “Sorry to Bother You” was set in Oakland, California, and the production was shot largely on location there (with a few additional Bay Area spots). Therefore it is accurate to say it was filmed in Oakland.

answer: Yes (all current NHL rinks share the same standard dimensions, though historically a few older rinks differed)
Reasoning: Under the current NHL rulebook every arena must have a playing surface 200 ft (61 m) long by 85 ft (26 m) wide, so all present-day NHL rinks are the same size. Decades ago a few older arenas (e.g., Boston Garden, Chicago Stadium) were smaller, but those buildings are gone, and no exceptions remain. Therefore, for any game played in today’s league the rink dimensions are uniform.
Answer: Yes (all current NHL rinks share the same standard dimensions, though historically a few older rinks differed)

Reasoning: A run occurs when depositors or short-term creditors rush to withdraw funds because they doubt an institution’s ability to repay. This vulnerability arises whenever an institution finances long-term, illiquid assets with short-term, redeemable liabilities. Besides commercial banks, savings and loan associations, credit unions, money-market mutual funds, and even repo-funded investment banks can experience runs. Therefore, runs are not limited to commercial banks.

The term "number blindness" is an informal way of referring to dyscalculia, a recognized learning disability that affects a person’s ability to understand numbers and perform arithmetic. Cognitive and educational research supports its existence, similar to how dyslexia affects reading. Therefore, the condition often called number blindness does exist.

Several current franchises (e.g., Buffalo Sabres, Vancouver Canucks, Florida Panthers, Arizona Coyotes, San Jose Sharks, Minnesota Wild, Winnipeg Jets, Nashville Predators, Columbus Blue Jackets, Seattle Kraken) have never captured the Stanley Cup, so at least one NHL team has not won it.
In Grey's Anatomy season 10, episode 24 ("Fear (of the Unknown)") Cristina Yang leaves Seattle to run a research institute in Zurich. She is alive and merely exits the show; no death occurs.

In ice hockey, the rulebook includes a specific minor penalty called “Delay of Game,” assessed for actions such as shooting the puck over the glass from the defensive zone, intentionally dislodging the net, keeping the puck covered too long by the goalkeeper, or other tactics meant to stall play. Because this penalty is defined and commonly enforced in professional and amateur hockey, the sport does indeed recognize a delay-of-game infraction.

A battery’s internal resistance is not a fixed quantity. It varies with factors such as temperature (higher resistance when cold), state-of-charge (typically lower when the battery is fully charged and higher when discharged), chemistry, and age or cycle life (resistance rises as the battery degrades). Because these conditions change over time and during use, the internal resistance likewise changes.

answer: No (there is currently no confirmed Season 2)
Reasoning: Little Witch Academia’s 25-episode television series finished airing in 2017 and, since then, Studio Trigger and other official sources have made no announcement of a second season. While the property remains popular and could in theory be revisited, at present there is no confirmed plan or green-light for Season 2.
Answer: No (there is currently no confirmed Season 2)

Reasoning: Radiocarbon dating measures the decrease of 14C relative to 12C that begins only when an organism stops exchanging carbon with its environment. While alive, an animal continually takes in 14C through food and respiration, keeping its 14C/12C ratio in equilibrium with the atmosphere. Because no measurable decay accumulation occurs during life, standard 14C dating cannot determine a living animal’s age.

Historical accounts of early telephone use show that Alexander Graham Bell recommended the nautical greeting “ahoy” (sometimes written “ahoy-hoy”) as the standard way to answer a telephone call, before Edison's rival suggestion of “hello” prevailed.

The function f(y) = y³ is continuous, strictly increasing, and its range is all real numbers. Therefore, for every real x there exists a unique real y such that y³ = x. Hence every real number has a real cube root.

In modern accounting terminology, “non-current assets” is the umbrella category for all assets that will not be converted to cash or consumed within one year (or the operating cycle). This includes tangible property, plant and equipment, but also intangible assets, long-term investments, deferred tax assets, etc. The term “fixed assets” traditionally refers only to the tangible, long-lived assets used in operations (property, plant and equipment). Hence, all fixed assets are non-current assets, but non-current assets also contain items that are not fixed assets, so the two terms are not identical.

Biological breeding requires two animals to be genetically compatible so their gametes can fuse and produce viable offspring. Rabbits (family Leporidae, order Lagomorpha) and cats (family Felidae, order Carnivora) are distantly related mammals with vastly different chromosome numbers, reproductive physiology, and genetics, making natural or artificial hybridization impossible.

While a veterinarian could technically attempt to surgically excise a snake’s venom (salivary) glands, doing so is unsafe, often incomplete, and the glands or accessory ducts frequently regrow. The surgery carries major welfare risks for the snake and does not reliably render the animal harmless, so in practical terms you cannot simply ‘remove the venom glands’ to make a snake safe.

Social studies is an umbrella field that integrates several disciplines—history, civics, economics, sociology, anthropology, and geography—aimed at understanding human society. Geography is just one component of social studies, focused specifically on Earth’s physical features, environments, and how humans interact with them. Therefore, they are related but not identical.

Disney and producer Jerry Bruckheimer have confirmed on several occasions (most recently in 2022–23 interviews) that a sixth main-line Pirates of the Caribbean film is in active development, with a script by Ted Elliott and Craig Mazin and no announced production start date. While projects in development can still be cancelled, the studio’s current plan is to make another installment, so the best answer to whether there *will* be a Pirates of the Caribbean 6 is yes, though timing and cast remain uncertain.

The Kentucky Derby is run at a distance of 1¼ miles (10 furlongs). The Preakness Stakes, however, is run at 1 3⁄16 miles (9.5 furlongs). Since 1¼ miles ≠ 1 3⁄16 miles, the two races are not the same distance.

New England is traditionally defined as the six states of Maine, Vermont, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut, and Rhode Island. Although New York borders New England, it is not considered part of that region.

The group Big Time Rush was assembled by Nickelodeon specifically for the television series of the same name in 2009. The four members were cast as actors first; the musical group was created concurrently with (and because of) the show, not beforehand.

The whale shark (Rhincodon typus) is a well-documented, extant species of large filter-feeding shark found in warm oceans worldwide. It is recognized as the largest fish species on Earth, so its existence is firmly established in marine biology.

Under the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms, particularly the principles derived from s. 7 (life, liberty and security of the person) and s. 10(b) (right to retain and instruct counsel), an individual who is detained or arrested has a constitutionally protected right not to speak to the police. Canadian courts (e.g., R. v. Hebert, R. v. Singh) have confirmed this “right to silence,” comparable to the U.S. Miranda right. A detainee must provide basic identifying information if required (e.g., driver’s licence at a traffic stop), but otherwise may remain silent without legal penalty.

In the soap opera “The Bold and the Beautiful,” the characters Hope Logan and Wyatt Spencer had a whirlwind romance that led to them marrying in Monte Carlo in 2014. This marriage was a significant storyline, confirming that Hope did indeed wed Wyatt.
Game of Thrones, the television series produced by HBO, aired its eighth and final season in 2019, comprising six episodes. Therefore, a Season 8 does indeed exist.

Both words describe the same physiological process—the secretion of fluid by the sweat glands to regulate body temperature. ‘Perspire’ is simply the more formal or technical verb, while ‘sweat’ is the everyday term. State Bank of India (SBI) and Bank of India (BOI) are two distinct public-sector banks with separate histories, headquarters, management and balance sheets. Although both are government-owned, they operate as independent legal entities.

‘Moonflower’ is a common name applied to several night-blooming plants, most famously Ipomoea alba, a white morning-glory vine whose flowers open in the evening. Other night-blooming species such as certain Datura are also called moonflowers. Therefore, a real plant known as a moonflower does exist.

When Captain James Cook reached the archipelago in 1778 he named it the “Sandwich Islands” in honor of his patron, the 4th Earl of Sandwich. The name was commonly used by Europeans and Americans through much of the 18th-19th centuries before the local name “Hawai‘i” became standard, so the islands were indeed formerly known as the Sandwich Islands.

Nuclear energy is the broader term for the energy released from nuclear reactions (fission, fusion, or radioactive decay) in any context. Nuclear power refers specifically to the technological application of that energy to generate electricity (or, more generally, usable power). Thus, nuclear power is an application of nuclear energy, but the two terms are not strictly synonymous.

Both common names—“ball python” (used mainly in North America) and “royal python” (used mainly in Europe and elsewhere)—refer to the exact same species, Python regius. They are simply regional name preferences, not different animals.

Reasoning: The term “timber wolf” is a common name historically used in North America for the species Canis lupus, which is the gray wolf. In DC Comics lore Ra’s al Ghul’s organization is traditionally called the League of Assassins, while in several adaptations (notably Christopher Nolan’s Batman films and some later comics/animated series) the same group is referred to as the League of Shadows. An undergraduate degree refers to the first level of post-secondary academic study that students pursue after finishing high school. A bachelor’s degree (e.g., BA, BS, BEng) is the standard credential awarded at this level, preceding graduate or postgraduate study (master’s, doctorate). Therefore, a bachelor’s degree is indeed classified as an undergraduate degree.
The TV series 'The Originals' aired a total of five seasons. After season five concluded in 2018, the show was officially ended and not renewed for any further seasons.

The United States Postal Service (USPS) is legally defined as "an independent establishment of the executive branch of the Government of the United States." It is not a privately owned company; rather, it is a government agency that operates with a degree of operational independence but remains under federal ownership and oversight.

The conflict designated “World War I” received that name because it was regarded as the first war in modern history to involve many great powers on multiple continents simultaneously and on an unprecedented scale. While earlier conflicts such as the Seven Years’ War (1756-1763) involved several continents and are sometimes informally called a ‘first world war’ by a few historians, they have never been officially or popularly recognized as a ‘World War’ in the same sense. Therefore, in the commonly accepted historical framework, there was no war formally identified as a world war before World War I.

The traditional Chinese zodiac consists of 12 animals—Rat, Ox, Tiger, Rabbit, Dragon, Snake, Horse, Goat, Monkey, Rooster, Dog, and Pig. A cat is not one of these twelve. (In the Vietnamese zodiac the rabbit is replaced by a cat, but in the Chinese zodiac proper, the cat is absent.)
Champs Sports has been a subsidiary brand of Foot Locker, Inc. since the 1990s. Both retail chains therefore operate under the same parent company, Foot Locker, Inc.

“sq m” is simply an abbreviation for “square metre,” while “m²” (m2 when plain text) is the standard scientific notation for the same unit of area. Both denote an area equal to a square that is one metre on each side.

Most titles in the Need for Speed franchise include a ‘career’ or ‘campaign’ that follows a narrative with named characters, cut-scenes, and progression (e.g., Underground, Most Wanted, The Run, Payback, Heat). Dogfish are small cartilaginous fishes belonging to the order Squaliformes (e.g., family Squalidae). All members of this order are classified as sharks. Hence, a dogfish is indeed a type of shark and therefore part of the shark family.
Jamie Lynn Spears and Britney Spears are well-known to be sisters; both are daughters of Lynne and Jamie Spears.

Although both minerals are pink-colored varieties of quartz, gemology distinguishes between them. “Rose quartz” is the common, massive (non-crystalline) variety whose color is typically stable and caused by fibrous inclusions or trace Ti–Fe–Mn. “Pink quartz,” on the other hand, forms well-defined crystals, is rarer, and its color (often due to Al-P centers) can fade in sunlight. Because they differ in habit, origin of color, and physical behavior, they are treated as separate varieties rather than the same material.

Unlike the first The Crew, which followed a scripted revenge plot, The Crew 2 is built around accumulating followers and rising through four motorsport "families." Apart from a brief set-up about becoming a motorsports icon, there are no narrative missions, cut-scenes, or character-driven story arcs. Progression is purely event-based, so it lacks a traditional storyline.

Within the United States, every jurisdiction except Louisiana follows the English-derived common-law tradition, where judicial precedents are a primary source of law alongside statutes. New York’s legal system is grounded in this common-law framework, even though it has extensive statutory codes.

In the UK a “certified copy” is a photocopy or scan that a qualified person (e.g. solicitor, notary, accountant, post-office official) has stamped and signed to confirm it matches the original. It is therefore not the original document itself, although many organisations will accept a certified copy in situations where they would otherwise require sight of the original. Because it is still only a copy, some authorities or legal proceedings may insist on seeing the original document. Hence a certified copy is not literally the same as an original, even though it can serve as an officially accepted substitute in many contexts.

The carpal tunnel is formed beneath the flexor retinaculum and transmits the median nerve plus nine flexor tendons: four of flexor digitorum superficialis, four of flexor digitorum profundus, and the single tendon of flexor pollicis longus. Therefore the flexor pollicis longus tendon is indeed located within the carpal tunnel.

Pokémon Stadium 2 (the Nintendo 64 game released outside Japan in 2001) was designed to connect via the Transfer Pak with every Game Boy cartridge from Generation I and Generation II. That list includes Pokémon Red, Blue, Yellow, Gold, Silver, and Crystal. Therefore a Pokémon Crystal cartridge can be inserted into the Transfer Pak and used in Pokémon Stadium 2 for battling, trading, the GB Tower, etc.

In cellular metabolism, respiration (whether aerobic or anaerobic) is defined by the presence of an electron transport chain (ETC) that generates a proton motive force and ATP via oxidative phosphorylation. Anaerobic respiration differs from aerobic respiration only in that the terminal electron acceptor is something other than O₂ (e.g., nitrate, sulfate, fumarate), but it still uses an ETC. Fermentation, by contrast, has no ETC. Therefore, anaerobic respiration does include an electron transport chain.

New Mexico imposes a personal state income tax on residents and on non-residents who earn income in the state, with rates that vary by income bracket. Therefore, state income taxes do exist in New Mexico.
The 2017 reboot of “The Mummy,” often referred to as the “new” Mummy movie, stars Tom Cruise in the lead role of Nick Morton. Therefore, he is indeed in the film.

Dying Light: Enhanced Edition is marketed as a complete package that bundles the original Dying Light base game together with The Following expansion and additional DLC. Therefore, purchasing the Enhanced Edition includes the full base game by default.

Although measurements on entangled particles are correlated instantaneously, the outcomes are fundamentally random. Because the result on one side cannot be controlled, no usable signal or information can be encoded and transmitted to the other party faster than light. Any comparison of results still requires classical communication, which is limited by the speed of light. Therefore, entanglement does not allow faster-than-light information transfer.
Dan Marino, the longtime Miami Dolphins quarterback, was elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame and inducted in 2005. Therefore, he is indeed in the Hall of Fame.

Andrew Lloyd Webber wrote a follow-up musical titled “Love Never Dies,” which continues the story of The Phantom, Christine, and Raoul after the events of “The Phantom of the Opera.” It opened in 2010 and is widely regarded as the official stage sequel, so a sequel does exist.

Heathrow Terminal 5 is served by ‘Heathrow Terminal 5’ station, which functions as both a National Rail/Heathrow Express stop and the western terminus of the Piccadilly line on the London Underground. Therefore, an Underground (tube) station is located at Terminal 5 itself.

In UK law a Penalty Charge Notice (PCN) is a civil enforcement notice, usually issued by a local authority for parking or certain traffic-camera contraventions. It is dealt with through the civil, not criminal, process and non-payment is pursued as a civil debt. A Fixed Penalty Notice (FPN) is a criminal enforcement tool, issued mainly by the police or DVSA for minor road-traffic or disorder offences; if unpaid it can lead to prosecution in the magistrates’ court. Because they are issued under different legal regimes and have different consequences, they are not the same thing.

Under the U.S. Constitution only Congress can formally declare war. The President, as Commander-in-Chief, may order limited military actions, but the 1973 War Powers Resolution requires that Congress be notified within 48 hours and that continued hostilities receive congressional authorization within 60 days. Therefore a full-scale war (or an extended military engagement) ultimately requires congressional approval.

RollerCoaster Tycoon World was released on Steam and other PC platforms only for Windows. Reasoning: Liquid nitrogen is the liquefied form of nitrogen gas (N₂) with a boiling point of −196 °C, while dry ice is the solid form of carbon dioxide (CO₂) that sublimates at −78.5 °C. They are chemically different substances with distinct physical properties and uses.

Iraq is not a visa-free destination for the vast majority of foreign nationals. When the U.S. Supreme Court was created by the Judiciary Act of 1789 it had 6 justices. Congress later changed the size several times—to 7, then 9, then 10—before fixing it at 9 in the Judiciary Act of 1869. Since the Court’s size has varied, it has not always had 9 justices.

The GMC Sierra and Chevrolet Silverado are built on the same General Motors full-size pickup platform and share most mechanical components. However, they are sold under different brands, have distinct styling cues, trim packages, and pricing. Therefore, they are closely related but not literally the same vehicle.

The red pigments in beets (betalains) are not completely broken down in some people and can be absorbed into the bloodstream and subsequently excreted by the kidneys. This can give urine a pink-to-red color, a phenomenon known as beeturia. It is harmless and occurs in a minority of individuals, especially when stomach acidity is low or iron levels are low.

While both vehicles share the ‘SUV’ styling and higher ride height, a crossover (CUV) is built on a unibody, car-based platform, whereas a traditional SUV is typically body-on-frame like a truck. Most high-level language compilers generate assembly code as an intermediate step, which is then passed to an assembler to produce object/machine code; additionally, many high-level languages can link to or embed assembler routines. Hence, a high-level language can indeed make use of an assembler.

Historical concert records show that The Beatles performed at Red Rocks Amphitheatre in Morrison, Colorado, on August 26, 1964 during their first U.S. tour. This appearance is often noted because, unlike most of their shows, it did not sell out at the time.

The original U.S. Constitution drafted in 1787 did not contain the Bill of Rights. Those first ten amendments, collectively called the Bill of Rights, were proposed in 1789 and ratified in 1791, two years after the Constitution took effect. Therefore, the Bill of Rights was not in the original Constitution, but was added later through amendments.

Fred and George Weasley are portrayed by actors James and Oliver Phelps in the Harry Potter films. James and Oliver Phelps were born on 25 February 1986 and are real-life twin brothers, so the actors playing Fred and George are indeed twins outside the films as well.

In Disney’s classic animated films, both Alice in ‘Alice in Wonderland’ (1951) and Wendy Darling in ‘Peter Pan’ (1953) were voiced by the same actress, Kathryn Beaumont.

Large predatory fish accumulate mercury as they feed on smaller fish over their lifetimes (bio-accumulation). Tuna—especially larger species such as albacore, yellowfin, and particularly bigeye and bluefin—therefore tend to have relatively high mercury concentrations compared with smaller, short-lived fish. While canned light (skipjack) tuna is lower than other tuna types, tuna as a category is still considered a higher-mercury seafood that health agencies advise limiting, especially for pregnant women and children.

The Federal Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act of 1938 greatly expanded the FDA’s authority, required safety testing for drugs, mandated accurate labeling, and created enforceable standards that substantially reduced the incidence of unsafe or mislabeled products on the U.S. market. Although not perfect and later amended, it is widely judged by historians and public-health scholars as achieving its primary objectives of improving consumer protection, indicating overall success.

After Germany invaded Poland on 1 September 1939, both the United Kingdom and France issued ultimatums demanding German withdrawal. When these were ignored, France formally declared war on Germany on 3 September 1939, entering World War II on the Allied side.

Under the Criminal Code of Canada (e.g., sections 320.13–320.19), operating a motor vehicle while impaired by alcohol or drugs, or with a blood-alcohol concentration at or above the legal limit (0.08), is explicitly designated as a criminal offence. Conviction can lead to fines, licence suspension, and possible imprisonment. Therefore, impaired driving is indeed a criminal offence in Canada.

Guernsey issues its own pound notes and coins that are pegged to, and backed by, pound sterling. While most UK retailers will often accept Channel Islands currency by choice, ‘legal tender’ has a specific legal meaning: only Bank of England notes (in England and Wales) and certain UK coins qualify. Turkey has been an official candidate for EU membership since 1999 and has conducted accession negotiations, but it has never completed the accession process, so it is not currently an EU member state.

British Overseas Territories, including the Falkland Islands, are not separate members of the Commonwealth of Nations, but they are regarded as being ‘part of the Commonwealth’ through their constitutional link with the United Kingdom (which is a full member). Therefore, in the sense usually intended by the question, the Falkland Islands are considered part of the Commonwealth.

A “correctional facility” is an umbrella term for any place where individuals are held for correctional purposes, including prisons, jails, detention centers, halfway houses, etc. A prison is just one specific type of correctional facility (typically long-term confinement after conviction). Therefore, prisons and correctional facilities are not identical concepts; prisons are a subset of correctional facilities.

The American Civil War lasted from 1861 to 1865. Michigan was admitted to the Union much earlier, on January 26, 1837, as the 26th state. Therefore, during the Civil War period, Michigan was indeed already a state.
Company of Heroes 2 launched with a single-player story mode that follows the Soviet Red Army on the Eastern Front, so it indeed contains a campaign.

Even in the very early days of professional baseball, no club recognized as a major-league team has ever completed a season—regular season and/or postseason—without a loss. The schedule is far too long (even in the 1800s it exceeded 60 games), and every club on record has at least one defeat. The closest thing was the 1869 Cincinnati Red Stockings, who went 67-0, but that was before the formation of the first professional major league (the National League began in 1876). Therefore, within Major League Baseball history, an undefeated season has never occurred.

Both cities are nominally in the Mountain Time Zone, but Arizona (Phoenix) does not observe daylight-saving time while Colorado (Denver) does. Since the question asks if they are the same time zone in general, the most accurate single answer is no.

Although both are brass instruments pitched in B-flat and look alike, the euphonium has a larger, mostly conical bore and wider bell, giving it a darker, more mellow tone, whereas the baritone horn has a smaller, more cylindrical bore and narrower bell, producing a brighter, lighter sound. Their tubing wrap and typical parts written in band scores also differ. Hence, they are not the same instrument.

Reasoning: Grizzly bears are native to North America and still inhabit several regions of the United States, including Alaska and portions of the northern Rocky Mountains (e.g., Montana, Wyoming, Idaho, and parts of Washington). Therefore, grizzly bears are indeed present in the U.S.

“Baby back” ribs is a common retail/restaurant name for the pork ribs cut from the top of the rib cage where it meets the loin. In the meat industry they are officially called “pork loin back ribs.” Thus, pork loin ribs (more precisely pork loin back ribs) and baby back ribs refer to the same cut.

The Xbox One includes a backward-compatibility feature that allows it to run a large catalog of Xbox 360 titles (both on disc and digital), though not every single 360 game is supported. Because the question asks in general whether Xbox 360 games can be played on an Xbox One, the answer is effectively ‘yes,’ with the understanding that support is limited to the approved list.
Elmendorf Air Force Base, now part of Joint Base Elmendorf-Richardson, is located adjacent to Anchorage, Alaska. Therefore an Air Force installation does exist in Anchorage.

Universal life insurance is a form of permanent life insurance. Part of each premium payment goes toward the cost of insurance, and the excess is credited to a policy cash-value account that earns interest. Therefore, by design, a universal life policy accumulates cash value.

Article II, Section 1 of the U.S. Constitution requires the president to be a “natural-born citizen” of the United States. Therefore, U.S. citizenship (specifically natural-born) is mandatory to run for and serve as president.

Under U.S. federal law (18 U.S.C. § 922(g)(6)), anyone who has received a dishonorable discharge from the Armed Forces is classified as a “prohibited person.” Prohibited persons are barred from purchasing, possessing, or receiving firearms or ammunition. Therefore, a dishonorable discharge disqualifies someone from legally buying a gun unless their firearms rights have been specifically restored (a rare occurrence).

The 2018 film “The Strangers: Prey at Night” is officially presented as a sequel (albeit loosely connected) to the 2008 movie “The Strangers,” not as a remake of that original film or of any other. While it features the same masked killers, its storyline and characters are different and it is marketed as a follow-up rather than a retelling.

Izzie Stevens flat-lined during season 5 after brain surgery, but she was resuscitated and ultimately recovered. She later left Seattle Grace in season 6; the character was written out of the series but was never killed off on screen.

Roma is one specific cultivar within the broader class of plum (paste) tomatoes. While every Roma tomato is a plum tomato, not all plum tomatoes are Roma; therefore they are not strictly the same thing.

In most poker variants, the Ace normally ranks as the highest card, but it can also be treated as the lowest card when completing the wheel straight A-2-3-4-5. Thus, an Ace can indeed function as a 1 in specific situations (mainly straights) even though it is otherwise the top-ranked card.

The modern “English Bulldog” (also called the British Bulldog) is a short-legged, heavily wrinkled, very brachycephalic breed developed in the U.K. Primarily a companion dog, it suffers from many respiratory and orthopedic issues. The “Olde English Bulldogge” (often shortened to old English bulldog) is a separate, newer breed created in the United States in the 1970s to recreate the healthier, more athletic bulldogs of the 18th century. It is taller, less wrinkled, has a longer muzzle, and is generally fitter and less prone to the extreme health problems of the modern English Bulldog. Because they have different breed standards, histories, and physical/health characteristics, there is indeed a difference between them.

The venom of a blue-ringed octopus (tetrodotoxin) can cause rapid paralysis and respiratory failure, and without assisted ventilation it is frequently fatal. However, there is no tissue necrosis and the toxin is eventually metabolised. With prompt first aid (pressure-immobilisation) and, critically, artificial respiration/ventilator support until breathing returns, many victims have fully recovered. Therefore survival is possible and documented, although it requires rapid medical intervention.

Indian law, specifically the Citizenship Act of 1955 and subsequent amendments, requires an Indian citizen to renounce Indian citizenship when they voluntarily acquire the citizenship of another country. The Overseas Citizen of India (OCI) card provides certain privileges but is explicitly not citizenship. Therefore, India does not allow dual or multiple citizenships.

In an ectopic pregnancy, the fertilized egg implants outside the uterus, most commonly in a fallopian tube. These locations lack the necessary space and blood supply to support normal fetal development and pose a high risk of life-threatening rupture and hemorrhage for the mother. Although there are extremely rare case reports of abdominal ectopic pregnancies progressing further, they are exceptional and still carry very high maternal and fetal mortality. Therefore, as a general medical fact, an ectopic pregnancy cannot be safely carried to term.

Maine’s current alcohol laws permit the sale of beer, wine, and spirits on Sundays (typically beginning at 9 a.m.). Earlier restrictions that prohibited or limited Sunday sales have been repealed, so consumers can purchase alcohol on Sundays at licensed retailers and restaurants/bars.

In automotive suspension terminology, the component that links the left and right sides of the suspension to reduce body roll is known by several interchangeable names: sway bar, stabilizer bar, and anti-roll bar. These terms all describe the same part and function.

Leonardo DiCaprio received the Academy Award for Best Actor at the 88th Oscars in 2016 for his performance in the film "The Revenant." This was his first acting Oscar win after several previous nominations.

The U.S. Netflix series “House of Cards,” developed by Beau Willimon, was explicitly adapted from the 1990 British miniseries of the same name (itself based on Michael Dobbs’ novel). Therefore, the American version is indeed based on the earlier British series.

Under Article II, Section 4 of the U.S. Constitution, all federal “civil officers,” which include Supreme Court justices, are subject to impeachment by the House and trial/possible removal by the Senate. The Chief Justice has the same constitutional status as the associate justices and therefore can be impeached; there is no immunity or special exception.

The title song “Footloose,” co-written by Kenny Loggins and Dean Pitchford, was commissioned specifically for and first released with the 1984 film ‘Footloose.’ Pitchford wrote the screenplay and collaborated on the soundtrack, so the song did not exist prior to the movie and was purpose-built to accompany it.

In the Marvel Cinematic Universe, the Time Stone is housed within the Eye of Agamotto, but the Eye itself is a separate mystical reliquary that Doctor Strange wears. The Eye can open or close around the Stone, and the Stone can be removed from it, meaning they are not the same object even though they are closely linked.

In the official rules of chess the king is never actually captured or removed from the board. Play stops when a player’s king is in check and there is no legal move to escape (checkmate) or when a player resigns. Any move that would leave one’s own king in check is illegal, so a king cannot be ‘taken out.’

Under the Articles of Confederation the national government consisted of a unicameral Congress only; there was no separate national executive or president with executive powers. Therefore, it is incorrect to say the Articles had an executive branch.

buybuy BABY (often written "Buy Buy Baby") was acquired by Bed Bath & Beyond in 2007 and, until Bed Bath & Beyond’s recent bankruptcy proceedings, operated as a subsidiary of that company. Therefore, in the general sense of corporate ownership, buybuy BABY is/was owned by Bed Bath & Beyond.

Sam’s Club briefly operated in Canada (2003-2009) but Walmart closed all Canadian Sam’s Club warehouse stores. At present the chain has no physical locations in Canada (only U.S. and Puerto Rico, plus e-commerce limited to those markets). Therefore, there are currently no Sam’s Clubs in Canada.

Chemically, you cannot convert lead (Pb) into gold (Au) because chemical reactions do not change atomic nuclei. However, modern nuclear physics shows that by changing the number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus—e.g., via neutron capture in a reactor or particle‐beam bombardment in an accelerator—you can transmute lead (or other elements like mercury or bismuth) into isotopes of gold. This has been demonstrated experimentally, though it is prohibitively expensive and yields minute amounts. Therefore, in principle it is possible, even if impractical.

Caesar Creek Lake in southwest Ohio is an Army Corps of Engineers reservoir formed in the early 1970s. To build the lake, the small farming community of New Burlington (along with scattered farms and structures) was acquired, razed, and the site was subsequently flooded. The remains of that community now lie beneath or at the margin of the lake basin, depending on water level. Hence, there is indeed a former town underneath Caesar’s Creek.

Engines differ in physical size, weight, mounting points, electronics, cooling, emissions requirements, and compatibility with the transmission and drivetrain. While with enough fabrication almost any swap is theoretically possible, in practical terms you cannot simply take any engine and install it in any car without extensive modification—often making the swap infeasible or illegal for road use.

Disposable income is the amount of personal income left after paying taxes. Discretionary income is what remains after paying both taxes and necessary living expenses (e.g., housing, food, utilities). Therefore, discretionary income is a subset of disposable income, and the two terms are not the same.

There are numerous published English versions of the Torah—such as the Jewish Publication Society (JPS) translation, the Artscroll Stone Edition, the Fox translation, Everett-Fox’s Schocken Bible, etc.—so an English translation definitely exists.

“Sausage dog” is simply a popular, informal nickname for the dachshund, referring to the breed’s long, low body shape. There is no separate breed officially called the sausage dog; both terms describe the same breed of dog.

The U.S. Virgin Islands (St. Thomas, St. John, St. Croix and surrounding islets) are located in the Caribbean Sea and are geographically part of the Lesser Antilles island chain. Therefore, they are considered a part of the Caribbean region.

answer: Yes, there is a season 2 of Case Histories.
Reasoning: The BBC television adaptation of Kate Atkinson’s ‘Case Histories’ starring Jason Isaacs first aired in 2011. A second series (often listed as Season 2) consisting of three 90-minute episodes was later produced and broadcast in 2013. It is available on various streaming and home-video platforms, confirming that a Season 2 exists.
Answer: Yes, there is a season 2 of Case Histories.

Reasoning: Legally, a signature is any unique mark that a person intends to use as their signature to authenticate a document. It can be a scribble, initials, a symbol, or even a digital mark; it does not have to clearly spell out the signer’s name as long as it is affixed with intent to sign.

Scotland’s men’s national football team has reached the FIFA World Cup finals on multiple occasions (e.g., 1954, 1958, 1974, 1978, 1982, 1986, 1990, 1998). Therefore, they have indeed qualified for the tournament.

In the U.S. Congress the tactic known as a filibuster—unlimited debate used to delay or block legislation—is only available in the Senate. The House of Representatives operates under strict rules that limit debate time, controlled by the Rules Committee and the Speaker, so members cannot employ an unlimited-debate strategy. Therefore, a filibuster cannot take place in the House under its current rules.

Great Britain is the geographical island that contains England, Scotland, and Wales. The Isle of Man is a separate island and a self-governing Crown Dependency; it is not part of that island nor politically part of Great Britain.

Canary Wharf is a major business district located in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets. Geographically, it occupies part of the peninsula in East London known as the Isle of Dogs. Therefore, Canary Wharf is situated on (within) the Isle of Dogs.

A standard American football field, including end zones, measures 120 yards (109.7 m) long by 53⅓ yards (48.8 m) wide, giving an area of about 6,400 m². A rugby union pitch can be up to 144 m (157 yd) long (including in-goal areas) and up to 70 m (77 yd) wide, for a maximum area of roughly 10,000 m². Even at the minimum allowed dimensions, a rugby field is still generally wider and often slightly longer than an American football field, so its overall playing area is larger.

In the species Antilocapra americana (the pronghorn), both sexes develop bony horn cores covered by a keratinous sheath. Males have prominent, up-curving horns with a forward-pointing prong, whereas females usually possess much smaller, sometimes rudimentary horns that may even be absent in some individuals, but the species is characterized by the presence of horns in both sexes overall.
By definition, a prime factor must itself be a prime number. The integer 1 is explicitly excluded from the set of prime numbers, so it cannot be a prime factor of any number.

Medically, the large intestine consists of the cecum, colon, rectum and anal canal. The colon—comprising the ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid segments—makes up the largest portion but not the entirety of the large intestine. Therefore the colon is a part of, but not identical to, the large intestine (though the terms are sometimes used interchangeably in casual speech).

In English the word orange entered the language via Sanskrit->Arabic->Old French to refer to the citrus fruit. Only after the fruit became familiar did English speakers adopt the same word to label the reddish-yellow hue. Therefore, the fruit is not named after the color; the color is named after the fruit.

In golf terminology, both a “double eagle” and an “albatross” describe completing a hole three strokes under par (e.g., scoring a 2 on a par-5 or a 1 on a par-4). The two terms are used interchangeably, so they denote the same achievement.

Under Major League Baseball’s official scoring rules, a player is not charged with an at-bat when he hits a sacrifice fly. It is still a plate appearance (used in the on-base-percentage calculation) but it is explicitly excluded from the at-bat total, so it does not lower the batter’s batting average.

In most jurisdictions jaywalking (crossing a street outside a marked crosswalk or against a signal) is a citable traffic infraction. Officers can and do issue tickets for it, though enforcement levels vary by location.

In an adiabatic process no heat is exchanged (Q = 0), but work can still be done on or by the system. For most adiabatic expansions or compressions this work changes the internal energy and therefore the temperature. Only in special cases (e.g., an ideal-gas free expansion with no work) would the temperature stay the same. Thus, temperature is not generally constant in an adiabatic process.

The term “Gulf Stream” refers specifically to the warm, fast north‐flowing ocean current originating in the Gulf of Mexico and moving along the eastern coast of the United States before crossing the North Atlantic. This current system is located in the Atlantic Ocean. While the Pacific has its own major currents (e.g., the Kuroshio Current, California Current), none of these are called the Gulf Stream.

A government-issued birth certificate establishes a person’s legal name, date of birth, and citizenship status, so it is technically a form of identification. However, it does not contain a photograph or signature, so many situations (e.g., air travel, purchasing alcohol) require a photo ID in addition to or instead of a birth certificate.

“Indefinite Leave to Remain” (ILR) is a specific UK immigration status granted under domestic immigration rules. EU citizens do not acquire ILR automatically by virtue of being EU citizens. Before Brexit they exercised free-movement rights, and since Brexit they must apply under the EU Settlement Scheme: after five years’ residence they can obtain “settled status,” which is equivalent to ILR, but it is not automatic. Therefore, simply being an EU citizen does not confer ILR.

The Brisbane River is generally not considered safe for recreational swimming due to several factors: poor water quality after rainfall, strong tidal currents, submerged debris, and the presence of bull sharks. Local authorities (e.g., Brisbane City Council and Queensland Health) advise against swimming in the river, recommending instead designated, monitored swimming areas such as public pools or patrolled beaches.

The 2000 film "Vertical Limit" is a fictional action-adventure story set on K2. While it borrows general elements from real high-altitude climbing (e.g., dangers of altitude sickness, rescue logistics), neither the characters nor the specific events depicted are based on an actual historical expedition. Thus, it is not a true story.

A CPAP (Continuous Positive Airway Pressure) device delivers a constant level of positive pressure through a mask to keep the upper airway open, primarily used for conditions such as obstructive sleep apnea. A mechanical ventilator, by contrast, can actively deliver breaths—controlling or assisting both inspiration and expiration—and is used for a wide range of respiratory failure situations, often via an endotracheal tube. While CPAP is considered a form of non-invasive positive pressure support, it does not perform the full range of ventilatory functions that a mechanical ventilator does. Therefore, they are related but not the same.

A regular pentagon can be divided into 5 congruent isosceles triangles by drawing segments from its center to the vertices, but those triangles are not equilateral (their vertex angle is 72°, not 60°). Five equilateral triangles meeting at a point would sum to 5×60° = 300°, leaving a gap, so they cannot form a pentagon. Therefore a pentagon is not made of 5 equilateral triangles.

Period 6 of the periodic table contains several s- and p-block elements such as Cs (Group 1), Ba (Group 2), and the p-block elements Tl, Pb, Bi, Po, At, and Rn. These groups constitute the main-group elements, so at least one (in fact, many) main-group elements are present in period 6.

Air Canada Rouge is a separate leisure-oriented, low-cost subsidiary owned by Air Canada. Although it is part of the Air Canada group and shares its parent company, it operates under its own brand, fleet configuration, and service model, so it is not exactly the same airline as Air Canada.

Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) opened the eBART extension to eastern Contra Costa County in 2018, which includes the Antioch Station located near Hillcrest Avenue in Antioch, CA. Therefore, Antioch does indeed have a BART station.

The United Kingdom is made up of England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. Canada and Australia are independent sovereign nations. Although they share the same monarch as the UK (they are Commonwealth realms), they are not constitutionally or politically part of the United Kingdom.

The European Economic Area (EEA) consists of the 27 European Union member states plus the three EFTA states Norway, Iceland, and Liechtenstein. Turkey is not an EU member and is not one of the three EFTA‐EEA states; it only has a customs union agreement with the EU. Therefore, Turkey is not part of the EEA.

The television series 'Sex and the City' was set in Manhattan and, unlike many shows that recreate New York on back-lot sets elsewhere, it was largely shot on location throughout New York City (with interior sets built in local studios such as Silvercup Studios in Queens). Therefore the series was indeed filmed in New York.

West Texas A&M University (WTAMU) is an independent regional university located in Canyon, Texas, but it is one of the 11 universities that belong to the Texas A&M University System. Therefore, while it is not a branch campus of Texas A&M University in College Station, it is indeed part of the larger Texas A&M University System.

In the sitcom ‘That ’70s Show,’ the character Laurie Forman (Eric’s sister) was originally portrayed by Lisa Robin Kelly (seasons 1-3 and brief return in season 5). After Kelly left the series, the role was recast with actress Christina Moore for season 6. Therefore, the show did change the actress who played the sister.

In C++ the common string type is std::string (or std::basic_string). Users do not have to supply or manage a terminating null character; the class manages its own storage. Accessors such as c_str() guarantee a null-terminated buffer, but the string object itself does not require the programmer to append '\0'. Therefore, the statement that C++ strings *need* to be null-terminated (by the programmer) is false.

In a mature seed, the micropyle is a small opening in the seed coat that originally allowed the pollen tube to enter the ovule. During germination, this same opening permits water uptake and is the point through which the radicle (embryonic root) commonly emerges. Hence, the micropyle indeed serves for the emergence of the radicle.

Croatia’s men’s national soccer team has not only participated in FIFA World Cups but has finished on the podium multiple times—3rd place in 1998, 2nd place in 2018, and 3rd place again in 2022. Therefore, Croatia has indeed ‘placed’ in the World Cup.

The 1981 film "Chariots of Fire" dramatizes the real lives of two British athletes, Eric Liddell and Harold Abrahams, and their preparation for and participation in the 1924 Paris Olympics. Although some details are fictionalized for dramatic effect, the central story and characters are historical, so the film is indeed based on true events.
The 2008 film “The Boy in the Striped Pajamas” was adapted from the 2006 novel of the same name by author John Boyne, so the movie is indeed based on a book.
Sudan and South Sudan are two distinct sovereign states. South Sudan declared independence from Sudan after a 2011 referendum and was internationally recognized as a separate country on 9 July 2011.

Traditional silk production normally kills the silkworm pupa when cocoons are boiled to reel off a long, continuous filament. However, several alternative methods (often marketed as “Ahimsa” or “peace” silk) allow the moth to emerge naturally or the cocoon to be carefully cut open first. The filament length is shorter and production costs rise, but viable silk can still be spun. Therefore it is indeed possible to make silk without killing the worm, though it is not the standard industrial approach.

The 1906 San Francisco earthquake occurred along the mainly strike-slip San Andreas Fault, which produced little vertical seafloor displacement. Contemporary observations and later USGS reviews note only minor water disturbances (seiches and small local waves), but no true or damaging tsunami was generated.

Home Bargains and Quality Save are both U.K. discount retailers and for many years Quality Save was supplied and merchandised by Home Bargains’ parent company (TJ Morris). Because of that agreement their product ranges, prices and even in-store signage looked very similar. Nevertheless they are (or, until recent store conversions, were) legally separate businesses with different ownership and separate store estates; only a handful of Quality Save branches have been re-branded as Home Bargains. Therefore they are not the same company, just closely linked.

The amniotic sac is formed by the amnion, which enlarges and envelops both the fetus and the connecting stalk. As the connecting stalk elongates to become the umbilical cord, it, too, becomes covered by the amnion and lies bathed in amniotic fluid alongside the fetus. Therefore the umbilical cord resides within (and is surrounded by) the amniotic sac.

Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory of the United States. Under the Territorial Clause of the U.S. Constitution, Congress has plenary power over territories, and federal statutes generally apply there unless Congress explicitly states otherwise.
