The Nobel Peace Prize is intended as an annual prize, but in a number of years—especially during the two World Wars and a few other occasions—no award was made. Therefore, the statement that it is awarded every single year is not strictly correct.
‘Finders Keepers’ is the second book in Stephen King’s Bill Hodges trilogy, directly following the events of the first book, ‘Mr. Mercedes,’ so it is indeed a sequel.

For the 2018 FIFA World Cup, the Republic of Ireland finished second in their UEFA qualifying group and entered a two-leg playoff against Denmark. They drew the first leg 0-0 and lost the second leg 5-1, so they were eliminated. Northern Ireland also failed in their playoff. Therefore no Irish team qualified for the 2018 World Cup.

In many Western folk traditions, four-leaf clovers are regarded as symbols of good fortune because they are rare mutations of the common three-leaf clover; therefore, finding one is widely interpreted as a lucky event.

Andrew Lloyd Webber’s 1986 stage production “The Phantom of the Opera” is one of the most famous works in musical theatre. While the story originated as a 1910 novel and has film adaptations, the title commonly refers to the long-running stage musical.

The Dominican Republic is an independent sovereign nation occupying the eastern portion of the island of Hispaniola in the Caribbean. It has its own government, constitution, and international recognition, and is neither a U.S. state, territory, nor commonwealth. Therefore, it is not considered part of the United States.

The person most commonly identified as the lead singer of Skid Row is the band’s original front-man, Sebastian Bach, who sang on their hit albums from 1987–1996. Sebastian Bach is still alive. (A later vocalist, Johnny Solinger, passed away in 2021, but he is not usually meant when people refer to “the” lead singer of Skid Row.) Therefore, the statement that the lead singer of Skid Row is dead is incorrect if referring to the primary/original singer.

Both institutions commonly referred to as the University of St. Thomas (Minnesota and Texas) are private Catholic universities organized under U.S. 501(c)(3) regulations as charitable, educational organizations. Such institutions are legally classified as nonprofit entities rather than for-profit corporations.

A stem-and-leaf plot is one of the classic exploratory data-analysis displays introduced by John Tukey. It visually represents the distribution of numerical data by splitting each value into a ‘stem’ and a ‘leaf,’ allowing the overall shape of the data to be seen at a glance. Because it is used to graphically depict data rather than just listing numbers in a table, it is classified as a type of graph or plot in statistics textbooks.
Mount Fuji is about 3,776 m tall. Many mountains are higher; for example, Mount Everest reaches 8,848 m above sea level. Therefore, Mount Fuji is not the tallest mountain in the world.

Historical records of the race show several incidents in which riders lost their lives while competing, such as Adolphe Hélière (1910), Francisco Cepeda (1935), Tom Simpson (1967) and Fabio Casartelli (1995). Therefore, at least one person has indeed died during the Tour de France.

The writer-director Dan Gilroy has said the film and its title character are his own creation, though he drew loose inspiration from the general history of civil-rights lawyers in Los Angeles. There is no single real-life lawyer or case that the plot follows, so it is considered a work of fiction rather than a true story.

In The Vampire Diaries, Damon is bitten by the werewolf-turned Tyler. A werewolf bite is normally fatal to vampires, but it is revealed that the blood of the Original hybrid Klaus can cure it. Stefan trades his loyalty to Klaus for a vial of Klaus’s blood, which Katherine brings to Damon. Damon drinks it and recovers, so a cure is indeed found and used on him.

The Heat Index is a standardized NOAA measure that combines only air temperature and relative humidity to indicate how hot it feels. “RealFeel” (or similarly branded ‘feels-like’ values) is a proprietary index that folds in additional factors such as wind speed, solar radiation, cloud cover, elevation, etc. Because RealFeel uses more variables and a different algorithm, it can differ from the Heat Index even under the same conditions. Therefore, they are not the same concept.

The U.S. Treasury did issue $1,000 bills for many years (mostly for large inter-bank transactions); the last printing was in 1945, and they were officially discontinued for circulation in 1969. Therefore, such bills were indeed made in the past.

The English Channel is commonly described in geographic references as an arm of the Atlantic Ocean that separates southern England from northern France and links the Atlantic with the North Sea. Therefore, it is considered part of the Atlantic Ocean.

In the United States the Constitution’s 16th Amendment gives Congress the power to levy an income tax, and Congress exercised that power by enacting the Internal Revenue Code (Title 26 of the U.S. Code). Sections such as 1, 61, 6012, 6151 and 6154 expressly impose the income tax and require individuals who meet filing thresholds to file returns and pay the tax. Courts have repeatedly upheld the validity of these provisions and rejected claims that no law requires payment of taxes.

Yes. In the early decades of Major League Baseball, games were sometimes called because of darkness, weather, travel curfews, or other factors and were recorded as ties. Although rules now allow most suspended games to be completed later, occasional ties can still be declared when a game is stopped and the result has no bearing on postseason qualification (e.g., Cubs-Pirates, Sept. 29 2016 ended 1-1). Therefore, MLB history does include games that officially ended in ties.

Automotive and most bicycle brake systems require specially formulated brake fluid (DOT 3, 4, 5, etc.) that can tolerate very high temperatures, will not absorb air or damage rubber seals, and meets strict compressibility standards. General-purpose hydraulic fluids or hydraulic oils used in industrial equipment are petroleum-based and are not compatible with the seals and materials in brake systems; they can cause swelling, leakage, or complete brake failure. Therefore, you should not substitute ordinary hydraulic fluid for brake fluid unless the system explicitly specifies a particular non-standard fluid (e.g., certain bicycles that call for mineral oil only). For typical vehicle brakes, the answer is no.
Only the 2018 FIFA World Cup was hosted in Russia; tournaments in other years have been or will be held in different host countries. Therefore, not all World Cup matches are played in Russia.

The Railroad Retirement system is a separate federal program administered by the Railroad Retirement Board, established specifically for railroad employees. While it has some coordination with Social Security (e.g., Tier I benefits are calculated similarly and payroll taxes are inter-changeable for eligibility), it remains legally and administratively distinct, with its own benefit structure, funding, and oversight. Therefore, railroad retirement is not the same program as Social Security.

Norway, Sweden, and Finland are Nordic countries situated on the Scandinavian Peninsula and adjacent areas, which are geographically and politically recognized as part of the European continent. They also belong to various European institutions (e.g., Council of Europe, EU for Sweden and Finland, EEA for Norway). Hence, they are unquestionably part of Europe.

Soy sauce and Worcestershire sauce are both dark, salty condiments, but they have different origins, ingredient lists, and flavor profiles. Soy sauce is primarily made from fermented soybeans, wheat, salt, and water. Worcestershire sauce, on the other hand, is a vinegar-based condiment that includes ingredients such as molasses, tamarind, anchovies, onions, garlic, and various spices. Because their compositions and tastes differ, they are not the same sauce, even though they may sometimes be used for similar culinary purposes.

In a vehicle, the engine is the power-producing unit that burns fuel (or uses electricity) to generate rotational force. The transmission is a separate system of gears and related components that takes that rotational force and adjusts the torque and speed delivered to the wheels. Because they serve different functions and are physically distinct assemblies, they are not the same thing.

As of my latest information, the most recent entry in the Child’s Play franchise was the Chucky television series (premiering in 2021 and renewed since). Neither the team behind the original Don Mancini continuity nor the studio that produced the 2019 remake has officially announced a new Child’s Play feature film in active production or with a firm release date. There have been only general statements of interest in returning to movies at some point. Therefore, at present, there is no confirmed new Child’s Play movie ‘coming out.’

On Earth, the summer solstice (in either hemisphere) is defined as the point at which that hemisphere is tilted most directly toward the Sun. Because of this tilt, the Sun follows its longest and highest apparent path across the sky, giving the location its greatest amount of daylight in the year. In everyday usage, this makes the summer solstice ‘the longest day of the year.’ (If one interprets ‘day’ as the 24-hour rotation period, the duration is the same, but the common meaning refers to daylight length.)

Some cultivars of watermelon have naturally yellow flesh due to lacking lycopene, the pigment that makes most watermelons red. These yellow-fleshed varieties are commercially grown and sold, so yellow watermelon does in fact exist.

A J.D. (Juris Doctor) is classified as a professional doctorate and is the first professional degree required to practice law in the United States. Although its formal title contains the word “Doctor,” it is not the same type of doctorate as a research doctorate such as a Ph.D. or Ed.D. Professional doctorates focus on preparing practitioners, whereas research doctorates emphasize original scholarly research. Because the term “doctorate” is commonly used to refer to research doctorates, a J.D. is generally not regarded as the same as ‘a doctorate’ in that sense.
Nitric oxide (NO) and nitrous oxide (N₂O) are different chemical compounds with distinct molecular formulas, properties and biological effects. Therefore they are not the same substance.

Eight Below is not a documentary, but its storyline is adapted from real events—the 1958 Japanese Antarctic Research Expedition, in which a team of sled dogs (most famously Taro and Jiro) were left behind and later survived. While many details were fictionalized for dramatic effect, the core premise is based on that historical incident, so it is considered to be inspired by a true story.

The July 27 total lunar eclipse (most recently on July 27–28, 2018) occurred during hours when North America was turned away from the Moon; the event was visible mainly from Europe, Africa, Asia, and Australia, but not from the continental United States (or most of North America). Therefore observers in the USA could not see that eclipse.

The ABC soap opera ‘One Life to Live’ ended its original network run in January 2012. A brief online-only revival occurred in 2013, but no new episodes have been produced or broadcast since then. While archived episodes may appear on streaming platforms or specialty channels, the series is no longer an active, regularly airing television program.

Michigan has hosted multiple commercial nuclear power facilities, including the Enrico Fermi Nuclear Generating Station (still operating) and the Donald C. Cook Nuclear Plant (also operating). Although the Palisades plant shut down in 2022, at least two reactors remain in service, so the state does have nuclear power plants.

In a ratio, the first number represents the amount of the first quantity relative to the second number’s quantity. Reversing the order (e.g., 2:3 vs. 3:2) changes the relationship unless the two numbers are equal, so the position of each number matters.

While both garments are intended to shape or support the body, a corset is a stiff, usually boned and lace-up garment that encases the torso to cinch the waist and support or shape the bust. A (modern) girdle is an elasticized undergarment that fits around the waist and hips to smooth or lightly compress the abdomen and thighs; it is generally flexible and lacks the rigid structure and lacing of a corset. Therefore, they are related but not the same item.

Microsoft added a backward-compatibility program for Xbox One that lets the console run a large library of Xbox 360 titles through software emulation—either by inserting the original disc or downloading a digital copy linked to the user’s account. Although not every single 360 game is supported, the majority of popular titles are, so in general you can play Xbox 360 games on an Xbox One.

Universal Orlando has two Harry-Potter–themed areas. The original Wizarding World of Harry Potter – Hogsmeade is located inside Universal’s Islands of Adventure. (Another area, Diagon Alley, is in the adjacent Universal Studios Florida.) Therefore the statement that Harry Potter world is in Islands of Adventure is essentially correct.

Under U.S. immigration law (INA §208), a person may apply for asylum only if he or she is ‘physically present in the United States or has arrived in the United States (whether or not at a designated port of arrival).’ Someone located outside U.S. territory must instead seek refugee status through the U.S. Refugee Admissions Program. Therefore, being on U.S. soil (or at a port of entry, which is legally treated as U.S. territory) is required to file an asylum application.

The original Twin Towers were destroyed in 2001. What many people think of as ‘lighting up the Twin Towers’ is actually the “Tribute in Light,” two powerful beams that are projected into the sky from lower Manhattan on the night of September 11 each year (and occasionally for special commemorations). Those beams are not illuminated on a nightly basis.

Yes. It is rare but it has happened several times in NHL history—for example, the 1942 Toronto Maple Leafs, the 1975 New York Islanders, the 2010 Philadelphia Flyers, and the 2014 Los Angeles Kings all erased 3-0 series deficits to win a best-of-seven playoff series.

answer: Yes. A law-abiding adult may carry a gun in a vehicle in Montana without a permit.
Reasoning: Montana is now a constitutional-carry state (HB 102, 2021). Anyone 18 or older who may lawfully possess a firearm may carry it—openly or concealed—without a permit, including in a motor vehicle, whether inside or outside city limits. Normal prohibitions (e.g., federal gun-free school zones, certain government buildings, private ‘no-guns’ property) still apply, but simply having or carrying a gun in your car is legal.
Answer: Yes. A law-abiding adult may carry a gun in a vehicle in Montana without a permit.

Reasoning: Beginning May 7 2025, to board a domestic commercial flight or enter certain federal facilities you must present either a state driver’s license/ID that is Real ID-compliant or another form of identification that the federal government already accepts. The U.S. passport card is a federally issued identity document and is on TSA’s list of acceptable IDs. Therefore, even though the passport card itself is not labeled “Real ID,” it satisfies the same federal identification requirement and can be used in place of a Real ID-compliant driver’s license.

Spark plugs are manufactured with several different hex sizes (e.g., 5/8 in., 13/16 in., 3/4 in., 14 mm, etc.), and different engines specify different plug sizes. Therefore no single socket size fits every spark plug.

In the United States (and most common-law jurisdictions) the Double Jeopardy Clause bars a person from being prosecuted twice for the same offense by the same sovereign once there has been a final verdict of guilty or not-guilty. Because the government is forbidden to prosecute again, it also cannot validly arrest you a second time for that identical charge arising from the same incident. There are limited exceptions—e.g., if the first case ended in a mistrial, the charges were dismissed without prejudice, or a different sovereign (state vs. federal) brings its own charges—but after an acquittal or conviction on the merits, the same authority cannot arrest you again for that same crime.

Steve Blass was a pitcher for the Pittsburgh Pirates whose career was shortened by control problems (often referred to as “Steve Blass disease”). While he had notable seasons—especially 1971—and later became a longtime broadcaster, his overall career résumé is not considered Hall-of-Fame caliber and he has never been elected to the National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown.

Since its introduction in 1991, the Ford Explorer has been offered in multiple drivetrain configurations. Many trim levels can be ordered with either rear-wheel drive (RWD), front-wheel drive (FWD on the unibody generations), all-wheel drive (AWD) or traditional selectable 4-wheel drive (4WD). Because two-wheel-drive versions have always been available alongside 4WD/AWD versions, it is not true that every Explorer comes with 4-wheel drive.

The ‘Ring of Fire’ refers to the chain of active subduction zones and associated volcanoes and earthquakes that generally trace the margins of the Pacific Plate. Mainland Australia sits well inside the Indo-Australian Plate and is distant from those active plate boundaries, so it is not usually described as being on the Ring of Fire, even though nearby regions such as Indonesia, Papua New Guinea and New Zealand (which lie on or near the Australia-Pacific plate boundary) are included. Thus, in common usage, Australia itself is considered outside the Ring of Fire.

In eukaryotic mRNA, transcription continues well past the stop codon. The pre-mRNA is then cleaved at a specific polyadenylation site located in the 3′ untranslated region (typically 10–30 nucleotides downstream of the AAUAAA signal). After cleavage, poly(A) polymerase adds the poly-A tail. Therefore, the poly-A tail is not added immediately after the stop codon; there is usually a stretch of 3′-UTR sequence between the stop codon and the polyadenylation site.

Under traditional common-law property principles, the defining characteristic of a joint tenancy is the right of survivorship: when one joint tenant dies, his or her interest automatically passes to the remaining joint tenants. Because this survivorship feature is inherent, the phrase “joint tenancy with right of survivorship” is essentially a more explicit way of saying “joint tenancy.” Some jurisdictions require the survivorship language to be stated expressly in the deed, but the legal estate being described is the same.

answer: Generally no—persistent symptoms are called PTLDS, not chronic ongoing infection.
Reasoning: Most major medical and public-health bodies (e.g., CDC, Infectious Diseases Society of America) do not recognize an ongoing, active infection called “chronic Lyme disease.” After appropriate antibiotic therapy, evidence shows that the Borrelia bacteria are usually eradicated. A subset of patients do experience fatigue, pain, or cognitive complaints lasting months to a few years; this is termed Post-Treatment Lyme Disease Syndrome (PTLDS). Thus, while persistent symptoms can occur, the concept of an ongoing, treatment-resistant infection dubbed “chronic Lyme disease” is not supported by current scientific evidence.
Answer: Generally no—persistent symptoms are called PTLDS, not chronic ongoing infection.

Reasoning: The basic ‘reflex’ or reflector sight—an unmagnified optic that projects an illuminated aiming mark onto a partially-silvered lens—was invented in 1900 (Collimator/Reflector sight by Howard Grubb).  By the 1930s these sights had become standard equipment on fighter aircraft, and during World War II they were widely fielded (e.g., British Mk II & Mk III reflector gunsights, American N-3/N-9, K-14 gyro-reflector sight, German Revi series).  Although far less common on individual infantry weapons, the technology clearly existed and was in extensive wartime use on aircraft and some naval/AA mounts.  Therefore, reflex sights did indeed exist in World War II.

Fox officially renewed New Girl for a seventh and final season in May 2017; the 8-episode Season 7 premiered in April 2018. Therefore, the answer to whether there will be a 7th season is yes (and it has already aired).

New York’s 1995 capital punishment statute was declared unconstitutional by the New York Court of Appeals in 2004 (People v. LaValle). The legislature has never amended the law to address the court’s concerns, and the remaining death sentences were vacated in 2007. Therefore, New York currently has no active death-penalty statute; capital punishment cannot be imposed under state law (though federal death penalty can still apply for federal crimes).
The FIFA World Cup, the premier international tournament in soccer, is normally held every four years (for both the men’s and women’s tournaments). Therefore, it is not an annual event.

In most contexts, ln x specifically means the natural logarithm (base e), whereas log x can denote a logarithm with a different base—commonly base 10 in engineering or base e in some higher-level mathematics texts. Because the base is not universally the same, log x is not inherently identical to ln x.

The coding region (CDS) is formally defined as the stretch of nucleotides that is translated into amino-acid sequence. Translation stops when the ribosome reaches a stop codon; because the stop codon itself does not encode an amino acid, it is conventionally excluded from the CDS. Thus, although the stop codon is present in the mRNA, it is not considered part of the coding region.

Continental groupings are based more on cultural-historical convention than tectonic plates. In most geographic classifications, the Caribbean islands (and the region as a whole) are treated as a sub-region of North America rather than South America, even though a few islands lie just off the South American coast.

The Big Dipper is an asterism—a recognizable pattern of stars—located within the larger constellation Ursa Major. While every star in the Big Dipper belongs to Ursa Major, the constellation also contains additional stars outside the Big Dipper pattern. Therefore, they are related but not identical.

PCP (phencyclidine) is the chemical name of a dissociative anesthetic. 'Angel dust' is a common street name that specifically refers to PCP in its illicit, powdered form. Therefore, they denote the same drug.

In 1898—14 years before the RMS Titanic was built—author Morgan Robertson published the novella “Futility, or the Wreck of the Titan.” The story describes an ‘unsinkable’ British passenger liner named the Titan that hits an iceberg in the North Atlantic in April and sinks with heavy loss of life because there are too few lifeboats, closely mirroring details of the real Titanic disaster in 1912. Because of these striking similarities, the book is frequently cited as having ‘predicted’ the Titanic’s fate, even though it was a work of fiction and not an intentional prophecy.
Answer: Yes. The 1898 novella “Futility, or the Wreck of the Titan” contained numerous parallels to the real Titanic disaster and is often said to have predicted it.

Reasoning: The question refers to Fred Sirieix, the maître d’ on Channel 4’s “First Dates.” Public interviews and social-media posts indicate that he is in a long-term relationship with a woman he calls “Fruitcake,” and in 2020 he announced they were engaged. Therefore, he does have a partner.

Many nations around the world observe daylight-saving time (DST) or similar seasonal clock changes—e.g., the United States, Canada, most of continental Europe, parts of Australia and New Zealand, Israel, etc. Therefore, England (the UK) is far from the only country that changes its clocks.

The word “buzzard” is used differently in different parts of the world. In Europe it refers to hawks in the genus Buteo, which are not vultures at all. In North America, however, people often use “buzzard” informally to mean a turkey vulture or other New World vultures. Biologically, vultures form their own distinct groups (Old World vultures in family Accipitridae and New World vultures in family Cathartidae), so the two terms are not strictly interchangeable. Therefore, a vulture is not necessarily the same thing as a buzzard, even though the names may overlap in casual North-American usage.

answer: No, there is nothing after the full credits (only mid-credits scenes).
Reasoning: Deadpool 2 contains several humorous scenes during the mid-credits (Deadpool using Cable’s time-travel device to ‘fix’ things), but once the full credits finish rolling there is no additional footage, stinger, or audio. Therefore, strictly speaking, there is nothing at the very end of the movie after all the credits have finished.

Reasoning: Left 4 Dead 2 is primarily a cooperative action game, but it does contain a light narrative that connects the five main campaigns (and the additional DLC campaigns) into a chronological journey of four survivors escaping the infected outbreak. Dialogue, environmental clues, and the order of the campaigns provide a cohesive—if minimal—story arc, so the game does indeed have a story rather than being a series of unrelated levels.

Several touchscreen-equipped mobile phones appeared well before Apple released the first iPhone in 2007 (e.g., IBM Simon in 1994, various Palm and Windows Mobile handsets, LG Prada in 2006). Therefore the iPhone was not the first touchscreen phone.

In the FIFA World Cup, the host nation is chosen years in advance through a bidding and voting process conducted by FIFA, not awarded automatically to the team that won the previous tournament. Past winners have not automatically hosted the following World Cup (e.g., Germany won in 2014, but Russia hosted in 2018). Therefore, winning the World Cup does not grant hosting rights for the next edition.

Genuine Apple-certified Lightning cables contain a small authentication/identification IC inside the Lightning-connector housing. Apple uses this chip to verify that the accessory is MFi-compliant and to manage power and data lines.

“Guy’s Grocery Games” is filmed on a purpose-built set called Flavortown Market that looks and functions like a grocery store but is actually a studio inside a warehouse, not a public, operating supermarket.

If we interpret the question in the usual NBA-playoff sense, the Chicago Bulls have never lost a best-of-series to the Boston Celtics without winning at least one game. Their most recent postseason meeting (2017) ended 4-2, not 4-0. Regular-season matchups in recent years have also included Bulls wins, so they were not swept there either.

Ford Fusion and Mazda6 are both mid-size sedans, but they are sold by different manufacturers (Ford vs. Mazda) with distinct styling, interiors, engines, and tuning. The first-generation Fusion rode on the Ford CD3 platform that was co-developed with Mazda and shared with the first-generation Mazda6, so they have some mechanical commonality, but they are not the same vehicle.

The ‘National Treasure’ film series currently consists of two theatrical releases: ‘National Treasure’ (2004) and its sequel ‘National Treasure: Book of Secrets’ (2007). Since there is more than one film, the statement is true.

Michigan enacted the Self-Defense Act (Public Act 309) in 2006, which removes the duty to retreat for a person who is not engaged in a crime and is somewhere they have a legal right to be. This statutory language is what is commonly called a stand-your-ground law.

The Chicago White Sox play their home games at Guaranteed Rate Field, while the Chicago Cubs play at Wrigley Field. These are two separate ballparks located on opposite sides of Chicago, so the teams do not share a stadium.

In the original 1960s anime and most subsequent versions of the franchise, Rex Racer disappears, becomes Racer X, and keeps his identity secret. Although Speed occasionally suspects the truth, he is never shown receiving confirmation, and the series ends without him discovering that Racer X is actually his brother.
The 2006 film "300" was followed by a second film titled "300: Rise of an Empire," released in 2014, which continues the story of the Greco-Persian wars. Therefore, a sequel does exist.

The word “privacy” does not appear in the Constitution, but the Supreme Court has long held that various provisions—especially the 1st, 3rd, 4th, 5th, 9th, and 14th Amendments—create an implicit, constitutionally protected right to privacy (e.g., Griswold v. Connecticut, Roe v. Wade, Lawrence v. Texas). Therefore, although not explicitly written, the Constitution is interpreted as protecting a right to privacy.

The Chevrolet Avalanche was built only under the Chevrolet badge; General Motors did not sell a GMC-branded twin with the Midgate cargo system. The only sibling to the Avalanche was the Cadillac Escalade EXT, not a GMC model.

Avengers: Infinity War (2018) was designed as the first part of a two-film story arc. The direct sequel, Avengers: Endgame, was released in 2019 and continues the narrative left unresolved at the end of Infinity War.

In ICD-10 (and in much UK clinical usage) the diagnosis ‘Emotionally Unstable Personality Disorder’ has two sub-types, impulsive and borderline. The borderline type corresponds to what the DSM calls Borderline Personality Disorder (BPD). In everyday clinical practice the terms EUPD and BPD are therefore used interchangeably to describe the same underlying condition.

In rare cases of heteropaternal superfecundation, a woman who releases two eggs in the same ovulatory cycle can have each egg fertilised by sperm from different men through separate acts of intercourse occurring within a few days of each other. The result is fraternal twins with different biological fathers. Documented cases confirm the biological possibility, though it is extremely uncommon.

The best-known Lake George (in the Adirondack region of New York State) is a natural, glacially formed lake that has existed since the last Ice Age, not the result of human construction. Other U.S. lakes named Lake George (e.g., in Florida or Minnesota) are also naturally occurring. Therefore, the statement that Lake George is man-made is incorrect.

A "SIM-free" phone is sold independently of any carrier, meaning it is supplied without a network’s SIM card and, crucially, without any carrier-applied lock. Because it is already unlocked at the point of sale, inserting a SIM from one network does not cause the phone to lock itself to that network; you can still swap in SIM cards from other compatible carriers at any time.

Both fromage frais and quark are spoonable fresh cheeses made by coagulating milk with lactic-acid bacteria and draining some whey, so they taste and look similar. However, EU food codes and common dairy practice treat them as separate products: fromage frais is required to contain live cultures at the point of sale and is usually made from whole or cream-enriched milk, while quark is typically made from skimmed or low-fat milk and may be heat-treated after fermentation so the cultures are no longer active. Their fat and moisture contents and legal definitions therefore differ, so they are considered distinct rather than the same thing.

In 2021 Cartoon Network and HBO Max officially ordered two brand-new seasons of Total Drama Island produced by Fresh TV. Production has been underway and the revival is expected to premiere in the near future (widely reported for 2024). Since an official order exists and episodes are being produced, it is accurate to say that a new Total Drama series is on the way.

Gamma-linolenic acid (GLA) is a naturally occurring omega-6 fatty acid found in several plants. Edible oils such as evening primrose oil, borage (starflower) oil, black-currant seed oil, and hemp seed oil contain appreciable amounts of GLA, so there are indeed dietary sources.

In the UK, the Access to Higher Education Diploma (often called an “access course”) is a Level-3 qualification, equivalent to A-levels or BTECs. It is delivered mainly in further-education colleges and is intended to prepare learners for university study. Because higher education is defined as Level 4 and above (e.g., HNC, HND, foundation degree, bachelor’s degree), an access course itself sits below that threshold and is therefore classed as further education, not higher education.

In standard casino blackjack rules, the dealer is required to continue taking cards (hit) until the dealer’s hand totals at least 17. Therefore, on any hard or soft total of 16 or less, the dealer must hit.

Reverse osmosis (RO) and deionization (DI) are different purification methods. RO forces water through a semi-permeable membrane that removes most dissolved salts, organics, and particles, but some ions usually remain. DI uses ion-exchange resins to specifically remove cations and anions, producing water that can be closer to ion-free. Because the processes and resulting purity differ, RO water is not the same as deionized water.

In the series finale of ‘Friends’, Rachel decides not to move to Paris after Ross confesses his love. She returns to his apartment, they affirm they love each other, and they commit to being together going forward. Hence, the show ends with Ross and Rachel together.

For centuries Europe’s reigning houses repeatedly married one another to cement political alliances. As a result, dynastic lines such as the Windsors (U.K.), Bourbons (Spain, Luxembourg), Glücksburgs (Denmark, Norway, Greece’ line feeding into Spain), Bernadottes (Sweden), Orange-Nassau (Netherlands), Liechtenstein, Grimaldi (Monaco) and others can all be connected through documented genealogies, often sharing common ancestors like Queen Victoria of the U.K. and King Christian IX of Denmark, and, further back, medieval monarchs such as Charlemagne. Although the degree of kinship varies and some houses are only distantly linked, every present-day European royal family can be traced into this interrelated web, making them all related in a genealogical sense.

In every Canadian province and territory the bar exam is part of a broader licensing process. To be eligible you must (1) hold a Canadian common-law (or civil-law in Québec) degree from an accredited law school, or have your foreign credential assessed and approved by the National Committee on Accreditation, (2) register with the provincial law society, and (3) usually complete articling or a practical training program. Because these prerequisites must be met before you are allowed to sit the bar exam, it is not open to just 'anyone.'

Multiple regional versions of the reality series (U.S., Australia, U.K., etc.) continue to produce and broadcast new seasons. For example, the U.S. edition aired Season 17 in late 2023 and has announced Season 18 for 2024, while the Australian and U.K. editions also have upcoming seasons scheduled. Therefore, the show is still on television.

Mexico and Germany have faced each other several times at the men’s FIFA World Cup. Germany (or West Germany) won in 1978 and 1998, and advanced on penalties in 1986. However, in the 2018 World Cup group stage in Russia, Mexico defeated Germany 1–0. Therefore, Mexico has indeed beaten Germany in a World Cup match.

The term “British Isles” is a geographical, not political, designation that covers the entire archipelago comprising Great Britain, the whole island of Ireland (both Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland, often called ‘southern Ireland’ in everyday speech), plus surrounding smaller islands. Therefore, geographically, southern Ireland is included in the British Isles, although the term can be contentious politically.

Public performances of songs are one of the exclusive rights of the copyright owner under U.S. (and most other) copyright laws. Unless an exception applies (e.g., the song is in the public domain, the performance is covered by a blanket license from a performing-rights organization, or the use qualifies as fair use or another statutory exemption such as a face-to-face classroom teaching activity), you must obtain permission or a license before performing a copyrighted song in public. Therefore, in the general case, you cannot legally perform a copyrighted song in public without authorization.

Father’s Day is celebrated on different dates in various countries. For example, the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada observe it on the third Sunday of June, Spain and Italy celebrate on March 19 (St. Joseph’s Day), and Australia marks it on the first Sunday in September. Because these observances fall on differing days, the holiday is not celebrated on the same day worldwide.

The European Renaissance is usually dated from the 14th to the early-17th century. The first practical steam engines (e.g., Thomas Savery’s in 1698, Newcomen’s in 1712) appeared after this period, during the late 17th and early 18th centuries. Earlier devices like Hero of Alexandria’s aeolipile (1st century AD) were curiosities, not true engines that powered industry. Therefore, the steam engine was not invented during the Renaissance.

Many nations, though not all, allow individuals to hold dual (or even multiple) citizenships simultaneously, so it is possible to be a legal citizen of more than one country at the same time. Rules vary by country but the concept is widely recognized.

Under the 1927 and 1952 federal statutes (now codified at 8 U.S.C. § 1406), persons born in or naturalized in the U.S. Virgin Islands are considered nationals and citizens of the United States. Although they do not have voting representation in Congress or vote for president, their legal status is that of U.S. citizens.

The MTV/VH1 television series “Scream” was developed as a TV adaptation of Wes Craven and Kevin Williamson’s “Scream” film franchise. While the show introduces new characters and storylines rather than continuing the exact plot of the movies, it is explicitly inspired by and modeled on the original film series’ concept of a masked killer, genre-savvy dialogue, and meta-horror tone. Therefore, the show is indeed based on the movie franchise, even if it is not a direct sequel.

Interpreting “World Cup” in the usual sense of the FIFA football (soccer) World Cup, Australia’s national teams (men’s or women’s) have never reached the tournament’s final match. The men’s side’s best result has been the round of 16 (2006 and 2022), and the women’s side reached the semifinals in 2023 but not the final. Therefore, the answer is no.

“Soft-tissue damage” is a broad term that covers any injury to muscles, tendons, or ligaments. A sprain is a specific kind of soft-tissue injury—damage to a ligament caused by stretching or tearing. Therefore, while every sprain is soft-tissue damage, not all soft-tissue damage is a sprain, so the two terms are not the same.

“The Boss Baby: Back in Business” is a DreamWorks-produced animated series that was released as a Netflix original beginning in 2018. Because it is branded as a Netflix original, it is carried on the Netflix platform in the regions where Netflix holds the streaming rights (which is most territories). Therefore, in general, the series is available on Netflix.

The original Netflix series 'Spirit Riding Free' ended with Season 8 in 2019 and was followed by related content such as the short-form series ‘Pony Tales’, the sequel series ‘Riding Academy’ (2020) and the feature film ‘Spirit Untamed’ (2021). Since then DreamWorks or Netflix have made no public announcement that the main series—or any new season of it—will continue. While the franchise is still used in spin-offs, there is currently no evidence that more episodes of the original show are planned.

A processor (CPU) is a single integrated circuit that performs computations and executes instructions, whereas a motherboard is the main printed-circuit board that connects and allows communication between the processor, memory, storage, and other peripherals. They are distinct components with different functions.

The TV series 'Desperate Housewives' concluded with its eighth season, which finished airing in 2012. ABC officially announced the show’s end, and since then no plans or credible announcements for a ninth season have been made. Given the long time span and lack of any revival news, it is almost certain that there will not be a season 9.

Florida State Road 91 is the designation for the mainline of Florida’s Turnpike. The Turnpike is operated by Florida’s Turnpike Enterprise and is funded through toll collection, not general taxation. Therefore, SR 91 (highway 91) is a toll facility.

The NBA first round used to be a best-of-five format, but since the 2003 playoffs it has been expanded to a best-of-seven series. Therefore, the statement that it is a 5-game series is no longer correct.

Gram-positive bacteria possess a multilayered peptidoglycan structure (≈20–80 nm thick), which retains crystal violet stain in the Gram staining procedure; in contrast, Gram-negative bacteria have a much thinner peptidoglycan layer. Therefore, the statement is correct.

The TV series “Designated Survivor” is set largely in the White House, but—like virtually all dramatic productions—it was filmed on soundstages and locations in Toronto (and some scenes in Washington, D.C.), not inside the actual White House.

White rice is produced by milling brown rice to remove the outer husk, bran and germ layers, then polishing the remaining endosperm. This mechanical process exposes the naturally white interior; no chemical bleaching agents are used to whiten the kernels.

The Washington Post is one of the largest and oldest newspapers in the United States (founded in 1877). It employs professional journalists, follows established editorial standards, and has won many Pulitzer Prizes, all indicators that media scholars and industry observers use to classify outlets as reputable. Like any publication it can make mistakes or exhibit some editorial bias, but in the context of mainstream journalism it is broadly considered a credible and reputable source.

answer: No, not unless an organization's bylaws or governing law specifically provide for it.
Reasoning: Under Robert’s Rules of Order Newly Revised (RONR), the right to speak and vote belongs to members who are actually present at the meeting. RONR states that voting by proxy is not permitted unless the organization’s bylaws (or an applicable statute) explicitly authorize it. Therefore, in the absence of such a bylaw or statutory provision, proxy voting is not allowed under Robert’s Rules.
Answer: No, not unless an organization’s bylaws or governing law specifically provide for it.

The U.S. version of the television series 'Shameless' aired its seventh season on Showtime in 2016. Therefore, a Season 7 does exist.

Exposure to high temperatures can dilate blood vessels and lead to dehydration, lowering blood pressure and reducing blood flow to the brain. This can result in heat syncope (fainting). Therefore, excessive heat can indeed cause a person to faint.

The Challenger Deep, the deepest point of the Mariana Trench, has been reached by the manned bathyscaphe Trieste (1960), the Deepsea Challenger piloted by James Cameron (2012), and several dives by the submersible Limiting Factor (2019-2023) as well as by unmanned ROVs. Although the area is vast and not completely mapped in detail, humans and instruments have physically reached and surveyed the trench’s deepest seafloor, so it has indeed been explored in that sense.

Black garlic (including Japanese black garlic) is produced by aging whole bulbs at gentle heat and high humidity for several weeks. During this process, Maillard reactions and moisture redistribution break down the cloves’ cell walls, yielding a soft, sticky, almost jam-like texture rather than the firm crunch of raw garlic. Therefore a properly made black garlic clove will feel tender and somewhat mushy when pressed.

Within the thoracic cavity the heart occupies the middle mediastinum, while the esophagus runs in the posterior mediastinum. Thus, the esophagus lies behind (posterior to) the heart rather than in front of it.

In the context of art, framing, and mounting supplies, both terms are commonly used interchangeably to describe a lightweight sheet that has a rigid polystyrene (or polyurethane) foam center sandwiched between two outer paper or plastic facings. Although “Foamcore” was once a specific trademarked brand, in everyday usage “foam core” (or “foamcore”) and “foam board” refer to the same type of product.

In everyday conversation the terms are often used interchangeably, but strictly speaking they are not identical. Quantum physics is the broad field that studies all phenomena governed by quantum principles—including quantum mechanics, quantum field theory, quantum statistical mechanics, etc. Quantum mechanics is the foundational, non-relativistic framework (Schrödinger equation, operators, wavefunctions) that sits inside this larger field. Therefore, quantum mechanics is a subset of quantum physics, not the whole of it.

answer: Partly—it is a fictionalized retelling of real historical events, not a completely true story in the nonfiction sense.

Reasoning: “Blade Runner 2049” is an official sequel set thirty years after the events of the original 1982 film “Blade Runner,” sharing the same universe, continuing plot threads about replicants, and featuring returning characters such as Rick Deckard. Therefore, they are directly connected.

The World Health Organization (WHO) is a specialized agency of the United Nations. It is an international, inter-governmental body made up of member states, rather than an organization belonging to any single national government. Therefore, it is not a government organization in the usual sense of being part of a national government.

Both products contain acetone as the active solvent, but they are formulated for different uses. Nail-polish remover sold for cosmetic use often contains additional ingredients (water, fragrances, oils, conditioners, colorants) and is produced to cosmetic-grade purity standards. Acetone sold for paint cleanup or thinning is typically industrial-grade; it can be close to 100 % acetone but may allow trace contaminants and lacks the cosmetic additives. Because of these formulation and purity differences, the two are not strictly the same even though the main solvent (acetone) is common.

Yes – several people have received two Academy Awards during the same ceremony. Therefore, the answer to whether anyone has ever won two Oscars in a single night is affirmative.

The Netflix revival of Arrested Development continued beyond its fourth season. Filming for a fifth season was confirmed, and Season 5 (released in two eight-episode halves) premiered on Netflix in 2018–2019.

Australia is the driest inhabited continent. Large parts of the interior are arid or semi-arid, and the nation regularly faces severe droughts, over-allocation of river systems such as the Murray–Darling Basin, and the impacts of climate change on rainfall patterns. All of these constitute major water concerns.

The U.S. Supreme Court has long held that corporations are ‘persons’ for many constitutional purposes and that the First Amendment’s free-speech clause protects corporate expression, including political speech (e.g., Citizens United v. FEC) and most other non-commercial speech, largely to the same extent as it protects speech by natural persons. Although commercial speech by corporations can be regulated somewhat more than individual political speech, the core constitutional protection applies; therefore, in general corporations do possess the same free-speech rights as persons.

In UK immigration law, a person with Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR) is no longer ‘subject to immigration control’. The ‘no recourse to public funds’ restriction only applies to people who are still under immigration control; it is lifted once ILR is granted. Therefore, an ILR holder can generally access public funds and means-tested or contributory benefits, provided they also meet the ordinary eligibility rules for each benefit (e.g., residence, income, contribution history).

Both are fipple flutes, but they differ in construction, fingering system, range and historical use. A recorder has seven front finger holes plus a thumb hole on the back, is usually made of wood or plastic, and is designed for chromatic playing over about two octaves. A tin whistle (penny whistle) has six front finger holes, no thumb hole, is commonly made of metal, and typically plays diatonically with a slightly different technique and range. Because of these distinctions, they are considered separate instruments.

From 2003–2016 the All-Star Game winner’s league received home-field advantage in the World Series, but MLB abolished that rule starting with the 2017 season. Since then, home-field advantage is awarded to the pennant-winner with the better regular-season record. Therefore, the All-Star Game no longer determines home-field advantage.
The Seattle SuperSonics won the NBA championship once, in the 1978-79 season, defeating the Washington Bullets in the Finals. Therefore, it is true that they have won a championship.

For most mailed items, the return address simply needs to be a deliverable location where undeliverable mail can be sent back. The U.S. Postal Service (and similar postal services in other countries) accepts a PO Box as a valid return address. Some private carriers (e.g., UPS, FedEx) may require a street address for certain shipments, but in the general context of postal mail, a PO Box is acceptable as the return address.

Static pressure is the true thermodynamic pressure of whatever fluid you are measuring, regardless of whether the fluid is moving. Atmospheric pressure is simply the static pressure of the Earth’s atmosphere at a given location and altitude. Therefore, when you are measuring the surrounding air outdoors, the static pressure you read will equal the local atmospheric pressure. In other situations (e.g., air inside a duct, liquid in a pipe, or gas in a pressurized tank) the static pressure can be higher or lower than the ambient atmospheric pressure. Thus the two terms are not inherently the same, though they can coincide under specific conditions.
The Croatian men’s national football team reached the FIFA World Cup final in 2018, where they played against France. Therefore, Croatia has indeed appeared in a World Cup final.

Living at high altitude has some potential benefits (e.g., increased red-blood-cell production, lower rates of obesity or ischemic heart disease in some studies), but it also carries clear risks such as chronic hypoxia, increased pulmonary-artery pressure, higher infant-mortality rates, and greater incidence of acute and chronic mountain sickness. On balance, the scientific literature does not support a blanket statement that residing at high altitude is categorically ‘good’ for everyone; the net effect depends on individual health status and adaptation. Therefore the universal claim is considered false.

Induction hobs work only with cookware whose base is ferromagnetic (can be magnetised). Cast iron is strongly ferromagnetic, so it couples very well with the magnetic field of an induction cooker and heats efficiently. The only caveats are that cast iron is heavy and can scratch the glass surface if slid roughly, but performance-wise it is fully compatible.

A motor unit consists of a single motor neuron and all of the muscle fibers it innervates. The number of fibers per neuron differs greatly between muscles that require fine, precise control (e.g., eye muscles, which have very few fibers per neuron) and those that generate large force (e.g., gastrocnemius, which has hundreds of fibers per neuron). Therefore the size of a motor unit is not fixed but varies with the functional demands of the muscle.

Cheryl Blossom and her twin brother Jason Blossom are recurring characters introduced in the Archie Comics universe in the early 1980s. They appear in multiple Archie comic series and storylines, establishing them as part of the Archie Comics canon.

In the UK crossbows are not classified as firearms and adults may buy, own and keep one at home without needing a licence. The Crossbows Act 1987 only restricts sale and possession to those under 18 and other laws make it an offence to carry a crossbow in a public place without lawful authority or reasonable excuse. Therefore simple ownership by an adult is not illegal.

A stop sign is public property and an officially designated traffic-control device. Removing or taking it constitutes theft/vandalism and creates a public-safety hazard, both of which are offenses under traffic and criminal statutes.

The last producing Cornish tin mine, South Crofty, ceased commercial production in 1998. Since then all other tin mines in Cornwall have also closed. Although exploration work and redevelopment plans to reopen South Crofty (and a few other prospects) continue, no site is currently extracting tin commercially, so there are effectively no operating tin mines left in Cornwall today.

Sabaa Tahir’s An Ember in the Ashes series contains four novels (An Ember in the Ashes, A Torch Against the Night, A Reaper at the Gates, and A Sky Beyond the Storm). Therefore the series is a quartet, not a trilogy.

Although each episode opens with a title card that claims the events are true, this is a storytelling device carried over from the original 1996 Coen brothers film. The creators (including Noah Hawley) have stated that the characters and crimes depicted in the television series are inventions, not dramatizations of real events.

The official unemployment rate counts only people without a job who are actively looking for work and are available to start. Discouraged workers have stopped looking because they believe no jobs are available for them; therefore they are categorized as ‘not in the labor force,’ not as unemployed. Hence they are excluded from the unemployment rate calculation.

The terms “soy sauce” and “soya sauce” are simply regional spelling preferences—“soy” is common in American English, while “soya” is used more in British and some other varieties of English. They refer to the same fermented seasoning made from soybeans, wheat (in most styles), salt, and a fermenting culture. Commercial formulations and flavor profiles can vary by brand or style (e.g., light, dark, tamari), but those variations are unrelated to whether the label says ‘soy’ or ‘soya.’ Therefore, there is no intrinsic difference implied by the two names.

Emotional distress activates the same brain regions that process physical pain, and intense grief or heartbreak can also trigger physiological responses (e.g., chest tightness, ‘broken-heart syndrome’/takotsubo cardiomyopathy). Therefore people really can experience physical pain from a ‘broken heart.’
The original iPhone released in 2007 featured only a single 2-megapixel rear camera and lacked a front-facing (selfie) camera, which was not introduced until the iPhone 4 in 2010.

Although the gigantic scale of the Nazca Lines makes their full designs easiest to appreciate from the air, portions of many lines and even some of the figures can indeed be viewed from ground level—especially from nearby foothills or purpose-built viewing towers along the Pan-American Highway. Therefore the statement that they can be seen from the ground is correct.

A bachelor’s degree is one type of undergraduate credential, but the term “undergraduate degree” also includes other awards (e.g., associate degrees) that are earned before any graduate‐level study. Therefore, while every bachelor’s degree is an undergraduate degree, not every undergraduate degree is a bachelor’s degree.

In a titration, the equivalence point is the theoretical point at which the amount of titrant added stoichiometrically equals the amount of analyte present. The end point is the experimental point at which the indicator signals that the titration should stop (e.g., a color change). A well-chosen indicator makes the end point occur very close to the equivalence point, but they are not inherently the same and can differ slightly.

In the Pixar film “Finding Dory,” the plot revolves around Dory searching for her long-lost parents, Charlie and Jenny. Near the end of the movie she successfully reunites with them at the Marine Life Institute, confirming that she does find her parents.

Turf toe is basically a sprain of the metatarsophalangeal (MTP) joint caused by hyper-extension. The big toe’s MTP joint is most often injured because it bears the greatest load during push-off, but the same mechanism can sprain the MTP joints of the lesser toes as well, though this is less common. Therefore, it is possible to get a “turf toe–type” injury on other toes.

Minute Maid Park, often informally referred to as Minute Maid Stadium, is the home ballpark of the Houston Astros. It is well-known for featuring a retractable roof that can open or close depending on weather conditions, allowing games to be played in both open-air and climate-controlled environments.

Historically, Blue Cross and Blue Shield were two distinct, non-profit health insurance programs (Blue Cross covering hospital care, Blue Shield covering physicians’ services). Over time, most state plans merged and today operate jointly under the Blue Cross Blue Shield Association umbrella, but they remain separate legal trademarks and can still exist as different corporate entities in some places. Therefore, they are not literally the same single company, though they are closely affiliated and often jointly branded.
According to general solubility rules, all nitrate (NO₃⁻) salts are soluble in water, regardless of the cation. Therefore, lead(II) nitrate, Pb(NO₃)₂, readily dissolves in water.

In most education systems, particularly those following the UK/Commonwealth model, an honours degree is an undergraduate qualification (usually a 3- or 4-year bachelor’s degree with an additional honours component), while a master’s degree is a postgraduate qualification that requires completion of an undergraduate degree first. Therefore, a master’s degree is generally regarded as a higher-level qualification than an honours degree.

Within the Church of England the sign of the cross is permitted and used, especially in Anglo-Catholic and more ‘high-church’ parishes, while evangelical or ‘low-church’ Anglicans may omit it. Because it is an accepted practice, even if optional, the Church of England as a whole can be said to make (or allow) the sign of the cross.

Fleetwood Mac has had many members since forming in 1967. Several prominent past members—including Bob Welch (d. 2012), Bob Weston (d. 2012), Danny Kirwan (d. 2018), Peter Green (d. 2020) and, most recently, Christine McVie (d. 2022)—have passed away. Therefore it is not true that all members of Fleetwood Mac are still alive.
The animated film "The Book of Life" (2014) was produced by Reel FX Creative Studios and distributed by 20th Century Fox, not by Pixar Animation Studios. Therefore, it is not a Pixar movie.
Hellyeah’s vocalist is Chad Gray, who is also well-known as the frontman for the band Mudvayne. Therefore the lead singer of Hellyeah indeed comes from Mudvayne.

In the FIFA Men’s and Women’s World Cups—the events most commonly meant when someone says “the World Cup”—the host nation is granted an automatic berth in the final tournament. This has been standard practice for every edition, and the rule is already confirmed for future tournaments (e.g., USA, Mexico, and Canada are all automatically qualified as 2026 co-hosts). While other sports sometimes call their championships “World Cups,” the default assumption is the FIFA tournament, where the host (or co-hosts) always qualify automatically.

Grizzly bears (Ursus arctos horribilis) and polar bears (Ursus maritimus) belong to the same genus (Ursus) and have overlapping ranges in parts of the Arctic. Documented cases in the wild and in captivity show they can interbreed and produce viable, even fertile, hybrid offspring often called ‘pizzly’ or ‘grolar’ bears. Therefore, mating between the two species is biologically possible.

The term ‘The Lord of the Rings trilogy’ refers to J. R. R. Tolkien’s three-volume work (The Fellowship of the Ring, The Two Towers, The Return of the King). ‘The Hobbit’ is a separate, earlier novel set in the same world and serves as a prequel, but it is not one of the three volumes that make up the Lord of the Rings trilogy.

Input lag measures the delay between a user action (e.g., pressing a key or moving a mouse) and the moment the result of that action becomes visible on-screen. Response time, in the display context, is how quickly a pixel can change from one color/brightness level to another (typically gray-to-gray). While both affect perceived responsiveness, they describe different phenomena and are measured differently, so they are not the same thing.

Anatomically, the respiratory tract is commonly divided into an upper portion (nose, nasal cavity, sinuses, pharynx, and sometimes larynx) and a lower portion (trachea, bronchi, bronchioles, and lungs). The trachea lies below the larynx and is therefore classified as part of the lower respiratory system, not the upper.

The current FIFA World Cup Trophy is crafted from 18-carat gold (75 % pure) with a malachite base, and its interior is hollow. If it were truly solid gold, it would weigh several times more than its actual 6.175 kg mass. Therefore, it is not made out of solid gold.
Only one goalkeeper has ever claimed the Ballon d’Or: Soviet legend Lev Yashin in 1963. No other keeper has won it since, so the correct response to whether a keeper has ever won is yes.

answer: True – it can, especially if done forcefully or chronically
Reasoning: Normal, gentle removal of nasal debris is unlikely to change how you smell things. However, frequent or forceful nose-picking can scratch or inflame the nasal lining, cause small infections or scabs, and even damage areas near the olfactory epithelium. Swelling, crusts, or infection can temporarily block or impair the airflow that must reach the olfactory receptors, reducing the sense of smell until the tissue heals. In severe, repeated trauma, scarring could potentially lead to longer-term problems. So while ordinary, mild nose-picking usually does nothing, aggressive or chronic picking can indeed diminish smell, at least transiently.
Answer: True – it can, especially if done forcefully or chronically

Reasoning: By definition, a deed of trust is a three-party security instrument involving (1) the trustor/borrower, (2) the beneficiary/lender, and (3) a neutral third-party trustee who holds legal title in trust. Without a named trustee, the instrument would not meet the legal requirements of a deed of trust and would generally be treated as another form of security, such as a mortgage. Therefore, a valid deed of trust must include a trustee.

At the start of Glee’s sixth season Kurt and Blaine are broken up, but over the course of the season they reconcile. In episode 8, “A Wedding,” they not only resume their relationship but get married. Therefore they do get back together in season 6.

“Blow Me Away” is a song by the rock band Breaking Benjamin that was commissioned and recorded specifically for the Halo 2 Original Soundtrack (released in 2004). It first appeared in that game’s soundtrack before later being released on other albums/compilations, so it was indeed made for Halo 2.

George W. Bush was part of the investment group that bought the Texas Rangers baseball team in 1989. He served as managing general partner until 1994. In 1998, before running for President, he and the group sold their stake in the team. Since then, Bush has had no ownership interest in the Rangers.

In a perfectly inelastic collision the colliding bodies stick together and move with a common velocity afterward. Linear momentum must be conserved, but some of the initial kinetic energy is transformed into internal energy (deformation, heat, sound, etc.). Therefore the total kinetic energy before and after the collision is not the same.

To date, the live-action drama ‘Good Morning Call’ has released only two seasons (‘Good Morning Call’ and ‘Good Morning Call: Our Campus Days’). There has been no official announcement from Netflix, Fuji TV, or the production team confirming a third season, and no new episodes have been released after Season 2. Therefore, as of now, a third season does not exist.

In the U.S. armed forces, the warrant officer ranks were phased out of the Air Force after the 1950s, and there have been no serving warrant officers in the Air Force for decades (apart from a few who remained on reserve status until the early 1990s). While some other nations’ air forces (e.g., the UK’s Royal Air Force) do still use a warrant officer rank, the common question usually refers to the U.S. Air Force, where the answer is no.

As of now, Marvel Studios has indicated plans to integrate the X-Men into the Marvel Cinematic Universe, and trade reports mention an untitled ‘X-Men’ project in development. However, no X-Men film has been officially announced with a confirmed title or release date. Therefore, we cannot say that a new X-Men movie is definitively ‘coming out’ at this time.

In display terminology, response time describes how quickly a pixel can transition from one color or brightness level to another (e.g., gray-to-gray), while input lag refers to the delay between a user action (like a mouse movement or controller press) and the moment the resulting image actually appears on the screen. They are measured differently, affect different perceptual qualities, and one can be low while the other is high. Therefore, they are not the same.

The value 1 atm (101.325 kPa) is a defined ‘standard’ pressure, roughly the average sea-level pressure. Actual atmospheric pressure changes with altitude and weather systems, so it is often higher or lower than 1 atm.

In the 2008 romantic comedy ‘Made of Honor,’ Tom (played by Patrick Dempsey) realizes he loves his best friend Hannah (Michelle Monaghan) just as she becomes engaged to another man. After various complications, Tom interrupts Hannah’s wedding in Scotland, confesses his feelings, and Hannah reciprocates. The film ends with Tom and Hannah marrying each other, showing they do end up together.

The Second Continental Congress convened from May 1775 to 1781. During this period, specifically in June–July 1776, a committee led by Thomas Jefferson drafted the Declaration of Independence, and the Congress adopted it on July 4, 1776. Therefore, the Declaration was indeed written during the Second Continental Congress.

Most sulfate salts are water-soluble; the common insoluble exceptions are sulfates of Ca2+, Sr2+, Ba2+, Pb2+. Fe3+ is not an exception, and Fe2(SO4)3 is known to dissolve in water (though it hydrolyzes and gives an acidic solution). Therefore iron(III) sulfate is considered water-soluble.

Many political systems are designed with both a head of state called a president and a head of government called a prime minister (e.g., France, Russia, Portugal). Therefore, it is entirely possible for a country’s constitutional framework to include both offices simultaneously.

Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood is not a sequel to the 2003 Fullmetal Alchemist anime. It is a separate adaptation that restarts the story from the beginning and follows the original manga much more closely, rather than continuing from where the 2003 series left off.

11.22.63 was produced and marketed by Hulu as a self-contained, eight-episode limited series that fully adapts Stephen King’s novel. Since its 2016 release there has been no announcement of a renewal, and the creative team has repeatedly referred to it as a one-off project. Given the elapsed time and lack of any credible reports of development, a second season is not planned.

‘Cougar’ and ‘mountain lion’ are two common names for the same species, Puma concolor. Other names such as puma, panther, and catamount also refer to this single species. Thus, a cougar and a mountain lion are the same animal.

answer: Yes (in the Disney adaptations, though not in the original books)
Reasoning: In A. A. Milne’s original Winnie-the-Pooh books there is no gopher character. However, when Disney adapted the stories it introduced a new character simply called “Gopher,” who even jokes that he’s “not in the book.” So, depending on the version, the answer differs, but in the well-known Disney cartoons there is indeed a gopher.
Answer: Yes (in the Disney adaptations, though not in the original books)

Reasoning: Both Pterodactylus (commonly called a “pterodactyl”) and Pteranodon are pterosaurs—flying reptiles that lived during the Mesozoic Era—but they are different genera with distinct physical traits, geologic ages, and classifications. Therefore, a pterodactyl is not the same animal as a pteranodon.
The airport commonly referred to as "MCO" is designated by that IATA code; its full official name is Orlando International Airport. Thus, the terms refer to the same airport.

The tower’s foundations were laid in 1173. Already while the second storey was being built, the soft, uneven sub-soil began to give way and the structure tilted. From that early stage onward—and for all of the centuries since—the tower has exhibited a noticeable lean (though its angle has varied with stabilization work). Thus, for virtually its entire existence the tower has been leaning.

answer: Probably not—there are no plans and it is considered unlikely.
Reasoning: The Warner Bros./CBS series “Cold Case” has never had an official season or complete-series DVD release. The main obstacle that has been cited for years is the extensive (and expensive) popular-music soundtrack that would have to be re-licensed for home video. No studio announcements, retail listings, or credible industry reports currently indicate that those licensing issues have been resolved or that a DVD (or Blu-ray) edition is in active production. While it is always possible that a future deal could be struck, the lack of movement more than a decade after the show ended makes a release increasingly unlikely.
Answer: Probably not—there are no plans and it is considered unlikely.

Reasoning: In Season 4 Sam Seaborn leaves the Bartlet White House to run for Congress. He reappears late in Season 7 when Josh Lyman asks him to join the Santos campaign/administration, and Sam is shown again in several episodes including the series finale. Therefore, yes—he does come back to The West Wing.

In UK company law, both public limited companies (plc) and private limited companies (Ltd) have limited liability, so a plc is indeed a kind of limited company. However, the term “limited company” is usually used to refer to a private limited company, which differs from a plc in share-capital requirements, ability to offer shares to the public, disclosure rules, etc. Therefore a plc is not the same as (i.e., interchangeable with) a private limited company, even though both are limited liability entities.

Although the two cheeses look similar and are sometimes used interchangeably, they are made differently. Queso fresco is traditionally made with rennet (or a combination of rennet and acid), while queso blanco is coagulated only with acid such as vinegar or lemon juice. This difference gives queso fresco a slightly more complex flavor and a crumbly texture, whereas queso blanco tends to be firmer and can be sliced. Because of the difference in production and resulting texture, they are considered distinct cheeses rather than exactly the same product.

Cats (Felis catus) did not evolve in Australia and were introduced by European settlers in the late 18th–19th centuries. Both pet (domestic) cats and the wild‐living feral populations descend from these introductions, so they are considered an invasive, non-native species in Australia.

Tornadoes are not unique to the United States; they have been documented on every continent except Antarctica. Significant tornado activity occurs in Canada, South America (especially Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay), Europe (e.g., the UK, Germany, Italy, France, Poland), Asia (notably Bangladesh, India, China), Africa (South Africa, Sudan), and Australia/New Zealand. Thus, the existence of tornadoes outside the U.S. and in many parts of the world is well established.

The U.S. men’s national soccer team has never won a FIFA World Cup. (The U.S. women’s team has won the Women’s World Cup multiple times, but in common usage “the World Cup in soccer” refers to the men’s tournament.) Therefore, to the straightforward reading of the question, the answer is no.

Alex Karev’s last on-screen appearance was early in Season 16, and the character was written out via letters explaining he had moved to Kansas to be with Izzie and their children. In all subsequent seasons of Grey’s Anatomy, he has not reappeared at Grey Sloan Memorial Hospital, nor has the show indicated any return.

According to Kellogg’s and independent taste-tests, every color of Froot Loops cereal is made with the same ‘mixed-fruit’ flavoring. The colors are purely visual; there are no distinct flavorings for red, orange, yellow, green, blue or purple pieces.

The Great Wall is a series of defensive walls built mainly along the northern frontier of historic Chinese states to keep out northern invaders. It stretches thousands of kilometers east-to-west but does not form a continuous structure encircling the whole country. Therefore it is not ‘all around’ China.

St George’s Chapel is located within Windsor Castle in Berkshire, whereas Westminster Abbey is a separate historic church in London. Since the chapel is not situated inside Westminster Abbey, the statement is incorrect.
Under the Basic Law and the Official Languages Ordinance, both Chinese and English have official status in Hong Kong. Government legislation, administration, and courts use both languages.

Call of Duty: WWII depicts actual World War II battles and settings, but the storyline and main characters are fictional creations by the game developers. It is therefore inspired by real historical events rather than being a direct retelling of a specific true story.

In everyday clinical and regulatory usage, the terms “extended-release” (ER/XR) and “sustained-release” (SR) both describe oral dosage forms that release drug over an extended period so that dosing can be less frequent than with an immediate-release product. While some technical texts make subtle distinctions (e.g., classifying sustained release as one subtype of extended release), in common practice they are treated as equivalent concepts.

answer: False – cars are not allowed on the Staten Island Ferry.
Reasoning: Automobiles were once carried on the Staten Island Ferry, but vehicle service was suspended for security reasons after September 11, 2001 and has never been reinstated. The ferry is now limited to pedestrians and bicyclists only.
Answer: False – cars are not allowed on the Staten Island Ferry.

Reasoning: The United States maintains several installations in the United Kingdom—e.g., RAF Lakenheath, RAF Mildenhall, RAF Fairford—that are operated by U.S. forces (while officially remaining Royal Air Force stations). Therefore, U.S. military bases do exist in the UK.

For most of its history the territory that is now Belgium formed part of the Low Countries under various rulers (Burgundian, Spanish, Austrian Habsburgs). However, from 1795 until 1815, after the French Revolutionary armies conquered the Austrian Netherlands, the area was formally annexed and reorganised into French départements, making it an integral part of France for two decades. Therefore, at least for that period, Belgium was indeed part of France in a political-administrative sense.

A 3-way lamp socket is wired to energize one filament, the other filament, or both filaments in a special 3-way bulb. If you screw in a standard single-wattage (regular) bulb, it will simply behave like any ordinary lamp: only one of the switch positions (usually the middle or high click) will light the bulb and the other two positions will do nothing. This causes no damage as long as the bulb’s wattage does not exceed the maximum rating on the lamp.
The 2000 comedy film "The Whole Nine Yards," starring Bruce Willis and Matthew Perry, did receive a follow-up film titled "The Whole Ten Yards," released in 2004. Hence, a sequel exists.
In the 2013 film 'G.I. Joe: Retaliation,' Duke (played by Channing Tatum) is killed during the early ambush on the G.I. Joe team, so he does not survive the film.

The central nervous system (CNS) is limited to the brain and spinal cord. Cranial nerves, including the vagus nerve (cranial nerve X), emerge from the brainstem but extend outside the CNS to innervate peripheral organs, so they are classified as part of the peripheral nervous system (PNS), not the CNS.

Although both can carry S/PDIF digital audio, the term “digital audio cable” usually refers to an electrical coaxial cable with RCA connectors, while an “optical cable” (TOSLINK) transmits light through optical fiber. They use different physical media and connectors, so they are not the same.
In the series, Meredith Grey first adopts Zola and later gives birth to two biological children, Bailey and Ellis. Therefore, she does indeed end up having (and raising) babies on Grey’s Anatomy.

answer: Yes, but only for one guest episode in Season 10.
Reasoning: Dr. Preston Burke (played by Isaiah Washington) leaves Grey’s Anatomy at the end of Season 3. He does, however, make a single-episode return in Season 10 (“We Are Never Ever Getting Back Together”) to offer Cristina a job. Therefore, strictly speaking, he does come back after Season 3, but only briefly and not as a regular character.
Answer: Yes, but only for one guest episode in Season 10.

Reasoning: During the American Civil War (1861-1865), infantrymen on both Union and Confederate sides were routinely issued rifled muskets or rifles with socket or saber bayonets. Drill manuals included bayonet tactics, and soldiers fixed bayonets for charges or defensive stands. Although actual hand-to-hand bayonet wounds were relatively uncommon compared with bullet casualties, the weapon was nevertheless standard equipment and was used occasionally in combat as well as for secondary tasks (e.g., cooking, digging, cutting). Therefore, the correct answer to whether bayonets were used in the Civil War is yes.

In Disney’s 1991 animated film, which introduced the character Gaston, he fights the Beast atop the castle, slips, and falls into a deep ravine. The film never shows him surviving and treats the fall as fatal, so he is presumed dead. (Earlier literary versions of Beauty and the Beast did not include Gaston, but within the ‘original’ Disney version, he dies.)

The title “Duke of Sussex” was first created in 1801 for Prince Augustus Frederick, the sixth son of King George III. That line became extinct when he died in 1843. The title was recreated in 2018 for Prince Harry. Therefore, at least one person held the title before Prince Harry.
