The captain of the USS Indianapolis was Captain Charles B. McVay III. He survived the sinking of the ship in July 1945 and lived for many years afterward (he died by suicide in 1968). Therefore, he did live through the tragedy.
Bruce Forsyth was the presenter of the UK revival of The Price Is Right (titled “Bruce’s Price Is Right”) on ITV from 1995 to 2001, so he did indeed host the show.

Nevada statute (NRS 200.120–200.130) explicitly states that a person who is not the original aggressor and is in a place where they have a right to be has no duty to retreat before using deadly force if they reasonably fear imminent death or great bodily harm. This language is characteristic of a stand-your-ground law, and Nevada is commonly listed among states with such statutes.

answer: Yes – a jump shot is legal on a free throw as long as the shooter doesn't cross the line before the ball hits the rim/backboard.
Reasoning: The basketball rules (NBA, FIBA, NCAA, NFHS) only state that the shooter must release the ball from behind the free-throw line and may not step on or over the line until the ball touches the rim or backboard. They do not forbid leaving the floor. Therefore a player is allowed to perform a jump shot, provided he/she lands behind the free-throw line and complies with the timing restrictions.
Answer: Yes – a jump shot is legal on a free throw as long as the shooter doesn’t cross the line before the ball hits the rim/backboard.

Reasoning: “Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them” was first published in 2001 as a companion Hogwarts textbook written by J.K. Rowling (under the pseudonym Newt Scamander). Although it later inspired a film series, it is indeed a standalone book.

A free market refers specifically to a system where prices and production are determined purely by supply and demand with little or no government intervention. A market economy is a broader category that prioritizes market forces for allocation of resources but can still include varying degrees of government regulation (e.g., taxes, antitrust laws, safety standards). Therefore, while every free-market system is a type of market economy, not every market economy is fully ‘free’; the terms are related but not identical.

In a typical long bone the medullary (marrow) cavity is the hollow central space within the diaphysis. It is lined by endosteum and normally contains bone marrow (yellow or red) but not trabeculae of spongy (cancellous) bone. Spongy bone is located mainly in the epiphyses and metaphyses surrounding, but not inside, the medullary cavity itself.

Both names refer to the species Cicer arietinum. In English, “chickpea” is the more common botanical and culinary term, while “garbanzo bean” is derived from Spanish. They are two names for the same legume, not different varieties.

‘Have I Been Pwned’ (haveibeenpwned.com) is a well-known, long-running project created by security researcher Troy Hunt. It is recommended by governments, major companies, and security professionals as a trustworthy resource for checking whether email addresses or usernames appear in known data breaches. Its code and data-handling practices are publicly documented, and it has operated transparently since 2013. Therefore, it is generally considered a legitimate site.

The film and novel "The Last King of Scotland" use real historical figure Idi Amin as a backdrop, but the central storyline (e.g., the Scottish doctor Nicholas Garrigan and many dramatic incidents) is fictional or heavily dramatized. Significant events, timelines, and characters are altered for narrative effect, so it cannot be considered historically accurate overall.

In Alberta, as in all Canadian provinces and territories, impaired driving (operating a motor vehicle while your ability is impaired by alcohol, drugs, or a combination of both, or having a blood-alcohol concentration at or above the legal limit) is prosecuted under the federal Criminal Code of Canada. Because federal criminal law applies uniformly across the country, impaired driving is indeed a criminal offence in Alberta, carrying potential penalties such as fines, licence suspensions, and possible jail time.

The UN Security Council has five permanent members (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom and the United States). Canada is not one of them. Canada sometimes serves as an elected, non-permanent member for two-year terms, but it is not currently on the Council and is never a permanent member.

DirecTV is a satellite television service that was acquired by AT&T in 2015 (and is now majority-owned by AT&T and TPG Capital after a 2021 spinoff). Dish Network is a separate publicly traded company, Dish Network Corporation. The two services are competitors and are not owned by the same parent company.

Normally ancient Egypt had a single reigning pharaoh, but there were several periods (e.g., planned co-regencies between a ruling king and his heir, or times of civil strife such as the Intermediate Periods when rival dynasties ruled different regions simultaneously) in which two or even more individuals held the title at the same time. Therefore, at certain moments there could indeed be more than one pharaoh concurrently.

‘Delhi University’ is an informal/short name that people commonly use for the institution whose official name is ‘University of Delhi.’ They refer to the same public university located in Delhi, India.

Under U.S. constitutional law, the Supreme Court has held that ‘fighting words’—words that by their very utterance are likely to incite immediate violence or breach of the peace—fall into a narrow category of speech that is not protected by the First Amendment’s Free Speech Clause.

The Venus flytrap is famous, but it is just one of many carnivorous plant species. Other genera such as Nepenthes and Sarracenia (pitcher plants), Drosera (sundews), Utricularia (bladderworts), Pinguicula (butterworts), and several others also capture and digest prey. Therefore, the Venus flytrap is not the only carnivorous plant.

Triamcinolone acetonide is a medium-potency topical corticosteroid that is routinely prescribed to reduce inflammation, redness, and itching in many inflammatory skin conditions, including allergic contact dermatitis caused by poison ivy. While lower-potency OTC hydrocortisone is often tried first, triamcinolone cream/ointment can be used when a stronger steroid is needed, applied thinly and for a limited duration per prescriber guidance.

Universal Music Group (UMG) and Universal Studios (the film studio/theme-park business under NBCUniversal) share historical roots and branding, but today they are separate, independently owned companies. UMG is a stand-alone, publicly traded music company (spun off from Vivendi in 2021), whereas Universal Studios is part of NBCUniversal, which is owned by Comcast. Therefore UMG is not part of Universal Studios.

Blue Bell Creameries temporarily halted production in 2015 due to a listeria outbreak, but after implementing new safety measures it resumed operations the same year and has continued to distribute its ice cream across many U.S. states. As of today the company is still producing and selling ice cream.

By the standard definition of causality, a cause is an event or condition that brings about (produces) an effect, and temporal priority—cause preceding effect—is built into that definition. Although some speculative interpretations of physics entertain retro-causation, these are not accepted as established. Therefore, under ordinary usage it is necessary that a cause occur before its effect.

In accounting terminology, the report that summarizes revenues, expenses, gains and losses for a period—ending with net profit or net loss—is called an Income Statement. This same report is also commonly referred to as a Profit and Loss (P&L) Statement or Statement of Earnings. While minor regional or corporate naming preferences exist, they describe the same financial statement.

Although both seas and oceans are large bodies of salt water and are interconnected, the term “ocean” is reserved for the five great, continuous expanses of water that cover most of Earth’s surface, whereas a “sea” is typically a smaller subdivision that is partly enclosed by land (e.g., the Mediterranean Sea) or delineated by oceanographic features. Thus, they are related but not the same thing.

Sea otters (Enhydra lutris) are native to coastal areas of the North Pacific Ocean, ranging from northern Japan and Russia across Alaska and down the west coast of North America. Therefore, they do live in the Pacific Ocean.
Avengers: Endgame (released in 2019) continues the story directly after the events of Avengers: Infinity War (2018), making it the official sequel.

“Ellen’s Game of Games” aired four seasons on NBC from 2017-2021. In January 2022 NBC officially canceled the series, and no new episodes have been produced or scheduled since. While reruns may appear on streaming or cable, the show is no longer in active production or on NBC’s current lineup.

The U.S. Air Force maintains several special operations career fields—Pararescue, Combat Control, Special Reconnaissance, Tactical Air Control Party, and Special Tactics Officers—organized under Air Force Special Operations Command (AFSOC) and units like the 24th Special Tactics Squadron. Therefore, the Air Force does have its own special operations ‘special forces.’

In the United States, Congress is the bicameral federal legislature composed of two separate chambers: the House of Representatives and the Senate. Therefore, the House is only one part of Congress, not the same entity.

In the New York City Subway system, the E train (8th Avenue Line) runs between Jamaica Center–Parsons/Archer in Queens and its southern terminal at World Trade Center in Lower Manhattan. Therefore, it stops at and indeed goes to the World Trade Center station.

A series titled “S.W.A.T.” aired in 1975-76. The current television show “S.W.A.T.” that premiered in 2017 on CBS re-imagines the premise and characters from that original series, making it a reboot/remake of the older show.

The United States instituted the Selective Training and Service Act of 1940 (the first peacetime draft in U.S. history) and continued conscription throughout World War II. Other major combatants, such as the United Kingdom, Germany, and the Soviet Union, also relied on compulsory military service. Therefore, a military draft clearly existed during World War II.
The University of Nevada, Las Vegas (UNLV) established the Kirk Kerkorian School of Medicine, which began admitting students in 2017. Therefore, Las Vegas does have an accredited medical school.

The question refers to the FIFA Women’s World Cup. Since the tournament began in 1991, England’s women’s national team has never lifted the trophy. Their best finish to date is runners-up in 2023, when they lost the final to Spain.

What flows from a maple tree is not maple syrup but maple sap, which is about 98 % water and only ~2 % sugar. It tastes only faintly sweet and has to be boiled down (roughly 40 : 1) to become the thick, very sweet maple syrup sold commercially.

Pure vanilla extract is produced by soaking or percolating vanilla beans in a solution that is predominantly ethyl alcohol and water. Under U.S. FDA regulations, a product labeled “pure vanilla extract” must contain at least 35 % alcohol by volume. Therefore, pure vanilla extract inherently includes alcohol.

In common public-relations and media terminology, the terms “news release” and “press release” are used interchangeably to describe an official written or recorded communication directed at members of the news media to announce something news-worthy. Although some practitioners may prefer one term over the other, there is no substantive difference in meaning or format.

The phrase “Triple Crown winner” most commonly refers to U.S. Thoroughbred horse racing, where a horse wins the Kentucky Derby, Preakness Stakes and Belmont Stakes in the same year. This feat has indeed been accomplished—13 horses have done so, with the most recent being Justify in 2018. Therefore, the answer is yes.

answer: No, UK citizens do not need a tourist visa for visits of up to 90 days.
Reasoning: Since 2 March 2020, Turkey has waived the visa requirement for British (UK) passport-holders who are visiting for tourism or business. They can enter visa-free and stay up to 90 days in any 180-day period, so a separate tourist e-Visa is no longer needed for ordinary short stays.
Answer: No, UK citizens do not need a tourist visa for visits of up to 90 days.

Reasoning: The terms “woodchuck” and “groundhog” are both common names for the same species of rodent, Marmota monax, found throughout much of North America.

The NBA used the 2-3-2 home-court format for the Finals from 1985 through 2013. Beginning with the 2014 season, the league returned to the 2-2-1-1-1 format for every best-of-seven series, including the Finals. Therefore, the NBA Playoffs are no longer played in a 2-3-2 format.

A U.S. Employment Authorization Document (EAD) only grants temporary permission to work; it does not confer permanent resident status or the broader rights of a Green Card (Permanent Resident Card). Therefore, an employment authorization card is not a Green Card.

In the English Football League (EFL) play-offs—which are commonly referred to simply as ‘the league play-offs’ for the Championship, League One and League Two—the away-goals rule has never applied. If the aggregate score is level after both legs, the tie goes to extra time and, if necessary, a penalty shoot-out, regardless of how many goals were scored home or away. Therefore, away goals do not carry any special weight in deciding the outcome.
Marvel’s Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. continued beyond season 5; ABC renewed it for season 6 and later for a seventh and final season. Therefore, season 5 was not the last season.

The 2018 FIFA World Cup, held in Russia, featured 32 national teams that advanced through regional qualifying tournaments. India competed in the AFC qualification rounds but was eliminated early and therefore did not earn one of Asia’s allotted World Cup berths.

A local maximum is a point where the function value is at least as large as nearby points. If that same point also has a value greater than or equal to every point in the entire domain, it simultaneously satisfies the definition of an absolute (global) maximum. Therefore a local maximum can indeed be an absolute maximum when it happens to be the highest point overall.

Cowpea is the species Vigna unguiculata, which includes many varieties. The ‘black-eyed pea’ (with a pale seed coat and black hilum) is just one of those varieties. Thus all black-eyed peas are cowpeas, but not all cowpeas are black-eyed peas. Because the question asks whether they are the same thing, the strict answer is No.

In the television series (and the comic source material), the Governor is ultimately killed—stabbed by Michonne and then shot by Lily in the Season 4 episode “Too Far Gone.” Therefore, the character does die in The Walking Dead story.

The United States maintained several large air bases in Thailand during the Vietnam War, but all U.S. forces were withdrawn by the mid-1970s. Today the U.S. conducts joint exercises (e.g., Cobra Gold) and occasionally deploys aircraft to Thai facilities such as U-Tapao, but these remain Royal Thai bases under Thai control rather than permanent U.S. military bases. Therefore, the U.S. does not currently have its own military base in Thailand.

Cape Canaveral is the name of the geographic cape on Florida’s east coast and of the nearby Cape Canaveral Space Force Station. The Kennedy Space Center is NASA’s civilian launch complex located on neighboring Merritt Island. Although they sit next to each other and both support rocket launches, they are distinct facilities operated by different organizations (U.S. Space Force vs. NASA). Therefore they are often associated but are not the same place.
Avengers: Endgame (2019) was released as the direct follow-up to Avengers: Infinity War (2018), concluding the storyline begun in that film. Therefore, a sequel does exist.

New York City maintains two main regulatory regimes for older apartments: rent control (for units continuously occupied by the same family since before 1971) and rent stabilization. Although the number of rent-controlled units has dwindled to a small fraction of the housing stock, the rent-control laws are still on the books and applicable to those remaining units. Therefore, the statement that New York City still has rent control is accurate.

Historically, a small group of U.S. servicemembers have indeed been recognized twice for separate acts of valor. In fact, 19 individuals are officially listed as double recipients of the Medal of Honor.

Chelsea F.C. spent several seasons outside the top flight before the Premier League era (e.g., they were relegated to the old Second Division in the mid-1970s and early 1980s). Although they have remained in the Premier League since its formation in 1992, they were not continuously in the top tier beforehand, so they have not ‘always’ been in the Premier League.

The spleen is classified as a secondary lymphoid organ within the lymphatic (immune) system. While it filters blood and is richly vascularized, the organs that are formally considered part of the circulatory system are the heart, blood vessels, and blood itself. Therefore, the spleen is not typically listed as a component of the circulatory system.

The uterine lining (endometrium) sheds during menstruation when no implantation occurs. If implantation does occur, hormones such as progesterone maintain and thicken the lining to support the embryo; it is not shed at that time.

Saigon cinnamon comes from the species Cinnamomum loureiroi (a type of cassia) and has a strong, spicy‐sweet flavor with high coumarin content. Ceylon cinnamon comes from the species Cinnamomum verum, is milder, and contains very little coumarin. Because they come from different species and differ in chemical composition, flavor, and culinary/health properties, they are not the same.

The First Amendment’s Establishment Clause (“Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion”) and Free Exercise Clause together forbid the government from establishing a religion or interfering unduly with religious practice. Although the exact phrase “separation of church and state” is not in the constitutional text, courts—most notably in Thomas Jefferson’s and later Supreme Court opinions—have interpreted these clauses to require such a separation. Therefore, in common constitutional understanding, the First Amendment does create a separation of church and state.

A common dictionary definition of a sandwich is ‘two or more slices of bread or a split roll having a filling in between.’ A bagel that has been sliced horizontally is effectively a split roll, and the cream cheese is the filling placed between the two halves. Under that widely accepted definition, it qualifies as a sandwich, though some people dispute this on cultural or culinary grounds. Because the classification depends on which definition one adopts, there is moderate uncertainty.

Horses (Equus ferus caballus) and donkeys (Equus africanus asinus) are closely related species within the same genus (Equus). They can mate and produce viable hybrid offspring: a mule (male donkey × female horse) or a hinny (male horse × female donkey). These hybrids are generally healthy but almost always sterile because the parents have different chromosome numbers (horse 64, donkey 62), leading to meiotic pairing problems in the hybrid (63 chromosomes). Thus, while they can indeed produce a baby, that baby typically cannot reproduce.

A blighted ovum (anembryonic pregnancy) is defined sonographically as an intra-uterine gestational sac that lacks evidence of an embryo. The classic criteria include a mean gestational-sac diameter large enough that one would normally expect to see at least a yolk sac or embryo, yet neither is present. Therefore, by definition a yolk sac is absent in a blighted ovum.

Anatomically, the cystic duct carries bile between the gallbladder and the common hepatic duct. When the cystic duct joins the common hepatic duct, they together form the common bile duct. Therefore, the cystic duct and the common bile duct are distinct structures, not the same.

Species called “flying fish” (family Exocoetidae) leap from the water and spread large pectoral fins to glide—sometimes hundreds of meters—before re-entering the sea. They do not beat their fins to generate thrust and cannot sustain powered flight like birds, bats or insects. Thus they glide rather than truly fly in the aerodynamic sense.

“Back to the Future” centers on time travel enabled by a scientist’s invention and is widely categorized by film scholars and media databases as a science-fiction adventure/comedy. Therefore, labeling it a science-fiction movie is accurate.

The Tower of London was originally constructed by William the Conqueror as both a fortress and a royal palace. Medieval and early-Tudor monarchs used it as a residence, especially before coronations. Although it later became better known as a prison and armoury, it did serve as a royal home for several centuries.

Under the U.S. Constitution’s Supremacy Clause (Article VI), the Constitution, federal statutes enacted pursuant to it, and treaties made under the authority of the United States are all deemed “the supreme Law of the Land.” Although a treaty is on the same hierarchical level as a federal statute (and below the Constitution), it is still considered part of the supreme law once duly ratified.

The United States military has, in rare cases, awarded the Medal of Honor to the same individual twice for separate acts of valor. Historical records list 19 such double recipients (e.g., Smedley Butler, Daniel Daly, Thomas Custer). Therefore, at least one person—and in fact several—has indeed been awarded two Medals of Honor.

In the context of the U.S. judicial system (and similarly in many other countries), the Supreme Court is constitutionally established as the court of last resort, with final appellate jurisdiction. Therefore, it is commonly referred to as the "highest court in the land."

The Water Club is a boutique hotel tower that is physically connected to and operated by Borgata Hotel Casino & Spa in Atlantic City. It is marketed as an upscale extension of Borgata and shares many of the same amenities and management, indicating it is indeed part of the Borgata complex.

U.S. two-dollar bills are still recognized as legal tender, meaning they can be spent for their face value of $2 anywhere U.S. currency is accepted. Certain older series or low-print–run notes can also fetch a premium from collectors, but at a minimum every genuine $2 bill is worth its face value.

The U.S. $10 000 note was last printed in 1945 and officially withdrawn from circulation by the Federal Reserve in 1969. Although any that still exist remain legal tender, they are removed whenever they surface and are held by collectors or museums, not used in everyday commerce. Hence, they are no longer considered to be in circulation.

The U.S. Mint is responsible for producing coins, not paper currency. Paper money is produced by the Bureau of Engraving and Printing, and high-denomination notes such as the $1,000 bill have not been printed since 1945 and were officially discontinued for circulation in 1969. Therefore, the U.S. Mint does not make $1,000 bills, and no new $1,000 bills are produced by the government at all.

An 8.5 × 11 inch sheet is the U.S. Letter size (216 × 279 mm). A4 paper is 210 × 297 mm, which converts to about 8.27 × 11.69 inches. The dimensions differ in both width and length, so they are not the same size, though they are close.

Call of Duty: Black Ops III is the next main installment after Call of Duty: Black Ops II within the Black Ops sub-series. It continues in the same fictional universe and timeline (set later in 2065), referencing events and technology developments from Black Ops II, so the games are narratively connected and part of the same storyline continuity.

The CW series “Life Unexpected” aired only two seasons (2010–2011). The network officially cancelled the show after season 2, and there have been no credible announcements or plans to revive it. Therefore, no season 3 is being made.

The Missouri River is one of North America’s major rivers and has multiple large dams along its course (e.g., Fort Peck Dam in Montana, Garrison Dam in North Dakota, Oahe Dam in South Dakota, among others). Therefore, the statement that there is a dam on the Missouri River is correct.

“Meet the Fockers” (2004) is the second film in the Meet the Parents trilogy. A third installment, “Little Fockers,” was released in 2010, continuing the story of the same characters. Therefore, there is indeed another movie after “Meet the Fockers.”

The television series ‘New Girl’ aired for a total of seven seasons. The seventh season was ordered and marketed as the show’s final season, wrapping up the storyline and characters’ arcs. No additional seasons have been produced or announced since.

In the North American Numbering Plan, an area code (NPA) has the format NXX where N can be 2–9. The digits 0 and 1 are reserved for other signaling purposes (0 for operator, 1 for long-distance prefix) and therefore cannot appear as the first digit of an area code. Consequently, no valid NANP area codes begin with the digit 1.

HCF (Hospitals Contribution Fund of Australia) is structured as a company limited by guarantee with no shareholders, and it publicly markets itself as “Australia’s largest not-for-profit health fund,” reinvesting surplus income back into member benefits rather than paying dividends. Therefore it is considered a not-for-profit health insurer.
Eastern Standard Time (EST) is one hour behind Atlantic Standard Time (AST). EST is UTC−5, while AST is UTC−4. Therefore, they are not the same time zone.

In clinical psychology a specific phobia centered on vomiting—whether doing it oneself or seeing/hearing others vomit—is well-documented. It is called emetophobia and appears in diagnostic literature and research on anxiety disorders. Therefore, a phobia of vomit does exist.

The Australian-New Zealand drama series “800 Words” originally aired on the Seven Network. It debuted in 2015 (Season 1), returned with an expanded Season 2 in 2016-17, and a further run of episodes was produced and broadcast as Season 3 in 2017-18 before the show was cancelled. Therefore, a third season does exist.

Czechoslovakia was a single country that existed from 1918 until it peacefully dissolved on January 1, 1993 into two independent states: the Czech Republic and Slovakia. Therefore, the Czech Republic represents only one part of what was formerly Czechoslovakia, not the entire former state itself. Hence, they are not the same entity.
The University of Michigan is funded and operated by the state of Michigan and is part of the state's public university system, so it is classified as a public institution rather than a private one.
The series 'This Is Us' concluded its sixth and final season in May 2022, so it is indeed over for the season (and the series overall) with no further episodes scheduled.

Princeton Theological Seminary is an independent institution of the Presbyterian Church (USA). Although it was founded in close association with Princeton University, and the two schools share historical ties and geographic proximity, the seminary has its own governance, endowment, and academic programs. It is therefore not an official part of Princeton University.

From 2003 through 2016, the league that won the MLB All-Star Game earned home-field advantage in that season’s World Series. Beginning with the 2017 season, the rule was changed: home-field advantage now goes to the pennant winner with the better regular-season record, regardless of the All-Star Game result. Therefore, at present the All-Star Game does not determine World Series home field.

Cholesterol itself is a sterol lipid synthesized de novo in the body; it is not produced by the partial degradation of other lipids. Therefore, calling it a “partial breakdown product” of lipids is incorrect.

In UK banking, a sort code identifies a particular bank and branch. Customers who hold accounts at the same branch will share that sort code, but customers at different branches or banks will have different sort codes. Therefore, sort codes are not universally the same for everyone.

Childhood typically encompasses the span from birth until the onset of adolescence or legal adulthood. A 10-year-old falls well within this range and is universally regarded as a child in medical, legal, and everyday contexts.

PlayStation Vita cannot run PlayStation 3 software natively. Only a limited subset of PS3 titles support Remote Play streaming or cloud streaming services, and those depend on having a PS3 or a service subscription. Therefore, the statement that you can play all PS3 games on a Vita is incorrect.

The Australian drama ‘A Place to Call Home’ was officially concluded by Foxtel after its sixth season, which aired in 2018. Producers and the network have stated that Season 6 was created as the definitive final chapter, and there have been no announcements of further seasons, revivals, or spin-offs. Therefore, the series is regarded as permanently finished.

In Highland cattle, horn growth is a breed characteristic controlled by genetics that is expressed in both sexes. While the horn shape differs (bulls’ horns usually grow more horizontally and forward, cows’ horns curve upward), neither sex is naturally polled, so both males and females develop horns.

Psalm 119 is universally recognized as the longest chapter in the Bible, containing 176 verses—far more than any other biblical chapter. While word counts can vary slightly between translations, no other chapter approaches its length by verse count, which is the standard metric for ‘longest chapter.’

All bacteria, including Gram-negative species, possess a peptidoglycan cell wall. In Gram-negative bacteria this wall is thinner than in Gram-positive bacteria and is located between the inner (cytoplasmic) membrane and an outer membrane, but it is still a true cell wall.

The WNBA uses a size-6 basketball (circumference 28.5 inches, weight 20 oz), whereas the NBA uses a size-7 ball (29.5 inches, 22 oz). Therefore the WNBA ball is intentionally smaller and slightly lighter.
Caesar is the principal ape leader throughout the reboot series. In ‘Dawn of the Planet of the Apes’ he is injured (shot by Koba) but ultimately survives and is alive at the film’s conclusion.

Many, but not all, European countries belong to the euro area. Others—such as the United Kingdom (pound sterling), Switzerland (Swiss franc), Sweden (Swedish krona), Denmark (Danish krone), Norway (Norwegian krone), Poland (złoty) and several more—continue to issue and use their own national currencies. Therefore at least some European countries still have their own currency.

answer: Yes, a U.S. passport card is acceptable for domestic flights.
Reasoning: The U.S. passport card is a REAL ID–compliant federal credential. TSA lists it among the acceptable forms of identification at airport security checkpoints. Therefore, for flights that both depart from and arrive within the United States, a traveler may present a valid passport card instead of a driver’s license or other ID. (It cannot be used for international air travel, which still requires a traditional passport book.)
Answer: Yes, a U.S. passport card is acceptable for domestic flights.

Reasoning: In Grey’s Anatomy, Mark and Lexie break up and, although they confess their love for each other in the Season 8 plane-crash episode, they never have the chance to resume an actual romantic relationship before Lexie dies (and Mark dies shortly afterward). Thus, they do not truly get back together as a couple on the show.

A salt-water pool relies on a salt-chlorine generator that converts dissolved salt into chlorine, so chlorine is still present. In addition, you still need to monitor and adjust pH, alkalinity, calcium hardness, and sometimes add stabilizer or algaecide. Therefore chemicals are indeed used in a salt-water pool.
Barn swallows (Hirundo rustica) typically produce two clutches (and occasionally a third in favorable conditions) within a single breeding season. Therefore, they do lay eggs more than once per year.

The bald eagle is a large raptor, but many birds are significantly larger either in mass (e.g., ostrich, cassowary) or wingspan (e.g., wandering albatross, Andean condor). Therefore it is not the biggest bird in the world by any common measure.

Over-the-air terrestrial television broadcasting, often received with an antenna at no cost to the viewer, is still widely available in the United States through networks such as ABC, CBS, NBC, FOX, PBS and many independent stations. Therefore, free-to-air TV does exist in the USA.

“The Tortoise and the Hare” comes from Aesop’s Fables, a collection of moral stories featuring talking animals. Fables are distinct from fairy tales: they convey a clear moral lesson and usually lack the magical or fantastical elements typical of fairy tales. Therefore, classifying it as a fairy tale is inaccurate.

Carbon is located in group 14 of the periodic table and is classified as a non-metal, exhibiting covalent bonding and lacking the typical properties of metals (such as high electrical conductivity and malleability). Therefore, it is not a metal.

Most jurisdictions treat mini bikes (a.k.a. pocket bikes or pit bikes) the same as other motor-driven cycles when they are operated on public roads: the rider must hold an appropriate motorcycle or motor-driven-cycle license (or endorsement) and the machine must be registered and street-legal. Riding on private property or closed courses usually does not require a license, but any use on streets or highways does. Because the question is generally interpreted as riding in public, the safest blanket answer is that a license is required.

In the CW television continuity, The Flash and Arrow both take place on Earth-1, making them part of the same universe. Supergirl, however, is set on a different Earth (Earth-38) within the CW multiverse, and characters cross over via inter-dimensional travel. Therefore, while all three shows share a multiverse, they are not originally set in the exact same universe (Earth).

According to the official Mattel UNO rules, you may play any Action card—including a Wild or Wild Draw Four—as your final card. If it is a Wild Draw Four and another player successfully challenges it, you would have to draw four cards and the hand would continue, but playing it is still allowed. Therefore, ending the round with a wildcard is permissible.

The United Nations recognizes the People’s Republic of China as the sole representative of China under Resolution 2758 (1971). After that resolution, the Republic of China (Taiwan) lost its UN seat and has been excluded from UN membership and most UN bodies ever since.

Seaplanes are specifically designed with floats or a boat-shaped hull that allows them to take off from and land on bodies of water, including oceans, provided sea conditions (waves, wind) are within the aircraft’s operational limits.

In a RACI matrix the roles Responsible (does the work) and Accountable (owns the result) are distinct, but the same individual may fill both roles on a given task. Many RACI guidelines even note that when only one person is involved it is acceptable for the R and A to be the same person, though only one A should exist per activity. Therefore, it is possible to be both responsible and accountable in a RACI.

Under UK law marriage is monogamous. It is a criminal offence (bigamy) to enter into a second marriage while still legally married to someone else. Although a polygamous marriage conducted abroad may have limited recognition for certain civil matters, a person cannot legally marry more than one person in the UK itself.

In the United States, the Constitution explicitly protects the right to a fair trial. The Sixth Amendment guarantees a speedy and public trial by an impartial jury in criminal prosecutions, while the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments’ Due Process Clauses and the Seventh Amendment (for certain civil cases) further safeguard fair-trial rights. Therefore, the Constitution does contain a right to a fair trial.
Yellow jackets belong to the wasp family (Vespidae), so every yellow jacket is a wasp, but many other wasp species exist that are not yellow jackets. Therefore the two terms are not interchangeable.

In chemistry and physics, the atomic number (Z) is defined as the number of protons in the nucleus of an atom. This distinguishes one element from another, as each element has a unique number of protons. Therefore, by definition, the atomic number represents the proton count.

Switzerland has universal male conscription, and many conscripts are allowed to keep their service weapon at home while they remain in the militia. However, there is no law that obliges every Swiss citizen—or even every adult male—to personally own a firearm. Gun ownership is common but entirely optional outside the context of military service.

So-called “X-ray glasses” are novelty items that use simple diffraction gratings or stereoscopic images to create an illusion; they do not emit or detect X-rays and cannot actually see through objects. True X-ray imaging requires bulky equipment, specialized detectors, and significant radiation shielding, none of which can be miniaturized into a safe pair of spectacles with current technology.

In the U.S. system and many other constitutional systems, the judiciary possesses the power of judicial review, which allows courts to strike down or refuse to enforce statutes enacted by the legislature if those statutes conflict with the constitution. While courts cannot rewrite legislation, they can effectively overrule (invalidate) laws that violate higher-level constitutional provisions.

In mammals, lactation is hormonally triggered by pregnancy and, more specifically, by calving. Dairy cows start producing milk only after they have been pregnant and have given birth. They do not need to remain pregnant continuously, but an initial (and then periodic) pregnancy is required to initiate each new lactation cycle.

Yes. The most well-known instance is Eight Belles, who finished second in the 2008 Kentucky Derby and was euthanized on the track after breaking both front ankles. There have been a few other fatalities in the Derby’s long history as well, so horse deaths have occurred.

answer: False – they are no longer made.
Reasoning: Commander was a Philip Morris filter-tip brand introduced in the 1950s. It disappeared from sales lists and advertising decades ago and does not appear in either Altria’s (U.S.) or Philip Morris International’s current brand portfolios. No recent retail listings or production reports exist, indicating the line has been discontinued.
Answer: False – they are no longer made.

Reasoning: Although Pinot Gris (also called Pinot Grigio) is a natural color mutation of Pinot Noir and the two share essentially the same DNA, in viticulture and wine labeling they are treated as distinct varieties with different berry colors and characteristic wine styles. Therefore, they are not considered the same grape.

In common usage, the defining element of a burger is the cooked ground-meat (or meat-substitute) patty. While a bun is traditional, many restaurants and recipes serve ‘bun-less’ or lettuce-wrapped burgers that are still marketed and understood as burgers. Because everyday language already accepts those variations, most people would still classify the patty plus toppings—minus the bun—as a burger, though there is some room for disagreement.

The equal time rule is a provision of U.S. broadcast law (Section 315 of the Communications Act) that requires radio and television stations licensed by the FCC to afford equal opportunities to legally qualified political candidates. It applies only to FCC-licensed broadcast media, not to print media. Newspapers are not subject to FCC licensing or the equal-time obligations that apply to broadcasters.

In the United States (the context in which the term “the Marines” is most commonly used), the United States Marine Corps is a separate branch of the Armed Forces. While it is administratively housed within the Department of the Navy, it is not part of the U.S. Navy itself; it has its own chain of command, mission set, uniforms, and budgets. Therefore, saying that the Marines are part of the Navy is inaccurate in this primary context, even though other nations (e.g., the U.K.’s Royal Marines) do place their marines inside their naval service.

Yes. Several engagements of the American Civil War occurred in Florida, the largest being the 1864 Battle of Olustee near Lake City. Other actions include the Battles of Natural Bridge, Santa Rosa Island, Tampa, Fort Brooke, and minor skirmishes around Pensacola and Jacksonville.

Astronomers classify bound collections of galaxies by size. The Milky Way belongs to the ‘Local Group,’ which contains a few dozen galaxies. A true galaxy cluster, such as the Virgo or Coma clusters, typically contains hundreds to thousands of galaxies and is much more massive than a group. Therefore, the Milky Way is in a galaxy group, not a galaxy cluster.

The European Union (EU) is a political and economic union composed primarily of European countries. The United States is a sovereign nation located in North America and has never been a member of the EU. Therefore, it is not part of the EU.

Since the release of Cult of Chucky (2017), the franchise has indeed continued. A new film—the 2019 Child’s Play reboot featuring Chucky—was released, and creator Don Mancini has also moved forward with a Chucky television series that debuted in 2021. These productions show that the franchise did not end with Cult of Chucky, so the statement that there will be another Chucky movie after Cult of Chucky is correct.

In relational database design, a foreign-key constraint links one or more columns in the current table to the primary (or unique) key of another table. A single table can participate in many such relationships simultaneously (e.g., one foreign key to a customers table, another to a products table, etc.). Most mainstream SQL systems impose no hard limit on how many foreign keys a table can have, aside from practical limits like performance or vendor-specific maximums, so it is entirely possible to define multiple foreign keys in one table.

Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs (1937) was the first full-length cel-animated feature produced in the United States and the first to gain wide international distribution, but earlier animated features existed (e.g., Argentina’s “El Apóstol” in 1917 and Germany’s “The Adventures of Prince Achmed” in 1926). Therefore, it was not the very first full-length animated film ever made.

An anatomical (synovial, fibrous, or cartilaginous) joint requires direct skeletal articulation. The scapula merely glides over the posterior thoracic cage, separated from the ribs by muscle and fascia; the so-called scapulothoracic ‘joint’ is only a functional interface, not a true skeletal joint.

In most U.S. states, every vehicle traveling in the same direction as the school bus must stop when the bus’s red lights are flashing and the stop arm is extended. Vehicles traveling in the opposite direction must also stop if the roadway is undivided (no raised median, barrier, or unpaved separation). However, on a divided highway or road with a physical median/barrier, traffic moving in the opposite direction is generally not required to stop. Therefore, not every lane of traffic is always required to stop—it depends on whether the roadway is divided or undivided.

Stop & Shop and the two Giant-branded supermarket chains in the U.S. (Giant Food of Landover, MD, and Giant/Martin’s of Carlisle, PA) are all subsidiaries of Ahold Delhaize (formerly Ahold USA before the Ahold–Delhaize merger). Therefore they share the same corporate parent.

Thanjavur (anglicised as Tanjore) painting is a well-known, centuries-old art tradition originating from the Thanjavur region of Tamil Nadu, India. It is widely recognised as one of the prominent traditional Indian art forms, along with related crafts such as the Tanjore doll. Hence, describing Tanjore as a traditional Indian folk (or classical) art form is correct.

Although originally an agricultural tool, the scythe (often straightened or given a new blade position and called a “war-scythe”) was repeatedly pressed into service by peasants and irregular troops throughout European history—for example, in various Polish uprisings and during the Hussite wars—so it can be said that a scythe was indeed used as a weapon, albeit mainly as an improvised or modified one rather than a purpose-built military arm.

Montgomery Ward filed for liquidation in 2000 and closed all of its brick-and-mortar department stores by 2001. The name was later revived as an online and catalog retailer, but no physical Montgomery Ward stores have reopened. Therefore, if the question refers to actual retail stores, none are still operating.

The question asks whether Trinidad and Tobago are in (i.e., qualified for and participated in) the 2018 FIFA World Cup. Only 32 national teams played in the Russia 2018 finals; Trinidad and Tobago did not qualify. They were eliminated during CONCACAF qualification (finishing last in the final Hexagonal round). Therefore, they were not in the 2018 World Cup.

Under FIFA eligibility rules, a player who has appeared in a competitive senior (“A-level”) match for one national team becomes cap-tied and may not switch to represent a different country. A one-time switch is possible only if the player’s previous appearances were limited to youth sides, friendlies, or (since the 2020 rule change) no more than three senior competitive matches played before the age of 21. Therefore a player cannot freely represent two different senior national teams in official competition; in almost all practical cases the answer is no.

In most jurisdictions you are allowed to add a motor to a bicycle provided the finished vehicle meets the local definitions for either an e-bike or a moped—usually limits on power (e.g., ≤750 W in the U.S., ≤250 W in the EU) and top assisted speed (20–28 mph in the U.S., 25 km/h in the EU). If those limits are exceeded the bike must be registered and insured like a motorcycle. Because the question is broad and laws vary, the safest generalized statement is that it is legal, subject to regulations.

Pretty Little Liars is shot on the Warner Bros. backlot in Burbank, California. The same town square set was previously used as Stars Hollow in Gilmore Girls, so the series does, in effect, film on the Stars Hollow set.

In the United States (and most other jurisdictions), a person cannot practice law or call themselves an attorney without being admitted to the bar of at least one jurisdiction. Admission almost always requires passing that jurisdiction’s bar examination (or, more rarely, qualifying for a special route such as Wisconsin’s diploma privilege, which still results in bar admission). Therefore, for practical purposes, passing the bar—or otherwise gaining bar admission—is required to be an attorney authorized to practice law.

Under modern official rules (e.g., FIDE Laws of Chess) a player is not obligated to verbally announce “check.” Players are expected to notice threats to their own king on their own. Announcing check is therefore optional and even discouraged in formal play, though it is common in casual games.
A joule is a unit of energy, while a watt is a unit of power (energy per unit time: 1 W = 1 J/s). Because they measure different physical quantities, they are not the same unit.

In the United States $1,000 notes (along with the $500, $5,000, and $10,000 notes) were last printed in 1945 and officially withdrawn from circulation by the Federal Reserve in 1969. They are still legal tender but banks no longer stock or distribute them; almost all surviving examples are in the hands of collectors and dealers. Therefore, walking into a bank today and requesting a $1,000 bill is not possible.

Rise of the Tomb Raider is the direct narrative sequel to the 2013 reboot title Tomb Raider and takes place roughly a year after the events on Yamatai, continuing Lara Croft's story. Therefore, it is set after Tomb Raider.

“The Girl in the Spider’s Web” (2015) is the fourth book in the Millennium series. It was followed by a fifth installment, “The Girl Who Takes an Eye for an Eye,” published in 2017 (and later a sixth, “The Girl Who Lived Twice,” in 2019). Therefore, there is indeed a book that comes after “The Girl in the Spider’s Web.”

Persian is written with a script derived from Arabic, but Persian adds four extra letters (پ، چ، ژ، گ) and omits a few Arabic phonemes. Pronunciation and sometimes letter usage differ as well. Therefore the two alphabets are related but not identical.

Wisconsin law (e.g., Wis. Stat. § 125.07(1)(a) & (4)(b)) allows persons under 21 to possess and consume alcohol if they are with and have the consent of their parent, guardian, or spouse of legal drinking age, including in licensed premises when the parent/guardian purchases the drink. Therefore, drinking with one’s parents is legally permitted under those conditions.

The Mazda Tribute and Ford Escape were co-developed by Mazda and Ford and built on the same CD2 platform. They share most mechanical components, engines, and chassis parts, and were even assembled in the same factories for many markets. Cosmetic styling, trims, and some tuning differ by brand, but functionally they are rebadged versions of the same compact SUV.

Historically, school shootings in the United States have occurred in a variety of educational settings, including public K–12 schools, private K–12 schools, public universities, and private colleges. Notable recent examples at private institutions include the 2023 shooting at The Covenant School (a private Christian elementary school in Nashville, TN) and the 2012 shooting at Oikos University (a private college in Oakland, CA). These events confirm that some school shootings have indeed taken place at private schools.

Cars are not limited to gasoline engines. Vehicles exist that operate on electricity (battery electric cars), diesel, biodiesel, ethanol blends, compressed natural gas, propane, hydrogen fuel cells, and even solar-assisted electric systems. Therefore, a car can indeed run on fuels or energy sources other than gasoline.
The famous leaning tower is located in the city of Pisa, in the Tuscany region of Italy, not in Rome. Therefore the statement that it is in Rome is incorrect.

During fetal development, a fine, soft hair called lanugo grows over almost the entire body. It helps protect the baby’s skin while suspended in amniotic fluid. Most of this hair is shed before birth (sometimes a bit remains, especially in pre-term babies), but while in the womb the fetus is indeed largely covered with this fine hair.

Pimentos (pimientos) are a specific, small, heart-shaped, sweet variety of red chili pepper that is usually sold diced and packed in brine. Roasted red peppers are typically larger red bell peppers that have been charred and peeled; they can come from several red bell pepper cultivars. Although both are red peppers and can sometimes be substituted in recipes, they are not the same ingredient.
The empty set, denoted ∅, by definition contains no elements at all. Therefore there cannot be any object— including another empty set— that is an element of ∅. So the statement ∅ ∈ ∅ is false.

In the 2004 live-action film "Garfield: The Movie" (and its sequel), the character Garfield was created with computer-generated imagery and voiced by Bill Murray, while the other animals (e.g., Odie) were live-action. Therefore, Garfield himself is not a real, live cat in the movie.

Under U.S. federal law (the 2019 ‘Tobacco 21’ amendment to the Food, Drug, and Cosmetic Act) it is illegal to sell any tobacco product—including e-cigarettes and vaping devices—to individuals under 21. Comparable age-restriction laws exist in most other countries and states as well. Therefore, selling e-cigarettes to minors is illegal in the United States and in many jurisdictions worldwide.

In practice the terms are used interchangeably. Both refer to the branch of accounting that produces internal financial and non-financial information to help managers plan, control and make decisions. Textbooks and professional bodies in different regions simply prefer one label over the other (e.g., “managerial accounting” in the U.S., “management accounting” in the U.K.), but the underlying concepts and functions are the same.

The Audience Network officially renewed “You Me Her” for both a fourth and a fifth season back in 2017. Season 4 has already been produced and premiered (April 2019 in the U.S.), so the existence of a fourth season is confirmed.

The London Marathon is one of the world’s six major marathons and regularly attracts more than 40,000 finishers, but the New York City Marathon generally has the highest number of starters and finishers each year (often 50,000+). Therefore, London is not the largest marathon by participant count, though it is among the biggest.

Guillermo del Toro’s 2017 film "The Shape of Water" originated from an original story and screenplay by del Toro and Vanessa Taylor; it was not adapted from an existing novel. Although there were later novelizations and claims of similarity to a stage play, the movie itself was not based on a book.

Yes. People can develop IgE-mediated hypersensitivity to proteins or the alpha-gal carbohydrate found in mammalian meat. This can cause hives, anaphylaxis, or other allergic symptoms after eating beef, pork, lamb, etc. Poultry and fish allergy also exist. Therefore a ‘meat allergy’ is medically documented.

CBS has repeatedly renewed “The Young and the Restless,” most recently extending it through the 2023-24 TV season, and there has been no credible announcement from the network or producers that the long-running soap opera is being cancelled. All available industry news and official statements indicate it will remain on the air for the foreseeable future.

A will is the instrument that directs how a person’s property is to be distributed after death and is enforceable in probate court. Because it must meet statutory requirements (proper form, signature, witnesses, etc.) to be valid and legally binding, it is, by definition, a legal document—even if it is handwritten or drafted without a lawyer.

Law 11 of the IFAB Laws of the Game states that a player cannot be penalised for offside when receiving the ball directly from a goal kick (as well as from a throw-in or corner kick). Therefore, no matter where the attacker is positioned, an offside offence cannot be called in that situation.

In the United States, a college football player is not required to declare for the NFL Draft while he still has remaining collegiate eligibility; he can simply continue playing in college or leave football altogether. Once a player has been out of high school for at least three years and has no remaining college eligibility (e.g., he is a senior who just finished his last season), he automatically becomes draft-eligible, but even then he is not compelled to pursue an NFL career—he may choose another profession, another league, or retire from football. Filing paperwork to ‘enter’ the draft is only necessary for underclassmen who wish to give up their remaining eligibility early. Therefore, college football players are not obliged to enter the NFL Draft.

The iliac crest is the superior curved border of the ilium, which is one of the three bones (ilium, ischium, pubis) that fuse to form each hip (coxal) bone of the pelvis. Therefore, it is anatomically considered part of the hip.

Northern Ireland is a constituent part of the United Kingdom, while the Republic of Ireland is an independent sovereign nation. They have separate governments, legal systems and international status, so they are not the same entity.

The 1952 film “The Greatest Show on Earth,” directed by Cecil B. DeMille, is generally classified as a drama/epic about circus life rather than a musical. While it contains circus performances, it is not structured as a musical with characters breaking into song to advance the plot.

The 2017 film "Roxanne Roxanne" is a biographical drama about real-life Queens rapper Roxanne Shanté (born Lolita Shanté Gooden). The plot is based on her life and career, so the movie is intended to depict a true story rather than a fictional narrative.

Under the U.S. Constitution, Supreme Court justices hold their offices during “good Behaviour,” which has consistently been interpreted as a lifetime appointment. They may choose to retire or can be removed only through impeachment, but there is no statute or constitutional provision that sets a mandatory retirement age.

Johnson & Wales University (commonly called Johnson and Wales) is chartered as a private, nonprofit institution; it is not operated to generate profit for owners or shareholders like a for-profit college would be.

Newborn puppies’ eyelids open at about 10–14 days of age, but the retina and optic nerve are still immature. For the first week or two after the eyes open they can only detect light, shapes, and movement; focused, detailed vision does not develop until several weeks later. Therefore, they essentially cannot ‘see’ in the usual sense immediately upon opening their eyes.

answer: Yes, for certain categories such as hate speech or incitement
Reasoning: Canada generally protects freedom of expression, but the Charter allows "reasonable limits" that are prescribed by law. Under the Criminal Code, certain kinds of speech—e.g., willful promotion of hatred against an identifiable group (s. 319(2)), public incitement of hatred likely to lead to a breach of the peace (s. 319(1)), advocating genocide (s. 318), uttering threats (s. 264.1) or counselling the commission of a crime—are criminal offences punishable by fines and/or imprisonment. Therefore, while merely being rude or ‘offensive’ is not criminal, speech that crosses those statutory lines can lead to arrest and possible jail time.
Answer: Yes, for certain categories such as hate speech or incitement

Reasoning: Victor Hugo’s “The Hunchback of Notre-Dame” is a work of fiction. Although Hugo may have drawn very loose inspiration from architecture-department records that mentioned a hunchbacked stone carver at Notre-Dame, the plot, characters (Quasimodo, Esmeralda, Claude Frollo, etc.), and events are products of the author’s imagination. Therefore, it is not a true historical story in the sense of actually having happened.

Pokémon: Let’s Go, Pikachu! and Let’s Go, Eevee! were developed by Game Freak, follow the traditional badge-collecting progression, and have been described by both Game Freak director Junichi Masuda and The Pokémon Company as part of the ‘core’ (main-series) Pokémon RPG line, even though they have streamlined mechanics influenced by Pokémon GO. While some fans view them as spinoffs, the official stance classifies them as main-series titles.

Banks are financial institutions that accept deposits and are regulated as depository institutions. Payday lenders provide short-term, high-cost loans but generally do not take deposits and are regulated under different non-bank lending rules. Therefore, a payday lender is classified as a non-bank financial service provider, not a bank.

‘Fear the Walking Dead’ is a separate companion series to ‘The Walking Dead.’ While both shows take place in the same fictional universe of the zombie apocalypse, they feature different casts, storylines, and locations, and they began airing at different times on AMC. Therefore, the two shows are distinct from each other, even though they occasionally share crossover elements.

In ordinary chemical reactions atoms keep their identities, but nuclear processes (radioactive decay, fission, fusion, particle-beam transmutation) can change the number of protons in a nucleus, thereby converting one element into another. Because such nuclear transformations are well-established experimentally, the statement that atoms can be changed from one element to another is correct.

Medical conditions such as stroke-induced aphasia, traumatic brain injury, neurodegenerative diseases, or damage/removal of the larynx can all result in partial or complete loss of the ability to speak, showing that speech loss is indeed possible.

Low Isles (comprising Low Island and Woody Island) is a small coral cay located off the coast of Port Douglas, Queensland, within the Great Barrier Reef Marine Park. Because it lies inside the marine park boundaries and is a coral formation of the reef system, it is considered part of the Great Barrier Reef.

Historically, the U.S. has printed denominations larger than $100, such as the $500, $1,000, $5,000, $10,000, and the $100,000 gold certificate. Although they are no longer produced or circulated for everyday use, they exist (or existed) and are legal tender, so something larger than a $100 bill does indeed exist.

The Amazon River flows through northern South America, primarily Brazil and Peru, traversing the vast tropical region known as the Amazon Basin. The Amazon Rainforest covers most of this basin, so the river indeed winds through the rainforest for much of its course.

A modern Vehicle Identification Number (VIN) is a 17-character code that contains several pieces of information, including the vehicle’s unique production or serial sequence within the manufacturer’s run. While people sometimes use the term “serial number” informally to mean the whole VIN, technically the serial number is only a part of the VIN (usually the last 6–8 characters). Therefore, a car’s serial number is not the same as the full VIN.

Percent change measures how much a value has increased or decreased relative to its starting (original) value: (new − original) / original × 100 %. Percent difference, on the other hand, measures how far apart two values are relative to their average: |value₁ − value₂| / [(value₁ + value₂)/2] × 100 %. Because the denominators (original value vs. average of the two values) and the intent (directional change vs. nondirectional comparison) differ, the two concepts are not the same.

The original Hunger Games trilogy was completed in 2010 (books) and 2012-2015 (four films). Suzanne Collins released a prequel novel, “The Ballad of Songbirds and Snakes,” in 2020. Lionsgate has officially green-lit a film adaptation of that prequel, with a targeted theatrical release in November 2023. Beyond this prequel movie, neither the studio nor Collins has announced any additional sequels or new books, so at present the only upcoming Hunger Games project that is known is the 2023 prequel film.
Answer: Yes – a prequel film adaptation of “The Ballad of Songbirds and Snakes” is scheduled to be released (currently slated for November 2023). No further books or movies have been confirmed.

Reasoning: Studio City is a neighborhood located within the city of Los Angeles, specifically on the southeastern side of the San Fernando Valley. Because it falls within the geographic boundaries that define the San Fernando Valley region, the statement is correct.

In the original 1980 "Friday the 13th," the killer is Pamela Voorhees, Jason’s mother. Jason himself does not appear as the hockey-masked killer; he is only shown briefly as a child in a dream sequence, which is often considered a hallucination. Therefore, if the question is asking whether Jason is a main character/killer in the first film, the correct answer is no.

Glacier National Park in Montana was named for the many glaciers that sculpted its landscape, and despite their retreat, several active glaciers (e.g., Grinnell, Sperry) still remain within the park boundaries.

Audi is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Volkswagen AG (the Volkswagen Group). Both Audi and Volkswagen vehicles are produced under the same corporate parent, so they are made by the same overarching company.

Although both serve the same purpose—authenticating a user—a passphrase is typically a longer series of words or a sentence, whereas a password is usually a shorter string of characters. Because of their structural and length differences, they are not considered exactly the same thing, even though a passphrase can be viewed as a type of password.

“Body of Proof,” the ABC television drama starring Dana Delany, originally aired from 2011 to 2013 and was cancelled after its third season. No new episodes have been produced or broadcast since 2013, and there has been no revival announced. Therefore, it is no longer an active, currently airing series.

Before becoming the 35th U.S. state in 1863, the counties that now make up West Virginia were part of the Commonwealth of Virginia. They separated during the Civil War to form a new state loyal to the Union.

The television series “This Is Us” premiered in 2016 and was renewed for additional seasons shortly thereafter. In fact, the show ultimately ran for six seasons in total, so a second season definitely exists.

Oceanographers classify the Caribbean Sea as a marginal sea that is connected to and forms a subdivision of the Atlantic Ocean, lying to the southeast of the Gulf of Mexico and the North American mainland and bounded by the Antilles islands and Central and South America.
The set {∅} has exactly one element, and that element is the empty set ∅ itself. Therefore, ∅ ∈ {∅} is a true statement.

Kristen Bell provides both the speaking and singing voice for adult/teen Anna in Frozen, but the younger versions of Anna in the song “Do You Want to Build a Snowman?” are sung by Katie Lopez and Agatha Lee Monn. Therefore Kristen Bell did not sing every vocal part for Anna.

The 2010 film “Burlesque,” starring Christina Aguilera and Cher, is an original work of fiction. While it draws on common show-business tropes about a small-town girl finding success in a Los Angeles nightclub, the filmmakers have never claimed it is drawn from specific real events or people. No credible sources identify it as a biographical or true-story adaptation.

In the United Kingdom there is no separate ‘Tax Identification Number’ for individuals. HMRC uses the National Insurance (NI) number as the unique identifier for tracking a person’s income-tax and social-security contributions. Therefore, for an individual in the UK the NI number functions as their TIN, even though the two terms differ in name and scope across countries.

In Season 2, episode 5 ("The Doctor"), Dr. Whale/Frankenstein uses his methods and a preserved heart to reanimate Regina’s fiancé Daniel. Although the resurrection is only temporary and he ultimately dies again, Daniel does in fact come back to life on-screen.
Creating a basic PlayStation Network (PSN) account is free; you only pay if you choose to subscribe to PlayStation Plus or make purchases. Therefore, joining the network itself does not cost money.

The excretory system (often called the urinary system in humans) consists of the kidneys, ureters, urinary bladder, and urethra. The bladder’s role is to store urine produced by the kidneys until it is expelled from the body, so it is indeed one of the organs that make up the excretory system.

Under Law 12 of the IFAB Laws of the Game, a goalkeeper is forbidden from handling the ball when it has been directly received from a throw-in taken by a team-mate; doing so results in an indirect free-kick to the opponents. (The keeper may handle it if the throw-in came from an opponent.) Therefore, the goalkeeper cannot legally pick up the ball from a team-mate’s throw-in.

In G.I. Joe lore, Snake Eyes and Storm Shadow are two distinct characters with separate identities—Snake Eyes is an American commando/ninja, while Storm Shadow (Tommy Arashikage) is his on-again/off-again rival and fellow ninja from the Arashikage clan. Although they share intertwined backstories and training, they are not the same individual.

Virtually all scheduled commercial airlines worldwide prohibit smoking on board due to international regulations and airline policies adopted since the 1990s. While an owner-operated private aircraft could technically permit smoking if local laws allow, the question is generally understood to refer to passenger flights offered to the public, for which smoking is not allowed.

“Chicken” is the species (Gallus domesticus) and can refer to any sex or age of the bird, whereas “rooster” specifically means an adult male chicken. Therefore, a rooster is a type of chicken, but the two terms are not interchangeable.

Most bacteria possess a cell wall composed of peptidoglycan, but notable exceptions exist. Members of the genus Mycoplasma (and related wall-less bacteria) lack a cell wall completely and therefore contain no peptidoglycan. Because at least some bacteria do not have peptidoglycan, the statement that all bacteria possess it is incorrect.

The Gulf of Mexico is classified as a marginal sea (a large gulf) of the Atlantic Ocean, bordered by the United States, Mexico, and Cuba. It is not itself one of the planet’s major oceans (Pacific, Atlantic, Indian, Southern, Arctic), but rather a smaller body of water connected to the Atlantic via the Straits of Florida and the Caribbean Sea.

The Burma–Thailand Railway and the forced labor of Allied POWs by the Japanese were real historical events, and bridges were indeed built over the Kwai Yai/Kwai Noi rivers. However, the central characters—especially Colonel Nicholson—and most of the dramatic plot points in the 1957 film are fictional inventions or extreme distortions. Therefore, the movie is only loosely inspired by history, not a true account.

Final Fantasy XII: The Zodiac Age is an HD remaster of the 2006 PlayStation 2 title, based specifically on the ‘International Zodiac Job System’ version released only in Japan. It features higher-resolution graphics, improved audio, quality-of-life tweaks, and a few balance changes, but the underlying game engine, assets, story, and design are essentially the same. A remake would entail rebuilding the game from the ground up (as with Final Fantasy VII Remake), which is not the case here.

St. Augustine, founded by the Spanish in 1565, is widely recognized as the oldest continuously inhabited European-established settlement within what is now the continental United States. While there are older Indigenous settlements and older European colonies elsewhere in the Americas (e.g., in Puerto Rico), within the territory that became the United States it holds the title of the oldest city.

Australia spans roughly 40° of longitude and officially uses three primary standard time zones (Australian Western, Central, and Eastern). Daylight-saving adjustments create even more offsets in some states. Therefore, not all of Australia shares a single time zone.

Call of Duty: Black Ops III, like other games in the Black Ops sub-series, includes a dedicated Zombies mode featuring cooperative, wave-based gameplay. This mode was a major advertised component of the game at launch.
The 2008 animated film “The Tale of Despereaux” was produced by Universal Pictures and Framestore Animation and distributed by Universal, not by Walt Disney Pictures or any Disney subsidiary.

Since 2017, Iowa state law allows the sale and use of consumer fireworks during specified periods (mainly June 1-July 8 and Dec 10-Jan 3), though cities and counties may restrict or ban their use locally. Therefore, fireworks are not outright illegal statewide, only regulated and potentially prohibited by some local ordinances.

RMS Titanic was the largest passenger ship when it was launched in 1912, but since then many ships—both passenger (e.g., Oasis-class cruise ships) and cargo (e.g., Seawise Giant, later Jahre Viking)—have been built that are far larger in length, gross tonnage, and displacement. Therefore, the Titanic is no longer anywhere near the biggest ship ever built.

Core body temperature follows a circadian rhythm, typically being lowest in the early morning hours and peaking in the late afternoon or early evening. This daily fluctuation occurs in healthy individuals and is considered normal.

There are two neighboring, sovereign states in Central Africa with similar names: the Republic of the Congo (capital: Brazzaville) and the Democratic Republic of the Congo (capital: Kinshasa). Although they share a border and a colonial history, they are distinct countries with separate governments, capitals, and territories.

In season 8 of Entourage, Ari and his wife separate, but in the series finale he decides to leave the agency to save their marriage and they reconcile. In the subsequent Entourage movie they are shown still married, confirming they got back together.

Like most rabbit breeds, Netherland Dwarfs are ground-oriented prey animals. Being lifted off the ground can make them feel unsafe, and this breed is known for being especially energetic and sometimes skittish. While an individual rabbit that has been carefully socialized from a young age may learn to tolerate or even enjoy brief cuddling, the typical Netherland Dwarf generally does not like being held for long periods and may struggle or become stressed.

New Hampshire is one of the few U.S. states that does not impose a general state sales tax on the purchase of most goods. While it does levy specific taxes on items such as prepared meals, rooms, and rentals, the common statement that “there is no sales tax in New Hampshire” refers to the absence of a broad retail sales tax.

A power (AC) adapter’s primary job is to convert household AC to a lower-voltage DC supply. A battery charger, on the other hand, not only provides DC power but also contains regulation circuitry that controls current/voltage over time to safely charge a battery. Many devices hide the charger circuitry inside the device while the external brick is only an adapter, so the two terms are often mixed up but technically they are not the same thing.

In English-speaking coffee culture, a “caffè latte” (Italian for “coffee and milk”) is commonly shortened to just “latte.” Both refer to the drink made with one or more shots of espresso and steamed milk topped with a little foam. While in Italy ordering simply “latte” would get you a glass of milk, in the context implied by the question—modern café terminology—“latte” is understood to be the same beverage as a caffè latte.

While both belong to the order Testudines, the word “turtle” is a broad term that commonly refers to species that live in or around water, whereas “tortoise” is reserved for primarily land-dwelling species with distinct anatomical and ecological differences (e.g., heavier domed shells, column-like legs). Hence they are related but not the same.

The Constitution grants states primary authority to regulate alcohol. Each state sets its own minimum drinking age. In 1984, Congress passed the National Minimum Drinking Age Act, which withholds a portion of federal highway funds from any state that allows purchase or public possession of alcohol by people under 21. This federal statute creates a strong financial incentive, but it does not itself establish a nationwide legal drinking age; states must enact their own laws to comply. Therefore, the minimum drinking age is not directly imposed as a single federal law—it is a set of state laws influenced by federal funding conditions.

In the United States, a state identification card (state ID) is produced and issued by a state’s department of motor vehicles or equivalent agency, which is an official government body. Because it is created, regulated, and distributed by a governmental authority, it qualifies as a government-issued identification document.

Bosnia and Herzegovina has applied for EU membership and was granted candidate status in 2022, but it has not yet completed accession negotiations or become a full member state. Therefore, it is not currently part of the European Union.

In U.S. pickup terminology, the label “½-ton” is traditionally applied to full-size light-duty trucks such as the Ford F-150 or Chevrolet 1500 series. Although the Nissan Frontier’s payload capacity can be around 1,000–1,500 lb (roughly a half-ton), it is marketed and classified as a midsize/compact pickup, not a ½-ton full-size truck.
ABC officially renewed Station 19 in May 2018, and its second season premiered on 4 October 2018.

Calcium chloride (CaCl₂) and calcium carbonate (CaCO₃) have different chemical formulas, structures, and properties. Calcium chloride is a salt of calcium and hydrochloric acid, while calcium carbonate is a salt of calcium and carbonic acid (and the main component of limestone and chalk). Therefore, they are not the same substance.

The 2008 film “Changeling,” directed by Clint Eastwood and starring Angelina Jolie, dramatizes real-life events surrounding Christine Collins, her missing son, and the 1928 Wineville Chicken Coop murders in Los Angeles. While some details are fictionalized for dramatic effect, the core story is drawn from documented historical events, so it is considered ‘based on a true story.’

Paris has historically been recognized as the pre-eminent center of high fashion, hosting some of the world’s most influential couture houses (e.g., Chanel, Dior, Louis Vuitton) and headline fashion weeks. While other cities such as Milan, New York, and London have gained comparable prestige, Paris remains widely cited by industry rankings, media, and designers as the foremost fashion capital. Because “fashion capital” is a partly subjective designation, there is room for debate, but the prevailing consensus continues to place Paris at the top.

A kippah is the Hebrew word for the small skull-cap traditionally worn by Jewish males, while “yarmulke” (often misspelled as “yamaka”) is the Yiddish term for the same head covering. They refer to the identical item, differing only by language of origin.

The Hughes H-4 Hercules—nicknamed the “Spruce Goose”—was constructed almost entirely from laminated birch and other wood composites because wartime restrictions limited aluminum use. Although the nickname references spruce, it was indeed a wooden aircraft.

Insulin resistance is a well-documented physiological condition in which the body’s cells (especially muscle, fat, and liver cells) respond less effectively to insulin, leading to impaired glucose uptake and higher blood glucose levels. It is recognized in both clinical practice and biomedical research as a key factor in type 2 diabetes and metabolic syndrome.

In the Netflix series “The Ranch,” the Bennett family lives near the town of Garrison, Colorado. That town was created for the show; there is no actual municipality named Garrison in Colorado (or in the specific area depicted). Thus, ‘Garrison’ as portrayed in the series is fictional rather than an existing real-world place.

Icelandic last names are traditionally patronymic or matronymic. Men usually receive a surname ending in “-son” (meaning “son of”), while women receive “-dóttir” (meaning “daughter of”). In addition, a minority of Icelanders have inherited family surnames that do not use either ending. Therefore, not every Icelandic name ends in “son.”
