Bank of America’s corporate headquarters are in Charlotte, North Carolina, and the bank operates numerous branches throughout the state. Therefore, there is unquestionably a Bank of America in North Carolina.

In FIFA World Cup history several host nations have gone on to win the tournament (e.g., Uruguay 1930, Italy 1934, England 1966, West Germany 1974, Argentina 1978, France 1998). Therefore, at least one country has indeed won the World Cup on home soil.

The text of the U.S. Constitution does not contain the words “right to privacy.”  However, the Supreme Court has interpreted several provisions—primarily the 1st, 3rd, 4th, 5th, 9th, and 14th Amendments—as creating an implied constitutional right to privacy.  Thus, while the right is judicially recognized, it is not expressly written into the Constitution itself.

The drama series “Outsiders,” which aired on WGN America from 2016-2017, was officially cancelled after its second season when the network shifted its programming strategy. Since that cancellation there have been no credible reports, announcements, or industry indications of a revival, reboot, or continuation on any network or streaming platform. Entertainment-news outlets and the show’s former cast have likewise not mentioned any plans to bring it back.

J.R.R. Tolkien wrote The Lord of the Rings as one continuous novel. It was his publisher, for economic and practical reasons, who decided to divide it into three volumes (The Fellowship of the Ring, The Two Towers, and The Return of the King). Therefore, in its original conception it was a single book.

In the context of the United States, the official national anthem is the song titled “The Star-Spangled Banner.” Therefore, when people in the U.S. refer to “the national anthem,” they are referring to “The Star-Spangled Banner,” so the two terms denote the same song.

In most electrical-engineering and physics contexts the term “dielectric constant” is simply another name for the relative permittivity εr, i.e., the ratio ε / ε0.  Although specialists sometimes reserve “dielectric constant” for the static (zero-frequency) value of εr, in ordinary usage the two terms refer to the same dimensionless property of a material.

The 1946 film “It’s a Wonderful Life” takes place largely on Christmas Eve, its central themes involve community, generosity and redemption associated with the holiday season, and it has become a staple of Christmas television programming. Therefore, it is widely regarded as a Christmas movie.

The idea that a unique 'vena amoris' runs directly from the ring finger to the heart is a romantic myth dating back to ancient cultures. Anatomically, all fingers have veins that ultimately connect to the heart through the larger venous network; the ring finger’s blood supply is not unique or more direct than that of any other finger.

answer: True – it is possible, but extremely rare and generally limited to situations such as organ or tissue transplantation (or a deep bite).
Reasoning: Rabies virus is usually spread through saliva entering broken skin (typically via animal bites). In humans, documented transmission to another person is extremely rare but has occurred, almost exclusively through corneal and solid-organ transplants, and theoretically could occur through a deep bite that transfers infected saliva. Casual contact, touching, or being near an infected patient does not transmit the virus. Therefore, while possible, person-to-person transmission can occur only under unusual circumstances.
Answer: True – it is possible, but extremely rare and generally limited to situations such as organ or tissue transplantation (or a deep bite).

Reasoning: The 1978 FIFA World Cup was held in Argentina and was won by the host nation, Argentina. Scotland participated in the tournament but were eliminated in the group stage and did not progress to the knockout rounds. Therefore, Scotland did not win the World Cup in 1978.

Diamonds are crystalline carbon and can be re-faceted by skilled cutters. While doing so sacrifices some weight and requires special equipment, it is routine in the trade to recut an existing stone into a different shape (e.g., an old-mine cut recut to a round brilliant). Therefore the statement that a diamond can be cut into a different shape is correct.

Under current UEFA and English FA regulations, the club that wins the FA Cup is awarded a place in European competition. Specifically, beginning with the 2021-22 cycle, the FA Cup winner qualifies directly for the UEFA Europa League group stage (previously it was a Europa League qualifying spot). If the FA Cup winner has already secured Champions League or Europa League football via its league position, the Europa League place is passed down to the next-highest Premier League team not already qualified. Therefore, winning the FA Cup does grant a European berth.

In corporate and securities law a “public company” is one that is allowed to offer its securities to the public and is subject to the fuller disclosure and reporting rules that go with that status. Listing on a stock exchange is only one way—though the most common—for its shares to be publicly traded. A company can register its shares with the securities regulator and have them trade over-the-counter or not trade at all, yet still be legally classified as a public company. Therefore being listed on an exchange is not a legal requirement for public-company status.
Both “The Alphabet Song” (A-B-C song) and “Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star” are set to the same 18th-century French melody, “Ah! vous dirai-je, Maman,” so they share the same tune.

A cow begins producing milk only after it has undergone a pregnancy and given birth (the hormonal changes of calving trigger lactation). Once lactation starts, the cow can keep giving milk for many months without being pregnant again, but the initial pregnancy is necessary to start milk production.

In common usage, the word “hamburger” refers to a sandwich (or patty) made from ground beef, even though the name contains the word “ham.” A “beef burger” likewise specifies that the patty is made from beef. Therefore, in everyday contexts a beef burger and a hamburger denote the same food item made from ground beef.

Eminem’s “’Till I Collapse” appeared on his 2002 album “The Eminem Show,” almost a decade before the 2011 movie “Real Steel.” The track was later used in trailers and promotional material for the film, but it was not written or produced specifically for the movie.

Under Article II, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution, the president’s pardon power extends only to “Offences against the United States,” i.e., federal crimes. State crimes are prosecuted under state law, and clemency for them can be granted only by the state’s governor or other state authority. Therefore, a president cannot pardon someone solely for a state conviction.

Human core body temperature follows a circadian (daily) rhythm. It typically reaches its lowest point in the early morning hours (around 4–6 a.m.) and gradually rises, peaking in the late afternoon to early evening (around 4–8 p.m.). Therefore, relative to the morning, body temperature is generally higher in the evening for most people.
The story follows the von Trapp family in and around Salzburg and the Austrian Alps during the late 1930s, making Austria the primary setting of the musical and film.

Sky Atlantic officially renewed the drama series “Riviera” for a second season (announced in late-2017, with Season 2 eventually airing in 2019). Therefore, a second series is planned/has been produced.

There have been several versions of “The Chase.” The original U.K. version on ITV, which launched in 2009 with host Bradley Walsh, has continued to produce new episodes each year and remains on the air. In the United States, a GSN version ended in 2015, but ABC revived the format in 2021 and has renewed it for additional seasons. Therefore, at least one current version of the game show is still being broadcast.
Answer: Yes – a current version of “The Chase” is still on the air.

Reasoning: Some males are born with only one testicle due to congenital absence (anorchia/monorchism) or because the second testicle fails to develop or descend. Therefore, it is possible to be born with a single testicle.

Liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) is a category of fuel gases that are liquefied under pressure and typically includes propane, butane, or a mixture of the two. Propane is therefore one specific type of LPG, but LPG as a term is broader and does not always consist solely of propane. Thus, LPG and propane are related but not identical terms.

In the FIFA World Cup final, if the score is still level after the standard 90 minutes plus the 30 minutes of extra time, the champion is decided by a penalty-kick shootout. (Normal in-play penalty kicks for fouls in the box can also occur, but the question typically refers to the shootout procedure.) Therefore, penalties are indeed part of the rules for the final.

Crayola Color Wonder markers are formulated to react only with the special Color Wonder paper coating; on ordinary paper (or skin, tables, clothing, etc.) the ink remains clear and does not produce visible color. Therefore we can say they do not ‘work’—i.e., they don’t leave colored marks—on regular paper.

Chicago no longer has a blanket handgun ban; Illinois residents may legally possess firearms in the city provided they comply with state and local regulations (e.g., obtain an Illinois Firearm Owner’s Identification (FOID) card, and, for carrying in public, a state concealed-carry license). Thus, gun ownership itself is not prohibited, only regulated.

Andy's mother in the Child's Play franchise is Karen Barclay. In the original 1988 film she survives the events and is alive at the end. Later continuity states she was placed in a psychiatric hospital (Child's Play 2) but she is still alive; she is not shown or mentioned as having been killed in any subsequent installment. Therefore, Andy’s mom did not die in the Child’s Play series.
Dwight Howard signed with and played for the Houston Rockets from the 2013-14 season through the 2015-16 season.

answer: Yes – you need a TV licence if you watch or record live TV or use BBC iPlayer; otherwise it's not required for purely non-BBC on-demand content.
Reasoning: In the UK, a TV Licence is legally required if you (a) watch or record live television on any channel or service, or (b) use BBC iPlayer (live or on-demand). If you only watch on-demand, non-BBC services and never watch or record live broadcasts, you do not need a licence. Therefore, most people who watch live TV or use iPlayer do need one.
Answer: Yes – you need a TV licence if you watch or record live TV or use BBC iPlayer; otherwise it’s not required for purely non-BBC on-demand content.

Reasoning: Cardiothoracic surgeon Teddy Altman (played by Kim Raver) leaves at the end of Season 8, but the character later reappears—first in guest spots in Season 14 and then as a full-time series regular starting in Season 15—so she does in fact return to Grey’s Anatomy.

SeaWorld ended its orca breeding program and theatrical shows, but the existing orcas were kept and remain on display for the rest of their natural lives. SeaWorld San Diego currently houses several killer whales (e.g., Corky, Ulises, Orkid). Therefore, the park still has killer whales.

Under most parliamentary authorities (e.g., Robert’s Rules of Order) and standard organizational bylaws, the draft minutes from a meeting do not become the official record until the body formally approves them, typically at the next regular meeting. Approval allows members to correct errors and ensures the record accurately reflects what occurred.

A PhD (Doctor of Philosophy) is a doctoral-level degree. Holders of any doctoral degree, including a PhD, are conventionally entitled to use the honorific 'Dr.' before their name in most academic and professional contexts.

Throughout the series Mac and Harm have an unresolved romantic tension. In the series finale they finally admit their feelings, exchange mutual marriage proposals and agree that one of them will resign so they can be together, leaving the exact details to a coin toss. Although the show ends without revealing the toss’s outcome, it is clear that by the finale they have decided to form a couple. Hence, in the context of the show, they do ‘get together.’

Yes. When people ascend to high elevations too quickly the lower atmospheric pressure leads to reduced oxygen saturation in the blood, which can cause a spectrum of illnesses collectively called altitude sickness (acute mountain sickness, high-altitude pulmonary edema, high-altitude cerebral edema). These conditions are well-documented in medicine.

Yes—Kathryn Bigelow (The Hurt Locker, 2009 awards ceremony in 2010) and later Chloé Zhao (Nomadland, 2021 ceremony) both won the Academy Award for Best Director, proving that women have indeed won an Oscar in the directing category.

In very rare cases, a woman can release two eggs during the same ovulation (fraternal twins). If she has intercourse with two different men within the window in which both eggs are viable (about 4–5 days), each egg can be fertilized by sperm from a different father. This phenomenon is called heteropaternal superfecundation and has been documented with DNA testing, making it scientifically possible, though uncommon.
The Eiffel Tower is 330 meters tall. Numerous structures worldwide exceed this height, such as the Burj Khalifa (828 m). Therefore, the Eiffel Tower is not the tallest structure in the world.

The thermal waters at Hot Springs, Arkansas are produced by rainwater that percolates deep into fractured rock along faults, is heated by the normal geothermal gradient, and then rises back to the surface. There is no known dormant or active volcanic cone or magma chamber beneath Hot Springs; the area’s igneous rocks are hundreds of millions of years old and no longer volcanically active. Therefore, Hot Springs is not located on a volcano.

In lever terminology, the pivot point about which the lever rotates is called the fulcrum. The load is the weight or resistance that the lever is intended to move, which is separate from the fulcrum. Therefore, the load is not the pivot point.

Since the wreck’s discovery in 1985, several expeditions (notably by RMS Titanic, Inc.) have recovered thousands of artifacts—including china, personal belongings, portions of the hull such as the 15-ton “Big Piece,” and machinery components—bringing them to the surface for conservation and display. Therefore, something has indeed been brought up from the Titanic.

HD DVD and Blu-ray were rival high-definition optical disc formats. They use different technical standards (laser wavelength, data capacity, disc structure) and their players/discs are not mutually compatible. Therefore, they are not the same format.

Yes. On October 24, 1971, Detroit Lions wide receiver Chuck Hughes collapsed late in a game against the Chicago Bears after suffering a massive heart attack brought on by undiagnosed arteriosclerosis. Though emergency personnel reached him quickly, Hughes never regained consciousness and was pronounced dead shortly thereafter. He is the only NFL player to have died during the course of an NFL game, effectively ‘on the field.’

Handedness and footedness are separate aspects of motor dominance governed by different neural pathways. While many people show the same dominance for both hand and foot, a significant minority display crossed laterality (e.g., right-handed but left-footed). This is well documented in biomechanics and sports science literature (e.g., many soccer players kick better with the left foot while writing with the right hand). Therefore such a combination is entirely possible and not unusual.

Both names refer to carbonated water that has been flavored with quinine. ‘Tonic water’ is the modern commercial term, while ‘quinine water’ is an older or alternate name; both describe the same basic beverage, although brands may vary in added sweeteners or quinine concentration.

Most common houseflies do not deposit eggs in intact human skin, but certain fly species (e.g., human botfly, tumbu fly) do lay eggs that penetrate or are placed on the skin, leading to a condition called cutaneous myiasis. Therefore, it is biologically possible for some flies to lay eggs in or on human skin.

Greece lost to Croatia in the UEFA qualification play-offs in November 2017 and therefore did not qualify for the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia. Since they were never in the final tournament, they cannot still be in it.

During the American Civil War, both Union and Confederate sides employed irregular fighters who conducted hit-and-run raids, sabotage, ambushes, and other partisan operations (e.g., Mosby’s Rangers in Virginia, Quantrill’s Raiders in Missouri). These activities are classic examples of guerrilla warfare, so the tactic was indeed used in the conflict.

In the television series “Little House on the Prairie,” the character Mary Ingalls (played by Melissa Sue Anderson) loses her sight after an illness early in the show’s run and is thereafter depicted as blind. Although she wasn’t blind in the very first seasons, the character is widely remembered for being blind for most of the series.

The Canadian men’s national soccer team qualified for and played in the 1986 FIFA World Cup in Mexico and again in the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar, so Canada has indeed participated in the World Cup.

Insidious: Chapter 3 was written as a prequel that shows Elise Rainier returning to paranormal work and meeting Tucker and Specs for the first time, events that occur several years before the Lambert family haunting depicted in Insidious (2010) and Insidious: Chapter 2 (2013). Therefore its story is set earlier in the timeline than the first two movies.

Under the rules of ice hockey, goaltenders are subject to the same rule book as any other player. If the goalie commits an infraction (e.g., tripping, delay of game, playing the puck in a restricted area), the referee can assess a minor, major, or even a misconduct penalty. The only special provision is that the goalie normally does not sit in the penalty box; instead, a teammate serves the time while the goalie remains in net (unless the penalty is a game misconduct or match penalty, in which case the goalie is ejected). Therefore, goalies absolutely can receive penalties.

Rocky Mountain National Park occupies a specific protected area in northern Colorado near Estes Park. Mount Evans is a 14,000-foot peak located farther south near Idaho Springs within the Mount Evans Wilderness of Arapaho and Pike National Forests, outside the park’s boundaries. Therefore, it is not part of Rocky Mountain National Park.

Both the federal ‘three-strikes’ statute (18 U.S.C. § 3559(c)) enacted in 1994 and most state three-strikes statutes—most notably California’s, which was amended by Proposition 36 in 2012 but not repealed—remain enforceable. While some states have modified or repealed their versions, the law as a legal mechanism still exists at the federal level and in several states, so in general the three-strikes law is still in effect.

In modern and historical English usage, ‘they/them’ can refer to a single person when the person’s gender is unknown, unspecified, or non-binary. This singular ‘they’ has been documented for centuries and is widely accepted by major style guides today.

While listing on a stock exchange is one way for a company to offer its shares to the public, it is not mandatory. Many jurisdictions allow ‘public’ or ‘publicly held’ companies to have a large shareholder base and be subject to public-company reporting rules even if their shares trade over-the-counter or are not traded at all. Therefore, being a public company does not automatically mean being exchange-listed.

In most jurisdictions the title “architect” is legally protected and may be used only by someone who has completed an accredited architecture degree, fulfilled internship requirements, and passed all parts of the professional licensure examinations. The term “architectural designer,” however, is not legally protected; it can refer to anyone who produces architectural drawings or concepts, including unlicensed graduates of architecture programs, interior designers, draftspersons, or even engineers. While both may perform design work, only a licensed architect can stamp drawings for permit and assume legal responsibility for the building’s design. Therefore, an architectural designer is not necessarily the same as an architect.

The U.S. Constitution lists only three eligibility criteria for the presidency: natural-born citizenship, at least 35 years of age, and 14 years of U.S. residency. It does not prohibit current federal judges, including Supreme Court justices, from running. While ethical or practical considerations might lead a justice to take leave or resign if elected, there is no legal bar to a Supreme Court justice becoming a presidential candidate.

Hart of Dixie aired for four seasons on The CW from 2011–2015 and was officially cancelled after the fourth season. Since then there has been no announcement of a renewal, revival, or additional season from the network, producers, or cast. Therefore, at present, there is no new season in development or airing.

Several digestive organs—including the liver, pancreas, small intestine, and even the stomach—are routinely or occasionally transplanted in modern medicine. Therefore, at least some organs of the digestive system can indeed be transplanted.

answer: Yes—standard Charlotte's Web CBD oil contains trace amounts (≤0.3%) of THC.
Reasoning: Charlotte’s Web markets its flagship CBD oil as a full-spectrum hemp extract, meaning it retains the naturally occurring cannabinoids from the plant, including THC. By U.S. law for hemp products, the THC content must remain below 0.3 percent, so the amount is only trace and non-intoxicating, but it is present unless you buy their specifically labeled “THC-Free” line introduced later.
Answer: Yes—standard Charlotte’s Web CBD oil contains trace amounts (≤0.3%) of THC.

Reasoning: In lower-limb venous anatomy the deep system is composed of the paired tibial and peroneal veins, the popliteal vein, the femoral vein and its continuation, the common femoral vein, before it becomes the external iliac vein. The common femoral vein accompanies the femoral artery deep to the fascia lata and is not part of the superficial (saphenous) system. Therefore it is classified as a deep vein.

Drug tolerance develops when the body compensates for repeated drug exposure. With chronic agonist stimulation, cells often down-regulate or desensitise their receptors, so a given dose produces less effect. Conversely, chronic blockade by an antagonist can lead to receptor up-regulation, again requiring higher doses for the same effect. Thus both receptor downregulation and upregulation are recognised cellular mechanisms contributing to tolerance (along with other pharmacokinetic factors).
Red-light enforcement or monitoring cameras are installed only at selected intersections where authorities choose to do so; many traffic lights have no cameras at all.

Private bail-enforcement/bounty hunting is permitted under federal law and is authorized by most U.S. states, though it is regulated and outright prohibited in a handful of states (e.g., Illinois, Kentucky, Oregon, Wisconsin). Therefore, in general it is legal to work as a bounty hunter in the United States, subject to state-specific rules.

In modern tennis, a point is awarded to whichever player or team wins the rally, regardless of who served that point. Both the server and the receiver can score on any given rally, unlike side-out systems in some other sports (e.g., old-style volleyball). Therefore, you do not have to be serving to earn a point in tennis.

Yes. Firms can ‘cross-list’ their shares on more than one stock exchange, including exchanges located in different countries. Examples include ADRs of foreign companies trading in the U.S. or dual primary listings such as Shell trading in London and Amsterdam. Regulations, disclosure rules and listing fees differ, but nothing prohibits a single company from meeting the requirements of multiple exchanges simultaneously.

The Australian series "Wentworth" concluded with its eighth season (marketed in two parts, the second subtitled "The Final Sentence") in 2021. Producers and the network (Foxtel) promoted that run as the show’s final season, and there have been no credible announcements of a continuation or revival. Therefore, at present no new season is planned.

answer: Yes – alcohol can be purchased on Sunday in Pennsylvania, but only at licensed outlets and during designated hours.
Reasoning: Pennsylvania’s liquor laws now allow Sunday sales. State-run Fine Wine & Good Spirits stores that hold a Sunday-sales permit may open (typically 11 a.m.–7 p.m., some 9 a.m.–8 p.m.). Beer distributors, grocery stores with beer/wine licenses, and bars/restaurants that have the required permit may also sell after 9 a.m. Thus alcohol can be purchased on Sunday, although only at licensed locations and during the permitted hours.
Answer: Yes – alcohol can be purchased on Sunday in Pennsylvania, but only at licensed outlets and during designated hours.

Reasoning: In the UK benefits system, Income Support and Housing Benefit are two distinct payments aimed at different needs. Income Support is a means-tested benefit intended to top up the general living income of people with a low or no income who meet certain criteria (e.g., not working full-time, carers, lone parents). Housing Benefit, on the other hand, is specifically designed to help claimants meet rental housing costs. Because they have different eligibility rules, purposes, and payment structures, they are not the same benefit.

Modern long-haul commercial and cargo routes between certain North American and Asian/European cities take great-circle tracks that pass through the high-Arctic and, on occasion, directly across 90° N (the geographic North Pole). Examples include some flights between New York and Hong Kong, Dubai and Seattle, or Helsinki and Anchorage, as well as occasional charter or scientific flights. Therefore at least a handful of scheduled or special flights do in fact fly over the North Pole.

For the 2008 film version of “Mamma Mia!” (and its 2018 sequel), the principal cast members – Meryl Streep, Amanda Seyfried, Pierce Brosnan, Colin Firth, Stellan Skarsgård, Christine Baranski, Julie Walters, Dominic Cooper, etc. – all recorded and performed their own vocals rather than being dubbed by professional singers. While studio enhancement, backing vocals, and the ensemble chorus were used, no outside singers replaced the actors’ lead vocals, even for those (e.g., Pierce Brosnan) whose singing received mixed reviews.

The belief that leaving an electric fan running in a closed room will somehow remove oxygen, create a vacuum, or cause fatal hypothermia (“fan death”) is a cultural myth, not a scientific reality. A standard household fan merely moves the existing air; it does not deplete oxygen, generate dangerous gases, or lower body temperature to lethal levels under normal indoor conditions. Barring extremely unusual circumstances (e.g., a fan with a malfunction that causes an electrical fire or someone already in a life-threatening state of hypothermia), keeping a fan on is not itself lethal.

The term “next of kin” is a legal designation based on blood relation, marriage, or adoption and follows a set hierarchy (spouse, children, parents, siblings, etc.). Because it is defined by statute rather than personal preference, a person cannot simply appoint someone of their choosing to be their next of kin (though they can name others for roles such as power of attorney or beneficiary). Therefore, you cannot choose who is legally recognized as your next of kin.

In chess, a queen’s legal moves are any number of vacant squares horizontally, vertically, or diagonally. It does not have the L-shaped jumping ability that a knight possesses. Therefore, a queen cannot move like a knight.

Yes. In addition to the seven-book Harry Potter series, J.K. Rowling has published other works: The Casual Vacancy (adult fiction), the Cormoran Strike detective novels written as Robert Galbraith, and several companion titles such as Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them, Quidditch Through the Ages, and The Tales of Beedle the Bard.

Under federal law (18 U.S.C. § 922(g)(1)), any person convicted of a felony punishable by more than one year in prison is barred from possessing firearms or ammunition unless their rights have been explicitly restored. Indiana law further prohibits ‘serious violent felons,’ but it does not create a special exception allowing non-violent felons to possess guns. Therefore, unless the individual has received a pardon, expungement, or other restoration of civil rights, a non-violent felon in Indiana may not lawfully own or possess a firearm.

The traditional heat index is calculated using only air temperature and relative humidity. AccuWeather’s proprietary “RealFeel” temperature, however, factors in additional elements such as wind speed, sun angle, cloud cover, elevation and others. Because RealFeel incorporates more variables than the standard heat index, the two measures can differ and are not identical concepts.

In Christopher Nolan's film "The Dark Knight" (2008), the Joker places Rachel Dawes and Harvey Dent in separate, explosives-rigged locations. Batman is tricked into rescuing Dent, and Commissioner Gordon cannot reach Rachel in time. Her building detonates, resulting in her death.

Polar bears (Ursus maritimus) and grizzly/brown bears (Ursus arctos) are closely related members of the same genus, possess the same chromosome number, and have overlapping ranges in parts of the Arctic. Documented cases in both captivity and the wild show they can interbreed and produce viable offspring, commonly called “pizzly” or “grolar” bears. Some hybrids have themselves been fertile.

Allied Waste Industries was a separate solid-waste company until 2008, when it was acquired by and merged into Republic Services. After the acquisition, the combined company kept the Republic Services name and branding. Therefore, while they were once distinct firms, Allied Waste now operates as part of Republic Services, so for practical purposes they are the same company today.

Precipitation refers to the water (rain, snow, hail, etc.) that actually falls from the atmosphere to the ground, whereas chance of rain (probability of precipitation) is the statistical likelihood that precipitation will occur in a given area and time period. One is the event itself; the other is the probability of that event.

AMC announced that Season 11, which began airing in 2021 and concluded in 2022, would be the last main-season installment of The Walking Dead. There are spin-offs, but no Season 12 is planned for the original series.

Solar-powered cars do exist, though most are prototype or limited-production vehicles. Companies and research teams have built cars whose onboard photovoltaic panels convert sunlight into electricity to run the motor or charge the battery (e.g., Lightyear 0, Sono Sion, vehicles in the World Solar Challenge). While not yet common in mass consumer markets, the technology demonstrates that solar-powered cars are feasible and do exist.

Tom Hardy was nominated for the Academy Award (Oscar) for Best Supporting Actor for his role in The Revenant, but the award that year went to Mark Rylance for Bridge of Spies. Therefore, Hardy did not win an Oscar for The Revenant.

Unlike the United States, the United Kingdom has no constitutional or statutory provision that grants a general individual right to keep and bear arms. Firearms ownership is treated as a privilege, tightly controlled through licensing under the Firearms Acts. Although the 1689 Bill of Rights mentions that ‘Protestants may have arms for their defence suitable to their conditions and as allowed by law,’ modern courts and Parliament interpret this as subject entirely to ordinary legislation, not as an entrenched right. Therefore, Britain does not recognize a broad right to bear arms.

Los Cabos is the name of the larger municipality/region at the southern tip of Baja California Sur, which encompasses both Cabo San Lucas and San José del Cabo (as well as the corridor between them). Cabo San Lucas is just one of the two main towns within Los Cabos. Therefore, they are related but not identical.

In Once Upon a Time, Emma takes on the Dark One’s powers at the end of season 4. During the first half of season 5 she works to rid herself of the darkness. In episode 5x10 (“Swan Song”), the darkness is removed from Emma and ends up back with Rumplestiltskin, so Emma is no longer the Dark One after that point.

High-maltose corn syrup is processed to contain a high proportion of maltose (a glucose–glucose disaccharide). High-fructose corn syrup is enzymatically converted to contain a high proportion of free fructose along with glucose. Because their dominant sugars, production methods, and functional properties differ, they are not the same product.

In Season 3 of Pretty Little Liars, Spencer Hastings is temporarily recruited by Mona to join the so-called “A-Team.” She agrees in order to learn more about ‘A’ and to protect her friends, and later leaves the group. Therefore, at one point in the series Spencer is indeed on the A-Team, albeit briefly and under false pretenses.
In A. A. Milne’s Winnie-the-Pooh stories and the Disney adaptations, Eeyore is explicitly portrayed as a grey, gloomy donkey. This is consistent across the books, animated films, and other media.

In normal (peacetime) operations, the U.S. Coast Guard is an agency of the Department of Homeland Security, not the Department of Defense. It can, however, be transferred to operate as part of the Navy under the DoD during wartime or by presidential direction, but that is the exception rather than the rule.

The 2015 FCC Open Internet Order that enforced net neutrality nationwide was repealed by the FCC in 2017, with the repeal taking effect in 2018. Since then there has been no federal‐level net-neutrality rule in force; a few states (e.g., California, Washington) have enacted their own protections, but these do not amount to nationwide net neutrality.

Canada and the European Union concluded the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement (CETA). Although not yet fully ratified by every EU member state, it has been provisionally applied since September 2017, removing most tariffs and functioning as a free-trade agreement between Canada and the EU.

answer: Yes, in the strict sense a person is only an orphan if one or both parents are dead.
Reasoning: The strict, traditional definition of an orphan is a child whose parents (one or both) have died. Other situations—such as abandonment, relinquishment for adoption, or state custody—do not technically make someone an orphan under this definition, even though the term is sometimes used loosely in conversation. Therefore, to be considered an orphan in the precise sense, at least one parent must be deceased.
Answer: Yes, in the strict sense a person is only an orphan if one or both parents are dead.

Reasoning: In pharmaceutical terminology, “modified-release” is a broad category that covers any dosage form in which the rate or place of drug release is altered from that of an immediate-release product. Sub-types include delayed-release and extended-/prolonged-/sustained-release forms. Thus “prolonged release” (often used synonymously with extended or sustained release) is only one kind of modified-release formulation. Therefore they are related but not identical concepts.
The 1951 MGM musical film “An American in Paris” was highly acclaimed and received six Academy Awards, including the Oscar for Best Picture. Therefore, the statement that it won an Oscar is correct.

Hallmark Channel announced in December 2015 that it was cancelling Cedar Cove after its third season, ending the series. No official plans or announcements have since been made to revive or continue it, making a Season 4 highly unlikely.

The sperm whale (Physeter macrocephalus) is classified as Endangered on the IUCN Red List and is also listed as Endangered under the U.S. Endangered Species Act. Thus, it is officially recognized as an endangered species.

While English is the dominant and de facto language used in government, business, and daily life, the United States has never declared an official language at the federal level. Therefore, English is not legally the official language of the U.S., even though many individual states have designated it as such.

In the franchise’s timeline, Han Lue dies in the crash/explosion in Tokyo (seen at the end of Fast & Furious 6 and revisited at the start of Furious 7). Furious 7 includes his funeral and treats him as deceased; he does not appear alive during its present-day events (his later return happens in F9, not Furious 7).

The Twilight Zone Tower of Terror attraction at Walt Disney World is located in Disney’s Hollywood Studios in Florida. While the version at Disney California Adventure in California was rethemed to Guardians of the Galaxy in 2017, the Florida version has remained open and continues to operate under the Tower of Terror theme.

Lily of the valley (Convallaria majalis) contains cardiac glycosides such as convallatoxin that can cause serious poisoning if ingested. All parts of the plant are toxic to humans and many animals, producing symptoms like nausea, vomiting, heart arrhythmias, and can be fatal in large doses.

On GSM-based mobile phones the ability to dial standardized emergency numbers (e.g., 112, 911) is built into the firmware and does not rely on an active subscriber identity module (SIM). When such a number is dialed, the phone will attempt to connect to any compatible network within range, and regulations in many countries (e.g., FCC rules in the U.S. and EU directives) require carriers to accept and route these calls even if the device lacks a SIM or active service. The call will go through as long as the phone has power and can detect at least one network signal. A few regions have recently restricted SIM-less emergency calls to curb abuse, but in most places you can still reach the police or other emergency services without a SIM card.

The Destin–Fort Walton Beach Airport (VPS), a commercial airport located on Eglin Air Force Base property in neighboring Valparaiso, is the primary airport that serves Fort Walton Beach, Florida. Although it is technically outside the city limits, it is commonly referred to as the airport for Fort Walton Beach.

On the 1996 Oasis single “Don’t Look Back in Anger,” the lead vocal is performed by Noel Gallagher rather than the usual Oasis front-man Liam Gallagher. This is widely documented in the song’s credits and live performances.

X-rays and MRIs are two different medical imaging modalities. X-rays use ionizing radiation to create images of dense structures such as bones, while MRI uses strong magnetic fields and radio waves to produce detailed images of soft tissues without ionizing radiation. Because they employ entirely different physical principles and are used for different diagnostic purposes, they are not the same.

The 2012 film 'The Cabin in the Woods' is widely categorized as a horror movie (specifically a horror-comedy that subverts and celebrates horror tropes). Therefore, the statement that it is a horror movie is correct.

The U.S. Army’s current medical accession standards (DoDI 6130.03) only disqualify an applicant if the flat feet are rigid or cause significant pain, functional limitation, or recurring injuries. Most people who simply have flexible or asymptomatic flat feet are allowed to enlist and serve. Therefore, being flat-footed by itself is not an automatic bar to joining the Army.

In kinship systems, people related through marriage (in-laws) are classified as affinal relatives. A brother-in-law—whether a spouse’s brother or a sibling’s spouse—falls into this category, so he is indeed considered a relative, though not a blood relative.

In most U.S. high schools, a student must earn a set number of credits during 9th grade (freshman year) to be promoted to 10th grade. If the student fails too many required courses and does not accumulate the needed credits, the school can require them to repeat those courses and remain classified as a freshman until the requirements are met. Therefore, it is possible to be ‘held back’ in freshman year.

The sharp ‘crack’ heard when a whip is snapped is produced because the thin, rapidly accelerating tip of the whip travels faster than the speed of sound, producing a small sonic boom. This means it is literally exceeding (i.e., breaking) the sound barrier.
Apple sells the iPad Pro and the Apple Pencil as separate products; the Pencil must be purchased on its own, and it is not included in the iPad Pro box.

As of the most recent publicly available information (2024), the studio and production committee behind “Soredemo Sekai wa Utsukushii” have made no announcement of a continuation. Anime sequels are typically confirmed within a few years if they are planned; nearly a decade has passed since season 1 (2014) without any official news. While a sequel is theoretically possible until explicitly denied, the safest factual statement right now is that no season 2 has been confirmed.

The PlayStation 2 itself does not contain built-in networking hardware (except for the later slimline models), but Sony sold an official Network Adapter and the slim models include an Ethernet port. With that hardware—and appropriate game/software discs—the console can connect to the internet for online gaming and limited web browsing. Therefore, internet connectivity is possible, though not available out-of-the-box on every unit.

In very rare cases, a woman can release two eggs during the same ovulatory cycle and have sexual intercourse with two different men within the several-day window in which sperm remain viable. Each egg can then be fertilized by sperm from a different father, producing fraternal (dizygotic) twins who have separate paternal genetic contributions. This phenomenon is known as heteropaternal superfecundation and has been documented with modern paternity testing.

Yorktown (October 1781) was the last major land battle between the main British and American-French armies and it led directly to peace negotiations, but several smaller engagements and naval actions (e.g., Battle of Blue Licks in 1782, naval battles in 1782-1783) occurred afterward. Therefore it was not literally the final battle of the Revolutionary War.

Home Hardware Stores Ltd. is a Canadian cooperative of independently owned hardware and building-supply stores, while The Home Depot is a large U.S.-based publicly traded home-improvement chain. They are separate companies with different ownership structures, branding, and geographic origins.

Call of Duty: World at War’s campaigns follow the U.S. Marines fighting the Japanese in the Pacific Theater and the Red Army fighting Nazi Germany on the Eastern Front—both key parts of World War II, not World War I.
Spain won the FIFA World Cup held in South Africa in 2010 by defeating the Netherlands 1-0 in the final, securing their first World Cup title.

The original anime series ran in the order Dragon Ball, Dragon Ball Z, and then Dragon Ball GT. GT was produced and broadcast after Z ended (GT aired 1996-1997, whereas Z ended in early 1996). Its story is also set chronologically after the events of Dragon Ball Z, even though it is not based on a Toriyama manga arc.

Arlington National Cemetery was established by the Union during the Civil War, but beginning in the late 19th century the U.S. government authorized the re-interment of Confederate dead there. Today a designated Confederate section (around the Confederate Memorial in Section 16) contains hundreds of graves of Confederate soldiers. Therefore, Confederate soldiers are indeed buried in Arlington National Cemetery.

Greenwich Village is the broader historic neighborhood in lower Manhattan. The "West Village" refers specifically to the western portion of Greenwich Village (generally the area west of Sixth or Seventh Avenue). While the terms are sometimes used interchangeably in casual conversation, technically the West Village is only a subset of Greenwich Village, so they are not identical.

The Wizarding World of Harry Potter is a themed land located inside Universal Studios Hollywood, alongside similar lands at Universal’s other parks. Therefore, it is indeed part of Universal Studios Hollywood.

Sumo wrestlers maintain extremely high body weight through intense training and calorie intake. While their training provides cardiovascular fitness that can offset some metabolic issues during their competitive years, the chronic obesity required for the sport markedly elevates long-term risks of hypertension, diabetes, heart disease, joint problems, and reduced life expectancy. Therefore, overall—especially in the long run—being a sumo wrestler is not considered healthy.

Father’s Day (Vaderdag) is observed in the Netherlands, traditionally on the third Sunday in June. It is recognized nationwide much like Mother’s Day, with children giving gifts or breakfast in bed to their fathers.

A fracture occurs when the stress placed on a bone exceeds its strength. Most wrist fractures result from impact (e.g., a fall onto an out-stretched hand), but a sufficiently powerful torsional force can also exceed the bone’s tolerance and cause a break, especially in more fragile or small bones and in children or the elderly. Although twisting the wrist typically produces ligament sprains rather than fractures, it is still physically possible—if enough torque is applied—to break one or more of the wrist bones.
France won UEFA Group A in the qualification campaign and therefore secured a spot in the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia, where they eventually became champions.
Dalmatian puppies are born almost entirely white; their characteristic black or liver-colored spots begin to appear only after the first week or two of life.

The 1964 film “633 Squadron” is adapted from a wartime novel by Frederick E. Smith. The squadron number, characters, and central mission were invented for dramatic purposes, though the plot borrows elements from several real RAF Mosquito operations carried out in World War II. Because the story and squadron themselves are fictional rather than a direct recounting of an actual event, the film is not based on a true story.

All modern versions of Microsoft Windows ship with built-in tools such as “Backup and Restore” (Windows 7/10) and “File History,” which both contain a restore function that lets users recover the data previously backed up. Therefore, Windows does include a utility expressly intended to restore backups.

Postal services such as the USPS do not require a return address for most classes of ordinary mail. As long as the correct destination address and sufficient postage are present, the letter will normally be processed and delivered. A return address is only needed if the item must be returned (e.g., insufficient address, postage-due) or for certain special services. Therefore, in the typical case, a letter without a return address will still reach its destination.

Diary of a Wimpy Kid blends prose with sequential cartoon illustrations to tell its story. Because the narrative is conveyed in large part through those comics‐style drawings, many libraries and booksellers shelve the series in the graphic-novel section and it is commonly referred to as a graphic novel for kids, even though it is sometimes described as a ‘novel in cartoons’ rather than a traditional, full-panel comic. Overall, it is generally accepted as a graphic novel (or graphic-novel hybrid).

In virtually every modern legal system, freedom of speech is not absolute. Governments may restrict speech that threatens public safety or infringes on the rights of others—for example, incitement to violence, true threats, defamation, or certain forms of obscenity. Therefore, limits on freedom of speech clearly exist.
“Lightning bug” and “firefly” are two common names for the same bioluminescent beetle in the family Lampyridae. The terms are interchangeable; regional preference determines which one is used.

In the Marvel Cinematic Universe, Scott Lang (Ant-Man) and Hope van Dyne (the Wasp) evolve from uneasy allies to romantic partners during the events of Ant-Man (2015) and Ant-Man and the Wasp (2018). By the end of the second film and in later appearances (e.g., Avengers: Endgame), they are clearly portrayed as a couple, indicating that they do indeed get together.

Within the United Kingdom there are three distinct legal jurisdictions: England & Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland. Scotland retained its own courts, procedures, and much of its substantive law after the 1707 Acts of Union. Although some UK-wide statutes apply to both, Scots law is a separate mixed system drawing on civil-law and common-law traditions, whereas English law is a common-law system. Therefore Scottish law is not the same as English law.

Disney Channel officially renewed Penny on M.A.R.S. and produced a second season, which has already been filmed and aired in several countries. Therefore, the answer to whether there will be a Season 2 is yes.
Humans have a flat bone called the sternum located centrally at the front of the chest, connecting to the ribs via cartilage. Therefore, there is indeed a bone in the middle of the chest.

The character Ignacio "Nacho" Varga physically appears only in Better Call Saul. In Breaking Bad he is never shown on-screen; Saul merely mentions an off-screen "Ignacio" once. Therefore, Nacho is not actually in Breaking Bad.

The famous Blackpool Tower Ballroom is situated within the tower’s base complex on the lower floors, not in the high-level observation areas at the top of the tower. The upper portion of Blackpool Tower contains viewing platforms and other attractions, but not the ballroom.

IHOP Corporation acquired Applebee’s International in 2007 and later changed its name to Dine Brands Global (formerly DineEquity). Both restaurant chains—IHOP and Applebee’s—are operated under this same parent company today, so they share common ownership.
Baker Street is an actual street in the Marylebone district of the City of Westminster, London, well-known for its association with the fictional detective Sherlock Holmes.

The rules of the FIFA World Cup place no restrictions on which confederation’s members can win. Although no African team has yet won the tournament, nothing in principle prevents an African nation from doing so; the result depends solely on performance in the competition.

Switzerland is a land‐locked country in central Europe that shares boundaries with five nations: France, Germany, Austria, Liechtenstein, and Italy. Therefore, there is definitely a national border between Switzerland and Italy.

A lone king cannot deliver checkmate because it cannot put the opposing king in check without help from other pieces. Under the rules, if you have only a king you also cannot win on time, since lacking mating material converts the result to a draw if the opponent’s clock runs out. The only theoretical way to ‘win’ would be an irrational resignation by the opponent, but from the standpoint of chess rules and practical play, a single king cannot force a win.

For EU (and most EEA/Schengen) citizens, a valid national identity card is accepted for crossing internal EU borders and is treated as sufficient proof of identity and nationality instead of a passport. While there are minor exceptions (e.g., travel to non-Schengen EU territories or if an airline has its own ID requirements), the general rule is that an EU citizen can travel between EU countries with just an ID card.

A U.S. passport card is accepted only for land and sea crossings between the United States and Canada, Mexico, Bermuda, and most Caribbean islands. It is not valid for any international air travel and cannot be used to enter other countries. Because the question is generally understood to mean whether it can serve as a full replacement for a passport book for international travel, the correct response is that it cannot.

There are documented cases (e.g., the “Liberator” pistol) where individuals have successfully produced firearms using consumer-grade 3-D printers. While such weapons often require some metal parts (firing pin, ammunition, sometimes reinforcement) and are usually less durable and reliable than factory-made guns, they can still discharge live rounds. Therefore, it is possible for a 3-D printer to create a functional gun.
Zendaya plays the character Michelle “MJ” Jones in both Spider-Man: Homecoming (2017) and its sequel Spider-Man: Far From Home (2019), appearing in a significant supporting role throughout the film.

‘Regular’ cinnamon on U.S. grocery shelves is usually cassia cinnamon (Cinnamomum cassia).  Saigon cinnamon (Cinnamomum loureiroi), sometimes called Vietnamese cinnamon, is a different species within the cassia family.  It has a higher oil-content and stronger, sweeter flavor, and it contains more coumarin.  Thus it is closely related to but not the same as standard cassia cinnamon, and it is also distinct from ‘true’ (Ceylon) cinnamon.

Estonia was incorporated into the Russian Empire from 1721 until 1918 and was later occupied and annexed by the Soviet Union (dominated by Russia) from 1940–1991. Therefore, historically Estonia was indeed under Russian rule.

The novel and subsequent film “Everything, Everything” were conceived and written as works of fiction by author Nicola Yoon. While the story draws on real medical conditions (e.g., SCID) as inspiration, the characters and events themselves are not drawn from any specific real‐life case. Therefore, it is not ‘based on a true story.’

The standard build for an In-N-Out hamburger, cheeseburger, or Double-Double includes lettuce, tomato, spread, and optional onions. Pickles are not part of the default toppings, though they can be added on request.

For ordinary domestic first-class letters and most other USPS mail classes, a return address is recommended but not mandatory, so the item will still be accepted and delivered even if no return address is provided. (If it proves undeliverable, it will be treated as ‘dead mail.’) Some situations—e.g., international shipments, parcels requiring customs forms, items sent by private carriers, or mail needing insurance—do require a sender (return) address. Therefore, in many common cases you can mail something without a return address, but there are exceptions.

Red and pink grapefruits are both varieties of grapefruit with colored flesh, but they are bred from different cultivars. Red grapefruit (e.g., ‘Rio Red’, ‘Star Ruby’) typically has a deeper red flesh and slightly higher sweetness/lycopene content, while pink grapefruit (e.g., ‘Ruby Red’) has a paler pink flesh. Although they are similar and often substituted for one another, they are not exactly the same variety.

According to official WPA/BCA rules for 9-ball, it is not a call-shot game. The shooter only has to contact the lowest-numbered ball on the table first; any ball that is pocketed as a result (including the 9) counts without calling a pocket. Some local or house variations require calling the 9, but this is not part of the standard rules.

During the real-life 1991 ‘Perfect Storm’ (the Halloween Nor’easter) an Air National Guard HH-60 Pave Hawk rescue helicopter ran out of fuel and was forced to ditch in the Atlantic Ocean; four of the five crew members were rescued while one was lost. This event is also depicted in the book and film ‘The Perfect Storm.’ Therefore, yes—a helicopter did crash during the Perfect Storm.

Since becoming an independent national team after the dissolution of the Soviet Union, Russia has never reached the championship match (the final game) of the FIFA World Cup. The Soviet Union era team’s best finish was fourth place in 1966, but even then they did not play in the final. Therefore, Russia has never appeared in a World Cup final.

In the series, Spencer Reid has an early crush on JJ and they share a close friendship, but the show never portrays them as actually dating. JJ later enters a long-term relationship and marriage with Will LaMontagne Jr., confirming that she and Reid never become a couple.

In most cities and counties, any business that sells food or beverages to the public is technically required to obtain a business license and (often) a temporary food-service permit. A lemonade stand therefore falls under those rules, so—strictly speaking—you do need a license.  However, many jurisdictions simply do not enforce the requirement against small, child-run stands, and in the last few years several U.S. states have passed laws specifically exempting minor-operated lemonade stands from licensing.  Thus, while the legal default is that a license is required, enforcement and exemptions vary.

Several franchises have successfully defended their title, including the Packers (Super Bowls I & II), Dolphins, Steelers (twice), 49ers, Cowboys, Broncos and Patriots, proving that consecutive championships have occurred multiple times.
The common name 'walking stick' refers to insects in the order Phasmatodea (stick insects), well-known for their stick-like appearance and camouflage abilities.

The 2001 World Series was contested between the New York Yankees and the Arizona Diamondbacks. The Diamondbacks won the series in seven games, famously with Luis Gonzalez’s walk-off hit in Game 7. Therefore, the Yankees did not win the World Series that year.

U.S. guidelines define one standard drink as any beverage containing about 14 g of pure alcohol. For distilled spirits that are 80-proof (40% ABV), this corresponds to 1.5 fluid ounces. Therefore 1.5 ounces of liquor meets the definition of a standard drink.
The Cincinnati Bengals have reached the Super Bowl three times (Super Bowls XVI, XXIII, and LVI) but lost on each occasion. Therefore, they have never secured a Super Bowl victory.

The redback spider (Latrodectus hasseltii) possesses a potent neurotoxic venom. Before antivenom became available in the 1950s, several deaths were documented. Today fatalities are extremely rare because of prompt medical care and effective antivenom, but in the absence of treatment the bite can be life-threatening and potentially fatal.

The English lexicon contains numerous loanwords and proper nouns in which the letter q is not followed by u (e.g., ‘qat’, ‘qi’, ‘qoph’, ‘Iraq’, ‘Qatar’), so the statement that there are such words is accurate.

In the sitcom “That ’70s Show,” Fez’s home country is a running joke. Although vague clues and contradictory hints are sprinkled throughout the series, the writers deliberately never reveal the exact country, and the mystery remains intact in later appearances (e.g., “That ’90s Show”). Therefore, viewers never definitively learn where Fez is from.

answer: No, there is no movie after I Am Number 4.
Reasoning: The 2011 film “I Am Number Four” was intended to launch a series based on the Lorien Legacies novels, but its box-office performance and reviews were underwhelming. Consequently, DreamWorks/Disney never green-lit a sequel, and no follow-up films have been produced.
Answer: No, there is no movie after I Am Number 4.

Reasoning: The U.S. Bureau of Engraving and Printing continues to print $2 Federal Reserve Notes in limited quantities, and they remain legal tender. Although they are not commonly encountered in everyday transactions, they are still issued by banks on request, so the bill is indeed still in circulation.
The series 'Orange Is the New Black' was ordered, produced, and first released by Netflix and is widely recognized as one of the streaming service’s earliest original shows.

The TV series 'One Tree Hill' concluded with its ninth season in 2012. There has been no official announcement from the network, producers, or cast indicating that a tenth season is planned or in production. Therefore, it is reasonable to state that the show will not be returning for a Season 10.

Very intense light (e.g., directly viewing the sun, laser pointers, welding arcs) can deliver enough energy to the retina to cause photochemical or thermal damage. This retinal damage can be permanent, leading to partial or complete loss of vision. Ordinary indoor lighting is generally not intense enough to cause lasting harm, but sufficiently bright sources can indeed cause blindness if stared at long enough.

A “3-peat” means winning three consecutive NBA championships. The Lakers franchise has done this twice: once as the Minneapolis Lakers (1952, 1953, 1954) and once as the Los Angeles Lakers (2000, 2001, 2002). Therefore, the answer is yes.

The official songwriting credits for the single “Freaky Friday” list Lil Dicky (David Burd) along with several other writers, including Chris Brown, DJ Mustard (Dijon McFarlane), Nicholas Audino, David Park and others. Because multiple people share writing credit, Lil Dicky did not write the entire song by himself.

Bumble bees (genus Bombus) and honey bees (genus Apis) belong to different genera, have distinct physical characteristics, colony sizes, behaviors, and ecological roles. Therefore, they are not the same species or even in the same genus.

Xbox One supports backward compatibility for many, but not all, Xbox 360 titles. Only games that Microsoft has specifically tested and enabled through its backward-compatibility program will run on an Xbox One. Therefore, saying that all Xbox 360 games can be played on Xbox One is incorrect.

Although Better Call Saul is a prequel and its story is set before the events of Breaking Bad, the series itself was produced and filmed after Breaking Bad had already completed its run (Breaking Bad filmed 2007-2013; Better Call Saul began filming in 2014). Therefore, it was not filmed first.

In most school districts, if a student does not meet academic, attendance, or other promotion requirements, they can be retained and asked to repeat 8th grade. Policies differ by state and district, but the possibility clearly exists.

Fear the Walking Dead is a separate companion/spin-off series that shares the same fictional universe as The Walking Dead, but it has different characters, storylines, and production. Therefore, they are not the same show.

Pensacola used to be served by Amtrak’s Sunset Limited, but service east of New Orleans (including Pensacola) was suspended after Hurricane Katrina in 2005 and has never been restored. Therefore, Amtrak presently has no active station or service in Pensacola, Florida.

Soy sauce is a fermented seasoning made mainly from soybeans, wheat, salt and water, originating in East Asia. Worcestershire sauce is a fermented liquid condiment from England made from ingredients such as malt vinegar, molasses, anchovies, tamarind, onions, garlic and various spices. Their ingredient lists, flavor profiles, cultural origins and culinary uses differ, so they are not the same product, even though both are dark, savory liquids.

In-N-Out Burger operates only in a handful of western and southwestern states (e.g., California, Nevada, Arizona, Utah, Texas, Oregon, Colorado). The company has no locations on the U.S. East Coast, and none have been announced or opened in Maryland.

The Canadian men’s national soccer team qualified for and played in the 1986 FIFA World Cup finals in Mexico (and again qualified for the 2022 tournament). Therefore, Canada has indeed competed in the FIFA World Cup at least once.

In most jurisdictions, statutes of limitation establish deadlines for prosecuting many criminal offenses. However, particularly serious crimes—such as murder, certain types of homicide, and often crimes like war crimes or crimes against humanity—are explicitly exempt and may be prosecuted at any time. Therefore, the limitation period does not cover every crime.

Interstate 75 is mostly toll-free, but there are tolled sections, including Alligator Alley in Florida, the Mackinac Bridge in Michigan, and optional express toll lanes in Georgia. Therefore, at least some portions of I-75 require a toll.

In the FIFA World Cup knockout (play-off) rounds, if a match is tied after 90 minutes, the game proceeds to two 15-minute periods of extra time before resorting to a penalty shoot-out. Therefore, extra time is indeed part of World Cup play-offs.

California has been one of the 50 U.S. states since it was admitted to the Union in 1850 and there has been no legal change to that status. Secession initiatives occasionally appear but have never succeeded or been recognized, so California remains part of the United States.

The United States maintained large, permanent bases in Saudi Arabia throughout the 1990s but withdrew most forces in 2003. However, since 2019 the U.S. has redeployed several thousand troops and operates from Prince Sultan Air Base and a few smaller facilities for air-defense and training purposes. Thus, the U.S. again maintains military bases (or at least U.S.-operated sections of Saudi bases) in the kingdom.

Good Times (1974) was spun off from the series Maude, which itself was a spin-off of All in the Family. The Jeffersons (1975) was another separate spin-off of All in the Family. Therefore, Good Times was not a spin-off of The Jeffersons.

Cape Town experienced a severe drought-driven ‘Day Zero’ water crisis in 2017-2018. Since then, dam levels have largely recovered thanks to improved rainfall, infrastructure upgrades and continued conservation measures. While the region remains water-stressed and maintains long-term demand-management policies, it is not presently in an acute crisis comparable to 2018.

Under standard basketball rules (NBA, FIBA, NCAA), the shooter is allowed to leave the floor while taking a free-throw attempt, provided that he or she does not step on or cross the free-throw line until the ball has touched the rim, backboard, or the free throw ends. Therefore, jumping at the free-throw line is legal as long as the shooter lands behind the line.
CBS officially announced on March 23, 2017 that the 2010 reboot ‘Hawaii Five-0’ was renewed for another year, which became its eighth season, premiering in the 2017-2018 TV cycle.
The 2016 comedy film “Wild Oats” lists Shirley MacLaine, Jessica Lange, and Demi Moore among its principal cast. Demi Moore plays the character Crystal. Therefore, she is indeed in the movie.

The large intestine is anatomically divided into the cecum, ascending colon, transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, rectum, and anal canal. Since the ascending colon is one of these divisions, it is indeed part of the large intestine.

In the typical military rank structure (e.g., U.S. Army, Air Force, Marine Corps and many others that follow similar conventions), the order from lower to higher is major (O-4), lieutenant colonel (O-5), and then colonel (O-6). Therefore, a colonel outranks a lieutenant colonel, not the other way around.

A dry spoonful of ground cinnamon can be dangerous because the fine powder is easy to inhale accidentally. Inhalation can cause choking, severe coughing, lung irritation, or even aspiration pneumonia. Although most people recover without lasting harm, there have been documented cases of serious lung injury and at least a few reports in which complications contributed to death. Therefore, while death is unlikely, it is possible under certain circumstances.

Dragon Ball Super is set after the defeat of Majin Buu in Dragon Ball Z and before the final World Martial Arts Tournament shown at the end of Z. It continues Goku and his friends’ storylines, introducing new arcs (e.g., Battle of Gods, Universe 6, Future Trunks, Tournament of Power) that build directly on events and character developments from Dragon Ball Z. Therefore, it functions as the canonical sequel series to Dragon Ball Z.
Red-eared slider (red slider) females leave the water and dig a nest in soil or sand on land to deposit their eggs; if eggs are laid in water they drown. Therefore, they do not lay eggs in water.

Most shark species are marine, but a few—most notably the bull shark (Carcharhinus leucas) and several river-shark species in the genus Glyphis—can live for extended periods, reproduce, and complete their life cycles in freshwater rivers and lakes. Therefore, freshwater sharks do exist.

The question is usually asked about the 2016 reboot “Ghostbusters: Answer the Call.” In that film only three of the original Ghostbusters actors (Bill Murray, Dan Aykroyd, Ernie Hudson) make cameo appearances. Harold Ramis had passed away before production, so he is not present except for a brief tribute. Therefore, not all four original Ghostbusters appeared in the new movie.

Batman Begins (2005) is the first film in Christopher Nolan’s Batman trilogy. The Dark Knight (2008) follows it chronologically, continuing the story of Bruce Wayne/Batman and referencing events from Batman Begins, making it its direct sequel.

answer: Neither – it is in the Indian Ocean
Reasoning: Port Louis is the capital of Mauritius, which is an island nation located east of Madagascar in the Indian Ocean. Therefore, it is not situated in either the Atlantic or the Pacific Ocean.
Answer: Neither – it is in the Indian Ocean

Reasoning: Carbohydrates are abundant in plant-based foods, but most animal products (meat, fish, eggs, some cheeses, fats/oils) contain essentially none. Therefore a person could, at least in theory and practice, consume only these foods and take in virtually zero carbohydrates. While such a diet (often called a ‘zero-carb’ or carnivore diet) is very restrictive and may raise nutritional concerns, it does exist, so the concept of a no-carb diet is real.

In any diploid cell there are pairs of homologous chromosomes. Cells that enter mitosis are typically diploid somatic cells, so homologous chromosome pairs are present, although they do not pair or recombine. Cells that enter meiosis are also diploid, and their homologous chromosomes pair and segregate during meiosis I. Therefore homologous chromosomes are present at the start of both mitosis and meiosis (the difference is how they behave).

Serbia, either as an independent national team (since 2006) or previously as part of Yugoslavia/Serbia and Montenegro, has never won the FIFA World Cup. Yugoslavia’s best finishes were reaching the semifinals (1930 and 1962). Therefore the statement that Serbia has won a World Cup is incorrect.

Human hair is surprisingly strong in tension: a single strand can support about 100 g, and a full head has tens of thousands of strands. Performers in circuses sometimes do ‘hair-hanging’ acts where they are fully suspended by their hair. While this is extremely painful and risks scalp injury or hair loss, it shows that—purely in terms of physics—it is possible to lift a person by their hair.

A Savannah cat is a hybrid between a domestic cat and a serval, while a Bengal cat is a hybrid between a domestic cat and an Asian leopard cat. They have different wild ancestors, appearances, and breed standards, so they are not the same.

The Emancipation Proclamation, issued on January 1, 1863, freed enslaved people only in those parts of the Confederacy that were still in rebellion against the United States. It specifically exempted the loyal border slave states (e.g., Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware) and certain Union-occupied areas within Confederate states. Therefore, it did not apply to every state in the Union or even every state that allowed slavery.

While the typical clover has three leaflets and the well-known ‘lucky’ variant has four, plants can occasionally produce additional leaflets because of genetic mutation or environmental factors. Documented specimens and photographs exist of clovers with five, six, or even more leaflets, though they are extremely rare.

The ‘pyramid’ that gives Pyramid Lake (Nevada) its name is a large tufa limestone formation that precipitated naturally from calcium-carbonate–rich spring water interacting with the lake water over thousands of years. It was not constructed by humans.

"I Can't Believe It's Not Butter!" is a branded, vegetable-oil–based spread that is marketed as an alternative to butter. Such products are classified as margarine or margarine-type spreads in food regulations.

The final stage of the Tour de France is officially a timed stage that counts toward the overall results. While riders usually treat the first part as a ceremonial parade, once they reach the finishing circuits (typically on the Champs-Élysées) the racing becomes real, especially among sprinters competing for the stage victory. Because times are still recorded and the stage win is contested, it is indeed a race.

The electron transport chain (ETC) refers specifically to the series of protein complexes that transfer electrons and pump protons across the inner mitochondrial membrane (or bacterial plasma membrane). Oxidative phosphorylation is the broader process in which the ETC creates a proton gradient that drives ATP synthesis via ATP synthase. Thus, the ETC is a component of oxidative phosphorylation, but the two terms are not identical.

answer: Yes, but only if they meet the licensing/permit requirements of the jurisdiction in which they are operating.
Reasoning: In the United States bounty hunters (bail-enforcement agents) are private citizens, not law-enforcement officers. They may carry firearms, but only if they comply with the same federal and state gun-possession and carry laws that apply to any other citizen. Many states require a concealed-carry permit or a special bail-enforcement license with firearms certification; a few states restrict or prohibit them from being armed while working. Thus, a bounty hunter is generally allowed to carry a gun, provided he or she satisfies the relevant licensing and permitting requirements of the jurisdiction.
Answer: Yes, but only if they meet the licensing/permit requirements of the jurisdiction in which they are operating.

Reasoning: Toll-free service is only free within the calling area the owner has paid for. Most U.S. toll-free numbers are configured for calls originating inside the United States; if you dial them from Canada the call may not complete or it will be billed as a regular long-distance call unless the number’s owner has explicitly added Canadian coverage. Therefore a U.S. toll-free number is not automatically free when dialed from Canada.

In materials science there is a product known as “dry water,” consisting of ~95 % water droplets individually coated with a fine layer of silica so they cannot coalesce. The result is a powder that pours like a dry solid even though most of its mass is water. It is studied for uses such as gas storage and controlled reactions. Therefore, a form of ‘dry water’ does exist.

In a diploid organism, a chromosome pair refers to homologous chromosomes—one inherited from the mother and one from the father. While they carry the same types of genes in the same order, the specific DNA sequences (alleles) can differ, so they are similar but not identical.
In the New York City Subway system, the A train (Eighth Avenue Express) stops at 34 St–Penn Station on the IND Eighth Avenue Line, providing service directly to Penn Station.

Both the 2018 reboot ‘God of War’ and its follow-up ‘God of War: Ragnarök’ are designed solely as single-player, story-driven experiences. They do not include any local or online two-player or co-op modes.

SWIFT codes (also called BICs) are internationally-standardised 8–11 character identifiers for financial institutions, used to route cross-border payments. A BSB is a 6-digit domestic routing number used only within Australia to identify a specific bank and branch for local payments. Because they serve different geographic scopes, have different formats, and are issued by different authorities, they are not the same.

Yes. Indian athletes and teams have earned several Olympic gold medals, beginning with the men’s field-hockey team in 1928 and including individual titles such as Abhinav Bindra’s shooting gold in 2008 and Neeraj Chopra’s javelin gold in 2021. Therefore, India has indeed won Olympic gold medals.

Under the Official Baseball Rules, when the umpire calls an infield fly, the batter-runner is out immediately, but the ball remains live. Runners may advance at their own risk (they can tag up if the ball is caught, or run if it is dropped). Therefore the ball is not dead on an infield fly.

Yes. Charles Evans Hughes served as an Associate Justice of the U.S. Supreme Court (1910-1916). He resigned from the Court to become the Republican nominee for president in 1916, running against Woodrow Wilson (he lost). Therefore, at least one Supreme Court justice has run for president.

Passive transport (e.g., simple diffusion, osmosis, facilitated diffusion) relies on the natural tendency of molecules to move from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. It does not require cellular energy precisely because it moves down, not against, the concentration gradient. Moving against the gradient requires active transport.

The jellyfish species Turritopsis dohrnii can repeatedly revert its mature medusa form back to the juvenile polyp stage, restarting its life cycle. This ability makes it biologically (theoretically) immortal, although individuals can still die from predation, disease, or environmental factors.

Ruby is specifically the red variety of the mineral corundum, its color caused by chromium impurities. Any corundum that is not red—including blue varieties—is classified as sapphire. Therefore, by definition, a “blue ruby” cannot exist; the blue counterpart is called sapphire.
Key West is a city located in Monroe County, Florida. Florida is one of the 50 states of the United States, so Key West is within U.S. territory.

In the original U.S. primetime version of “Are You Smarter Than a Fifth Grader?”, only one contestant has ever answered all 11 questions correctly and claimed the $1 million grand prize—Georgia Schools Superintendent Kathy Cox in September 2008. No other U.S. contestant has matched that feat (the syndicated daytime version’s top prize was $250 000). Therefore, the correct response is that someone has indeed won the million-dollar prize.
The United Kingdom (UK) consists of England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. The Republic of Ireland is a separate sovereign nation and is not part of the UK.

Ridley Scott’s 2012 film “Prometheus” was followed by “Alien: Covenant,” released in 2017, which continues the storyline (e.g., the android David) and is officially marketed as the sequel in the same pre-Alien franchise timeline.

“Mamma Mia!” was first produced as a stage musical (premiered in London’s West End in 1999) and only later adapted into the feature film released in 2008. Therefore, it existed as a play before becoming a movie.

Canada operates multiple commercial nuclear power plants, such as Bruce, Darlington, Pickering (all in Ontario) and Point Lepreau (in New Brunswick), so the statement that there are nuclear power plants in Canada is correct.
