Dublin’s Roman-Catholic Archdiocese uses St Mary’s Pro-Cathedral as its principal church. Because it is only a ‘pro-cathedral’ (a temporary substitute) and the archdiocese has never had an official cathedral building, strictly speaking Dublin does not have a Roman Catholic cathedral.

In the most recent FIFA World Cup where the two teams met (Russia 2018), Belgium defeated England twice—1-0 in the group stage and 2-0 in the third-place play-off. Although England did beat Belgium once before (in 1990), the common question usually refers to the latest tournament, in which England did not beat Belgium.

Pokémon: Let’s Go, Eevee! was developed by Game Freak and published as a remake/re-imagining of Pokémon Yellow for the Nintendo Switch. The Pokémon Company and Nintendo list it alongside the mainline role-playing games (it counts toward the ‘core RPG’ releases, not the side-series like Mystery Dungeon, Ranger, etc.). Therefore, it is not officially treated as a spin-off title.

In Maxwell’s amended Ampere law (∇×B = μ₀J + μ₀ε₀ ∂E/∂t), the magnetic field’s curl is produced by the sum of the conduction-current density J and the displacement-current density ε₀∂E/∂t. Therefore a time-varying electric field (displacement current) contributes to the magnetic field in exactly the same formal way as a real (conduction) current, even though no charges are physically moving.
The Chrysler PT Cruiser was discontinued; production ended in July 2010. No new PT Cruisers have been manufactured since then, so it is no longer being made.

The Riviera Maya lies on the eastern side of Mexico’s Yucatán Peninsula, stretching from south of Cancún to Tulum along the coast that faces the Caribbean Sea. The Gulf of Mexico is on the peninsula’s northern and western coasts, not its eastern shore. Therefore, the Riviera Maya is not on the Gulf of Mexico.
Creedence Clearwater Revival (CCR) was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1993, so they are indeed members of the Hall.

In air (and most ordinary gases and liquids) at a fixed temperature, the speed of sound is determined by the medium’s elastic properties and density (v = √(γRT/M) for an ideal gas). These properties are independent of the sound wave’s frequency over the audible range, so the medium is essentially non-dispersive. Therefore, changing frequency while holding temperature constant does not change the speed of sound.

"Won't You Be My Neighbor?" is the 2018 feature-length film by director Morgan Neville that chronicles the life and career of Fred Rogers. It is widely categorized and marketed as a documentary film (not a scripted drama or fictionalized biopic), so the answer is yes.

Although the second-generation Ford Ka (2008–2016) was co-developed with Fiat and shares the same basic platform and many mechanical components as the Fiat 500, the two cars are marketed under different brands, have distinct exterior and interior styling, different suspension/engine calibrations, and the first-generation Ka was entirely Ford’s own design. Therefore, they are related but not the same car.

In the most recent FIFA World Cup cycle (Qatar 2022), North Korea withdrew from Asian qualifying in 2021 due to COVID-19 concerns, so they did not qualify. They have appeared in past tournaments (1966 and 2010), but for the latest World Cup they did not make it.

Cannabis (weed) remains a controlled substance under Ireland’s Misuse of Drugs Acts. Possession, cultivation, or use for recreational purposes is illegal, and offenders can face criminal penalties. Only very limited medical cannabis access is permitted under strict prescription schemes, but smoking cannabis recreationally is not legal.

The Companies Act 2006 is the principal statute for companies that are incorporated in the United Kingdom under that Act (or earlier Companies Acts). Its provisions do not extend to entities that are not incorporated under UK company legislation — for example, overseas-incorporated companies (except where specific provisions are expressly applied), limited liability partnerships, friendly societies, or statutory corporations. Therefore, it is not correct to say that the Act applies to ‘all companies’ in an absolute sense.

In common usage and in the essential-oil industry, the terms “cedar oil” and “cedarwood oil” are used interchangeably to denote the essential oil distilled from the wood (and sometimes foliage) of cedar/juniper species. Although more technical texts may distinguish among oils from different plant parts or species (e.g., cedar leaf oil), the everyday name “cedar oil” refers to what is formally called cedarwood oil.

The TV series “Nashville” is a fictional drama set within the country-music industry. While it draws inspiration from the real Nashville music scene and amalgamates traits of various real-life artists, its characters and storylines are original creations, not retellings of actual events.

Resolution describes the total count or arrangement of pixels on a display (e.g., 1920×1080), while pixel density expresses how tightly those pixels are packed into physical space (pixels per inch or ppi). Two screens can share the same resolution yet have different pixel densities if their physical sizes differ. Therefore, the two terms are related but not identical.

A motor unit consists of a single α-motor neuron and all the muscle fibers it innervates. The number of fibers served by one neuron depends on the functional demands of the muscle: muscles requiring fine, precise movements (e.g., extra-ocular or intrinsic hand muscles) have very small motor units (a handful of fibers per neuron), whereas large, powerful postural or locomotor muscles (e.g., gastrocnemius, quadriceps) have motor units containing hundreds to thousands of fibers. Therefore motor-unit size is not fixed but varies substantially across different muscles.
Poland won UEFA qualifying Group E and took part in the finals in Russia (Group H), so they did qualify for the 2018 FIFA World Cup.

In most U.S. universities and arts institutions, the Master of Fine Arts (MFA) is treated as the highest academic credential required to teach studio art, creative writing, theatre, film, and related disciplines at the collegiate level. There is generally no higher practice-based degree in these fields (a Ph.D. is research-focused and uncommon in studio arts). Therefore, the MFA is widely regarded as a terminal degree.

Eligibility for America’s Got Talent is open to acts worldwide; contestants simply need to meet the show’s audition requirements and be legally able to travel and work in the United States. Numerous past contestants have come from other countries, confirming no U.S. nationality requirement.

In SmackDown vs. Raw 2006 and 2007 there was a dedicated General Manager (GM) Mode. For SmackDown vs. Raw 2008 THQ removed that stand-alone mode and replaced it with the new “WWE 24/7” mode, which merges elements of Season Mode and GM Mode but is not the classic GM Mode itself. Therefore the game does not include a separate GM Mode.

In the edible-oil industry, the term “palm oil” is conventionally used for the reddish oil pressed from the fleshy mesocarp of the oil-palm fruit. Some manufacturers label this same product as “palm fruit oil” to distinguish it from “palm kernel oil,” which is obtained from the seed (kernel) and has a different fatty-acid profile. Therefore, ‘palm oil’ and ‘palm fruit oil’ designate the same oil extracted from the fruit’s flesh, not the kernel.

If the question refers to the senior men’s FIFA World Cup in football (soccer), India have never actually appeared in the final tournament. Although India qualified for the 1950 World Cup after other Asian teams withdrew, they themselves withdrew before the competition and therefore have never played a World Cup match.

Under the federal Law Enforcement Officers Safety Act of 2004 (LEOSA, often called HR-218), any “qualified law-enforcement officer” or “qualified retired law-enforcement officer” may carry a concealed firearm nationwide, regardless of individual state laws. They must meet the definition of ‘qualified,’ carry proper identification, and they remain subject to restrictions on certain categories of property (e.g., federal buildings, secure areas of airports, private property that forbids firearms, etc.). Therefore, apart from those specific exclusions, a police officer who meets LEOSA’s requirements can legally carry in every U.S. state.

Street signs are public property owned by a city, county, or state. Taking one without authorization constitutes theft of government property, which is a crime in every U.S. jurisdiction (and in most other countries). It can also create public-safety hazards, which can add further charges or penalties. Therefore, it is illegal.

The term “Amur tiger” refers to the tiger population that inhabits the Russian Far East along the Amur River basin. This is the same population historically called the “Siberian tiger.” Modern taxonomy and conservation organizations treat them as the same subspecies, Panthera tigris altaica. Therefore, the two names describe the same animal.

Under the Svalbard Treaty, the archipelago is a visa-free zone; Norwegian immigration rules do not require a visa for entry to Svalbard itself. Travellers may still need a Schengen visa for transit through mainland Norway, but for visiting Svalbard alone no visa is mandated. Therefore the statement “You need a visa to visit Svalbard” is false.

Historic Ellicott City was founded at the falls of the Patapsco River, and the river (along with its tributary, the Tiber Branch) still runs through the town. Frequent flooding from this river system is a well-known issue for the community, confirming that a river is indeed present.

WordPad is a free, basic word-processing program that comes bundled with Windows and offers only limited formatting and feature sets. Microsoft Word is a full-featured, separate, commercial application that is part of Microsoft Office/365, supporting advanced layout, collaboration, and formatting tools. Because their capabilities, licensing, and intended use differ, they are not the same application.

answer: No – the basic ITV Hub can be watched for free (with adverts); payment is only needed for the optional ad-free ITV Hub+ subscription.
Reasoning: The standard ITV Hub service is funded by advertising, so viewers can stream programmes for free once they have registered for a (free) account. There is an optional paid tier called ITV Hub+ that removes adverts and allows offline downloads, but payment is not required to watch ITV Hub content in general.
Answer: No – the basic ITV Hub can be watched for free (with adverts); payment is only needed for the optional ad-free ITV Hub+ subscription.

Reasoning: The moment of inertia is defined as I = Σ mᵢ rᵢ², where rᵢ is the perpendicular distance of each mass element mᵢ from the chosen axis. Changing the axis changes these distances rᵢ, so the numerical value of I changes. Therefore the moment of inertia is axis-dependent.

G-major and E-minor share the same key signature (one sharp, F♯), which makes E-minor the relative minor of G-major. However, they have different tonics (G vs. E) and different scale degree functions, chord progressions, and tonal centers, so they are not literally the same key—just closely related.

The Nissan Pathfinder is classified by Nissan and by automotive industry standards as a midsize (or mid-size crossover) SUV. Full-size SUVs are larger vehicles such as the Chevrolet Tahoe, Ford Expedition, or Nissan Armada. Therefore, calling the Pathfinder a full-size SUV is inaccurate.

For a spark to occur, the ignition system must create a complete electrical circuit. The high-voltage pulse travels down the spark-plug’s center electrode, jumps the gap to the side (ground) electrode, and then returns through the engine block back to the ignition coil. This return path exists only if the metal shell of the spark plug is electrically connected—i.e., grounded—to the engine. Without that ground, the circuit is open and no spark can form.

Although the traditional common-law jury consisted of 12 people, modern U.S. law does not invariably require that number. The Supreme Court has ruled that smaller juries (typically six members) are constitutionally permissible in many state criminal trials (e.g., Williams v. Florida) and in civil cases; some jurisdictions also allow parties to stipulate to an even smaller panel. Only certain serious federal criminal cases still mandate 12 jurors. Therefore, a jury does not always have to have 12 members.

‘The Good Fight’ was created by the same creators as ‘The Good Wife,’ begins shortly after the events of the final season of ‘The Good Wife,’ and follows several of the same characters (e.g., Diane Lockhart). It is officially described as a spin-off and sequel series.

The term “commodity code” (often used in the EU for Customs tariff/Combined Nomenclature or TARIC numbers) contains the 6-digit Harmonized System (HS) code but is usually longer (8 or 10 digits) to give extra detail required by the importing jurisdiction. Therefore, while every commodity code starts with an HS code, the two terms are not strictly identical.
At the climax of Dexter’s fourth season finale, the Trinity Killer murders Rita, and Dexter discovers her body. Therefore, Rita does indeed die during Season 4.

The term “AstroTurf” began as a brand name for one particular, early generation of artificial playing surface. Today people sometimes use it generically, but technically AstroTurf refers only to that brand’s products, whereas “artificial grass” (or “artificial turf”) is the entire category of synthetic grass surfaces from any manufacturer. Thus they are related but not literally the same thing.

The modern Clash of the Titans franchise consists of the 2010 remake and its sequel, Wrath of the Titans (2012). A third installment (sometimes referred to in the press as ‘Revenge of the Titans’) was discussed in development, but the project was never green-lit or produced. No third Clash of the Titans film has been released.

The main character that closely matches “Lonnie” on Days of Our Lives is Lani Price-Grant. As of the most recent storylines, Lani has not been killed off; she was written off-screen by being sent to prison, but she remains alive in the show’s continuity. No major character named Lonnie has been definitively killed either.

Nevada law does not prohibit a player from mentally tracking the ratio of high- to low-value cards; only the use of external devices or assistance is illegal. While casinos may remove or ban a suspected counter from their private property, the act of card counting itself is legal in Las Vegas.

Although contemporary dance developed out of modern dance and both share some techniques, in the dance world they are treated as separate genres. Modern dance refers to a specific historical movement (roughly early- to mid-20th century) with codified techniques by pioneers such as Graham, Horton, and Limón. Contemporary dance emerged later and is a fusion form that borrows from modern, ballet, jazz, and other styles, and emphasizes experimentation rather than adherence to the modern dance lineage. Therefore they are related but not the same.

In hospital settings, an Intensive Care Unit (ICU) looks after the sickest patients who usually need life-support such as mechanical ventilation, multiple organ support and very close (often 1:1) nursing. A High Dependency Unit (HDU) cares for patients who are seriously ill and need more monitoring and nursing than on a general ward, but who do not require the full range of life-support available in an ICU. Therefore, high dependency and intensive care are related but not the same level of care.

The main person shown in Avicii’s official music video for “The Nights” is adventure videographer Rory Kramer, who performs stunts and narrates the story. Avicii (Tim Bergling) composed and produced the track but does not appear as the featured ‘guy’ in the video.

The Hatch Act limits partisan political activity by most federal executive-branch employees. However, it specifically exempts the President, the Vice President, and members of Congress, along with other elected officials. Therefore, in general, elected officials are not covered by the Hatch Act’s restrictions.

In Cassandra Clare’s The Mortal Instruments series, Valentine tells Clary and Jace that they are both his children, which makes them believe they are siblings for two books. However, it is later revealed that this was a lie: Clary is Valentine’s biological daughter, while Jace is actually the son of Stephen Herondale (raised briefly as Jace Wayland). Therefore, they are not biologically related.

In Ian McEwan’s novel “The Child in Time,” the protagonist’s daughter Kate is abducted early in the story. Throughout the novel her disappearance remains unresolved and she is never located or returned. The narrative focuses instead on Stephen’s grief, the passage of time, and existential themes rather than a reunion.

The United Kingdom consists of England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. The Netherlands is an independent sovereign country located on the European mainland and is not included in the political entity of the United Kingdom.

In modern U.S. (and most other) armed-forces standards, only severe or symptomatic flat feet—those that cause pain, impaired function, or require orthotics/surgery—are disqualifying. Many recruits with mild or asymptomatic flat feet are accepted after passing the physical. Therefore, simply being flat-footed does not automatically bar someone from military service.

Both terms describe the force per unit area exerted by the weight of the Earth’s atmosphere. In everyday scientific usage, “air pressure,” “atmospheric pressure,” and “barometric pressure” are interchangeable.

Under the U.S. Constitution’s Supremacy Clause (Article VI, Clause 2), valid federal statutes and regulations that fall within Congress’s constitutional authority are “the supreme Law of the Land.” When a federal law and a state law conflict, the federal law preempts and overrides the state law to the extent of the conflict. There are some limits—e.g., the federal law must itself be constitutional and within Congress’s enumerated powers—but assuming those conditions are met, the federal act controls.

“Crawfish” and “crawdad” are simply regional colloquial names for the same freshwater crustacean that is also called a crayfish. There is no biological difference between animals referred to by these two terms.

In the UK, seat belt use has been compulsory for drivers and front-seat passengers since 1983 and for rear-seat passengers (where a belt is fitted) since the early 1990s, with only limited medical and professional exemptions. Therefore, it is indeed a legal requirement to wear a seat belt in the UK where one is available.
Xbox One is backward-compatible with a large, curated list of Xbox 360 titles, but many games were never added to that list. Therefore, an Xbox One cannot run every single Xbox 360 game.

GDP per capita divides total economic output (value of all final goods & services produced) by population, while per-capita income divides the total personal income received by residents (wages, salaries, transfers, dividends, etc.) by population. Because GDP includes items that are not paid out as personal income (e.g., retained corporate profits, depreciation, some taxes) and excludes some cross-border income, the two measures are related but not the same.
The common names “groundhog” and “woodchuck” both refer to the same species of rodent, Marmota monax. They are simply two different names used for the same animal in North America.

YG (born Keenon Dequan Ray Jackson) is a rapper from Compton, California, while Yo Gotti (born Mario Sentell Giden Mims) is a rapper from Memphis, Tennessee. They have different legal names, backgrounds, and careers, so they are distinct individuals.

Under common parliamentary and procedural rules, “unanimous” means that of the votes actually cast, none are in opposition. An abstention is not a vote for or against; it is simply a choice not to vote. Therefore, if some members abstain and every member who does cast a vote votes the same way, the result is still considered unanimous among those voting.

In the men’s FIFA World Cup, which is typically what is meant when people ask about ‘the’ World Cup, the United States has never won the tournament (best finish: third place in 1930). While the U.S. women’s national team has won four Women’s World Cups, the question asks generally about a FIFA World Cup title, and the men have not captured one.

Clostridium botulinum produces botulinum toxin which, in carefully controlled and purified form (e.g., Botox), is widely used for medical and cosmetic purposes such as treating muscle spasms, cervical dystonia, chronic migraines, hyperhidrosis, and wrinkle reduction. Therefore the organism’s toxin clearly has beneficial clinical applications.

Rain is produced when water vapor condenses into cloud droplets that grow large enough to fall as precipitation. That condensation process, by definition, forms a cloud (even if it is thin, high, or not directly overhead). Phenomena such as a sun-shower occur when the rain-bearing cloud is upwind or outside the observer’s line of sight, but a cloud is still present somewhere in the column of air. Therefore, if absolutely no cloud exists anywhere above or upwind, rain cannot occur.
Voltron: Legendary Defender continued past season 6; Netflix released season 7 in August 2018 and the eighth and final season in December 2018. Therefore, season 6 was not the last season.

Time value is defined as the portion of an option’s market price that exceeds its intrinsic value: Time Value = Option Premium − Intrinsic Value. Because the market will not allow an option to trade for less than its immediate exercise (intrinsic) value—arbitrageurs could buy the under-priced option and instantly exercise it for a risk-free profit—the premium must be at least as large as the intrinsic value. Therefore the time value is always zero or positive; if a quote appears to show a negative time value it is either a data error or a fleeting mispricing that is quickly arbitraged away.

In all extant rhinoceros species, both sexes grow at least one horn (one in the Indian/Javan species, two in White, Black, and Sumatran). Horn size and shape can differ between males and females, but the physical presence of a horn is characteristic of the species regardless of sex.

All known organisms on Earth, from bacteria to humans, are built from the same set of major chemical elements—chiefly carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur—along with a similar suite of trace elements. While different species need these elements in different amounts and may tolerate wide environmental conditions, no confirmed form of life has been shown to substitute an entirely different element for one of these essentials. Thus, for all life we currently know, the required elemental toolkit is the same.

In the United States, the term “Congress” refers to the entire federal legislature, which is composed of two separate chambers: the House of Representatives and the Senate. Therefore, while the House of Representatives is one part of Congress, it is not itself ‘also called’ Congress; the word applies to the combined body, not just the House alone.
Mexico finished second in CONCACAF qualifying and therefore secured a place in the 2022 FIFA World Cup in Qatar, so they did indeed make it to the tournament.

The classic Martingale strategy assumes you can double after every loss until you eventually win, recovering all previous losses plus one unit. In reality, casinos impose maximum‐bet limits and every player has a finite bankroll. A sufficiently long losing streak (which is inevitable given enough plays) will either push you past the table limit or deplete your funds, making it impossible to continue doubling. Therefore, you cannot keep doubling your bet indefinitely, and the house edge still guarantees a negative expected return.

answer: Yes – new episodes are still being produced and aired.
Reasoning: Family Guy has not been cancelled; in 2023 FOX renewed it for seasons 22 and 23, which are scheduled to air through 2025. Production of new episodes is therefore ongoing.
Answer: Yes – new episodes are still being produced and aired.

answer: Yes – eligible adults may open carry a handgun in Tennessee without a permit.
Reasoning: Since July 1, 2021, Tennessee law (T.C.A. § 39-17-1307(g)) allows any person who is at least 21 years old (18 if on active military duty or honorably discharged) and who may lawfully possess a firearm to carry a handgun, either openly or concealed, without first obtaining a Tennessee carry permit. The permit system still exists for reciprocity in other states and for carrying in certain restricted locations, but it is not required simply to open carry a handgun in most public places where firearms are otherwise allowed.
Answer: Yes – eligible adults may open carry a handgun in Tennessee without a permit.

Reasoning: In Disney lore, Maleficent is the horned fairy antagonist from Sleeping Beauty, while the Evil Queen (often called Queen Grimhilde) is the villain from Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs. They appear in separate stories, have different origins, motives, and designs, and are treated as distinct characters across Disney media. Therefore, they are not the same character.

In-N-Out Burger is privately owned and operates all of its restaurants itself. The company has repeatedly stated that it does not sell franchise rights and keeps every location company-owned to maintain strict quality control.

Diary of a Wimpy Kid combines sequential cartoon panels with accompanying text to tell a continuous story. In libraries, bookstores, and award lists it is frequently shelved within the children’s graphic-novel section, even though the author sometimes calls it a ‘hybrid’ or ‘illustrated novel.’ Because the industry and readers generally treat it as part of the graphic-novel category, it is considered a graphic novel.

Turpentine is a natural solvent obtained by distilling resin from pine trees, whereas white spirit (mineral spirits) is a petroleum-derived solvent. Although both are used as paint thinners and cleaning agents, their chemical origins and compositions differ, so they are not the same product.

Jet lag arises whenever you cross multiple time zones faster than your internal circadian clock can adjust. This happens in both directions. In fact, most people find east-bound (west → east) travel harder because you effectively ‘lose’ hours and must advance your body clock, which is physiologically tougher than delaying it.

Although laughter is generally harmless, prolonged or intense bouts can trigger physiological events such as cardiac arrhythmias, respiratory arrest, asphyxiation, or rupture of an aneurysm in susceptible individuals. A handful of well-documented historical and modern medical case reports describe deaths that occurred during uncontrollable laughter, indicating it is possible, albeit extremely rare.

For a Newton’s third-law action-reaction pair, the two forces must (a) be equal in magnitude and opposite in direction, and (b) act on two different bodies. In an inertial frame, only the centripetal force (directed toward the centre) acts on the circling object; there is no real outward force. In a rotating (non-inertial) frame one introduces a fictitious ‘centrifugal’ force outward, but it acts on the same body, not on a different one, and therefore cannot form an action-reaction pair with the centripetal force. Thus, centripetal and centrifugal forces are not action–reaction partners.

The 1938 film “Bringing Up Baby” featured a leopard character called Baby. RKO hired a trained leopard (reportedly named Nissa) handled by animal trainer Olga Celeste. Although rear-projection and a stuffed double were occasionally used for safety, many scenes—especially the wider shots—were filmed with the live animal on set under close supervision. Therefore a real leopard was indeed employed in the production.

The Waterloo & City line of the London Underground is a short shuttle service primarily for weekday commuters travelling between Waterloo and Bank. TfL’s published timetable shows trains operating Mondays through Saturdays only; there is no scheduled service on Sundays (or most public holidays). Therefore, it does not run on Sundays.

Home Park (sometimes called ‘Home Park Private’) is the area of parkland immediately adjoining Windsor Castle. Unlike Windsor Great Park, it is not normally accessible to the general public; access is restricted to the Royal Household, Crown Estate employees and guests, except for occasional special-permission open days (e.g., when Frogmore House or the Royal Mausoleum gardens are briefly opened). Therefore, in ordinary circumstances it is not open to the public.

The illness we call the common cold is not caused by a single virus but by many viruses, chiefly rhinoviruses (which alone have more than 100 known serotypes), as well as certain coronaviruses, adenoviruses, enteroviruses, etc. Each distinct serotype or virus species can be considered a different strain responsible for cold-like symptoms, so multiple strains do exist.

“The Flight of the Phoenix” originated as a 1964 novel by Elleston Trevor and was adapted into the 1965 and 2004 films. The author conceived the plot—survivors of a desert crash building a new aircraft from the wreckage—as a work of fiction. Although viewers sometimes look for historical parallels, no documented incident matches the events depicted, and the story was not written to dramatize a real crash. Therefore it is not based on a true story.

Home Depot and Lowe’s are two separate, publicly traded corporations that compete in the home-improvement retail market. They have different corporate structures, stock tickers (HD and LOW), headquarters, and management teams. Therefore they are not the same company.

‘Avatar: The Last Airbender’ was an original animated series created for Nickelodeon by Michael Dante DiMartino and Bryan Konietzko. It was not adapted from a pre-existing novel or book series; rather, tie-in novels and comics were published later, after the show’s debut.
The 2018 film “Tully,” directed by Jason Reitman and written by Diablo Cody, is an original screenplay. It is not adapted from, nor directly based on, any novel or other book.

The founding lineup of Lynyrd Skynyrd (Ronnie Van Zant, Gary Rossington, Allen Collins, Larry Junstrom, Bob Burns, etc.) is no longer alive. The last surviving founding member, guitarist Gary Rossington, passed away in March 2023. Therefore, there are currently no surviving original members of Lynyrd Skynyrd.

The original World Trade Center’s North and South Towers had roof heights of 1,368 ft and 1,362 ft, respectively, compared with the Empire State Building’s roof height of 1,250 ft. Even if the Empire State Building’s spire height (1,454 ft) is considered, the North Tower’s antenna height reached about 1,728 ft. Thus, by standard comparisons the Twin Towers were taller overall.

Madeleine L’Engle’s novel “A Wrinkle in Time” is the first book in what is commonly called the Time Quintet. The next book, “A Wind in the Door,” continues the story of the Murry family, followed by three additional volumes. Therefore, there is indeed a sequel (and more).

“Corinthian leather” was an advertising phrase coined for the 1970s Chrysler Cordoba interiors. The hides actually came from standard U.S. cattle and were tanned in New Jersey; there is no recognized leather-grading or tanning process called Corinthian. It was purely a marketing invention, not a genuine leather variety.

The 2007 film “Gone Baby Gone” is an adaptation of Dennis Lehane’s 1998 crime novel of the same name. Both the book and the screenplay present a fictional story, although the author has noted that he drew loose inspiration from several real-world child-abduction cases. The events, characters, and outcome depicted in the movie are products of fiction, not a direct retelling of an actual case.

A cam belt (timing belt) is a specific application of a toothed or synchronous belt that drives the camshaft(s) in an engine. While every cam belt is a toothed belt, not every toothed belt is used as a cam belt; toothed belts are also employed in many other power-transmission applications. Hence, the terms are related but not strictly interchangeable.

Magic: The Gathering is not only a collectible-card game but also has an extensive narrative (lore) that is advanced through each card set, web fiction, comics, and novels. The storyline follows characters called Planeswalkers and the events that happen on various planes of the Multiverse. Because of this well-documented lore, it is accurate to say that MTG has a story.

The Home Insurance Building, erected in 1885 and often cited as the world’s first skyscraper, was demolished in 1931 to make way for what is now the Field Building (135 S. LaSalle Street). Therefore, it no longer exists in Chicago.

Multiple species of dolphins, such as the Atlantic white-sided dolphin, common dolphin, and bottlenose dolphin, are well-documented residents of the North Atlantic. Therefore, dolphins are indeed present in that ocean.

The canonical Jewish and Christian Bibles do not contain a text titled “The Book of Jasher.” It is mentioned (Joshua 10:13; 2 Samuel 1:18) as an external source, but the book itself is not included in the recognized biblical canon.

Europe stretches thousands of kilometers east–west, encompassing countries that observe several different standard times (e.g., Portugal/UK at UTC+0, Central Europe at UTC+1, Eastern Europe at UTC+2, parts of Russia at UTC+3, plus varying daylight-saving practices). Therefore, Europe is divided into multiple time zones.

The Missile Technology Control Regime (MTCR) is a voluntary export-control arrangement aimed at limiting the proliferation of missile and unmanned aerial vehicle technology capable of carrying a 500 kg payload at least 300 km. India formally joined the MTCR as its 35th member on 27 June 2016, after completing the necessary accession procedures. Therefore, at present, India is indeed a member of the MTCR.

In most U.S. jurisdictions a permit or license is required only to purchase, own, or carry a firearm in public. Simply using a firearm while on the premises of a commercial or private shooting range is generally permitted without a gun license, provided the shooter is legally allowed to possess or handle firearms (e.g., not a prohibited felon) and follows the range’s rules. Many ranges even rent firearms to customers who do not own one. Some states or ranges may impose additional age or ID requirements, but a formal ‘gun license’ is typically not necessary just to shoot at a range.

Although St James’s Palace is one of the sovereign’s official residences and is used for ceremonial and administrative functions, recent monarchs (including Queen Elizabeth II when she was alive and King Charles III now) have not actually lived there. They reside primarily at Buckingham Palace, Windsor Castle, and other homes. Therefore, saying that the Queen (or King) ‘stays’ at St James’s Palace is incorrect in the usual sense of residence.

The U.S. series “The Killing” was cancelled by AMC after its third season, then revived by Netflix for a fourth and explicitly final, six-episode season released in 2014. Since that release there have been no announcements from Netflix, AMC, the show-runners, or the cast about developing or producing a fifth season, and the fourth season was marketed as the definitive conclusion. Therefore, all available information indicates the series has ended and a 5th season is not planned.

Traditional angel food cake is made primarily from whipped egg whites, sugar, and a small amount of (usually cake) flour to provide structure. While it omits fat such as butter or oil, flour is still an essential ingredient.
Belgium’s national men’s team has participated in many World Cups and achieved its best finish with third place in 2018, but it has never captured the tournament title.

The question appears to refer to the tornado storyline in the television series “Desperate Housewives.” In the Season 4 episode “Something’s Coming,” Lynette Scavo, her husband Tom, and their children take shelter in Mrs. McCluskey’s basement during a tornado that strikes Wisteria Lane. While Ida Greenberg (a neighbor who is with them) is killed, Lynette’s immediate family all survive the storm. Therefore, Lynette’s family does not die in the tornado.
Wells Fargo is one of the largest U.S. banks and operates branches in every major U.S. market, including multiple locations in New York City and elsewhere in New York State.

In most U.S. workplaces, the term “administrative leave” specifically refers to a temporary, non-disciplinary removal from duties with full pay and benefits, often while an internal investigation is conducted. Policies can vary by employer or by union contract, and a small minority of organizations may designate an unpaid form of administrative leave, but the standard practice—and what employees and HR professionals usually mean by the term—is paid leave.

The 1998 film "U.S. Marshals" features Tommy Lee Jones reprising his role as Deputy Marshal Sam Gerard from the 1993 film "The Fugitive." While it follows a new storyline (and a new fugitive), it is generally regarded as a follow-up/spin-off sequel because it continues with a major character and is marketed as such.

The 2018 film 'A Star Is Born,' directed by and starring Bradley Cooper, is the fourth cinematic iteration of the story, following versions released in 1937, 1954, and 1976. Therefore, Cooper’s film is indeed a remake.

For an ideal gas the internal energy depends only on temperature. In an isothermal process the temperature remains constant, so the change in internal energy ΔU is zero. Thus the internal energy of the ideal-gas molecules does not change during an isothermal transformation.

In NCAA softball, there is an 8-run (mercy) rule: if a team leads by eight or more runs after five innings (or 4½ if the home team is ahead), the game is ended early. This confirms that a run rule does exist.

"Little House on the Prairie" is a novel by Laura Ingalls Wilder. While it is rooted in her real childhood experiences, it is presented as a narrative story and classified as historical fiction rather than a purely factual account. Therefore, it counts as fiction.

The 2016 film “Fantastic Beasts and Where to Find Them” takes its title, premise, and bestiary concept from J.K. Rowling’s 2001 companion book of the same name. Although the screenplay is original and expands far beyond the short reference book, the movie is still considered to be based on that book’s idea and universe.

The Channel Tunnel (often called the “Chunnel”) is a well-known rail tunnel connecting Folkestone, England, with Coquelles, France, running beneath the English Channel. It has been in operation since 1994, so the statement that there is a tunnel under the English Channel is correct.

Honey-bee venom and hornet (wasp) venom are produced by two different families of insects (Apidae vs. Vespidae) and contain different primary toxins and allergenic proteins. Bee venom is dominated by melittin, phospholipase A2, and apamin, whereas hornet venom contains components such as antigen 5, mastoparans, phospholipase A1, etc. Although a few enzymes are shared and some cross-reactivity can occur in allergic people, the overall compositions are distinct, so their venoms are not the same.

The 2016 TV series ‘Shooter’ is adapted from the same source novel as the 2007 film and shares the basic premise and main character names, but it is a separate production with different actors, expanded plotlines, and significant differences in details. Therefore, the TV show is not the same as the movie.

The stage musical (and later film) "Mamma Mia!" was created in the late-1990s using ABBA’s back catalogue. Benny Andersson and Björn Ulvaeus licensed their previously released songs and supervised their adaptation, but they did not compose new material expressly for the musical; all the featured numbers were written years earlier during ABBA’s active period (1972-1982). Therefore ABBA did not write songs specifically for "Mamma Mia!".
The moose (Alces alces) belongs to the biological family Cervidae, which also includes deer such as elk, caribou, and white-tailed deer. Therefore, it is indeed a member of the deer family.

Warner Bros./DC Studios currently have no officially scheduled Green Lantern feature film with a release date. The character is set to appear in the HBO Max/Max series "Lanterns" announced by DC Studios heads James Gunn and Peter Safran, but that project is a television series, not a movie. While various Green Lantern film scripts have been in development for years (e.g., the once-planned "Green Lantern Corps"), none has been green-lit for production or placed on the release calendar. Therefore, as of now, there is no Green Lantern movie definitively coming out.

Historically, ketchup referred to a variety of seasoned sauces made with ingredients such as mushrooms, walnuts, oysters, bananas, and other fruits, long before tomato ketchup became dominant. These non-tomato ketchups are still produced and used today, so tomato is only one of several kinds.

The crime drama ‘Ozark’ is an original work of fiction created by Bill Dubuque and Mark Williams. While the writers drew loose inspiration from real-world money-laundering cases and the geography of the Lake of the Ozarks region, the plot, characters (including Marty and Wendy Byrde), and events are not based on any specific real people or true story.

In the series ‘The Vampire Diaries,’ Caroline Forbes and Stefan Salvatore transition from friends to romantic partners. Their romantic relationship begins to develop in seasons 5–6, they officially start dating in season 6, become a couple through season 7, and even become engaged/married (though briefly). Therefore, within the show’s storyline, they do indeed date.
Grey’s Anatomy was renewed for additional seasons after season 14 (it has aired seasons 15-19 and is already renewed for season 20). Therefore, season 14 was not the final season.

The 1983 film “The Outsiders” adapts S. E. Hinton’s 1967 novel of the same name. Hinton wrote the story as fiction, drawing loosely on her observations of teenage cliques in Tulsa, Oklahoma, but the plot and characters are invented rather than dramatizations of specific real events. Therefore the movie is not based on a true story.

Although San Diego is known for its mild, Mediterranean-type climate, historic weather records show that light snow has fallen on rare occasions. Notable events include measurable snowfall at Lindbergh Field on 28 January 1949, and flurries observed in parts of the city in February 1967 and December 1967. Therefore, the correct answer to whether it has ever snowed in San Diego is yes.

“Keeping Up with the Kardashians” is widely known as an American reality television series that follows the personal and professional lives of the Kardashian–Jenner family. It is categorized, marketed, and aired as a reality show.
In the 2006 film “X-Men: The Last Stand,” Jean Grey (as the Phoenix) is ultimately killed by Wolverine in order to stop her destructive power. Thus, within that movie’s storyline, she does die.

In the North American pickup classification system, the term “half-ton” refers to full-size light-duty trucks (e.g., Ford F-150, Chevy 1500 series, Ram 1500, Nissan Titan). The Nissan Frontier is a smaller, midsize pickup and is not marketed or categorized as a half-ton truck.

The Nintendo DS Lite has a Slot-2 that accepts Game Boy Advance cartridges only. Original Game Boy and Game Boy Color cartridges are physically larger and use different hardware that the DS Lite does not support. Therefore, while you can play Game Boy Advance titles, you cannot play original ‘Game Boy’ games on a DS Lite.

In men’s rugby-union Test matches, Ireland have won on Australian soil on several occasions: first in 1979 (Brisbane) and most recently twice in the 2018 tour (Melbourne and Sydney). Therefore, Ireland have indeed beaten the Wallabies in Australia.

Under U.S. Postal Service rules (and in most other postal systems) a return address is recommended but not mandatory for ordinary domestic letters and parcels. You can therefore drop mail in a box without one, and it will be processed and delivered. However, if the item is undeliverable it will be discarded because it cannot be returned, and certain services (e.g., Priority Mail Express, international mail, hazardous-materials shipments) do require a valid return address. So, in general, yes—you can mail something without a return address, though there are exceptions and drawbacks.

Long Island Sound is a marine estuary connected to the Atlantic Ocean. Multiple shark species such as sand tiger, sandbar, smooth dogfish and occasionally others are documented there by scientists and fisheries records. Therefore, sharks do inhabit Long Island Sound, albeit generally in low numbers and mostly smaller, non-dangerous species.

“Lord of All Hopefulness” is a general-purpose Christian hymn (words by Jan Struther, set to the Irish tune ‘Slane’). It was not written solely for funerals, but because its words speak of God’s presence ‘at our waking and our sleeping’ and of hope and peace at life’s close, it has become a popular and widely accepted choice for funeral services. Therefore, while it is not exclusively a funeral hymn, it is commonly used as one and is regarded as suitable for funerals.
Hawaii was annexed by the United States in 1898 and became the 50th U.S. state in 1959, making it fully part of U.S. territory.

Hydrogen is a combustible fuel that, with appropriate modifications to the fuel-air mixture system, storage, and ignition control, can be burned in spark-ignition or even converted compression-ignition internal-combustion engines. Demonstration vehicles and some commercial prototypes already exist, showing the feasibility of hydrogen-fueled combustion engines.

Snake venoms are mixtures of proteins and enzymes that the human immune system can recognize as foreign antigens. Repeated, carefully controlled exposure to small, non-lethal doses of a specific snake’s venom can stimulate production of neutralising antibodies (this is how animals and some human donors are hyper-immunised to make antivenom). Historical cases (e.g., Bill Haast) show that humans can achieve measurable immunity to the particular venoms they inject. However, this protection is specific to the venoms used, takes time to develop, and is risky outside medical supervision, so ordinary accidental bites do not reliably create immunity.

A broken neck (cervical spine fracture) can sever or severely damage the spinal cord, disrupt respiratory control, and injure critical blood vessels, leading to immediate or rapid death. While not every neck fracture is fatal, it certainly can be, so the statement is correct.
The Washington Post Company, then the parent company of The Washington Post newspaper, conducted its initial public offering (IPO) in 1971, listing a minority class of shares on the stock market.

The Tower of Pisa was designed to stand vertically. Its tilt developed gradually during construction because the soft, uneven sub-soil could not properly support the structure’s weight, causing it to sink on one side. Therefore, the leaning was accidental, not intentional.

Borderlands: The Handsome Collection bundles Borderlands 2 and Borderlands: The Pre-Sequel together with every piece of DLC that had been released for those two games up to the time the collection launched (campaign add-ons, characters, level-cap packs, headhunter packs, skins, etc.). Later add-ons that were created after the compilation’s release (e.g., 2019’s “Commander Lilith & the Fight for Sanctuary” for Borderlands 2) are not part of the original package, but everything available when the collection shipped is included. In the sense most people ask, the Handsome Collection “comes with all DLC.”

In normal cardiac circulation, blood returns from the body (systemic circulation) to the right atrium through the superior and inferior venae cavae and the coronary sinus. Blood that has been oxygenated in the lungs returns to the heart via the pulmonary veins and enters the left atrium, not the right. Therefore, the right atrium does not receive blood coming directly from the lungs.

Traditional wedding etiquette distinguishes between a “maid of honor” (unmarried) and a “matron of honor” (married), but these titles are purely conventional. Etiquette guides note that the couple is free to use whichever term they prefer, and many weddings list a married chief attendant as a "maid of honor" without issue. Therefore, there is no obligation to call a married woman a "matron of honor."

In the Pirates of the Caribbean films, Elizabeth Swann’s romantic storyline resolves with her marrying Will Turner. Although she shares flirtation and a kiss with Captain Jack Sparrow in Dead Man’s Chest, their relationship never progresses beyond that, and they do not become a couple by the end of the series.

Under the Arizona Constitution and statutes, all appeals in which a sentence of death has been imposed bypass the Court of Appeals and go directly to the Arizona Supreme Court. Therefore, the Arizona Court of Appeals does not have jurisdiction to hear death-penalty cases.

Northern Ireland fields its own national football (soccer) team that competes separately from the Republic of Ireland in FIFA World Cup qualification. The team has qualified for the World Cup finals in the past (1958, 1982, 1986) and continues to attempt to qualify in every cycle, so it does have a World Cup team.

Under the U.S. Constitution’s Double Jeopardy Clause, once a defendant has been acquitted and jeopardy has attached, the government cannot prosecute that same person again for the same offense—even if later-discovered evidence clearly shows guilt. The rule has only narrow exceptions (e.g., separate prosecution by a different sovereign or if the first trial ended before jeopardy attached). Therefore, if you have already been tried and acquitted, the discovery of new evidence does not permit a retrial for that same crime.

Dynamite and TNT are not the same substance. Dynamite is nitroglycerin stabilized by an absorbent such as diatomaceous earth and was invented by Alfred Nobel. TNT (trinitrotoluene) is a distinct chemical compound with different molecular structure, properties, sensitivity and uses. Therefore, saying there is a difference between dynamite and TNT is correct.

In the real 1988 Winter Olympics crash, the Jamaican team got out of the overturned sled and walked alongside it, pushing it on its runners to the finish. They did not lift and carry it. The popular movie “Cool Runnings” dramatizes the moment by showing them hoisting the sled, but that did not occur in reality.

In basketball rules (NBA, NCAA, FIBA), a flagrant foul is defined as a specific type of personal foul involving excessive or violent contact. Because it falls under the category of personal fouls, it is charged to the player’s personal-foul count and to the team’s foul total, in addition to the extra flagrant-foul penalties (free throws, possession, possible ejection).

The 1999 film "The Green Mile" received four Academy Award nominations (including Best Picture, Best Supporting Actor for Michael Clarke Duncan, Best Adapted Screenplay, and Best Sound). Therefore it was indeed nominated for Oscars.
Applebee’s Grill + Bar and IHOP are both restaurant chains operated by the parent company Dine Brands Global (formerly known as DineEquity). Thus, they share the same corporate owner.

In the Westminster systems of Canada and Australia, a bill does not become law until it receives Royal Assent from the governor general. Constitutionally, however, the governor general has the power to assent, withhold assent (effectively veto), or reserve the bill for the monarch’s consideration (e.g., s. 58 of the Australian Constitution; similar powers exist in Canada). By convention a governor general virtually always grants assent, but the constitution does not compel them to sign every bill. Therefore, they are not strictly required to sign all bills passed by the federal parliament, even though in practice they almost always do.

Semolina is the coarse, hard wheat (specifically durum wheat) endosperm used for pasta and couscous, while Cream of Wheat is a brand name for farina made from finely ground non-durum hard wheat. They are both wheat products but come from different wheat varieties and have different granulation and culinary uses, so they are not the same product.

Electronic devices that transmit radio signals on the same frequencies used by mobile phones can prevent phones in the vicinity from making or receiving calls. These devices are commonly referred to as cell-phone jammers. While they are illegal to market or operate in many countries (e.g., the United States), they do in fact exist and are commercially available in other parts of the world or on the gray market.

Humans normally develop only two dentitions—a primary (baby) set and a permanent (adult) set. While isolated extra or ‘super-numerary’ teeth can appear, a true additional complete set (a third dentition) is exceptionally rare and not considered a normal possibility. Therefore, for practical purposes, people cannot have more than two sets of teeth.

Under Article II, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution, the President appoints Supreme Court justices, but those appointments require the 'advice and consent' of the Senate, meaning the Senate must hold a confirmation vote for the nominee to take office.
The 1971 film 'Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory' features numerous song-and-dance numbers written by Leslie Bricusse and Anthony Newley and is commonly categorized as a musical fantasy film.

Under the Laws of Cricket, when a no-ball is called most modes of dismissal are disallowed (bowled, caught, LBW, stumped, hit wicket) but run-out remains a valid way to be dismissed. Therefore, if the batters attempt a run and the fielding side legally puts down the wicket, the batsman can indeed be run out even though the delivery was a no-ball.

Yes. The most cited case is Houston Colt-.45s pitcher Ken Johnson, who in 1964 threw a complete 9-inning no-hitter yet lost 1–0 because of errors and an unearned run. (There have also been a few combined no-hitters in which the team still lost.) Therefore at least one pitcher has indeed thrown a no-hitter and taken the loss.

In most jurisdictions there is no statute that directly prohibits driving solely on the basis that you have had no sleep. However, if your lack of sleep leaves you impaired so that you weave, speed, or otherwise drive unsafely, you can be cited under general reckless- or careless-driving laws. A few places (e.g., New Jersey’s “Maggie’s Law”) specifically make driving after 24 hours awake a traffic offense, but these are the exception rather than the rule. Therefore, in a broad sense, simply having no sleep is not automatically illegal, although it can easily lead to behavior that is illegal.

Yes. In NHL playoff history, teams have overcome a 3–0 deficit on several occasions: the 1942 Toronto Maple Leafs, 1975 New York Islanders, 2010 Philadelphia Flyers, and 2014 Los Angeles Kings. Therefore, such a comeback has happened.

In chess the king is allowed to move one square in any direction—forward, backward, sideways, or diagonally—provided the destination square is not attacked by an opposing piece (except in special cases like castling). Therefore a backward move is legal for a king.

Under the Torrens title system, registration is the primary means by which legal title is obtained and protected, but the system still acknowledges certain unregistered or ‘off-register’ interests. Examples include equitable interests (e.g., trusts, certain contractual rights protected by caveats), short-term leases that need not be registered, and interests arising through fraud or overriding statutes. Hence, it is incorrect to say the Torrens system recognises only registered interests.

Under the U.S. National Organ Transplant Act of 1984, it is a federal crime to knowingly acquire, receive, or otherwise transfer any human organ for valuable consideration for use in human transplantation. While reimbursing donors for certain expenses is allowed, outright buying or selling organs is prohibited, making such transactions illegal.

The term “termination” is a broad HR category that simply means an employment relationship ends; it can occur voluntarily (resignation, retirement) or involuntarily (layoff, firing for cause). “Being fired” refers specifically to an involuntary, for-cause termination. Therefore, not every termination is a firing.

answer: Yes, there is a difference: input power is greater than output power in real systems.
Reasoning: For any real machine or circuit, some of the power taken in is inevitably lost as heat, sound, friction, electromagnetic radiation, etc. Because of these losses the useful power delivered at the output is lower than the power drawn at the input (efficiency < 100 %). Only in an ideal, perfectly efficient device—which does not exist in practice—would the input and output powers be equal.
Answer: Yes, there is a difference: input power is greater than output power in real systems.

Reasoning: Data science encompasses the entire process of extracting insight and value from data, which includes collecting, cleaning, analyzing, modeling, and communicating findings. Communicating findings typically relies on data visualization techniques, making visualization an integral step in the data-science workflow.

Lake Michigan is the only one of the five Great Lakes that lies entirely within the United States (bordered by Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana and Michigan). The Canadian-U.S. boundary does not touch Lake Michigan at any point.

Several films titled “Stalingrad” (e.g., the 1993 German film and the 2013 Russian film) tell fictionalized stories set during the real World War II Battle of Stalingrad. While the main characters and specific plotlines are invented, the backdrop—the battle itself, dates, locations, and many broad events—are drawn from actual history. Therefore the movie is ‘based on a true story’ in the sense that it dramatizes real historical events, though it is not a literal retelling of particular individuals’ experiences.

In the climax of ‘Train to Busan,’ the father (Seok-woo) is bitten by an infected passenger. To protect his daughter and the pregnant woman, he locks them in the locomotive cab and then sacrifices himself by jumping off the moving train, leading to his death.

The interior angles of any triangle must sum to 180°. An obtuse angle is greater than 90°. If a triangle had two obtuse angles, their sum would already exceed 180°, leaving no degrees for a third angle. Therefore, such a triangle cannot exist.

In the film “Thelma & Louise,” the closing scene shows the two women deliberately driving their car off the edge of the Grand Canyon. The last shot freezes on the car mid-air and then fades to white, strongly implying they plunge to their deaths. Although the on-screen depiction is stylized, the consensus among viewers and filmmakers is that the characters do not survive the fall.

Consuming a large quantity of milk in a short period can distend the stomach, trigger nausea, and in some people provoke intolerance-related symptoms (e.g., from lactose). These factors can indeed cause vomiting.

While several sea-snake species (e.g., the Belcher’s sea snake) have extremely potent venom, toxicological studies that compare LD₅₀ values in mice show the inland taipan (a terrestrial snake) has the highest venom toxicity recorded. Therefore, a generic statement that “the sea snake is the most venomous snake” is inaccurate; sea snakes are among the most venomous, but not the single most venomous.

As of the latest public information before late-2023, Vogtle Units 3 and 4 in Georgia are the only large light-water reactor units still under active construction in the United States: Unit 3 entered commercial operation in July 2023 and Unit 4 is expected to follow in 2024. Because at least one unit (Vogtle 4) is still being finished—and no other large reactors have been canceled or completed since then—the correct response is that there is indeed a nuclear power plant currently being built in the US.

The term “rain crow” (or “rain-crow”) is a traditional common name used in parts of North America for the Yellow-billed Cuckoo (and sometimes the Black-billed Cuckoo). People believed its call foretold coming rain, hence the nickname. Although it is not the official scientific name, the nickname is widely documented in field guides and folklore, so a bird is indeed referred to as a rain crow.

ABC is the American Broadcasting Company, which has been owned by The Walt Disney Company since 1996. NBC is the National Broadcasting Company, owned by NBCUniversal, a subsidiary of Comcast. Because they belong to two entirely different parent corporations (Disney vs. Comcast), they are not owned by the same company.

Humans normally develop male or female reproductive anatomy, but variations in chromosomes, hormone exposure, or developmental processes can lead to intersex conditions in which a person is born with genital, gonadal, or chromosomal characteristics that do not fit typical definitions of male or female. These conditions are rare but well-documented in medical literature, so it is indeed possible to be born with both male-typical and female-typical anatomical features.

Under the Laws of the Game used in professional association football, a player who is substituted leaves the match and is not permitted to re-enter. Because they cannot come back onto the field, they therefore cannot be taken off (substituted) a second time. (Some youth or friendly competitions use ‘rolling’ or unlimited substitutions, but in the standard Laws applied to competitive adult football, a player may only be substituted once and cannot return.)

Israel’s men’s national soccer team qualified for the finals of the FIFA World Cup once, in 1970 (Mexico). They have not qualified in any other edition, but that single appearance means the correct answer to whether they have ever qualified is yes.

Interstate 70 in Kansas is partly on the Kansas Turnpike. The stretch from Topeka eastward to the Kansas City area is tolled, while the remainder of I-70 across the state is free. Because at least a portion of I-70 in Kansas requires a toll, the correct overall answer to whether it is a toll road is “yes.”
The imperial (UK) gallon is defined as 4.546 litres, whereas the US liquid gallon is defined as 3.785 litres. Because they represent different volumes, they are not the same unit.

In the United States, the Fifth Amendment privilege against self-incrimination exists at all times, not just after a formal arrest. Therefore you may generally refuse to answer officers’ questions before you are arrested. The well-known Miranda warning (which includes the phrase “you have the right to remain silent”) must only be read once you are in custodial interrogation, but the underlying constitutional right already exists. Limited statutory exceptions apply (e.g., during a lawful stop in some states you may have to provide your name or ID), yet these do not negate the basic right not to answer substantive questions.

A peripherally-inserted central catheter (PICC) terminates in a central vein (often the superior vena cava). Because it is a central line, it can safely deliver hyper-osmolar solutions such as total parenteral nutrition (TPN), and it is routinely used for that purpose in both inpatient and home settings.

answer: Yes – the Lakota/Pawnee dialogue is supposed to be subtitled in English.
Reasoning: The 1990 film “Dances with Wolves” contains extended dialogue in the Lakota language (and some Pawnee). In every official theatrical and home-video release, those non-English lines are accompanied by forced English subtitles so the audience can understand them, while the English dialogue is not subtitled by default. Therefore the movie is indeed meant to show subtitles whenever Lakota/Pawnee is spoken; if a copy plays without them, the subtitle/closed-caption track may be turned off or the disc/file may be faulty.
Answer: Yes – the Lakota/Pawnee dialogue is supposed to be subtitled in English.

Reasoning: To enter Canada, adults normally need a passport or another Western Hemisphere Travel Initiative-compliant document (e.g., passport card, NEXUS, Enhanced Driver’s License). A birth certificate alone is accepted only for U.S. citizens aged 15 or younger (and 16–18 when traveling with a school or youth group) arriving by land or sea. It is never sufficient for air travel and not valid for most adult travelers. Therefore, for the typical traveler the answer is no.

By definition, a (rooted) tree is an acyclic connected graph in which every node except the root has exactly one parent. If a node had two parents, there would be two distinct paths from the root to that node, creating a cycle or violating the single-parent property, so the structure would no longer be a tree.

Cristiano Ronaldo has played in multiple FIFA World Cups for Portugal (2006, 2010, 2014, 2018, 2022), but Portugal has never won the tournament during his career. His major international titles are the UEFA Euro 2016 and the UEFA Nations League 2019, not the FIFA World Cup.

In the U.S. military (and in many other nations’ forces) the general grooming standard requires members to be clean-shaven, so routinely growing a beard is not permitted. However, service regulations do allow beards in specific, approved situations—most commonly for medical conditions such as pseudofolliculitis barbae or for sincerely-held religious beliefs, and occasionally for certain special-operations roles or exercises. Because those officially sanctioned exceptions exist, it is accurate to say that a service member can have a beard, but only with an approved waiver or under special circumstances.

Spain’s national anthem is the “Marcha Real.” Although unofficial lyrics have been proposed over the years, no official words have ever been adopted. Therefore, the anthem is considered purely instrumental and does not have official lyrics.

In baseball, a run batted in (RBI) is credited to the batter for every run that scores as a direct result of the batter's action, except in a few special cases. When a batter hits a home run, every runner on base scores, and the batter himself also scores. The batter therefore receives an RBI for each of those runs, including his own. Hence, a home run always produces at least one RBI.

The current world record for running a mile is about 3 minutes 43 seconds, and no human physiology or projected performance models suggest the capability to sustain the ~30 mph pace needed for a 2-minute mile. Barring non-human assistance (e.g., vehicles or external propulsion), it is beyond realistic human limits.

In real-estate transactions, the day on which the buyer and seller sign the final documents, exchange funds, and transfer title is commonly referred to as both the “closing” and the “settlement.” Although different industries (e.g., securities trading) distinguish between trade and settlement dates, within standard real-estate usage the terms “closing date” and “settlement date” are used interchangeably to describe the same calendar day.

Under Article I, Section 3 of the U.S. Constitution, the vice president serves as president of the Senate and has no vote unless the Senate is equally divided, in which case the vice president may cast a tie-breaking vote.

Both dishes use navy (or similar) beans and may include bits of pork, so they are related, but they are prepared and sauced differently. Pork-and-beans is typically a stewed bean dish in a thinner, tomato-based sauce with only a small piece of salt pork for flavor, whereas baked beans are slow-baked in a thicker, sweeter molasses or brown-sugar sauce (often still containing some pork). Because of these consistent differences in preparation and flavor profile, they are considered different dishes, not the same thing.

Most of the United States observes Daylight Saving Time, but several jurisdictions do not, including nearly all of Arizona (apart from the Navajo Nation), Hawaii, Puerto Rico, Guam, the U.S. Virgin Islands, American Samoa, and the Northern Mariana Islands. Therefore, it is not the case that the entire U.S. observes daylight saving.

Identical (monozygotic) twins arise from a single fertilized egg that splits. Because they come from the same zygote, they normally share exactly the same genetic sex chromosomes, so both are genetically male (XY) or both female (XX). Opposite-sex ‘identical’ twins would require an exceptionally rare post-zygotic mutation or chromosomal anomaly (e.g., one twin losing a Y chromosome to become XO/Turner), which makes them no longer genetically identical. Therefore, in the usual sense of identical twins, a boy–girl pair is not possible.

The 2005 film “Hostage,” starring Bruce Willis, is adapted from Robert Crais’s 2001 crime-thriller novel of the same name. Both the novel and the screenplay are works of fiction; they were not written to dramatize any specific real-life incident, even though they draw on familiar crime-story elements (kidnapping, standoffs, etc.). Therefore, the movie is not ‘based on a true story.’

For thousands of years the Nile’s flow rose every summer because of monsoon rains in the Ethiopian highlands, producing the predictable annual flood that fertilized the floodplain in Egypt and Sudan. Since the completion of the Aswan High Dam (and other upstream dams) in the 1960-s/70-s, the river’s discharge is now stored and released in a regulated way. As a result, the large natural flood that once occurred every year no longer reaches most of the Nile downstream of the dams; only controlled variations in flow occur. Occasional unplanned floods can still happen upstream when rainfall is extreme, but the traditional annual inundation no longer happens.

In many tax systems, a property tax is assessed on the total value of real property—both the land itself and any improvements (houses, buildings, etc.). A land tax, by contrast, is levied only on the unimproved value of the land, ignoring the value of buildings or other structures. While some jurisdictions may colloquially use the terms interchangeably, in strict fiscal terminology they refer to different bases of taxation, so they are not the same.

The best-known film titled “Hush” is the 2016 horror–thriller directed by Mike Flanagan (about a deaf writer stalked in her isolated home). The story was conceived and written by Flanagan and co-writer/star Kate Siegel as a wholly fictional scenario, not drawn from real events. Earlier movies titled “Hush” (1998 U.S. thriller, 2008 U.K. thriller) are likewise original works and not marketed or documented as being based on true stories. Therefore, none of the films called “Hush” are based on a true story.

An ounce (avoirdupois ounce) is a unit of weight/mass (≈ 28.35 g), whereas a fluid ounce is a unit of volume (≈ 29.57 mL in the U.S. system, ≈ 28.41 mL in the imperial system). They measure different physical quantities, so they are not interchangeable.

Puerto Rico is an unincorporated U.S. territory. Although most Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens and the major parties hold presidential primaries on the island, Puerto Rico has no electoral votes in the Electoral College. Therefore, residents who remain on the island cannot cast ballots that count in the general U.S. presidential election; only those who establish residence in a U.S. state or the District of Columbia may vote for President.

An infinite geometric series of the form a + ar + ar² + … can converge to a finite sum provided the common ratio r satisfies |r| < 1. In that case the sum equals a/(1-r). If |r| ≥ 1 the series diverges. Therefore, yes—some infinite geometric series do have a sum.

“Day of the Dead: Bloodline” (2018) is marketed as a remake/reimagining of George A. Romero’s 1985 film “Day of the Dead,” not as a continuation of its story. Therefore, it is not considered a sequel.

In the series ‘Gossip Girl,’ Jenny Humphrey and Nate Archibald share brief flirtations and a kiss, but they never enter into an official romantic relationship or become a steady couple at any point in the show.

Tennessee lies near the New Madrid Seismic Zone and the East Tennessee Seismic Zone, both of which generate frequent small-to-moderate earthquakes. Numerous events have been recorded in state history, such as the magnitude-4.4 quake near Decatur on 12 Dec 2018, demonstrating that earthquakes have indeed occurred in Tennessee.

J. K. Rowling has said that while she admires Tolkien, she was not consciously drawing on The Lord of the Rings when creating Harry Potter. The two series share some broad fantasy tropes that ultimately trace back to older mythic sources, but there is no substantial evidence that Harry Potter was directly inspired by Tolkien’s work.
The 1939 film “Gone with the Wind” was awarded the Academy Award for Best Picture (then titled Outstanding Production) at the 12th Oscars ceremony in 1940.

In storytelling, the term “antagonist” refers to whatever force opposes the protagonist’s goals. While that role is often filled by a human character, it can just as easily be an impersonal force such as nature (a storm), society (oppressive laws), technology, or even the protagonist’s own inner conflict. Because the definition hinges on opposition rather than personhood, the antagonist does not have to be a person.

The original World Trade Center’s North Tower stood 417 m to the roof (about 526 m with its antenna), and the South Tower was 415 m to the roof. The Empire State Building is 381 m to the roof (about 443 m with its antenna). Thus, even by roof height—and certainly including antennas—the Twin Towers were taller than the Empire State Building.

The Republic of Ireland participated in the UEFA qualification play-offs for the 2018 FIFA World Cup but lost to Denmark and therefore did not qualify for the tournament. Hence, Ireland was not one of the 32 teams at the 2018 World Cup in Russia.

In networking terminology, a host is any device (computer, server, etc.) that has an IP address and can provide or consume network services. A web server is a computer configured to provide web pages over HTTP/HTTPS and therefore meets the definition of a host.

Margaret Mitchell never wrote a follow-up, but the Mitchell estate authorized Alexandra Ripley to write the novel “Scarlett,” published in 1991, as an official sequel to “Gone with the Wind.” Later, Donald McCaig also wrote “Rhett Butler’s People” (2007) with the estate’s approval. Therefore at least one authorized sequel exists.

In India, the National Human Rights Commission (NHRC) was set up by Parliament through the Protection of Human Rights Act, 1993. Bodies created by an act of Parliament are ‘statutory bodies’; only those explicitly established by provisions in the Constitution itself are ‘constitutional bodies’. Since the NHRC is not mentioned in the Constitution but rather in a statute, it is not a constitutional body.

Both are Howard Hawks Westerns with similar plots and overlapping cast members (e.g., John Wayne), which sometimes leads to confusion. However, they were produced and released at different times—Rio Bravo in 1959 and El Dorado in 1966—and are distinct films with different titles, supporting casts, and story details.

answer: Yes – as of March 2018, Sunday carry-out alcohol sales (noon-8 p.m.) became legal.
Reasoning: Indiana had long prohibited retail carry-out sales of alcohol on Sundays. Senate Bill 1 was signed by the governor on February 28 2018 and took effect immediately, allowing grocery, package-liquor and convenience stores to sell alcohol on Sundays from noon to 8 p.m. (Bars and restaurants had already been able to serve alcohol on Sundays.) Therefore, beginning March 4 2018, consumers could legally buy carry-out alcoholic beverages on Sundays in Indiana.
Answer: Yes – as of March 2018, Sunday carry-out alcohol sales (noon-8 p.m.) became legal.

Reasoning: Five Guys began in Arlington, Virginia, but it has since expanded well beyond the East Coast. The chain now operates restaurants across the entire United States (including the West Coast) and in many other countries. Therefore it is not limited to the East Coast.

In British/Commonwealth usage the term “white spirit” refers to a petroleum-derived solvent used as paint thinner. In North American usage the identical solvent is called “mineral spirits” (or Stoddard solvent). Although there can be slight formulation variations from brand to brand, the two names denote the same type of product.

In the classical brigade de cuisine hierarchy, the executive chef (chef de cuisine) is at the top, followed by the sous-chef as the second-in-command. Below the sous-chef are the chefs de partie, who are responsible for specific stations (e.g., grill, sauté, pastry). Therefore, a sous-chef outranks a chef de partie.

Ireland’s Got Talent is broadcast on Virgin Media One (formerly TV3), an Irish channel that is not carried on standard Freeview, Sky, Virgin or BT line-ups in mainland England. Unless you subscribe to a specialist package that includes Irish channels, use a satellite dish pointed at the Irish feed, or stream it through Virgin Media Player with an Irish IP address, you will not be able to watch the full programme live or on-demand in England. Short clips are, however, uploaded to the show’s official YouTube channel and can be viewed anywhere. Therefore, for the average viewer in England, the answer is effectively “no”, unless you use one of the work-arounds mentioned.
Answer: Generally no, unless you access the Irish channel or stream it via a workaround

Reasoning: The Syrian Arab Republic signed the United Nations Charter in 1945 and has remained a UN member state ever since. Although Syria’s participation in some other regional organizations has been suspended at times, its UN membership has never been revoked or suspended.

The Isle of Man is a self-governing British Crown Dependency. It is under the sovereignty of the British Crown but it is not constitutionally part of the United Kingdom, nor represented in the UK Parliament.

Under NCAA rules, Division II institutions are permitted to award athletic scholarships, and most do so, although the scholarship limits per sport are lower than in Division I and awards are often partial rather than full. Therefore, in general, Division II schools do offer athletic scholarships.

answer: No. A fixed pulley's mechanical advantage is 1, so it provides no force amplification.
Reasoning: A single fixed pulley only redirects the force you apply; the output (load) force equals the input (effort) force. Therefore its ideal mechanical advantage is 1, meaning it does not multiply force.
Answer: No. A fixed pulley’s mechanical advantage is 1, so it provides no force amplification.
