Reasoning: Both the original stage musical/2008 film “Mamma Mia!” and its sequel, 2018’s “Mamma Mia! Here We Go Again,” are jukebox musicals whose soundtracks are built entirely from songs by the Swedish pop group ABBA. Therefore the new Mamma Mia movie still features ABBA music.

Pokémon Gold, Silver, and Crystal are all Generation II games set in the same world, but they are distinct versions. Each has different version-exclusive Pokémon, Crystal adds story and gameplay changes (e.g., Suicune storyline, Battle Tower, animated sprites), and there are other small differences. Therefore, they are not the same game, just closely related versions.

In traditional European nobility, a prince and a duke are distinct ranks. A prince is usually of royal blood—often the son or close relative of a king or queen—and ranks higher in the hierarchy. A duke is a high-ranking noble, but typically not of direct royal lineage and generally ranks below prince. Because the titles denote different positions and privileges, a prince is not the same as a duke.
The Twilight Zone Tower of Terror attraction at Walt Disney World is located in Disney’s Hollywood Studios, not in Magic Kingdom.

Bull sharks (Carcharhinus leucas) are capable of living in both salt and fresh water. Documented sightings and captures show they can swim from the Gulf of Mexico up the Mississippi River, with records as far north as Illinois. While they are not common, their presence confirms that sharks do indeed occur in the river on occasion.

The inclusion of 0 in the natural numbers is convention-dependent. In many elementary mathematics texts (particularly number theory), ℕ = {1, 2, 3, …}, so 0 is excluded. In set theory and computer science, however, it is common to define ℕ = {0, 1, 2, …}. Because the traditional school-level definition excludes 0, the answer is usually taken to be ‘no’ unless the convention is explicitly stated otherwise.

Mauna Loa erupts from its summit caldera (Moku‘āweoweo) as well as from long rift zones and flank vents that extend down the mountain’s sides. Many historic lava flows have started along these rift zones or lower-elevation vents rather than at the top. Therefore, not all Mauna Loa lava flows originate at the volcano’s summit.

The Great Firewall is the censorship and surveillance system applied to mainland China's internet. Under the 'one country, two systems' arrangement, Hong Kong maintains a separate telecommunications and legal regime, and major international websites (e.g., Google, Facebook, Twitter) remain freely accessible there. Although political pressure and surveillance have increased in recent years, Hong Kong is not technically routed through or filtered by the Great Firewall infrastructure that applies on the mainland.

Puerto Rico is an unincorporated territory under U.S. sovereignty. Its residents are U.S. citizens, and federal laws apply there, although it is not a state. Therefore, it is considered part of the United States.

Canada practices unconditional jus soli: anyone born on Canadian soil automatically acquires Canadian citizenship at birth, except for the narrow case where a parent is a foreign diplomat or other recognized representative with diplomatic immunity. Therefore, in almost all ordinary situations, a child born in Canada becomes a Canadian citizen.

Without additional context, one would infer that if the question is being asked (often in reference to a news report about the archbishop’s return), the most likely implication is that he has indeed come back and the exile is over. This is an educated guess, but uncertainty is high because no specific background is provided.

In the film, Marion Ravenwood appears to die when a truck carrying her seemingly explodes, but it is later revealed that she survived and is held captive by the Nazis. She is alive at the end of the movie, so she does not die in Raiders of the Lost Ark.
Lac Léman is the French name used primarily in Switzerland and France for the lake commonly referred to in English as Lake Geneva; they are the same body of water on the Swiss-French border.

The term “October Revolution” refers to the armed insurrection in Petrograd in October 1917 (Julian calendar) in which Lenin’s Bolshevik Party seized power. Because the Bolsheviks were the leading force in that uprising, historians and popular usage frequently call the same event the “Bolshevik Revolution.” They are two names for the same historical episode, not separate events.

Compressed natural gas (CNG) has been used as a vehicle fuel for decades; many manufacturers and fleet operators (e.g., Honda Civic GX, various Ford and GM trucks, city buses, taxis) have produced or converted vehicles to run on natural gas. Therefore, cars that run on natural gas do exist.

Most large, ocean-going cruise vessels are registered under so-called ‘flags of convenience’ such as the Bahamas, Panama, or Malta. However, there are a few exceptions: Norwegian Cruise Line’s Pride of America is registered in Honolulu under the U.S. flag, and several smaller coastal and river cruise ships operated by lines like American Cruise Lines and UnCruise Adventures are also U.S-flagged. Therefore at least some cruise ships are indeed registered in the United States.

answer: True – they did make a Season 4 of The Flash.
Reasoning: The CW officially renewed The Flash for a fourth season on January 8, 2017, and that season has already been produced and aired (premiered October 10, 2017). Therefore, a Season 4 does exist and was indeed made.
Answer: True – they did make a Season 4 of The Flash.

Reasoning: If the question refers to the FIFA World Cup (the most common meaning of “World Cup”), the United States men’s national soccer team has participated many times, beginning with the inaugural 1930 tournament and most recently in 2022. Therefore, the USA has indeed played in the World Cup.

Under Law 11 of the Laws of the Game, a player is in an on-side position if at least two opponents are nearer to their own goal line than the attacker when the ball is played. The goalkeeper is simply another opponent for this purpose, so he normally provides one of those two opponents. If the goalkeeper is out of position, then two outfield defenders must instead be between the attacker and the goal line. Therefore, the goalkeeper does indeed ‘count’ when applying the offside rule.

A hurricane is a type of tropical cyclone whose overall circulation is driven by a warm-core low-pressure system. At its center is the eye, where air descends and conditions are relatively calm, but the barometric pressure is lower than in the surrounding eyewall and outer bands. Therefore, the eye is indeed a region of low pressure.

In the UK, section 24A of the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 (and equivalent provisions elsewhere) allows 'any person' to arrest someone who is committing, or whom they reasonably suspect to be committing, an indictable offence, provided certain necessity conditions (e.g., preventing escape) are met. Therefore, it is legally possible for an ordinary citizen to make an arrest in limited circumstances.

In NHL history, several Stanley Cup Final series have ended in four-game sweeps (e.g., Detroit Red Wings over the Philadelphia Flyers in 1997 and over the Washington Capitals in 1998). Therefore at least one team has indeed swept the Final.
In-N-Out Burger has only expanded as far east as Texas and Colorado. The company has no announced plans or operating locations in any Midwestern or Eastern states, including Ohio.
In the 1933 original King Kong film, the giant ape is gunned down by airplanes while atop the Empire State Building and falls to his death, making his demise explicit.

In Major League Baseball history it has happened once: on April 23, 1999 Fernando Tatís of the St. Louis Cardinals hit two grand slams in the third inning against the Los Angeles Dodgers, both off pitcher Chan Ho Park.

A Doctor of Physical Therapy (DPT) is a clinical doctorate specific to the practice of physical therapy. Holders are licensed physical therapists, not physicians, and they do not earn the Doctor of Medicine (MD) degree or practice as medical doctors.

The primary articulations of the knee joint are between the femur and tibia (tibio-femoral) and between the femur and patella (patello-femoral). The fibula does not articulate with the femur; its proximal head forms a separate tibio-fibular joint below and outside the knee capsule. Therefore it is not considered part of the knee joint.

A classic Bloody Mary cocktail is prepared with vodka, which is a distilled spirit containing alcohol, mixed with tomato juice and seasonings. Therefore, by definition, a standard Bloody Mary includes alcohol.

Penn & Teller: Fool Us first aired in 2011, moved to The CW in 2014, and has been renewed each year since. The CW announced another renewal in 2023 and began airing Season 10 in late 2023, with additional episodes scheduled for 2024. Therefore, the show is still in production and currently airing new episodes.

Both catbirds and mockingbirds belong to the mimid (mimic-thrush) family, but they are different genera and species (e.g., Gray Catbird – Dumetella carolinensis vs. Northern Mockingbird – Mimus polyglottos). Therefore, they are related but not the same bird.
The area commonly called “the Las Vegas Strip” lies largely in the unincorporated towns of Paradise and Winchester within Clark County, not within the official city limits of Las Vegas.

Gandalf in the Lord of the Rings and Hobbit films is played by Sir Ian McKellen. The character of Professor Albus Dumbledore in the Harry Potter films was portrayed first by Richard Harris and, after his death, by Michael Gambon. Ian McKellen never played Dumbledore, though he was rumored to have been considered for the role.

A longer second toe (often called Morton’s toe or a ‘Greek foot’) is a common, harmless anatomical variation found in a sizable percentage of the population. It usually has no medical significance unless it causes shoe-fit problems or mechanical pain. Therefore, it is considered within the range of normal human variation.

A cow’s lactation is hormonally triggered by giving birth. The animal must first become pregnant and calve before milk production starts. After calving, the cow will continue to lactate for many months even though she is no longer pregnant, but without that initial pregnancy and birth she would not produce milk at all.

Celery (Apium graveolens) belongs to the Apiaceae (parsley or carrot) family, whereas rhubarb (Rheum species) belongs to the Polygonaceae (knotweed) family. Since they belong to different botanical families, they are not from the same family.

Yes. In the 2016 NBA Finals, the Cleveland Cavaliers trailed the Golden State Warriors 3–1 and won the next three games to take the series 4–3. This is the only time a team has overcome a 3–1 deficit in the Finals, so such a comeback has indeed happened.

The U.S. $2 note was never discontinued; the Bureau of Engraving and Printing produces it periodically when the Federal Reserve orders more. Print runs occurred in the 2000s and again for Series 2013 and Series 2017, so the note was still being produced (or available to be produced) in 2018.

Craftsman is well-known for offering a full lifetime warranty on many of its hand tools (wrenches, screwdrivers, sockets, etc.). However, other Craftsman product lines—such as power tools, lawn-and-garden equipment, air compressors, electronics, and storage boxes—carry limited or fixed-term warranties rather than lifetime coverage. Therefore, it is not true that every Craftsman tool is backed by a lifetime warranty.

The user is referring to the series “Cobra Kai.” YouTube Premium officially renewed Cobra Kai for a second season shortly after the first season premiered in 2018, and Season 2 was subsequently released in April 2019. Therefore, the correct answer is that a Season 2 does (or did) exist.

Zürich Airport (Flughafen Zürich) is directly served by the Zürich Flughafen railway station, located beneath the airport terminal complex, providing frequent intercity and regional train connections.

Lake Ontario is the last lake in the Great Lakes–St. Lawrence system. Its outlet is the St. Lawrence River, which flows northeast and empties directly into the Gulf of St. Lawrence and then the Atlantic Ocean. Therefore, Lake Ontario is hydrologically connected to the Atlantic Ocean.

Only three movies in The Divergent Series were actually produced and released (Divergent, Insurgent, Allegiant). A planned fourth film, tentatively titled Ascendant, was cancelled and never made. Therefore, no fourth Divergent film exists.

Since 1946, the Bank of England has been wholly owned by the UK government, making it a public institution rather than a privately-owned company. It operates with operational independence but is legally an emanation of the state, not a private corporation.

answer: Yes, both second and third place contestants receive prize money (about $100,000 and $85,000 respectively).

While the champion receives the grand prize (typically $1 million), the runner-up and third-place finisher still receive guaranteed payouts from CBS. For most seasons the second-place contestant is paid about $100,000 and the third-place contestant around $85,000, with smaller amounts given to all remaining jury and pre-jury players. Therefore, both second and third place do receive money, just less than the winner.
Answer: Yes, both second and third place contestants receive prize money (about $100,000 and $85,000 respectively).

Reasoning: Both the 1962 original and the 1991 remake of Cape Fear are adaptations of John D. MacDonald’s 1957 novel “The Executioners.” The characters and events—ex-convict Max Cady stalking lawyer Sam Bowden and his family—are products of that fiction, not a dramatization of real‐world incidents. No evidence links the plot to any specific true story.

Quartz cuvettes have a broad transmission window that extends from the ultraviolet region (~190 nm) through the entire visible range and into the near-infrared. Because they do not absorb significantly in the visible wavelengths (≈400-700 nm), they are routinely used for visible-range spectroscopic measurements.

For a Student’s t-distribution with ν degrees of freedom, Var(T) = ν / (ν − 2) when ν > 2 (it is infinite or undefined for ν ≤ 2). The standard deviation is therefore √[ν / (ν − 2)], which is greater than 1 for any finite ν > 2 and not defined for smaller ν. It approaches 1 only in the limit as ν → ∞ (where the t becomes the standard normal). Hence, a t-distribution does not generally have a standard deviation of 1.

Himalayan pink salt is simply naturally mineral-colored sodium chloride, used like table or cooking salt. Curing salt (e.g., Prague Powder) is a blend of regular salt plus added sodium nitrite and/or nitrate, dyed pink so it is not mistaken for table salt. Because curing salt contains these curing agents and Himalayan pink salt does not, they are not the same product.

Scottish banknotes – including the £1 note – are promissory notes issued by Scottish banks. Under UK law, no Scottish banknote is classed as “legal tender,” even in Scotland; only coins (and, in England and Wales, Bank of England notes) have that status. So, strictly speaking, a Scottish £1 note is not and never has been legal tender, though it can still be accepted as lawful currency if a seller agrees.

Although the first-generation iPhone SE (2016) has a body that looks very similar to the earlier iPhone 5/5s, its internal hardware (processor, camera, battery, connectivity, etc.) is significantly upgraded and different. Therefore, they are not the same device.

Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother (often called the Queen Mum) purchased the derelict Barrogill Castle in Caithness, Scotland, in 1952 and restored it, renaming it the Castle of Mey. Therefore she did indeed buy a castle in Scotland.
New York City (often simply called New York) is a municipality located within the U.S. state of New York, so it is indeed a city in New York.

Only one film adaptation of the Lorien Legacies series, “I Am Number Four” (2011), was produced. Although sequels were planned, the studio cancelled them due to the first movie’s modest box-office performance. Therefore, there are currently no additional movies that follow it.
“Mine Would Be You” is performed by Blake Shelton, but the songwriting credits belong to Jessi Alexander, Connie Harrington, and Deric Ruttan—not to Blake Shelton himself.

Elmer’s standard white “Glue-All” is formulated primarily from polyvinyl acetate emulsion (along with water and small amounts of additives). Polyvinyl acetate-based adhesives are commonly referred to as PVA glues, so Glue-All fits this category.

The ‘original members’ generally refers to the founding lineup from the mid-1960s: Ronnie Van Zant, Gary Rossington, Allen Collins, Larry Junstrom, and Bob Burns. Ronnie Van Zant died in 1977, Allen Collins in 1990, Bob Burns in 2015, Larry Junstrom in 2019, and the last surviving founder, Gary Rossington, died in March 2023. Therefore, all of the original members have now passed away.

A rare developmental abnormality called fetus-in-fetu has been documented in which one twin becomes enveloped by the other during early pregnancy, resulting in a malformed ‘parasitic’ twin living inside its sibling’s body. Fewer than one in half-a-million births are affected, but the medical literature confirms that it can occur.

While the vast majority of people experience only local pain and swelling, a small percentage are allergic to bee venom and can develop anaphylactic shock, which can be fatal without prompt treatment. Multiple stings can also inject enough venom to be lethal even to non-allergic individuals.

Bensons for Beds and Harveys (the furniture/sofa retailer) are two separate retail brands. While they have at times shared the same parent ownership (most recently under Steinhoff’s Blue Group before going into administration in 2020), they operate as distinct companies with different product ranges and branding. Therefore, they are not the same company, even though they have been sister companies under a common owner.

Mercury travels around the Sun in an elliptical orbit, so its distance continually changes between perihelion and aphelion during each 88-day revolution. In addition, gravitational perturbations and relativistic effects cause its orbital parameters (e.g., perihelion position) to shift slowly over the years. Therefore, Mercury does not remain at a single, fixed distance from the Sun year after year.

After Wrath of the Titans (2012) there were early discussions about a third installment, sometimes referred to as Clash/Wrath of the Titans 3. However, the project never advanced beyond preliminary development and Warner Bros. ultimately shelved it. No sequel has been green-lit or put into production since, and the series is considered dormant.

Social science is an umbrella term for the academic disciplines that study society—such as sociology, economics, political science, anthropology, psychology, etc.—usually undertaken at the university/research level. Social studies, in contrast, is a school curriculum area (especially in K-12) that integrates several social science fields along with history, civics, geography and sometimes elements of the humanities to promote civic competence. Because social studies is an applied, instructional blend rather than a distinct scholarly discipline, the two terms are related but not the same.

The 2015 Christian drama “War Room,” directed by Alex and Stephen Kendrick, is an original fictional narrative. While the Kendricks were inspired by real-life ‘prayer warriors’ and the personal practice of setting aside a closet for prayer, the plot and characters (e.g., Elizabeth, Tony, and Miss Clara) are not depictions of specific real people or events. Therefore the film is not ‘based on a true story’ in the usual sense; it is a work of fiction with thematic inspiration drawn from real practices.

The Washington National Cathedral—formally the Cathedral Church of Saint Peter and Saint Paul—is part of the Episcopal Church, which is in the Anglican Communion. It is therefore Protestant, not Roman Catholic.

The soft tissue lining the inside of the cheeks is called the buccal mucosa. Gums (gingiva) are the tissue that surrounds the base of the teeth and covers the alveolar bone, not the inner cheek lining.
The Sea of Galilee, despite its name, is actually a freshwater lake fed mainly by the Jordan River. It lacks the high salinity characteristic of saltwater bodies like oceans or the nearby Dead Sea.

The date of Father’s Day varies by country. In the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada and many other countries it is observed on the third Sunday in June, not the first Sunday in September. Only a few countries such as Australia, New Zealand, Fiji and Papua New Guinea celebrate Father’s Day on the first Sunday in September. Since the question is asked generally without specifying a country, the most common global answer is that Father’s Day is not on the first Sunday in September.

The 2011 film “We Bought a Zoo” was adapted from Benjamin Mee’s memoir of the same name, which recounts his real-life purchase and rehabilitation of the Dartmoor Zoological Park in England. While the movie fictionalizes and relocates some details, its core premise and main characters come from Mee’s true story.

The attraction called “The Walking Dead: The Ride” at Thorpe Park (formerly ‘X:\ No Way Out’ and later ‘X’) is an indoor steel roller coaster manufactured by Vekoma and classified as a roller coaster in park documentation and industry databases.

An induction machine is electrically symmetrical; if its rotor is driven by a prime mover slightly above synchronous speed, the slip becomes negative, the air-gap flux leads the stator voltage, and the machine delivers active power back to the supply. It therefore operates as an induction generator provided it is supplied with reactive power from the grid or capacitors. This is a well-established mode of operation (e.g., wind turbines, small hydro).

Harry Potter and the Cursed Child was written as a stage play, not a narrative novel, but its complete rehearsal script was published in book form in 2016 (and a revised script in 2017). Therefore, while there is no traditional novel, there is indeed a book—the published script—that readers can buy.

In honey bees, workers have barbed stingers that lodge in the thick skin of mammals, so when they pull away the stinger tears out and the worker dies. A queen’s stinger is smooth, allowing her to sting—usually other queens within the hive—without the stinger getting stuck, so she can survive and sting again.

Natural gas and oil are both fossil fuels formed from ancient organic matter, but they differ in physical state and chemical composition. Natural gas is primarily methane and exists as a gas under normal surface conditions, while oil (crude petroleum) is a liquid mixture of longer-chain hydrocarbons. Therefore, they are distinct substances.

The Larry O’Brien Championship Trophy that is presented to the NBA Finals winner is not a traveling trophy; the victorious team keeps it permanently. Therefore the league commissions a brand-new Larry O’Brien Trophy each season to award to that year’s champion.

Musician’s Friend was acquired by Guitar Center in 2000 and now operates as a wholly-owned subsidiary. Although they maintain separate brand names and websites, they are part of the same corporate organization under Guitar Center Holdings.

In the Justice League film released by Warner Bros./DC (both the 2017 theatrical cut and Zack Snyder’s 2021 director’s cut), Superman does appear alongside Batman, Wonder Woman, Aquaman, Flash and Cyborg. Because Superman is a core member of the Justice League in DC canon and marketing for the movie has confirmed his presence, the correct answer is that he is in the film.

All parts of lily-of-the-valley (Convallaria majalis) contain cardiac glycosides such as convallatoxin, which can cause nausea, vomiting, arrhythmias and other toxic effects if ingested. Therefore the plant is considered poisonous to humans and many animals.
The CW television series ‘The Flash’ premiered its fifth season on October 9, 2018 and concluded in May 2019. Therefore, Season 5 has already been released.

Lymphoma is a malignant tumor of lymphocytes, and it usually arises within lymph nodes or other lymphatic tissues. Because it originates in and primarily affects lymph nodes, it is commonly referred to as “lymph node cancer.” Therefore, in general usage, lymphoma and lymph node cancer refer to the same disease entity.
The television series Grey's Anatomy has been renewed and produced for many seasons. Season 14 aired on ABC from 2017 to 2018, so such a season definitely exists.

A shear wall is designed primarily to resist lateral (in-plane) loads such as wind or seismic forces, but in almost all practical building systems it is also part of the gravity-load-carrying structure. Because it supports both its own weight and, typically, portions of the floor and roof loads above it, it is classified structurally as a load-bearing wall.

answer: Yes, but only in the 1978 reunion movie; in the original series they did not.
Reasoning: In the 1964-67 sitcom “Gilligan’s Island” the castaways were never rescued—the final televised episode still has them stranded. However, in the later 1978 reunion movie “Rescue from Gilligan’s Island,” the characters are finally picked up and make it back to civilization (though subsequent movies maroon them again). So within the original series the answer is no, but in the later TV-movie continuity they do escape.
Answer: Yes, but only in the 1978 reunion movie; in the original series they did not.

Reasoning: Interpreting “the World Cup” in the most common current-events sense—the 2022 FIFA men’s World Cup—South Africa’s national soccer team (Bafana Bafana) was eliminated in the CAF qualifying group stage (losing out to Ghana in Nov 2021). Therefore they did not book a place at that tournament. (They last appeared in 2010 as hosts.) If another sport were meant, the answer could differ, but for the most typical reading the answer is no.

Milan is certainly regarded as one of the world’s key fashion capitals (alongside Paris, New York, and London), but no single city is universally accepted as ‘the’ fashion capital. Many rankings and experts still give the prime title to Paris. Therefore the statement that Milan is the fashion capital of the world is not strictly correct.

By rule, the Kentucky Derby is restricted to 3-year-old Thoroughbreds. A horse is only eligible for the race in its three-year-old season, so it can start in the Derby only once. Therefore no horse can run, much less win, the Kentucky Derby twice.

A ribeye steak is a clearly defined cut taken from the rib section of the cow. “Delmonico steak,” however, is a historic restaurant term with no single, industry-standard definition; depending on butcher or region it has been used for ribeye, strip, or other thick-cut steaks. Because ‘Delmonico’ can refer to several different cuts while ribeye always refers to one specific cut, the two terms are not inherently the same, even if ribeye is sometimes marketed as Delmonico.

When an ocean or lake wave becomes too steep it breaks, plunging forward and entraining air and surrounding water. This process injects energy into the upper layer, creating strong, chaotic, swirling motion—i.e., turbulence. Therefore, breaking waves are a primary source of turbulent water in the surf zone.

Geographically, the “Outer Banks” usually denotes the chain of barrier islands that stretches along the North Carolina coast from the Virginia line southward to Cape Lookout. Cape Lookout sits on the southern end of the Core Banks and marks the southern tip of that barrier-island chain, so by most geographic and tourism definitions it is included within the Outer Banks, even though some colloquial uses restrict “OBX” to the more northerly islands.

Several U.S. states (e.g., Colorado, Iowa, Texas, and a handful of others) still allow or recognize common-law marriages formed under their statutes, and the federal government recognizes such marriages if they are valid in the state where they were entered. Therefore, while not universally available in every state, common-law marriage is legally recognized within the United States where state law permits it.

A Bachelor of Education (B.Ed.) is classified at the bachelor’s level and, in most educational systems, bachelor’s degrees are considered undergraduate degrees. Although some countries structure the B.Ed. as a subsequent professional program taken after another bachelor’s degree, the qualification itself is still at the undergraduate (bachelor) level rather than graduate (master’s) level.

In the United States, every state (and the District of Columbia) has enacted some form of Good Samaritan statute that offers at least limited liability protection to laypersons who voluntarily render emergency aid. While the scope and specific protections vary by jurisdiction—and specialized ‘overdose Good Samaritan’ laws do not yet cover every state—the basic, general Good Samaritan protections exist nationwide.

‘Danger Zone’ (often referred to by its lyric “Highway to the Danger Zone”) was composed by Giorgio Moroder with lyrics by Tom Whitlock specifically for the 1986 film ‘Top Gun’ and recorded by Kenny Loggins for the movie’s soundtrack.

A 52-year-old woman is usually perimenopausal or post-menopausal, so natural ovulation is very infrequent or has stopped. Therefore natural conception is extremely rare, but it is still biologically possible if she has not completely gone through menopause. In addition, pregnancy is possible with assisted reproduction, especially with donor eggs. Hence, while the odds are very low without medical help, it is not absolutely impossible to become pregnant at 52.

Kingda Ka holds the record for the tallest roller coaster in the world (456 ft) and is among the fastest, but other coasters surpass it in overall length and track size (e.g., Steel Dragon 2000 is the longest). Because “biggest” is usually interpreted as the largest in every respect, saying Kingda Ka is the biggest is not strictly correct.

The original Mason–Dixon Line, surveyed in the 1760s, marks the boundaries between Pennsylvania and Maryland and part of the boundary involving Delaware and West Virginia. It does not cross the state of New Jersey.

Great Britain is the geographic island comprising England, Scotland and Wales. The Channel Islands (Jersey, Guernsey, etc.) are separate Crown Dependencies and are neither part of that island nor constitutionally part of the United Kingdom.

The question refers to the pop group Frankie Valli & The Four Seasons. Of the four classic/original members (Frankie Valli, Bob Gaudio, Tommy DeVito, Nick Massi), Nick Massi died in 2000 and Tommy DeVito died in 2020, while Frankie Valli and Bob Gaudio are still alive. Because at least two original members are deceased, it is not true that all members are still alive.

Allergic reactions can develop to virtually any food protein. Although rare compared with common food allergies (e.g., peanuts, shellfish), IgE-mediated allergy to garlic has been documented in the medical literature, causing symptoms such as contact dermatitis, rhinitis, asthma, or gastrointestinal distress after ingestion or handling of garlic.

The Israeli series ‘Fauda’ was renewed, filmed, and Season 3 premiered on Israeli television in December 2019 and was later released internationally on Netflix in 2020. Therefore, a third season not only was planned but has already been released.

Lightning is produced by electrical discharge within or between clouds and the ground. While this usually occurs in cumulonimbus (thunderstorm) clouds that also contain precipitation, the rain does not always reach the ground—especially in dry thunderstorms where rain evaporates before hitting the surface. Lightning can also accompany volcanic eruptions or snowstorms without rainfall at the observer’s location. Therefore, lightning can occur without observed rain.

Under the current IFAB Laws of the Game (changed for the 2016/17 season), the ball is in play once it is kicked and clearly moves; it may be played in any direction, including backward. The earlier requirement that the first touch had to send the ball forward was removed. Therefore a kick-off no longer has to go forward.

Mission San Luis Rey de Francia was founded as a Spanish mission in 1798. Before that date the site was simply indigenous Luiseño territory, and after secularization in the 1830s it was used for other purposes (ranch, military post, seminary) before being restored to the Church. Therefore, it has not been a mission for its entire history.

Universal health care is a goal—everyone is covered—while socialized medicine is a specific model in which the government owns the clinics/hospitals and employs the providers. A country can have universal coverage without having government-owned facilities (e.g., single-payer systems that reimburse private doctors), and conversely a socialized system is just one way to reach universality. Therefore, they are not the same.
The NFL’s Chargers franchise moved from San Diego to Los Angeles in 2017 and now plays its home games at SoFi Stadium in Inglewood, California. Therefore, they no longer play in San Diego.

In accounting, the terms “profit and loss (P&L) statement” and “income statement” are used interchangeably. Both summarize revenues, expenses, and resulting net profit or loss over a specific period. Although some organizations might have minor formatting or naming preferences, conceptually they refer to the same financial report.

Under the U.S. system, federal courts are courts of limited jurisdiction, but Congress has granted them authority to hear state-law claims in several situations. The two most common are (1) diversity jurisdiction, where the parties are citizens of different states and the amount in controversy exceeds $75,000, and (2) supplemental (pendent) jurisdiction, where the state-law claim is part of the same case or controversy as a federal claim already properly before the court. Therefore, while not every state-law case can be brought in federal court, federal courts can and do hear many state-law causes of action when one of these jurisdictional bases exists.

Mineral oil is a broad class of petroleum-derived oils used for many purposes (lubrication, cosmetics, etc.). Hydraulic oil is a functional category of fluid formulated for hydraulic systems; while many hydraulic fluids are mineral-oil based, there are also synthetic, water-glycol, and other types. Likewise, most mineral oils are not suitable hydraulic fluids without specific additives. Therefore they are not inherently the same thing.

In most culinary contexts (especially in the UK and much of Europe) “elderflower cordial” refers to a non-alcoholic, concentrated, sweet elderflower extract that is diluted with water or other liquids before drinking. That product is essentially a flavored syrup; many recipes and commercial producers use the terms “elderflower cordial” and “elderflower syrup” interchangeably. Although the word “cordial” can sometimes mean an alcoholic liqueur (particularly in North America), when people speak of elderflower cordial they almost always mean the same non-alcoholic syrup used for drinks, desserts, etc.

Abu Dhabi and Dubai are two separate emirates (and cities) within the United Arab Emirates. Each has its own government, geography, and characteristics—Abu Dhabi is the federal capital of the UAE, while Dubai is a neighboring emirate known for its commercial and tourism hubs. Hence, they are not the same place.

The Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) is an aspirational, non-binding document. While the United States complies with many of its principles through the Constitution and various federal and state laws, it does not fully implement or respect all UDHR articles in practice. Examples include retaining the death penalty (in tension with Article 5’s ban on ‘cruel, inhuman or degrading punishment’), gaps in economic and social rights such as universal healthcare (Articles 22-25), and documented issues in areas like racial discrimination, immigration detention, and privacy. The U.S. has also not ratified several binding treaties that elaborate UDHR rights, such as the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights. Therefore, it cannot be said that the United States fully “follows” the UDHR.

Scientific surveys and satellite/drifter data have documented a large accumulation zone of floating plastic debris in the North Pacific subtropical gyre, commonly called the Great Pacific Garbage Patch. While not a solid island, it is a region with a markedly higher concentration of plastics and other trash than surrounding waters, confirming that such a ‘garbage patch’ exists.

In most poker games (e.g., No-Limit or Pot-Limit Texas Hold’em) the rule is that a raise must increase the bet by at least the size of the previous bet or raise. That means if someone has bet $10, the smallest legal raise is to $20 total—an additional $10, not necessarily a full ‘double’ each time. You may raise more than the minimum, but you are not obligated to keep doubling the total amount with every raise.

In the average adult human, fingertip-to-fingertip arm span is roughly the same as standing height, which is why artists (e.g., da Vinci’s Vitruvian Man) use it as a proportional guideline. However, there is wide normal variation—many people have arm spans a few centimeters longer or shorter than their height. Since the statement implies an exact one-to-one rule for everyone, it is not strictly true.

Yes. On the U.S. version of “Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,” multiple contestants have reached the top prize—beginning with John Carpenter in 1999—and many others have done so in international versions as well. Therefore, at least one person has definitely won the million-dollar (or local-currency equivalent) jackpot.

Whether an employee is legally entitled to paid maternity leave depends on the jurisdiction. Many countries (e.g., most of Europe, Canada) mandate some form of paid leave, but others (notably the United States at the federal level) do not require employers to provide paid maternity leave—only unpaid leave under the FMLA. Therefore, it is not universally true that the law guarantees paid maternity leave.

The 2017 film “Roman J. Israel, Esq.” was an original story written and directed by Dan Gilroy. While the character and narrative may draw thematic inspiration from real‐world social-justice lawyers, the movie is not a biographical account of any actual person or event; it is a fictional work.

In standard materials science, scratching is defined as one material plastically deforming or cutting the surface of another. This requires the scratching material to be at least as hard as, and typically harder than, the material being scratched. Therefore, a material that is softer on the Mohs or similar hardness scale cannot on its own scratch a harder material.

The 2018 game “A Way Out,” developed by Hazelight Studios, was designed explicitly for two-player cooperative play and cannot be played with just one player. It requires either local split-screen or online co-op with a second player.

The TV series “Once Upon a Time” concluded with Season 7, which aired its final episode in May 2018. Since then, ABC has not renewed the show and there have been no official announcements of an additional season. Therefore, there is currently no new season in production or airing.

Mother’s Day, or an equivalent holiday honouring mothers, is observed in many parts of the world (e.g., UK, Canada, Australia, most of Europe, much of Latin America, parts of Asia and Africa), though dates and customs vary. Therefore, the concept is not unique to one country.

Hellmann’s and Best Foods originated as two regional mayonnaise companies (Hellmann’s in the East, Best Foods in the West). Best Foods bought Hellmann’s in 1927, and today both are simply brand names owned by the same parent (currently Unilever). The recipes are essentially identical, with labeling differing by U.S. region. Thus, in corporate terms they are the same entity/under the same ownership.

There is indeed a recognized spin-off series of Breaking Bad titled “Better Call Saul,” which focuses on the character Saul Goodman/Jimmy McGill. This series is widely acknowledged as a direct spin-off (and prequel) to Breaking Bad, so the correct yes/no evaluation of the question is affirmative.

Chinua Achebe’s novel “Things Fall Apart” is a work of fiction. While it draws on real Igbo cultural practices and the broad historical reality of British colonial intrusion into Nigeria at the end of the 19th century, the characters (e.g., Okonkwo) and specific plot events are invented by Achebe, not based on an actual documented individual or true story.
The Phoenix Suns have reached the NBA Finals three times (1976, 1993, and 2021) but lost each series, so they have never secured an NBA championship.
South Africa recognises 11 official languages in its constitution, and English is included among them. Although it is not the only official language, it does hold official-language status.

In nearly every U.S. jurisdiction (and in many other countries with similar systems), admission to the bar—and thus the legal right to practice law—requires passing that jurisdiction’s bar examination. Although a handful of narrow exceptions exist (e.g., Wisconsin’s diploma privilege or limited-scope practice rules for in-house counsel licensed elsewhere), the general rule is that you must first take and pass the bar exam to practice law.

The 16-ounce red plastic cup made by the Solo Cup Company was developed and introduced in the early-to-mid 1970s. Because these cups were already on the market in the 1970s, they were certainly available by 1982.

The cartridge that Colt introduced in 1872 is officially designated .45 Colt by SAAMI and industry standards. Shooters began informally calling it the ".45 Long Colt" in the late 19th century to distinguish it from the shorter .45 Schofield (sometimes called the .45 Short Colt). Dimensionally and ballistically, the rounds labeled ".45 Colt" and ".45 Long Colt" today are identical; there is no separate, longer cartridge officially recognized. Therefore, the two names refer to the same cartridge.

In most U.S. states and many other jurisdictions, the credential issued to beginner drivers is referred to interchangeably as a “learner’s permit,” “instruction permit,” or “learner’s license.” All denote the same restricted license that allows supervised driving practice before obtaining a full driver’s license. While a few places may use slightly different terminology, the underlying document and its purpose are effectively identical, so the terms are generally considered the same.

In the FIFA World Cup, the two losing semifinalists play a third-place playoff. The winner of that match is officially awarded third place and receives bronze medals, just as the runners-up get silver and the champions gold. Therefore, third place does receive medals.

Natural gas and crude oil are both fossil fuels formed from ancient organic matter, but they differ in chemical composition, physical state, methods of extraction, and typical uses. Natural gas is primarily methane and exists as a gaseous hydrocarbon mixture at standard conditions, whereas crude oil is a liquid mixture of heavier hydrocarbons. Because of these clear distinctions, they are not the same substance.

In Marvel Comics, both the X-Men and the Avengers operate on the same primary continuity (Earth-616), frequently interacting in shared story lines. Although the film rights were historically split (X-Men at Fox, Avengers in the MCU) and therefore separate on screen until Disney’s acquisition of Fox, within the core Marvel comic universe they are part of the same world.

In France there is an established holiday called “Fête des Pères,” observed since the mid-20th century. It is held each year on the third Sunday in June (unless that conflicts with Pentecost in which case the date may shift). Therefore Fathers’ Day is indeed celebrated in France.
Raiders of the Lost Ark is the first film in the Indiana Jones series, and the character Indiana Jones (portrayed by Harrison Ford) is the central protagonist, so he indeed has a role in the movie.

Over seventy years of separate political, social, and media environments have caused the Korean language to develop noticeable pronunciation and vocabulary differences in the North and the South. Linguists generally describe the standard speech of Pyongyang (North Korea) and Seoul (South Korea) as distinct accents/dialects.

The Cleveland Cavaliers and the Golden State Warriors met in four consecutive NBA Finals from 2015–2018. Golden State won in 2015, 2017, and 2018. Cleveland won the 2016 NBA Finals, defeating Golden State 4–3 after coming back from a 3–1 series deficit. Therefore, Cleveland has beaten Golden State in the Finals at least once.

In gardening literature the variegated form of Aegopodium podagraria is commonly sold under several interchangeable common names, including “bishop’s-weed,” “gout-weed,” and “snow-on-the-mountain.”  Although another plant (Euphorbia marginata) sometimes shares the name “snow-on-the-mountain,” when people refer to an aggressive, variegated ground-cover in shady gardens they are talking about Aegopodium podagraria—the same species called bishop’s weed.
Grey’s Anatomy, the long-running medical drama created by Shonda Rhimes, was renewed for and aired a 14th season during the 2017-2018 television year. Therefore, Season 14 definitely exists.

The movie and book “Soul Surfer” recount the real-life experience of professional surfer Bethany Hamilton, who lost her arm in a 2003 shark attack and returned to competitive surfing, so it is indeed based on actual events.

Although Sri Lanka does not share a land border with India, it lies immediately to India’s south across the narrow Palk Strait and is commonly referred to in geography and international relations as one of India’s neighbouring countries.

Multiple contestants across various international versions—including John Carpenter in the U.S. (1999) and Judith Keppel in the U.K. (2000)—have indeed taken home the top £1 million/$1 million prize, proving it has been won before.

Mark Ruffalo has played Bruce Banner/The Hulk in several Marvel Cinematic Universe ensemble films (e.g., The Avengers, Thor: Ragnarok), but no standalone Hulk film has starred him. The only modern Hulk-titled features are Hulk (2003) with Eric Bana and The Incredible Hulk (2008) with Edward Norton.

The cartridges are dimensionally similar and often interchangeable, but they were developed to different specifications. 7.62×51 mm NATO brass is usually thicker and its official maximum pressure is lower, while commercial .308 Winchester is loaded to higher pressures and has slightly different chamber tolerances. Because of these differences, they are considered distinct rounds even though many rifles can fire both.

Interpreting “this year” as the current calendar year, 2024. Disney/Lucasfilm’s theatrical release schedule lists no Star Wars feature film for 2024; the next planned movie is slated for 2026, with others penciled in for 2027-2028. 2024 does include Star Wars streaming series (e.g., The Acolyte, Skeleton Crew) but no movie. Therefore, the answer is No/False.

Tartar sauce is a condiment made from mayonnaise, pickles, capers, herbs, etc., served with seafood. Cream of tartar is a dry, acidic powder (potassium bitartrate) used in baking to stabilize egg whites or prevent sugar crystallization. They have different ingredients, purposes, and forms, so they are not the same.

For the FIFA World Cup, only two official trophies have existed: the Jules Rimet Trophy (1930-1970) and the current FIFA World Cup Trophy (used since 1974). The same physical trophy is presented at every tournament, then returned to FIFA; the winning team keeps only a replica. Therefore, a brand-new trophy is not made for each World Cup.

NASA’s Voyager 2 spacecraft performed a close fly-by of Neptune and its moons in 1989, becoming the first (and so far only) robotic probe to visit the planet. No landers or orbiters have been sent, but Voyager 2’s fly-by means at least one robotic spacecraft has indeed reached Neptune’s vicinity.

Lightning is produced by electrical charge separation in clouds. Although thunderstorms often bring rain, the rain can evaporate before reaching the ground or be falling far from the observer. ‘Dry’ thunderstorms and distant cloud-to-ground or cloud-to-cloud flashes show that lightning can occur even when no rain is observed at ground level.

A dishwasher is normally plumbed to the home’s hot-water line; it does not generate all of its own hot water from a cold supply. Most models do contain an internal heating element that can boost the incoming water temperature or heat the final rinse, but this is supplemental. Therefore the dishwasher itself doesn’t independently ‘make’ its hot water—it relies primarily on the household hot-water heater.

The television series 'The Game' was developed by Mara Brock Akil as a direct spin-off of her earlier sitcom 'Girlfriends'; it introduced characters first appearing in 'Girlfriends' before launching as its own show.

The term “chickpea” is the English common name for the legume Cicer arietinum, while “garbanzo bean” is the Spanish-derived name for exactly the same species. They refer to the same plant and the same edible seed.

A tongue that has been deliberately or accidentally split can usually be repaired surgically. An oral or plastic surgeon can freshen the cut edges, suture the two halves together, and the tissue will generally heal as one piece again. Results depend on factors such as how long ago the split was made, scarring, the amount of tissue lost, and postoperative care, but in principle the procedure is feasible and commonly performed for people who wish to reverse a tongue-split body modification.

The animated series "Steven Universe" was renewed beyond its fourth season; Cartoon Network officially confirmed and released a fifth season, which ultimately served as the show’s final full season (airing 2017–2019). Therefore, the statement that there will be a season 5 is correct.

Under official World Pool-Billiard Association / BCA rules for 8-ball, when a player commits a standard foul (e.g., scratches the cue ball, fails to hit their own group first, drives no ball to a cushion, etc.) the opponent is awarded ball-in-hand and may place the cue ball anywhere on the table before the next shot. Therefore, the concept of ball-in-hand absolutely exists in 8-ball.

On Grey’s Anatomy, Jackson Avery and April Kepner divorce in Season 12. Although they briefly sleep together and have another child (Harriet), they never rekindle their romantic relationship long-term or remarry. April ultimately marries Matthew in Season 14, and Jackson pursues other relationships. Therefore, they do not truly get back together after the divorce.

During a cruise the inner ear adapts to the constant rocking motion of the ship. When you return to solid ground, that adaptation can temporarily persist, leading to a sensation of continued motion, dizziness, or mild nausea (sometimes called ‘land sickness’ or mal de débarquement). This is a common, usually short-lived reaction, so experiencing some motion-sickness-like symptoms after a cruise is considered normal.

answer: Yes, runs must all be in the same suit.
Reasoning: In gin rummy a meld can be either a set (three or four cards of the same rank in different suits) or a run/sequence. A run is defined as three or more consecutive cards in the SAME suit (e.g., 5♣-6♣-7♣). Therefore, for a run to be valid, all cards must share the suit.
Answer: Yes, runs must all be in the same suit.

Reasoning: In most jurisdictions you can visit a commercial shooting range, rent a firearm on-site, and shoot under staff supervision without holding a firearm licence; you usually only need government ID and to meet age/background requirements. A licence or permit is typically required only if you are bringing and shooting your own personally owned firearm. Because regulations differ by country and even by local area, there are exceptions, but the general rule is that no licence is needed just to go to a range and shoot rental guns.

The word “keg” is a generic term for any metal container used to hold draft beer; it comes in several standard sizes (eighth-barrel, quarter-barrel, half-barrel, etc.). A half-barrel (15.5 U.S. gallons) is just one of those sizes. Because it is the most common size, people often call a half-barrel simply “a keg,” but strictly speaking not every keg is a half-barrel, so they are not inherently the same thing.

In most English-speaking jurisdictions a person is free to style their surname as they wish, provided it is used consistently for legal and identification purposes. A double-barrelled surname can therefore be written either with a hyphen (e.g., Smith-Jones) or simply as two separate words (e.g., Smith Jones). The hyphen is a common convention but is not a legal requirement.

GDP per capita is calculated by dividing a country’s gross domestic product (the total value of all final goods and services produced) by its population. While this produces a figure that looks like an ‘average’ economic output per person, it is not the same as the average (mean or median) personal income people actually receive. GDP per capita includes corporate profits, government services, depreciation, and other components that do not flow directly to households, and it ignores how income is distributed among individuals. Therefore, equating GDP per capita with average income is incorrect.

In standard English, names of chemical elements are treated as common nouns, so they are written in lowercase within sentences (e.g., "oxygen," "gold," "einsteinium"). They are only capitalized at the beginning of a sentence or in a title-style heading, not because they are elements. Therefore, one should not routinely capitalize element names.

Humans are normally diphyodont: we develop one primary (baby) dentition and one permanent (adult) dentition. After the permanent teeth erupt, the body does not have the genetic programming to generate a complete third set. Although rare ‘super-numerary’ teeth or isolated replacement teeth can occur, a full third dentition does not naturally form. Any ‘third set’ would have to be artificial prosthetics or implants, not biologically grown replacement teeth.

Netflix officially renewed Marvel’s ‘The Punisher’ for a second season in December 2017, and that season was produced and released in January 2019. Therefore, a Season 2 has indeed been (or was going to be) made.

The CW series 'Riverdale' features characters such as Archie Andrews, Betty Cooper, Veronica Lodge, and Jughead Jones, all of whom originate from the long-running Archie Comics franchise. The show is an adaptation that reimagines these characters and their hometown in a darker, teen-drama style.

Rocky Balboa is a fictional character from the Rocky film series. The International Boxing Hall of Fame inducts real people—boxers, trainers, journalists, etc. While Sylvester Stallone (the actor/screenwriter who created and portrayed Rocky) was inducted in 2011 as an ‘Observer,’ the character Rocky Balboa himself has not been inducted.

“Alsatian” is simply the British name historically used for the breed that is internationally called the German Shepherd. No physical or genetic distinction exists between an Alsatian and a German Shepherd; they are the same breed of dog, just known by different names.
The Leaning Tower of Pisa is located in the city of Pisa, in the Tuscany region of Italy, not in Rome. Rome is a separate city located in the Lazio region.

“Gotham City” is the fictional home of Batman in DC Comics. While New York City is sometimes nick-named “Gotham,” there is no municipality officially named “Gotham City” anywhere in the state of New York or elsewhere in the United States. Therefore the statement that there is a real Gotham City in New York is incorrect.
In the history of Major League Baseball, the single-game record for home runs is four, accomplished by several players. No player has ever hit five home runs in one MLB game.

The egg tooth is the standard, temporary structure bird embryos develop on the tip of the bill specifically to pip (crack) the shell. It has been documented across all avian orders studied to date; no bird species is known to hatch without some form of egg-tooth or hatching tooth. After hatching, the structure is shed or absorbed within a few days. Hence, it is considered a universal feature of baby birds.

Douglas A. Munro, a Signalman First Class in the U.S. Coast Guard serving with a Navy landing force at Guadalcanal in 1942, was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor. He remains the only Coast Guardsman ever to receive the nation’s highest military decoration.

“Troy: Fall of a City” was co-produced by the BBC and Netflix. Outside the UK, Netflix holds the international streaming rights and lists it as a Netflix Original, so subscribers in most regions can watch it there (the main exception is the UK, where it streams on BBC iPlayer). Therefore, in general usage, the series is considered to be ‘on Netflix.’

“Visa Delta” was the original brand name used in the United Kingdom for Visa’s debit card product. In the late-1990s Visa dropped the Delta name and unified its branding worldwide under “Visa Debit.” Therefore a Visa Delta card is essentially a Visa Debit card; the name is just an earlier branding.

In U.K. immigration law, ‘right of abode’ is an absolute status held by British citizens and certain Commonwealth citizens. A person with right of abode is entirely free from immigration control: they may enter and live in the U.K. without any conditions and cannot be made subject to immigration restrictions.  ‘Indefinite leave to remain’ (ILR) is a permission granted under the Immigration Act 1971 that allows a non-citizen to live and work in the U.K. without a time limit, but the person remains subject to immigration control—for example, ILR can lapse after an absence of 2 years and the holder may need to apply for a returning-resident visa. Because ILR can be lost and does not give the same unconditional entry rights as right of abode, the two statuses are similar in effect (no time limit) but are legally distinct and not the same.

Verizon Communications Inc. is the parent corporation that offers a variety of services (wireline, fiber, enterprise solutions, etc.). Verizon Wireless (legally Cellco Partnership) is the mobile-network subsidiary of Verizon Communications. While Verizon Communications now owns 100 % of Verizon Wireless, they remain distinct legal entities (parent vs. subsidiary), so they are not literally the same company.

Wolf spiders (family Lycosidae) and grass spiders (genus Agelenopsis, family Agelenidae) belong to different taxonomic families. They differ in web-building behavior (grass spiders build sheet webs with funnel retreats, wolf spiders are active hunters that do not spin capture webs), eye arrangements, body shapes, and habits. Therefore, they are not the same type of spider.

Poison oak rash is an allergic contact dermatitis triggered by urushiol. Standard therapy for localized or moderately extensive rashes includes mid- to high-potency topical corticosteroids to reduce inflammation and itching. Triamcinolone acetonide 0.1 % cream/ointment is a medium-to-high potency corticosteroid that is routinely prescribed for this purpose and is generally effective when applied as directed (usually twice daily for 1-2 weeks). Therefore it is considered a good treatment option for poison oak, though very widespread or severe cases may require oral steroids.

Castling is legal provided all castling conditions are satisfied at the moment you try to castle: the king is not currently in check, the squares the king passes over and lands on are not attacked, and neither the king nor the chosen rook has moved before. A previous occurrence of check does not by itself revoke castling rights. Therefore, even if the king was checked earlier in the game, once the check has been resolved and the other conditions are met, castling is still allowed.

Under the NBA traveling rule a player is allowed to ‘gather’ the ball, then take up to two steps before they must pass, shoot, or stop. The gather is not counted as a step in the rule-book, so while it can look like three motions to casual viewers, the official allowance is still only two counted steps. Therefore you do not actually get three legal steps in the NBA.

The term “Blue Heeler” is an informal nickname for the Australian Cattle Dog that has the blue-mottled coat color. All Blue Heelers are Australian Cattle Dogs; the name just highlights the blue coloration. Therefore, they refer to the same breed (though ‘Blue Heeler’ excludes the red-speckled variety).

In transfusion medicine, the term “universal donor” refers to the red-blood-cell type that can be safely transfused to people of any ABO and Rh blood group. Because O-negative blood lacks A, B and Rh (D) antigens, it fits that definition. O-positive blood still carries the Rh (D) antigen, so it cannot be given to Rh-negative recipients without risking an immune reaction. Therefore, O-positive is not considered a universal donor type; only O-negative is.

Cabot Cove is widely known as the fictional hometown of Jessica Fletcher in the television series “Murder, She Wrote.” It was created for the show and no actual town or city by that name exists on the map of Maine.

For several centuries, beginning in the late 14th and early 15th centuries, the Ottoman Empire conquered and ruled most of the Balkan Peninsula—including present-day Greece, Bulgaria, Serbia, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Albania, North Macedonia, Montenegro, and parts of Romania and Croatia—until these territories gradually gained independence in the 19th and early 20th centuries. Thus, the Balkans (or large portions of them) were indeed part of the Ottoman Empire.

The MLB All-Star Game follows the standard Major League Baseball rules: if the score is tied after nine innings, play continues into extra innings to determine a winner (e.g., 2002, 2017, 2018 All-Star Games all went past nine). Therefore, the All-Star Game can and does go into extra innings when necessary.

A park called Six Flags New Orleans (formerly Jazzland) did exist, but it was permanently closed after being flooded by Hurricane Katrina in 2005 and has remained abandoned ever since. Therefore, there is no operating Six Flags park in New Orleans today.

In the film/novel "Gone Baby Gone," the investigation ultimately leads to discovering that the missing girl, Amanda McCready, is alive and being secretly raised in police captain Jack Doyle’s home. Thus, the child is indeed found by the end of the story.

Derek Shepherd, portrayed by Patrick Dempsey, is killed off in Season 11 of Grey's Anatomy after sustaining critical injuries from a car accident, confirming that the character dies within the series.

The sitcom is set in New York City, but nearly all principal photography took place on soundstages at 20th Century Fox Studios in Los Angeles. Only occasional exterior establishing shots were filmed in New York.

Under U.S. law (Military Selective Service Act), nearly all male citizens and male immigrants ages 18-25 must register with the Selective Service System. While there are narrow exemptions (e.g., certain visa holders, active-duty military, some disabled men), for the vast majority of men in that age range registration is legally required, so it is considered mandatory rather than voluntary.

During the 7 December 1941 attack, U.S. Army Air Forces fighters and naval/army anti-aircraft batteries managed to destroy several attacking aircraft. Official Japanese loss records list roughly 29 aircraft lost, virtually all to defensive fire. Therefore at least some Japanese planes were indeed shot down during the Pearl Harbor attack.

.380 ACP (Automatic Colt Pistol) was designed by John Browning in 1908. The designation ".380 Auto" is simply a shortened commercial name for the exact same 9×17 mm cartridge. There are no dimensional or pressure differences—manufacturers use the two terms interchangeably on ammunition boxes.

For people and other living beings we naturally use the word “birthday.” A company’s founding, however, is an event that occurred on a specific calendar date. Recurring observances of that date are technically anniversaries (e.g., “the 10-year anniversary of the company’s founding”). Although “birthday” is sometimes used informally, the precise, generally accepted term is “anniversary.”

AMC’s horror-anthology series ‘The Terror’ currently has two seasons: Season 1 (2018) that dramatizes the doomed Franklin Expedition, and Season 2, subtitled ‘Infamy’ (2019), set around Japanese-American internment camps. Therefore, it is not limited to a single season.

The television series “The Frankenstein Chronicles” is a work of historical fiction. While it incorporates real 19th-century settings and occasionally features historical figures (e.g., Mary Shelley, Sir Robert Peel), the plot—centered on re-animated corpses and a detective investigation—derives from Mary Shelley’s novel and is not drawn from an actual historical event. Therefore, it is not based on a true story, only loosely inspired by period history and literature.

Massachusetts follows the general U.S. rule that a driver may turn right after coming to a complete stop at a steady red light and yielding to pedestrians and cross-traffic, unless a posted sign specifically prohibits a right turn on red at that intersection.

Univision officially renewed the Spanish-language series “La Piloto” for a second season shortly after the first ended, and that second season was produced and aired in 2018. Therefore, there is (and has been) a season 2.

Because the Earth rotates from west to east, the apparent motion of the Sun is the same in both hemispheres: it rises roughly in the east and sets in the west (allowing for seasonal shifts toward northeast/southeast). Therefore, it does not rise in the west in the northern hemisphere.

E-ZPass is the electronic toll collection system used by a multi-state consortium covering most states in the U.S. Northeast, Midwest, and parts of the South. EZ TAG is the system operated by the Harris County Toll Road Authority (Houston area) and is part of the Texas toll network (interoperable with TxTag and NTTA’s TollTag). The two systems are run by different agencies, use different billing accounts, and—at present—transponders from one system are not accepted on the other’s toll roads. Therefore they are not the same, even though their names are similar.

The American game show Wheel of Fortune has been adapted in numerous countries, including the UK, Australia, Spain, Germany, France, Brazil, and many more, with localized hosts, languages, and prize structures. Therefore, there is indeed a version (or multiple versions) of Wheel of Fortune in other countries.

Credit-card networks allow “card-not-present” transactions (online, mail-order, phone, in-app, digital wallets). For those you type the PAN (the number) plus expiry date, CVV and billing ZIP; no physical plastic is required. Therefore, yes—you can legitimately use the account without having the physical card in hand (though doing so without the cardholder’s permission is illegal).

Guillermo del Toro and Vanessa Taylor wrote The Shape of Water as an original screenplay. A novelization co-written by del Toro and Daniel Kraus was published afterward, adapting the film’s story, not the other way around. Therefore the movie is not based on a pre-existing book.

In the history of the NCAA Division I men’s basketball tournament, a No. 16 seed has indeed defeated a No. 1 seed. The first occurrence was in 2018, when the University of Maryland–Baltimore County (UMBC) beat Virginia. It has since happened again (e.g., Fairleigh Dickinson over Purdue in 2023). Therefore, the correct response is that it has happened at least once.

“A Series of Unfortunate Events” is a children’s fiction series written by Daniel Handler under the pen name Lemony Snicket. The narrative is presented as though the author is documenting real tragedies that befell the Baudelaire orphans, but this framing is purely a literary device. There is no historical evidence or record that the events or characters actually existed; they were invented for the stories.

Research is the systematic investigation to establish facts and reach new conclusions, while the scientific method is the structured set of principles and procedures (problem definition, hypothesis formation, data collection, analysis, interpretation) used to carry out such investigations. In practice, most formal research in science and many social sciences is designed around the scientific method. Hence the two concepts are inherently connected: the scientific method provides the framework that guides research activities.

Both come from the short loin and have the characteristic T-shaped bone with strip steak on one side and tenderloin on the other. However, USDA definitions say a porterhouse must include a tenderloin section at least 1.25 in. wide, while a T-bone only needs 0.5 in. Thus a porterhouse is essentially a larger, rear-end cut with more filet, so the two are related but not the same.

Parcelforce Worldwide is a separate parcel-delivery arm within the Royal Mail Group. It operates under its own brand and service structure, focusing on express parcels, whereas Royal Mail handles the general postal service. They share ownership but they are not the same service.

King’s College London is an independent institution that is one of the constituent colleges of the University of London. It is distinct from the University of Cambridge, which has its own separate constituent college called King’s College, Cambridge. Therefore, King’s College London is not part of Cambridge University.

The Cold War (c. 1947-1991) was defined by geopolitical, ideological, and economic rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union. They formed opposing blocs (NATO vs. Warsaw Pact) and competed for global influence rather than cooperating militarily or politically. Although they were temporary allies during World War II, that alliance dissolved before the Cold War began.

Under Pennsylvania Liquor Code (Title 47), the minimum age to be employed in a licensed establishment to serve, sell, or dispense alcoholic beverages is 18. Therefore, an 18-year-old may work as a server or bartender of alcohol, provided any required Responsible Alcohol Management Program (RAMP) training is completed within the allotted time.

Many people experience a temporary sensation of rocking or swaying—sometimes called ‘land sickness’ or mal de débarquement—after disembarking from a cruise ship. This occurs because the brain and inner-ear balance system have adapted to the ship’s constant motion; once on stable ground, it can take hours to a few days for the vestibular system to readjust. Therefore, your equilibrium can indeed feel off after a cruise.

Adjusted gross income (AGI) is your gross income after certain above-the-line adjustments (such as student-loan interest or IRA contributions). Taxable income is calculated after AGI by subtracting either the standard deduction or itemized deductions (and any other allowable deductions) from AGI. Because taxable income is derived from AGI but includes further subtractions, the two figures are not the same.

At launch in 2014 the game required a monthly subscription, but in March 2015 Bethesda switched to a buy-to-play model called “The Elder Scrolls Online: Tamriel Unlimited.” Today you only need to purchase the base game (or play via services like Xbox/PC Game Pass); the ‘ESO Plus’ subscription that exists now is optional and just grants extras such as DLC access and bonus XP. Therefore a recurring monthly fee is not required to play.

In L. M. Montgomery’s Anne of Green Gables series, Anne Shirley and Gilbert Blythe progress from childhood rivals to close friends, become engaged in ‘Anne of the Island,’ marry in ‘Anne’s House of Dreams,’ and remain together throughout the later novels, eventually raising a family. Thus, they definitively end up together in the books.

An emulsion requires two (or more) liquids that are not mutually soluble so that separate phases exist and a surfactant can stabilise the dispersed droplets. Water and ethanol, however, are completely miscible in all proportions; they form a single homogeneous phase rather than two distinct phases. Because there is no interfacial boundary to stabilise, adding an emulsifier (surfactant) will not create or maintain dispersed droplets—the mixture will simply remain one uniform solution. Therefore an emulsion cannot be formed with only water, ethanol, and an emulsifier.

Although Net10 and TracFone are sister brands owned by the same parent company, the refill (air-time/service) cards are keyed to their specific brand databases. A TracFone handset will accept only TracFone-branded airtime or service plan PINs, while Net10 phones accept only Net10 cards. Therefore a Net10 card will not add airtime or service days to a TracFone account.

Los Lobos has been eligible for induction for many years (25 years after their first release in 1978) but, as of the most recent class announced by the Rock & Roll Hall of Fame, the band has never been inducted. They have appeared on some fan and critic short-lists but have not been selected for the Hall.

Internal energy of a system is the total microscopic energy contained within it, including both the kinetic energy of molecular motion and the potential energy arising from intermolecular forces. Potential energy, on the other hand, refers only to the energy associated with position or configuration (e.g., gravitational, electric, or intermolecular potential). Therefore, potential energy is just one component of internal energy, not the whole of it.

Stephen King wrote an official follow-up novel titled “Doctor Sleep,” published in 2013, which continues the story of Danny Torrance from “The Shining.” A film adaptation of “Doctor Sleep” was also released in 2019. Therefore, a genuine sequel to “The Shining” exists.

Coca tea is made from the raw leaves of the coca plant, which naturally contain cocaine alkaloids. Under the U.S. Controlled Substances Act, coca leaves (unless they have been ‘decocainized’) are Schedule II controlled substances. Importation, sale, or possession of products containing non-decocainized coca leaf—such as traditional coca tea—is therefore prohibited without specific DEA authorization. Although small quantities are sometimes brought in by travelers or sold online, they are subject to seizure and are not legally permitted.

Paget’s disease of the bone is a chronic, benign disorder of bone remodeling, not a malignant neoplasm. While a small percentage of patients may later develop osteosarcoma or other bone cancers, Paget’s disease itself is not classified as cancer.

Tornadoes are not restricted to the central United States; they can form wherever the necessary atmospheric conditions (instability, wind shear, and lift) exist. New York State averages several tornadoes each year, and even New York City has documented weak tornadoes on rare occasions. Therefore, it is indeed possible for a tornado to occur in New York.

Both soft drinks are made by the same parent company (originally Royal Crown/RC Cola), but they are distinct products. Diet Rite was introduced in 1958 as a standalone zero-calorie cola and today is marketed as a caffeine-free, sodium-free ‘Pure Zero’ line with several flavors. Diet RC is simply the diet (low/zero-calorie) version of RC Cola and still mirrors the taste profile and caffeine content of the original RC. Because they have different formulas, flavor profiles, and branding, Diet Rite and Diet RC are not the same beverage.

Although Switzerland is not a member of the EU, it has a bilateral Agreement on the Free Movement of Persons with the EU (and is part of the wider EFTA free-movement framework). This agreement grants EU citizens the right to enter, reside and work in Switzerland, subject mainly to registration formalities after three months and limited transitional quotas for a few newer member states. Therefore, Switzerland does allow the free movement of EU citizens in practice.

Some individuals exhibit a condition called heterochromia iridum in which the two irises differ in pigment, leading to visibly different eye colors. This can be congenital or acquired through injury, disease, or medication, so yes—it is biologically possible for a person to have two different colored eyes.

The EU Single Market also extends to the three EEA-EFTA countries (Norway, Iceland, Liechtenstein). Through the EEA Agreement, Norway adopts most EU single-market legislation and enjoys the four freedoms of movement. Therefore, Norway is considered part of the single market, even though it is not an EU member state.

The 2014 CW television series "Star-Crossed," created by Meredith Averill, was developed as an original concept for television about a romance between a human girl and an alien boy integrating into a high-school environment. There is no underlying novel or book series credited as its source material; press releases and production notes list it as an original series.

Although A23 and N batteries have somewhat similar lengths, they differ in diameter and—more importantly—in chemistry and voltage. An A23 (23AE, 8LR932) battery is an alkaline 12-volt battery made up of a stack of eight button cells and is about 10 mm in diameter. An N (LR1, E90) battery is a 1.5-volt single-cell alkaline battery roughly 12 mm in diameter. Because their sizes and electrical characteristics are different, they are not interchangeable.

answer: Yes – they are essentially the same mayonnaise sold under different brand names.
Reasoning: Hellmann’s and Best Foods are both mayonnaise brands owned by Unilever. They share the same recipe (aside from negligible regional tweaks) and are marketed as equivalents: Hellmann’s is sold east of the Rocky Mountains in the U.S., while Best Foods is sold west of them. Therefore, for practical purposes, they are the same product under different names.
Answer: Yes – they are essentially the same mayonnaise sold under different brand names.

Reasoning: TBS (Turner Broadcasting System) and TNT (Turner Network Television) are both networks that originated within Turner Broadcasting. Today they are part of the same corporate family under Warner Bros. Discovery (previously under WarnerMedia). Therefore, they share the same parent company.

answer: Yes. Each state is guaranteed at least one representative.
Reasoning: Under Article I, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution and subsequent apportionment acts, seats in the House of Representatives are allocated among the states according to population, but no state can be left without representation. Therefore, every state is guaranteed at least one seat in the House.
