Answer: Yes. Each state is guaranteed at least one representative.

Reasoning: In the A Song of Ice and Fire novels, George R. R. Martin created the lyrics to the fictional song “The Rains of Castamere.” The melody used in the television adaptation was composed later by Ramin Djawadi, but the question of who ‘wrote’ it generally refers to its original creation in the books, which is Martin’s work.

While several bank holidays—such as Christmas Day and Good Friday—are shared, Scotland also has holidays that England does not (e.g., 2 January, St Andrew’s Day) and England/Wales have some dates that fall differently or are absent in Scotland (e.g., the late-August bank holiday). Therefore the two nations do not have identical sets of bank holidays.

Reese's Peanut Butter Cups are specifically marketed and widely recognized for their peanut butter filling encased in chocolate. The product’s name, ingredients list, and consumer knowledge all confirm the presence of peanut butter.

By convention, electric current is defined as the flow of positive charge. In metallic conductors the actual mobile charges are electrons, which carry negative charge, so their motion is opposite to the defined direction of conventional current.

An ectopic pregnancy refers to implantation of a fertilized ovum outside the uterine cavity. While the vast majority occur in the fallopian tubes, rare ectopic implantations can take place in other sites, including the ovary. Ovarian ectopic pregnancies are uncommon but well-documented in obstetric literature.

Like most major touring acts, Panic! At The Disco usually brings one or more support artists who perform before the band’s own set. For example, the 2022 ‘Viva Las Vengeance’ tour listed MARINA and Jake Wesley Rogers as openers, while earlier tours featured acts such as Two Feet and Betty Who. The specific opener can change by tour or date, but in general they do have an opening act.
England’s men’s national soccer team won the FIFA World Cup once, in 1966 when they hosted the tournament. Therefore, the answer is yes.

Both are reusable adhesive putties used for mounting lightweight items, but Blu Tack is a specific Bostik-branded blue product, whereas White Tack is a similar white formulation sold by Bostik or other companies. They can differ slightly in composition, colour, and holding strength. Therefore, they are not literally the same product, even though they serve the same purpose.

A learner’s permit authorizes only limited, supervised driving and is legally classified as a provisional credential, not a full, unrestricted driver’s license. In most jurisdictions, when forms, insurance policies, or legal documents ask whether you have a driver’s license, they expect a regular (non-restricted) license; a learner’s permit does not satisfy that requirement.

The E! reality show ‘Total Bellas’ was renewed by the network after its third season; press releases and entertainment news outlets reported that Season 4 was officially ordered and scheduled to air (it ultimately premiered in early 2019). Therefore, the correct response to whether there will be a Season 4 is ‘yes’.

An "assault rifle" is generally defined (e.g., by the U.S. military/NATO) as a selective-fire rifle chambered for an intermediate-power cartridge (e.g., 5.56×45 mm). The original ArmaLite AR-10 is selective-fire but is chambered in the full-power 7.62×51 mm NATO cartridge, placing it in the “battle rifle” category rather than “assault rifle.” Civilian AR-10 style rifles are typically semi-automatic only, which also disqualifies them from the strict technical definition of an assault rifle.

The CW television series “The Carrie Diaries” aired two seasons (Season 1 in 2013 and Season 2 in 2013–2014). It was cancelled by the network in May 2014, and no third season was produced or released.

Across The Texas Chainsaw Massacre franchise there are several separate timelines and reboots. Although each film features a chainsaw-wielding killer nicknamed “Leatherface,” his back-story, real name (e.g., Bubba Sawyer in the original continuity vs. Thomas Brown Hewitt in the 2003 remake continuity), family members, and even personality traits differ, and he is played by different actors. Therefore the Leatherface seen from film to film is not literally the same character in a single continuous story; he is a re-imagined or alternate-timeline version.

In the United States (and in many other countries), there is generally no absolute federal or national ban on a 14-year-old handling or firing a firearm at a licensed range, provided a parent/guardian (or certified instructor acting with parental consent) is present and supervising. Most states and commercial ranges explicitly permit minors to shoot under direct adult supervision, though some ranges set their own higher minimum ages or require signed waivers. Because laws and range policies differ from place to place, a parent or guardian must verify local regulations and the specific range’s rules, but in most jurisdictions the practice is lawful with proper supervision.
Panama City Beach, Florida, is a coastal city located in the Florida Panhandle and its shoreline lies directly on the Gulf of Mexico.

Scotland is one of the four constituent countries that make up the United Kingdom. Although it is not a fully sovereign state (foreign affairs and some other powers are reserved to the UK Parliament), it is officially described and widely referred to as a ‘country’ in its own right within the UK framework, with its own legal and education systems and a devolved parliament.

A barcode is a general machine-readable symbol system that can encode data in various formats (e.g., UPC, EAN, Code-128, QR, etc.). A UPC (Universal Product Code) is just one specific type of barcode used primarily for retail products in North America. Therefore, while every UPC is a barcode, not every barcode is a UPC, so they are not strictly the same thing.

The 2014 video game ‘LEGO The Hobbit’ adapts the plots of the first two films—‘An Unexpected Journey’ and ‘The Desolation of Smaug.’ Content from the third film, ‘The Battle of the Five Armies,’ was planned as DLC but was never released, so the game does not cover all three movies.

Pipelining divides an operation into sequential stages so that multiple tasks can be in different stages concurrently, increasing overall throughput. However, a single task must still pass through every stage, and the addition of pipeline registers can even add a small overhead. Therefore, the total time (latency) for one individual task is not improved by pipelining.

Since the National Minimum Drinking Age Act of 1984, every U.S. state (and the District of Columbia) has set 21 as the minimum legal age to purchase or publicly possess alcoholic beverages, because failure to do so would cost states a portion of their federal highway funds. While individual states allow limited exceptions (e.g., under-21 drinking on private property with parental consent, religious ceremonies, etc.), all states enforce 21 as the general minimum drinking age for purchase and public consumption.
Joe Namath, the former New York Jets quarterback, was elected to the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1985. Therefore, he is indeed in the NFL Hall of Fame.

The length of a suspension bridge is usually compared by its main span. The Mackinac Bridge’s main span is about 1,158 m (3,800 ft). Several bridges have longer main spans, including the 1915 Çanakkale Bridge (2,023 m), Akashi Kaikyo Bridge (1,991 m), and others. Therefore, the Mackinac Bridge is not the longest suspension bridge in the world.

Under the Supremacy Clause of the U.S. Constitution (Article VI, Clause 2), the Constitution and federal laws made pursuant to it are the supreme law of the land. State constitutions and laws are subordinate and cannot conflict with or override the U.S. Constitution. If a state constitutional provision conflicts with the federal Constitution, courts will invalidate the state provision.

The Better Business Bureau is a private, nonprofit organization (a 501(c)(6) business league). It operates independently of any federal, state, or local government agency, providing business accreditation and dispute resolution services on a voluntary basis.

As of early 2023 FOX officially renewed Bob’s Burgers for Seasons 14 and 15, meaning the writers, cast, and animation team are continuing production on new episodes scheduled to air through at least the 2024-25 TV season. No announcement has been made about cancellation, so the show is actively in production.

The Lord of the Rings was originally published by J.R.R. Tolkien in three volumes—The Fellowship of the Ring, The Two Towers, and The Return of the King—commonly referred to collectively as a book series (or trilogy). Therefore, describing Lord of the Rings as a book series is accurate.

Iron Man is a Marvel Comics superhero and a member of the Avengers. The Justice League is a DC Comics superhero team whose members include characters such as Superman, Batman, and Wonder Woman. Therefore, Iron Man is not a member of the Justice League.

Several private companies—e.g., Celestis, Elysium Space, Aura Flights—sell memorial services in which a small capsule containing part of a person’s cremated remains is placed on a commercial rocket. Depending on the package chosen, the ashes can be sent on a brief sub-orbital flight (returning to Earth), placed into Earth orbit, sent to the Moon, or launched on a deep-space trajectory. These services have been operating for decades (the first Celestis flight was in 1997), so it is indeed possible, though only a symbolic portion of the ashes is usually flown and the cost ranges from a few thousand to tens of thousands of dollars.

Until recently no team had ever played a Super Bowl in its home stadium, but the Tampa Bay Buccaneers did so in Super Bowl LV (2021) at Raymond James Stadium, and the Los Angeles Rams did the same in Super Bowl LVI (2022). Therefore, a Super Bowl team has indeed played at home.

The 1980 film “Raging Bull,” directed by Martin Scorsese, is adapted from the autobiography of real-life middleweight boxing champion Jake LaMotta (“Raging Bull: My Story”). The film dramatizes LaMotta’s boxing career and personal life, so it is indeed based on true events.

The Executive Residence of the White House functions as both a home and a working building. Like any residence, it needs facilities to prepare meals. Indeed, the White House contains a main kitchen (on the Ground Floor) and additional kitchen facilities such as the Family Kitchen and Pastry Kitchen. Therefore, the White House residence does have a kitchen.

All Nobel Prizes, including the Nobel Peace Prize, come with three components: a gold medal, a diploma, and a cash award. The cash award is financed by the Nobel Foundation and is the same for all Nobel laureates in a given year (recently about 10 million Swedish kronor, roughly 1 million USD). Therefore, recipients of the Nobel Peace Prize do receive a monetary prize.

Head-lice and their eggs die when exposed to sustained temperatures above roughly 54 °C (130 °F). A typical household hair dryer on a high-heat setting can reach or exceed this temperature at the scalp, and studies have shown that repeated, thorough drying sessions can kill a substantial portion of lice and nits. However, effectiveness varies with technique, exposure time, and dryer model, so it is not a fully reliable stand-alone treatment.

A cow begins to lactate only after it has gone through pregnancy and given birth; the hormonal changes associated with calving trigger milk production. While a cow can continue to produce milk for many months if it is milked regularly, an initial pregnancy (and calving) is required to start lactation.

answer: True (loosely/fictionally based on a real case)
Reasoning: Both Judith Rossner’s novel “Looking for Mr. Goodbar” (1975) and the 1977 film adaptation were inspired by the real-life 1973 murder of New York City schoolteacher Roseann Quinn. While the characters and many plot details are fictionalized, the basic premise— a young teacher who frequents singles bars and is ultimately killed by a man she meets—comes directly from that case. Thus it is not a strictly factual retelling, but it is indeed based on a true story in a loose, dramatized sense.
Answer: True (loosely/fictionally based on a real case)

Reasoning: Public/commercial shooting ranges usually have firearms available for rent and allow newcomers to shoot under supervision, so owning a gun is typically not required. Although some private or members-only clubs may require shooters to bring their own firearms, in general the answer is no—you can attend most ranges without bringing your own gun.

Throughout all currently aired seasons of Grey's Anatomy, Dr. Jackson Avery survives every major medical crisis and eventually leaves Seattle to head the Catherine Fox Foundation in Boston. There is no episode in which he dies.

In ants, social organization varies by species. While many colonies are monogynous (a single queen), numerous species are polygynous and naturally maintain multiple reproductive queens in the same nest (e.g., Argentine ants, fire ants, pharaoh ants). Therefore, it is biologically normal for some ant colonies to have more than one queen.

In almost all U.S. jurisdictions a person must pass a bar examination to obtain an initial license to practice law.  However, a few limited exceptions exist that allow someone to become a licensed attorney without ever sitting for the traditional bar exam.  The main modern example is the ‘diploma privilege’ in Wisconsin, where graduates of in-state ABA-approved law schools may be admitted automatically.  In addition, lawyers already licensed in another state can sometimes be admitted to a new state ‘on motion’ (reciprocity) without another exam.  There are also narrow federal or corporate counsel admissions that waive the general bar test.  Because these routes exist, the accurate answer to whether it is possible is “yes,” even though it is uncommon.

The original Constitution was drafted and ratified in 1787-1788 without the first ten amendments. Those amendments, collectively called the Bill of Rights, were proposed in 1789 and ratified in 1791, so they were added after the Constitution was already in force.

In Lewis Carroll’s novel “Alice’s Adventures in Wonderland,” one of the animals Alice meets after she swims ashore is the Dodo, featured prominently in the ‘Caucus-Race’ scene. Therefore, the story does include a dodo character.

Anzac Day (25 April) specifically commemorates the landing of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps at Gallipoli in 1915 and honours all Australians and New Zealanders who have served and died in wars, conflicts and peacekeeping operations. Remembrance Day (11 November) marks the armistice that ended World War I and is a broader day of remembrance for those who died in military service, particularly in WWI. Because they occur on different dates and arose from different historical events, they are not the same observance.

The 23rd Amendment to the U.S. Constitution (ratified in 1961) granted the District of Columbia electors in the Electoral College, enabling its residents to cast ballots for President and Vice-President beginning with the 1964 election. Therefore, DC residents can and do vote in presidential elections.

Trophic levels describe the position of an organism in a food chain based on what it eats. Many organisms are omnivorous or have life stages with different diets; for example, bears eat both plants (primary consumer level) and fish (secondary or tertiary consumer level). Such dietary flexibility places the same organism at multiple trophic levels within the food web.
The Second Amendment is one of the first ten amendments (the Bill of Rights) that were ratified in 1791 and are formally incorporated into the text of the U.S. Constitution.
The television series 'Better Call Saul' was renewed multiple times and ultimately ran for six seasons (2015-2022). Season 3 premiered in 2017, so a third season definitely exists.

Anatomically, the large intestine begins with a pouch-like section called the cecum, which receives chyme from the ileum via the ileocecal valve. Therefore, the cecum is indeed considered a component of the large intestine.

Colorado School of Mines competes in NCAA Division II athletics under the nickname “Orediggers,” and one of their varsity sports is American football, playing in the Rocky Mountain Athletic Conference.
Encino is officially designated as a neighborhood in the San Fernando Valley region governed by the City of Los Angeles; it is not an independent municipality.

The modern English alphabet has 26 letters (A–Z). The current official Spanish alphabet, as defined by the Royal Spanish Academy since 2010, has 27 letters: the same 26 letters as English plus the additional letter ñ. Therefore, the Spanish alphabet contains one more letter than the English alphabet.

The Plaza Hotel on Fifth Avenue at Central Park South continues to operate as a luxury hotel (in addition to having privately owned residences). It has undergone ownership changes and renovations over the years, but it has not closed permanently. Therefore, the hotel is still open to guests.

Under UK law, there is generally no expectation of privacy for individuals who are in a public place, so taking photographs of people in public is lawful provided you are not harassing them, causing alarm or distress, or breaching specific restrictions (e.g., court orders, national security zones). Commercial use may need a model release, and photographing in ways that are voyeuristic or indecent can be illegal. But the basic act of taking a photo of someone in a public setting is permitted.

The question does not specify which gang or who its members are. Without any contextual information, there is no factual basis on which to determine whether any members are alive. Because the proposition cannot be assessed from the information given, any True/False choice would be essentially a guess.

The original Norwegian series ‘Skam’ concluded with season 4 in 2017, and the creator (Julie Andem) as well as NRK confirmed that the show ended with that season. While several international remakes have produced additional seasons, the original ‘Skam’ itself has no announced or planned season 5.

‘Sheetrock’ is a trademarked brand name owned by United States Gypsum (USG) for gypsum wallboard panels. The generic product itself is called ‘drywall.’ In common usage people often use “sheetrock” to refer to any drywall panel, and the material composition and purpose are identical. Thus, while one is a brand name and the other is the generic term, they refer to the same type of building material.

Walgreens is part of Walgreens Boots Alliance, while Rite Aid remains an independent, publicly traded company. Although Walgreens Boots Alliance purchased roughly 1,900 Rite Aid locations in 2017 (those stores were converted to Walgreens), the remaining Rite Aid stores and corporate entity were not acquired. Therefore, the two chains are not owned by the same parent company.

In 2015 the feature film “The 33,” starring Antonio Banderas and based on the 2010 Copiapó mine collapse that trapped 33 Chilean miners, was released. Several documentaries have also been produced. Therefore, a film about the Chilean miners exists.

The Dutch/German fashion retailer C&A withdrew from the British market and closed all of its UK stores in 2000–2001. Since then it has not reopened any physical branches in the United Kingdom, nor does it operate UK-specific online retail. Therefore, at present there are no C&A stores in the UK.

A hot tub is the generic term for a large tub of heated water used for relaxation or hydrotherapy, regardless of manufacturer. “Jacuzzi” is a specific brand that popularized whirlpool jets; it has become a genericized trademark in casual speech but technically refers only to units made by that company. Therefore, while all Jacuzzis are hot tubs, not all hot tubs are Jacuzzis, so they are not literally the same thing.

answer: Yes, mild short-term dizziness is normal.
Reasoning: Many people experience a brief sensation of rocking or swaying—sometimes called ‘land sickness’ or mal de débarquement—after leaving a cruise ship. This is caused by the brain readjusting to being on solid ground after several days of constant motion. The feeling usually resolves within hours to a couple of days. Persistent or severe dizziness lasting weeks would be atypical and should be evaluated by a doctor, but short-term dizziness right after a cruise is common and generally considered normal.
Answer: Yes, mild short-term dizziness is normal.

Reasoning: The New Orleans Saints’ current base alignment under defensive coordinator (now head coach) Dennis Allen features four down linemen and three linebackers—a 4-3 scheme. While Rob Ryan briefly switched them to a 3-4 look in 2013–2014, they moved back to a 4-3 afterward and have stayed there, mixing in multiple fronts situationally. Therefore, they are not primarily a 3-4 defense at present.

A hydrogen ion (H⁺) is just a bare proton. In aqueous solution a free proton does not exist in isolation; it immediately bonds to a water molecule to form H₃O⁺, the hydronium ion. Thus hydronium contains the proton plus a coordinated H₂O molecule, so the two species are related but not chemically identical.

The edible ‘chestnut’ comes from trees in the genus Castanea (a true nut that grows in a spiny burr on trees). A ‘water chestnut’ is the corm (swollen stem) of an aquatic sedge, Eleocharis dulcis (or sometimes Trapa natans in Europe). They are botanically unrelated, grow in very different environments, and have different culinary properties. Therefore they are not the same thing.

Baylor College of Medicine began as the medical school of Baylor University and kept the Baylor name when it moved to Houston in 1943. Although it became an independent institution in 1969 and now has no governance ties to Baylor University, the historical connection and shared heritage mean the two institutions are indeed related.

Travis Scott signed a production deal in 2012 with Kanye West’s G.O.O.D. Music imprint “Very G.O.O.D. Beats,” but he was never signed to G.O.O.D. Music as a recording artist and is not listed on their current artist roster. In the usual sense of being a G.O.O.D. Music artist, the answer is therefore no.

Yes—while less common than allergies to foods like peanuts or shellfish, people can develop IgE-mediated allergies to meats such as beef, pork, poultry, or lamb. A well-known example is alpha-gal syndrome, in which a tick bite sensitizes an individual to a carbohydrate in red meat, leading to allergic reactions hours after eating it. Therefore, meat allergy is a documented medical condition.

Andrew Lloyd Webber wrote ‘Love Never Dies’ as a follow-up musical that continues the story of the characters from ‘The Phantom of the Opera,’ set roughly ten years later. It is officially promoted and generally recognized as the sequel to ‘The Phantom of the Opera.’

Netflix came on board as a co-producer starting with Season 2 of The Last Kingdom, and since then Netflix has hosted all existing seasons. Season 2 has been available on the platform worldwide since its 2017 release, aside from rare regional licensing anomalies.

The ABC television series ‘Once Upon a Time’ ran from 2011 to 2018 and was cancelled after its seventh season. Season 7, which concluded in May 2018, served as the series finale, so no additional seasons followed.

Across the majority of mainstream DC Comics continuities—and in most film, television, and animated adaptations—Clark Kent (Superman) and Lois Lane ultimately become a couple, often marrying and, in some versions, having a child. While individual story arcs or alternate universes may diverge, the prevailing canon portrays them ending up together.

In common and anatomical usage, “the gut” refers to the entire gastrointestinal tract (especially the intestines), whereas the stomach is just one specific organ within that system. Therefore, they are not the same thing.

New York City is made up of five boroughs—Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, the Bronx, and Staten Island. Manhattan is only one of those boroughs, so the two terms are not synonymous, even though people sometimes colloquially use “the city” to mean Manhattan.

Eastern Kentucky University’s athletic programs (the EKU Colonels) compete in the NCAA’s top subdivision for most sports. EKU is currently a member of the ASUN Conference (and competes in the Division I Football Championship Subdivision for football). Thus, it is classified as an NCAA Division I institution.

Both terms refer to the condition in which the medial arch of the foot is depressed so that the entire sole comes closer to, or touches, the ground. In everyday usage they’re considered synonymous, though clinicians may sometimes use “fallen arches” to emphasize an arch that has collapsed over time rather than one that was never present. Functionally, they describe the same foot posture.

Traditionally, a “print source” is something that was distributed in a physical, printed form (e.g., a bound book, a journal issue, a newspaper). A PDF is a digital file; even if it is an exact scan of a printed work, the version you are accessing is electronic. Most citation styles therefore treat a PDF you download or view online as an electronic/online source, not a print one (unless you actually consult the physical copy).

In the long-running mainstream Archie Comics continuity, Betty Cooper’s primary romantic interest is Archie Andrews, while Jughead Jones is portrayed as largely uninterested in dating anyone. There is no canonical storyline in the classic comics in which Betty and Jughead become a romantic couple. (Their pairing happens only in the separate TV series “Riverdale,” not in the original comics.) Therefore, they were not together in the comics.

The 26 December 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake generated a tsunami that swept across the Maldives, flooding most of the atolls, destroying infrastructure and causing fatalities. This is a well-documented event, confirming that the Maldives has indeed experienced a tsunami.

Super Bowl championship rings are commissioned by the winning team and given only to players, coaches, and staff of that team. Members of the losing team do not receive a Super Bowl ring; instead, their organization may issue an AFC or NFC championship ring, which is different. Therefore, the Super Bowl loser does not get a Super Bowl ring.

The E train (Eighth Avenue Local) is scheduled to operate 24/7 in the NYC subway system. While weekend schedules may differ from weekday frequencies and there can be occasional planned service changes, the line itself continues to run on Saturdays and Sundays.

Under U.S. federal law, any seller who holds a Federal Firearms License (FFL) must perform the same National Instant Criminal Background Check System (NICS) check at a gun show as they would in a storefront. However, many sellers at gun shows are private, unlicensed individuals; federal law does not require them to run a background check (though some states do). Therefore, attending a gun show does not automatically mean a buyer will undergo a background check—whether one is performed depends on who the seller is and the laws of the state where the show is held.

In chess, any legal piece move may be played on the first turn so long as it follows the rules of movement for that piece. Knights are not blocked by their own pawns because they jump, so either of White’s knights (b1 or g1) can be moved on move one. Therefore, it is legal to move a knight first.

In everyday usage, especially in the UK, the terms “steel wool” and “wire wool” are used interchangeably to describe the fine, abrasive pads made from thin strands of steel that are used for cleaning and polishing. While in theory “wire wool” could encompass wools made from other metals, in common practice it almost always refers to the same steel product. Therefore, for normal household or workshop contexts, they are treated as the same thing.

The well-known Statue of Liberty (often called “Lady Liberty”) stamp that has been sold at post offices in recent years was issued as a First-Class Mail Forever stamp (not carrying a printed monetary value). Earlier historical Lady Liberty stamps did have denominations, but the version people generally refer to today is indeed a Forever stamp.
A meter is defined as exactly 100 cm, while a yard is defined as exactly 36 inches (0.9144 m). Therefore a meter is longer than a yard; they are not the same length.

Most laboratories do not require you to fast before an ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone) blood draw or ACTH stimulation test; the critical requirement is usually that the sample be drawn in the early-morning hours because ACTH has a strong diurnal rhythm. Some centers may prefer fasting to reduce variability, but this is not a universal or strict requirement.

Under the Japanese Civil Code, marriage is prohibited between lineal relatives and siblings, but marriage between first cousins is not prohibited. Therefore, from a legal standpoint, cousins are allowed to marry in Japan (though social attitudes may vary).

In Phase 10, a hand ends when any player both lays down the current phase and then gets rid of all remaining cards (by hitting or discarding). There is no rule preventing this from happening in the very first hand of the game (the round in which everyone is working on Phase 1). Therefore, if a player is able to meet Phase 1 requirements and empty their hand on the same turn, the hand ends—meaning you can indeed ‘go out’ in the first round.
In baseball scoring, a sacrifice fly is recorded as a plate appearance but is specifically excluded from the official at-bat total. Therefore it does not count as an at bat.

The cartridge’s official SAAMI designation is .45 Colt. Historically, shooters began calling it the “.45 Long Colt” to distinguish it from other .45-caliber rounds such as the shorter .45 Schofield. Dimensionally and ballistically, however, .45 Colt and .45 Long Colt refer to the identical cartridge; there is no separate, distinct round called the .45 Long Colt.

Lake Michigan—one of the Great Lakes—connects to the Mississippi River system via man-made and natural waterways. The Chicago River was reversed and linked to the Illinois Waterway (Chicago Sanitary and Ship Canal) so vessels can travel from Lake Michigan to the Illinois River and then down to the Mississippi. Historically, there was also the Fox–Wisconsin water route. Therefore, there is a navigable connection from the Great Lakes to the Mississippi River.

Under U.S. House of Representatives rules, members may introduce a “motion to vacate the chair,” which, if passed by a majority vote, removes the sitting Speaker. Therefore, the Speaker of the House can indeed be removed from the position.

In the open ocean, salinity is governed mainly by evaporation-precipitation balance and ice melt at the surface. These processes create high-salinity surface waters in the subtropics and low-salinity surface waters near the equator and poles. Once water sinks and becomes deep water, its salinity stays almost constant as it spreads, so the deep ocean tends to have a fairly uniform salinity (~34.7 PSU) that is often lower than the salinity of the subtropical surface but higher than the high-latitude surface. Therefore, it is not generally ‘saltier at the bottom’; salinity depends more on where the water last contacted the surface than on depth itself.

The 2017 film “The Greatest Showman” takes its premise and main characters from the real-life impresario P. T. Barnum and the creation of his circus. While many story details are fictionalized or dramatized, the movie is nevertheless inspired by real historical events and people, so it is considered to be (loosely) based on a true story.

Seagate Technology and Western Digital Corporation are two separate, publicly traded companies that independently design, manufacture, and sell data-storage products. They are competitors in the hard-drive and SSD markets, not divisions of a single entity.
Stephen Curry won gold medals with USA Basketball at the FIBA World Cups in 2010 and 2014, but he has never played in an Olympic Games, so he has not earned an Olympic gold medal.

In Alice Sebold’s novel (and the film adaptation) The Lovely Bones, the protagonist Susie Salmon is the one who is murdered. Her younger sister, Lindsey Salmon, remains alive throughout the story; she grows up, graduates, and eventually marries. Therefore, the sister does not die.

The 1987 film “The Stepfather” (and its 2009 remake) was a fictional story, although writer Donald Westlake has said he took loose inspiration from real-life murderer John List. Because the movie is not a factual recounting of actual events and only borrows a general idea, it is not properly ‘based on a true story’ in the usual sense.

The FIFA World Cup trophy (introduced in 1974) is a single, original gold trophy that is presented to the winning team at each tournament, after which it is returned to FIFA; the team keeps only a replica. Thus, the same physical trophy is re-used every tournament (the competition is held every four years, not annually).

Yes—through practices such as multiple-cropping, intercropping, improved seed varieties, irrigation, fertiliser use, and precision agriculture it is possible to raise the output per unit of land. Because agronomic research and on-farm evidence consistently show yield gains from these methods, I am confident the statement is true, though some uncertainty exists because the question is broad and context-dependent.

A sonogram is a general ultrasound image of any part of the body, whereas an echocardiogram is specifically an ultrasound (sonogram) of the heart. Thus, every echocardiogram is a sonogram, but not every sonogram is an echocardiogram; they are not identical terms.

Ganglion-blocking drugs are agents that antagonize (or prevent depolarization of) nicotinic Nn receptors in autonomic ganglia, e.g., hexamethonium or mecamylamine. Nicotine is a nicotinic receptor agonist that first stimulates ganglia; only at very high or prolonged exposure does it produce a secondary ‘depolarizing block’. Because its primary pharmacologic action is stimulation, it is not classified among the therapeutic or classical ganglion blockers.

Puppies are born with their eyelids sealed. They usually open them around 10–14 days of age, but the retina and optic nerve are still immature at that point. When the lids first separate, the puppy can detect light and vague movement, yet true, focused vision does not develop for another week or two. Therefore, in the sense of having functional sight, they cannot really ‘see’ right when the eyes first open.

The folk trio Peter, Paul and Mary consisted of Peter Yarrow, Noel ‘Paul’ Stookey, and Mary Travers. Mary Travers passed away in 2009, while Peter Yarrow and Paul Stookey are still living. Therefore, not all members are alive today.
The 2017 film “Get Out” was written and directed by Jordan Peele as an original screenplay. There is no underlying novel or published source material on which the movie is based.

Tennessee has long issued handgun carry permits (either ‘Concealed’ or ‘Enhanced’) that allow permit-holders to carry a handgun concealed. In addition, as of July 1 2021 the state adopted permitless carry for most adults 21 years or older (18 + for military), allowing them to carry a handgun, openly or concealed, without a permit so long as they are otherwise eligible to possess a firearm. Long guns are not covered by this permitless carry provision, and certain locations (schools, courthouses, posted private property, etc.) remain off-limits. Therefore, for most law-abiding adults it is legal to carry a concealed handgun in Tennessee.

Roger Bannister famously ran a mile in 3:59.4 in 1954, breaking the four-minute barrier. Since then, thousands of athletes have also run the mile in under four minutes, so at least one person (in fact, many) have indeed done it.

In many places (e.g., most U.S. states) a person can shoot at a commercial range without holding a personal gun license as long as they use firearms supplied and supervised by the range. A license or permit is usually only required if you are transporting or using your own firearm, and some jurisdictions have stricter rules. Because requirements vary by country, state, or municipality, the safest answer is that a license is not universally required, though local laws should always be checked.
Avengers: Age of Ultron was released in May 2015, whereas Captain America: Civil War was released in May 2016. Therefore, Civil War came out after Age of Ultron, not before.

The Try Guys (Keith Habersberger, Ned Fulmer, Zach Kornfeld, and Eugene Lee Yang) left BuzzFeed in 2018 and created their own independent production company, 2nd Try LLC. Since then, they have produced and distributed their content independently and are no longer employees of or creators for BuzzFeed.

West Virginia changed its alcohol laws in 2020. Retail liquor outlets (and bars/restaurants with liquor licenses) are now permitted to sell distilled spirits on Sundays, but only during limited hours—generally from 1 p.m. until midnight—unless a locality has imposed stricter rules. Therefore, in most of West Virginia you can indeed purchase liquor on Sunday after 1 p.m.

Marvel Studios has no plans to make another film titled “Avengers: Infinity War.” That story arc was completed with its follow-up, “Avengers: Endgame” (2019). While future Avengers films such as “Avengers: The Kang Dynasty” and “Avengers: Secret Wars” have been announced, none are additional ‘Infinity War’ movies.

Shea butter is extracted from the seeds (often called ‘nuts’) of the shea tree (Vitellaria paradoxa). Because the source is the fruit of a tree and the oily kernel inside is termed a nut botanically, it is classified as a tree nut product, even though it rarely causes typical tree-nut allergic reactions.

The Swedish men’s national football team reached the FIFA World Cup final in 1958, losing 5-2 to Brazil. Sweden’s women’s team also played in the Women’s World Cup final in 2003. Therefore, Sweden has indeed appeared in a World Cup final.

Across L. M. Montgomery’s Anne series, Anne Shirley and Gilbert Blythe move from childhood rivals to friends, then sweethearts; they become engaged in ‘Anne of the Island’ and marry in ‘Anne’s House of Dreams.’ Thus, in the overall story arc Anne ultimately ends up with Gilbert, even though the first book only hints at their future together.
Canada is an independent sovereign country that occupies the northern part of North America. The United States is a separate country composed of 50 states, none of which is Canada.

While the United States and many former operators have retired the F-4 Phantom II, a handful of countries (notably Iran and, in smaller numbers, Turkey and possibly a few others) continue to fly upgraded or refurbished F-4s for frontline or secondary roles. Therefore, the aircraft type has not been completely withdrawn worldwide.

Ontario adopted anti-discrimination statutes in the early 1950s and enacted a consolidated Human Rights Code in 1962. Several other provinces (e.g., New Brunswick 1967, Manitoba 1970, Newfoundland 1970, Prince Edward Island 1976) did not pass comparable legislation until years later. Therefore, Ontario was actually among the earlier—not the last—provinces to introduce human-rights legislation.

The novel and film “The Prince of Tides” are works of fiction written by Pat Conroy. While Conroy drew on some autobiographical elements and family experiences, the plot and characters are not a factual recounting of real events. Therefore, it is not considered to be based on a true story.

Eli Manning’s two Super Bowl appearances (XLII and XLVI) were against the New England Patriots. Peyton Manning’s four Super Bowl appearances (XLI, XLIV, XLVIII, 50) were against the Bears, Saints, Seahawks, and Panthers, respectively. None of those games featured the Giants against a team led by Peyton, so the brothers never faced each other in a Super Bowl.

The Cincinnati Bengals have represented the AFC in the Super Bowl three times: Super Bowl XVI (1982 season), Super Bowl XXIII (1989 season), and Super Bowl LVI (2021 season, played February 2022). Therefore, they have indeed been to the Super Bowl.

In U.S. pickup-truck nomenclature, the weight-class numbers roughly correspond to payload ratings: 1500 ≈ ½-ton, 2500 ≈ ¾-ton, and 3500 ≈ 1-ton. The Dodge (Ram) 3500 therefore falls into the traditional one-ton category, even though actual modern payload can exceed one ton.

answer: Yes – the full-length version exists (released as the Chris Brown remix).
Reasoning: On Rihanna’s 2011 album “Talk That Talk,” “Birthday Cake” appeared only as a 1-minute-18-second interlude, so many listeners wondered if a longer cut existed. In February 2012 Rihanna released an official full-length version as a remix featuring Chris Brown, running about 3:40. No fully released solo version longer than the interlude has surfaced, but the Chris Brown remix is an official ‘full’ version of the song.
Answer: Yes – the full-length version exists (released as the Chris Brown remix).

Reasoning: “Daddy’s Little Girls” was written and directed by Tyler Perry as an original, fictional drama. While it deals with real-world themes such as single fatherhood and custody battles, it is not adapted from or officially based on any specific real-life events or individuals.

Across both generations (2007–2017 and 2017-present), the Jeep Compass has only been offered with 4-cylinder gasoline or diesel engines (e.g., 2.0L, 2.4L, 1.3L turbo, 2.0L diesel). There has never been a factory 6-cylinder option.

A condition called heterochromia iridum can be congenital, meaning a person is born with two differently pigmented irises. It is uncommon but well-documented in medical literature, so the statement is correct.

The Lockheed P-38 Lightning was produced in large numbers during World War II. Although most were scrapped after the war, several were preserved or later recovered and restored. A handful—generally cited as about half a dozen to ten—are currently maintained in air-worthy condition by museums and private collectors (examples include “Glacier Girl,” “23 Skidoo,” and “Scat III”). These aircraft appear at airshows and occasionally fly for commemorative events, confirming that some P-38s are still flying today.

Dwyane Wade’s rookie season was the 2003-04 NBA campaign. The Miami Heat finished 42-40 that year, qualified for the Eastern Conference playoffs, and advanced to the second round, where Wade had several memorable performances. Therefore, he did make the playoffs as a rookie.

Vehicle registration in the District of Columbia is handled by the DC DMV, which issues its own distinctive license plates featuring slogans such as “End Taxation Without Representation.” Therefore, Washington, D.C. does indeed have its own license plate design separate from the 50 states.

Only honey-bees (worker honey bees) have a strongly barbed stinger that usually remains lodged in the victim’s skin. Other bees—such as bumblebees, carpenter bees, and most solitary bees—have smoother stingers that they can withdraw and use again, so no stinger is left behind. Therefore, a ‘bee sting’ does not always contain a retained stinger.
Yes—several competitors have achieved “Total Victory” on American Ninja Warrior (e.g., Isaac Caldiero in Season 7, Drew Drechsel in Season 11). Therefore the statement that someone has won is true.

The ABC television series 'Once Upon a Time' aired from October 2011 to May 2018 and concluded with Season 7, which was announced and promoted as the final season. ABC officially canceled the show after Season 7, and no Season 8 has ever been produced or released.

Both North and South Korea officially speak Korean, sharing the same grammatical structure and mutual intelligibility. However, 70+ years of separation have produced noticeable differences in accent, vocabulary, and some spelling conventions. Despite these divergences, linguists still classify both as regional varieties of one language rather than separate languages.

In the film/novel “The Fundamentals of Caring,” Trevor is a teenager with Duchenne muscular dystrophy who embarks on a road trip with his caregiver, Ben. The story ends with Trevor still alive—he gains new experiences and personal growth, but there is no death scene or indication that he dies during the events depicted.

In the original Nickelodeon television series “Blue’s Clues,” the titular puppy Blue is explicitly referred to with she/her pronouns by the characters and in official show materials, establishing that Blue is female.

Under U.S. federal law mescaline is a Schedule I controlled substance, but the San Pedro cactus itself is not scheduled. It can be legally bought, sold, and grown as an ornamental plant. Only extracting or ingesting it for its mescaline content would violate drug laws, not mere possession of the cactus.

The original game launched on PlayStation 3, was later remastered for PlayStation 4, has a remake for PlayStation 5, and has been released on PC. Therefore, it is not confined solely to the PS4 platform.

In England (and the wider UK) a TV Licence is legally required if you use a television (or any other device) to watch or record live broadcast TV or to watch BBC iPlayer. Merely owning a TV set that is not used for those purposes does not require a licence. Because the common interpretation of the question is about having a TV for normal viewing, the practical answer is that, yes, a licence is required.
The Make-A-Wish Foundation is publicly recognized as a 501(c)(3) charitable organization that grants wishes to children with critical illnesses, which by definition makes it a nonprofit entity.

At 7,000 ft (≈2,100 m) the barometric pressure is ~77 % of sea-level, so the partial pressure of oxygen is lower. Healthy people usually adapt with only mild, transient shortness of breath during exertion, not a sense that breathing is truly ‘hard.’ Significant breathing difficulty is uncommon unless someone has cardiorespiratory disease or is very sensitive to altitude.

While the Snellen letter chart is the one most patients recognize, eye-care professionals choose among several standardized charts depending on the patient’s age, literacy, language and the precision required. Alternatives include the LogMAR chart, Tumbling-E, Landolt-C, Lea symbols and others. Therefore, usage varies from clinic to clinic and patient to patient.

The folkloric tale of Little Red Riding Hood existed prior to the Brothers Grimm, but it was collected and published by Jacob and Wilhelm Grimm in their 1812/1815 editions of Kinder- und Hausmärchen (Grimm’s Fairy Tales). Because it appears in that collection and is widely associated with it, it is considered one of the Grimm fairy tales.

The 2014 Syfy miniseries “Ascension” was developed as an original television project by Philip Levens, loosely inspired by the real-world 1960s Project Orion concept of a generation starship. There is no underlying novel or book series on which the show is formally based.

In 2011, Landry's, Inc. made a tender offer to purchase McCormick & Schmick's Seafood Restaurants and completed the acquisition in early 2012. Since then, McCormick & Schmick's has been part of Landry's portfolio of restaurant brands.

Under the North American Numbering Plan, toll-free area codes include 800, 833, 844, 855, 866, 877 and 888. These toll-free codes are valid throughout all NANP countries, which cover both the United States and Canada. Therefore numbers that begin with the 866 area code are treated as toll-free when dialed from Canada.

In the television series "Castle," Detective Kate Beckett’s long-running story arc involves investigating her mother Johanna’s murder. Over several seasons she pieces together that contract killer Dick Coonan (alias Rathborne) was the triggerman and that the murder was ordered to cover up corruption orchestrated by Senator William Bracken. In the season-6 episode “Veritas,” Beckett gathers conclusive evidence, confronts Bracken, and has him arrested, definitively learning who was responsible for her mother’s death.
The CW television series “The Messengers” premiered in 2015 and was cancelled by the network after its first season. No renewal was announced and no second season was produced or released.

answer: No permit is required to open carry in North Carolina.
Reasoning: North Carolina is an open-carry state. Anyone who is at least 18 years old and otherwise legally allowed to possess a firearm may openly carry a handgun without obtaining a permit, except in places where firearms are prohibited (e.g., schools, certain government buildings, private property that is posted, or areas where local ordinances restrict open carry). A permit is only required for concealed carry, not for open carry.
Answer: No permit is required to open carry in North Carolina.

Reasoning: While a continuous function can be differentiable everywhere, its derivative need not be continuous. A classical counter-example is f(x) = x^2 sin(1/x) for x ≠ 0 and f(0) = 0. This function is continuous and differentiable at every point, but its derivative fails to be continuous at x = 0. Hence, the statement is not universally true.

A basis point is a standardized unit equal to 0.01 % (0.0001 in decimal terms) and is used across all types of interest-rate and percentage changes. A pip is the smallest quoted price increment for a particular currency pair (typically 0.0001 for most non-JPY pairs, 0.01 for JPY pairs, and can be subdivided into ‘pipettes’). Thus, while a pip happens to equal one basis point for many 4-decimal-place currency pairs, the terms refer to different concepts and the equivalence does not always hold.

Benzalkonium chloride is a quaternary ammonium compound used mainly as a disinfectant and preservative, whereas hydrogen peroxide is an oxidizing agent (H₂O₂). Their chemical structures, modes of action, and uses differ, so they are not the same substance.
By definition, cod-liver oil is the oil that is rendered from the livers of cod (traditionally Atlantic cod). Therefore it literally comes from the liver of the cod fish.

Thunder is the sound produced by lightning. You can hear thunder even if the rain produced by the same storm evaporates before reaching the ground (common in ‘dry thunderstorms’) or if the rain shaft is falling some distance away. Therefore thunder can occur at a location where no rain is observed.

The full run of Phineas and Ferb (2007-2015) comprises well over 100 half-hour episodes—most sources list 129 (made up of about 222 eleven-minute segments plus several specials). Because the total exceeds 104, the statement that there are exactly 104 episodes is incorrect.

A 2-stroke engine does not have a separate oil sump like a 4-stroke. Instead, its moving parts are lubricated by oil that is either pre-mixed with the fuel or supplied by an oil-injection system. Running it without the required oil quickly leads to inadequate lubrication, overheating, and engine seizure. Therefore, oil is essential for safe operation.

DNA and RNA are polymers composed of repeating nucleotide monomers (each consisting of a sugar, phosphate group, and nitrogenous base). Therefore, nucleotides are indeed the fundamental building blocks of both DNA and RNA.

Yes. Multiple NFL franchises have won consecutive Super Bowls—for example, the Green Bay Packers (I & II), Miami Dolphins (VII & VIII), Pittsburgh Steelers (twice: IX-X and XIII-XIV), San Francisco 49ers (XXIII & XXIV), Dallas Cowboys (XXVII & XXVIII), Denver Broncos (XXXII & XXXIII), and New England Patriots (XXXVIII & XXXIX). Therefore, at least one team has done it.

The County Court Business Centre (CCBC) in Northampton is operated by HM Courts & Tribunals Service. It issues and processes county-court money claims and can enter judgments; those orders carry the same legal weight as any made in a conventional county-court hearing. Although the CCBC is an administrative processing centre rather than a courtroom open to the public, it forms part of the official County Court of England and Wales, so it is legally a real court.

Throughout the God of War series (beginning with the 2005 PlayStation 2 title), Kratos’ main adversaries include numerous figures from the Greek and later Norse pantheons. He directly battles and kills gods such as Ares (the original God of War), Poseidon, Hades, Zeus, Baldur, and others. Therefore, it is correct to say that you do fight gods in God of War.

The redback spider (Latrodectus hasselti) is native to Australia. Although individual specimens have occasionally been intercepted in the UK in imported goods, there is no evidence of an established, breeding population outdoors. Therefore, for practical purposes, the UK does not have redback spiders living naturally.

Under Japan’s Nationality Act, individuals who possess Japanese citizenship and another nationality are required to choose one by age 20 (or within two years of acquiring dual nationality after age 20). Except for this temporary allowance for minors and a few narrow exemptions, adults are not legally permitted to remain dual citizens. While enforcement can be lax in practice, the law requires renunciation of one nationality, so legally speaking dual citizenship is not allowed.

The Constitution contains no clause permitting a state to leave the Union, and the Supreme Court’s ruling in Texas v. White (1869) held that the United States is “an indestructible Union” from which states cannot unilaterally secede. Any change to that status would require a constitutional amendment approved by the states and Congress, not unilateral action by a single state.

A traditional Long Island Iced Tea is a cocktail made with several clear spirits (vodka, gin, rum, tequila), triple sec, sour mix (or lemon juice and simple syrup), and a splash of cola to give it a tea-like color. Despite its name, no actual tea is used in the standard recipe.

Connecticut legalized adult-use (recreational) cannabis in 2021. Adults 21 + may possess and consume marijuana, including smoking it, on private property or in other locations where smoking is permitted. It remains illegal for people under 21, in most public places, in vehicles, and on federal property. Therefore, smoking weed is not categorically illegal in Connecticut, though there are restrictions.

answer: No, the host country automatically qualifies and does not have to go through regular qualifying.
Reasoning: In modern FIFA World Cups, the host nation (or co-host nations) are granted automatic berths and therefore do not need to take part in the qualification process. While there were rare historical exceptions (e.g., Italy in 1934), the established rule for many decades has been automatic qualification for the host country.
Answer: No, the host country automatically qualifies and does not have to go through regular qualifying.

Reasoning: Intersex conditions can result in individuals being born with reproductive or sexual anatomy that does not fit typical definitions of male or female, which can include the presence of both ovarian and testicular tissue or other combinations of male- and female-typical organs.

Under the current rugby-league Laws of the Game the pack may not push and the non-feeding side has no realistic way to win possession. The ball must be fed down the middle and the hookers can strike, but in practice the feed-side hooker simply heels it back unopposed. Therefore scrums in rugby league are, by law and in practice, effectively uncontested.

Under the UN Charter, the veto power is reserved exclusively for the five permanent members of the Security Council (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom, and the United States). The ten non-permanent members have one vote each but lack veto authority.

FIFA introduced goal-line technology at the 2014 World Cup in Brazil and has retained it for every men’s and women’s World Cup tournament since. Therefore, World Cups are played with goal-line technology in place.

Scottish Gaelic and Irish Gaelic both descend from Old Irish and are members of the Goidelic branch of the Celtic language family, so they are closely related and share many similarities. However, over centuries they have developed separate phonology, vocabulary, spelling conventions, and some grammatical differences, and today they are considered two distinct languages with only partial mutual intelligibility.

The term 'bicuspid valve' refers to the left atrioventricular valve of the heart, which has two cusps (leaflets). The standard anatomical name for this valve is the mitral valve. Hence, they designate the same structure.

Robert Jordan stated in interviews that the world of The Wheel of Time is meant to be our own Earth, but in a different turning of the Wheel—so far in the future (and/or past) that geography, languages, and cultures have shifted beyond recognition. Hints of this connection appear in the books through distorted legends of our time. Therefore, while it does not resemble present-day Earth, the series is canonically set on Earth in another Age.

In Canadian law, contempt of court is an offence against the administration of justice. Superior courts have an inherent common-law power to try and punish contempt, and the Criminal Code also contains contempt-related provisions (e.g., disobeying a court order, refusing to testify). Although courts distinguish between civil and criminal contempt for procedural purposes, the conduct is punishable and treated as a criminal matter in the sense that it can lead to fines or imprisonment.

Elton John was a friend of Marc Bolan and appeared with T. Rex on more than one occasion. Most notably he played piano in the 1972 concert/film “Born to Boogie,” jamming with the band (and Ringo Starr). A year earlier he had also mimed piano for T. Rex’s performance of “Get It On” on BBC’s Top of the Pops. These guest spots mean he did indeed perform with T. Rex, even if he was not an official member of the group.

“Somewhere Over the Rainbow,” written for The Wizard of Oz, expresses Dorothy’s longing for a better, trouble-free place. The lyrics are about hope and escapism rather than romantic affection for another person, so it is not generally classified as a love song.

A dog’s genetic makeup can include contributions from any number of different breeds, depending on how its parents, grandparents, and earlier ancestors were bred. If one parent is itself a two-breed mix and the other parent is a purebred of a third breed, the offspring will carry genes from all three breeds. Therefore, it is entirely possible for a single dog to be a mix of three distinct breeds.

Dalmatian puppies are born almost entirely white; their characteristic dark spots begin to appear a few days to weeks after birth and continue to increase in number and size during the first year or so of life, gradually slowing as the dog reaches maturity. Therefore, as they grow, dalmatians do indeed develop more visible spots.

Although Toys “R” Us filed for bankruptcy and closed its company-owned U.S. stores in 2018, the brand still exists through licensees and new ownership in a number of countries. Full-size Toys “R” Us stores continue to operate in Canada, several Asian markets (e.g., Japan, Singapore, Hong Kong, Malaysia, Thailand, Taiwan, Philippines), parts of the Middle East, and elsewhere. In the United States the name has also re-appeared inside many Macy’s stores and at a flagship location in the American Dream mall. Therefore, at least some Toys “R” Us stores are still open in the world.

Volkswagen (VW), Audi, and Porsche are separate legal entities/brands—even though Volkswagen AG is the parent company that owns controlling stakes in both Audi AG and Porsche AG. Therefore, they are related but not literally the same company.

‘Cougar’ and ‘mountain lion’ are two regional common names for the same North American big cat species, scientifically known as Puma concolor. Other names for the same animal include puma, panther, catamount, and painter. Because they refer to the identical species, the terms describe the same animal.
Within the state of New York, one of its 62 counties is officially named Orange County, located in the Hudson Valley region. Therefore, an Orange County does exist in New York.

“Spider-Man: Turn Off the Dark” concluded its Broadway run in January 2014 and no subsequent commercial production is currently running. Announced plans for a Las Vegas sit-down never materialized. Therefore, the show is not playing anywhere at present.

In the CW series “Nikita,” Alexandra Udinov and Navy SEAL/Division agent Sean Pierce develop romantic feelings in season 2, share their first kiss, and are explicitly a couple through much of season 3 before Sean’s death. Therefore, they do, in fact, get together romantically, even though the relationship ends tragically.

A fidelity bond specifically protects an employer against losses caused by dishonest acts of its own employees, whereas crime insurance is a broader category that can also include coverage for burglary, robbery, computer fraud, forgery, etc. Fidelity bonds are therefore one form of crime insurance, but they are not synonymous with the entire category.

Several TMNT animated series have aired over the years (1987, 2003, 2012-2017, and most recently “Rise of the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,” 2018-2020). The most recent series finished broadcasting new episodes in 2020. While reruns or streaming availability continue, there is no TMNT series currently producing or premiering first-run episodes on a television network, so in the usual sense of ‘still on TV’ (i.e., airing new episodes), the answer is no.

Xbox One X can play many Xbox 360 titles through Microsoft’s backward-compatibility program, but only the games that have been specifically whitelisted and adapted. A large portion of the Xbox 360 library is still not supported, so it is incorrect to say that *all* Xbox 360 games work on an Xbox One X.

The song “What a Wonderful World” was written by Bob Thiele (d. 1996) and George David Weiss (d. 2010) and first released in 1967. In the United States (and most other Berne-convention countries) a song remains under copyright for 70 years after the death of the last surviving author. Because the last co-writer died in 2010, the copyright will not expire until 2080 at the earliest. Therefore, the work is still under copyright and not in the public domain.

“Elephant ears” is a broad common name used for several large-leaved aroid genera (mainly Colocasia, Alocasia and Xanthosoma). Taro root is the edible corm of Colocasia esculenta, which is one particular species within that group. Thus taro is one kind of ‘elephant ear,’ but not every plant called elephant ear is taro; the terms are not strictly interchangeable.

Since the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in the early 1970s, the U.S. dollar has operated under a largely free-floating (market-determined) exchange-rate regime. The Federal Reserve does not peg the dollar to another currency or a basket of currencies, so the United States does not maintain a fixed exchange rate.

The current (W177) Mercedes-Benz A-Class is built on Mercedes’ MFA2 platform, which is designed for transverse engines and standard front-wheel drive. While some variants can be equipped with 4MATIC all-wheel drive, the default drivetrain layout is front-wheel drive.

The 1929 stock market crash was an important shock that undermined confidence and wiped out wealth, but historians and economists agree it was only one of several factors (banking panics, deflationary monetary policy, international debt problems, etc.) that together produced the Great Depression. Therefore, saying the crash itself 'caused' the Depression is an oversimplification.

The TV series “Once Upon a Time” was cancelled by ABC after Season 7; the 2017-2018 television season was announced as the show’s final one. Therefore, if the question is being asked during that season, the answer is yes—this is the last year/season for the show.

Historical records show that Ethiopia (then commonly referred to as Abyssinia) was admitted to the League of Nations on 28 September 1923 and remained a member throughout the 1930s, famously appealing to the League after the 1935–1936 Italian invasion. Therefore, Ethiopia was indeed a member.
The song “Footloose,” written and performed by Kenny Loggins, was commissioned specifically as the title track for the 1984 film of the same name and released on the movie’s official soundtrack.
The Tampa Bay Lightning, an NHL team, captured their first Stanley Cup championship in 2004 and added additional titles in 2020 and 2021, so they have indeed won the Stanley Cup.

Dietary proteins of either animal or plant origin are too large to cross the intestinal epithelium intact. In the digestive tract they must first be broken down by gastric, pancreatic and brush-border enzymes into amino acids and very small peptides. Only these small units are transported through enterocytes into the bloodstream (with the rare neonatal exception of antibody uptake). Therefore the human body cannot directly absorb whole animal proteins.

In Florida the general age of consent is 18, but the state has a close-in-age (“Romeo and Juliet”) exception that allows consensual sexual activity when one partner is 16 or 17 and the other partner is no more than 23 years old and not in a position of authority over the younger teen. Since an 18-year-old is only two years older than a 16-year-old, the relationship is within that exemption. Dating without sexual activity is not criminalized at any age. Therefore a 16-year-old and an 18-year-old can legally be together in Florida, provided the relationship is consensual and the older teen is not in a supervisory or custodial role over the younger teen.

‘Property tax’ is a broad, generic term for any tax levied on real property. In the UK, one form of local property taxation on domestic dwellings is called Council Tax, but there are other property-related taxes (e.g., business rates, stamp duty land tax, capital gains on property). Therefore Council Tax is a specific type of property tax, not the same thing as the whole category ‘property tax’.

Guam is an unincorporated territory of the United States. Under the Organic Act of Guam of 1950, Congress granted U.S. citizenship to persons born in Guam. Therefore, anyone born in Guam today acquires U.S. citizenship at birth (with very limited exceptions such as children of foreign diplomats, which apply the same as in the fifty states).

Red Dead Revolver (2004) was the first title in Rockstar’s western-themed franchise. Red Dead Redemption (2010) was developed by the same studio and marketed as its spiritual successor/second installment, sharing the series name, genre, and overarching universe even though their stories and characters are largely separate. Therefore the two games are indeed related as parts of the same franchise.

The question is most commonly asked about the WWE Hall of Fame when referring to “Macho Man” Randy Savage. He was posthumously inducted into the WWE Hall of Fame as part of the class of 2015, so he is indeed a Hall of Famer.

In the Just Dance scoring hierarchy, the judgements for individual moves (from lowest to highest) are typically X/Miss, OK, Good, Perfect, and then Super. Therefore, ‘Super’ is a higher (better) rating than ‘Perfect’.
Both leeks and onions belong to the genus Allium and are classified in the same botanical family (Amaryllidaceae, previously referred to as Alliaceae). Therefore they are indeed in the same family.

Yes. There have been multiple documented cases of players dying during football games. In American football, Detroit Lions wide receiver Chuck Hughes collapsed and died of a heart attack on the field in an NFL game in 1971. In association football (soccer), Cameroon midfielder Marc-Vivien Foé died after collapsing during the 2003 FIFA Confederations Cup. These and other examples confirm that fatalities have occurred during football matches.

Child psychology concentrates on the mental, emotional and behavioral development of humans from birth through adolescence. Developmental psychology, however, studies change and continuity across the entire lifespan—infancy, childhood, adolescence, adulthood and old age. Therefore, while child psychology is part of developmental psychology, the two terms are not identical.

The Great Depression, originating with the 1929 U.S. stock-market crash, quickly propagated through international trade links, gold-standard monetary ties, and capital flows. Countries in Europe, Latin America, Asia, and parts of Africa experienced sharp declines in output, employment, and prices, although severity differed by nation. Because nearly every integrated economy felt its effects, historians characterize the Depression as a worldwide phenomenon.

In the United States, the National Minimum Drinking Age Act mandates that states prohibit the purchase or public possession of alcoholic beverages by anyone under 21. Although a few states allow limited exceptions (e.g., drinking on private property with parental consent or for religious ceremonies), the general rule remains that it is illegal to consume alcohol under 21 in most circumstances.

Alaska was purchased from Russia in 1867, became a U.S. territory, and was admitted as the 49th state in 1959. It has never legally separated from the United States, so it remains part of the country today.

Several airlines operate so-called polar routes (e.g., between North America and Asia) that take advantage of great-circle paths passing near or directly over the geographic North Pole. These routes have been in regular use since the early 2000s, after regulatory, navigation, and communication advances made them practical and safe.

USA Network officially renewed the television series “Suits” for Season 8 in early 2018, and the season went on to premiere in July 2018 (followed later by a ninth and final season). Therefore, a Season 8 was indeed produced.

School uniform policies are set by individual schools or their governing bodies, not mandated nationally by law. The vast majority of UK schools—state and independent—do require uniforms, but a minority choose not to. Therefore it is incorrect to say that every UK school has uniforms.

Grouse and partridges are both ground-dwelling birds in the order Galliformes, but they belong to different taxonomic groups: grouse are generally placed in the family Phasianidae, subfamily Tetraoninae (or in their own family Tetraonidae), whereas partridges belong to the family Phasianidae, subfamily Perdicinae. They differ in morphology, habitat preferences, and behavior, so they are related but not the same bird.

The Philippines allows private individuals to possess firearms provided they meet strict requirements such as passing background checks, obtaining a License to Own and Possess Firearms (LTOPF), and registering each firearm. Therefore, firearm ownership is legal, though heavily regulated.

Humans are diphyodont, meaning they develop two successive sets of teeth. Although only the primary (baby) teeth will eventually erupt first, the buds (germs) of both the primary and the permanent teeth are already present in a baby’s jaws at birth. Thus, in a developmental sense, a baby is born with the beginnings of both sets of teeth.

Star Wars: The Last Jedi is Episode VIII of the Skywalker saga. Lucasfilm had already announced and has since released Episode IX, titled ‘Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker,’ which serves as the direct sequel to The Last Jedi. Therefore, the answer is affirmative.

The Palace of Versailles operates today as a major French national museum and tourist attraction. Visitors can buy tickets and freely tour the palace and its grounds during published opening hours, indicating that it is indeed open to the public.

Under U.S. federal law (the National Organ Transplant Act of 1984) and similar statutes in many other jurisdictions, it is illegal to buy or sell most human organs or body parts for transplantation or other purposes. While certain renewable tissues such as hair, blood, sperm, or plasma can be compensated for, the sale of non-renewable organs (kidneys, hearts, livers, etc.) is prohibited. Therefore, the blanket statement that it is legal to sell human body parts is incorrect.

The NFL approved the Raiders’ relocation from Oakland to Las Vegas in March 2017, construction of Allegiant Stadium was completed in 2020, and the team officially began play as the Las Vegas Raiders with the 2020 season. Therefore, the move is real and has already happened.

Compression fittings seal by the ferrule being squeezed between the nut and the fitting body. The seal is made on the ferrule/pipe interface, not on the threads. Adding plumber’s (PTFE/Teflon) tape to the threads is unnecessary and can actually keep the ferrule from seating properly, causing leaks. Therefore the statement "You should use plumber’s tape on compression fittings" is incorrect.
Tomatoes (genus Solanum) and peppers (genus Capsicum) are both members of the nightshade family, Solanaceae, so they do belong to the same botanical family.

Oklahoma’s self-defense statute (21 O.S. § 1289.25), enacted in 2006, explicitly states that a person has no duty to retreat and may use deadly force if they reasonably believe it is necessary to prevent death or great bodily harm. This language establishes a stand-your-ground policy in the state.

Kansas City, Kansas (abbreviated KCK) and Kansas City, Missouri (KCMO) are legally distinct municipalities located in two different U.S. states, separated by the Missouri–Kansas state line. While they form part of a single metropolitan area and share the name “Kansas City,” each has its own city government, boundaries, and incorporation history. Therefore, they are not the same city.

“Everybody’s All-American” is a fictional novel by sportswriter Frank Deford that was later adapted into a 1988 film. Although Deford drew on general themes and composite experiences of real college-football stars, the characters and events—including protagonist Gavin Grey—are inventions, not portrayals of an actual person’s life. Therefore it is not a true, factual story.

In everyday and industrial usage, the terms ‘activated charcoal’ and ‘activated carbon’ are used interchangeably. Both refer to a highly porous, adsorptive form of carbon produced by “activating” a carbon-rich material (e.g., wood, coal, coconut shell) with heat and/or chemicals. While ‘charcoal’ historically implies a wood-derived feedstock and ‘carbon’ can come from a wider variety of sources, the activation process yields the same porous carbon structure and the same functional properties, so for practical purposes they are the same material.

The 1993 film 'Jurassic Park' was followed directly by 'The Lost World: Jurassic Park' (1997) and 'Jurassic Park III' (2001). 'Jurassic World' (2015) is the fourth installment in the overall franchise and serves as a soft reboot set years after the original trilogy, but it is not the immediate or direct sequel to the first film.

In the television series ‘The Vampire Diaries,’ Elena Gilbert and Damon Salvatore progress from antagonists to friends and eventually lovers. Beginning in season 4 they officially start dating, and by the series finale they end up together and live a long, human life as a couple. Therefore, Elena does indeed ‘get with’ Damon in the show.

The European Union (EU) is a political and economic union made up primarily of European countries. The United States is a separate sovereign nation located in North America and has never been a member of the EU.

In contemporary English, the noun ‘actor’ is considered gender-neutral and is commonly applied to performers of any gender, though ‘actress’ is still sometimes used specifically for women. Therefore, it is correct to use ‘actor’ for females.

“Spring fever” is not a formal medical diagnosis, but the term is commonly used to describe real, documented physical and psychological changes that many people experience when winter ends and days lengthen. Longer daylight boosts serotonin and vitamin-D synthesis, temperatures rise, people become more active, and pollen/allergy levels change. Studies show measurable shifts in mood, energy, sleep patterns, and even immune activity tied to seasonal changes. Therefore, while it is colloquial, the phenomenon it refers to is real.

The 2000 Disney film "Remember the Titans" was written as an original screenplay by Gregory Allen Howard and is inspired by real events surrounding the 1971 T.C. Williams High School football team in Alexandria, Virginia. It was not adapted from or based on any prior book.
Beyoncé contributed guest vocals to Coldplay’s single “Hymn for the Weekend” and also appears in the official music video, making her part of the song’s recording.

.17 HMR bullets have a diameter of about 0.172 inch, whereas .22 LR bullets are about 0.222-0.223 inch in diameter. Although the .17 HMR case is longer and it delivers higher velocity and energy, the actual bullet (caliber) is smaller. Therefore, in terms of caliber size, a .17 HMR is not bigger than a .22 LR.

The .org top-level domain was originally intended for non-profit organizations, but the registration rules were never restricted to that use. Anyone—individuals, for-profit companies, or non-profits—can register a .org domain today, so holding a .org address does not require non-profit status.

South Africa has a mixed legal system that combines elements of English common law and its earlier Roman-Dutch civil law heritage. The Roman-Dutch component was never repealed; it continues to operate as the country’s underlying common law and is applied by the courts except where it has been altered or superseded by legislation or constitutional principles. Therefore, Roman-Dutch law still forms an essential part of South African law today.

The Strait of Gibraltar separates Morocco and Spain by about 14 kilometres at its narrowest point. While there have been proposals for a bridge or a tunnel, none has been built. At present the only regular connections are by ferry and air; there is no physical bridge linking the two countries.

After the 1993 murder of James Bulger there was heavy media pressure and the distributor temporarily withdrew the video from shops, but the British Board of Film Classification never revoked or refused a certificate. The film has always been legally classified (18) and therefore was not officially banned in the UK.

In the Countdown numbers round you are given six source numbers, but the rules state you may use any, all, or none of them to reach (or get as close as possible to) the target. Therefore it is not obligatory to use every number provided.

To enter Canada, most travelers—including U.S. service members on personal trips—must present a valid passport (or other WHTI-compliant document such as a passport card or NEXUS card). A U.S. military ID by itself is accepted only when the service member is traveling on official military orders under the Status of Forces Agreement; it does not work for ordinary leisure or personal travel. Therefore, for typical travel, a military ID alone will not get you into Canada.
