Under the current NBA collective bargaining agreement and draft eligibility rules, a U.S. player must be at least 19 years old during the calendar year of the draft and at least one NBA season removed from his high-school graduating class. Therefore, players can no longer jump directly from high school to the NBA (the last class able to do so was in 2005). They must first spend a year elsewhere (college, G-League, overseas, etc.) before entering the draft.

For observers in the Southern Hemisphere the Sun’s apparent position at midday is toward the north, so sunlight comes from the north.  Even in the Northern Hemisphere, near the Tropic of Cancer or above the Arctic Circle, there are times (e.g., around the summer solstice) when the Sun can appear slightly north of the zenith or circle around the horizon and thus shine from a northerly direction.  Therefore, while it does not happen for mid- and high-latitude Northern-Hemisphere observers during most of the year, the Sun can indeed shine from the north depending on location and season.
ABC officially announced the renewal of Grey’s Anatomy for a 14th season, and production/premiere dates have already been set, so the statement that there is going to be a 14th season is accurate.

Across all Australian states and territories the legal minimum age to purchase alcohol or consume it in licensed venues and public places is 18. Some jurisdictions allow a person aged 16‒17 to drink under direct parental supervision in a private residence, but the general rule – and what most people mean when they ask – is that you cannot legally drink alcohol at 16 in Australia.
The creators released an official alternate ending on the Season 9 DVD/Blu-ray set (and later online) that differs from the broadcast finale, so an alternative ending does exist.

All Australian states and the ACT permit altruistic (non-commercial) surrogacy arrangements, although commercial surrogacy is prohibited. Therefore it is legally possible to have a surrogate mother in Australia provided the arrangement complies with the relevant state or territory laws.

Commercial law is a broad field that governs business and commercial transactions in general, including sales of goods, secured transactions, negotiable instruments, and broader mercantile activities. Corporate law is a sub-field that focuses specifically on the formation, governance, and dissolution of corporations (e.g., shareholders’ rights, directors’ duties, mergers). Therefore, while related, they are not the same; corporate law is just one part of the wider commercial law landscape.

The 2007 film “The Golden Compass” was originally planned as the first in a trilogy, but disappointing U.S. box-office results and production difficulties caused the planned sequels to be cancelled. Therefore, no second movie was ever produced or released, although the story has since been adapted as a television series (“His Dark Materials”).

Humans have completed 24-hour ultramarathon races where participants run continuously (aside from brief stops) for the entire 24-hour period. While it requires exceptional endurance training and conditioning, it is physically possible and regularly documented in endurance sports.

The 2018 FIFA World Cup was held in Russia. In CONCACAF qualifying, Trinidad and Tobago finished last in the final ‘Hexagonal’ round and were eliminated from contention. Therefore, they did not qualify for the 2018 World Cup.

Ronnie O’Sullivan was one of the top-16 seeded players and did take part in the 2016 Betfred World Snooker Championship at the Crucible Theatre, where he reached the second round (losing 13-12 to Barry Hawkins). Therefore, he was indeed ‘in’ the 2016 World Championship.

In the 2014 “Burma Special,” the Top Gear presenters (with a team of hired local workers and production staff) constructed a wooden bridge over the River Kok in northern Thailand, which they referred to as the River Kwai. The bridge was genuine and strong enough for their lorries to drive across, although it was dismantled after filming. Therefore, yes, they really did build a bridge over the river, even if it was a temporary structure and involved considerable off-screen assistance.

“La Casa de Papel” is the original Spanish title of the television series that is marketed in English-speaking regions under the title “Money Heist.” They refer to the same show, just in different languages.

In everyday culinary usage the terms refer to the same product: beef that has been run through a mincer/grinder into small particles. ‘Ground beef’ is the common North-American term, while ‘minced beef’ is widely used in the U.K. and other Commonwealth countries. Although minor regional regulations over fat content or the method of chopping can vary, for practical purposes they denote the same thing.
The Syfy television series “The Magicians” is an adaptation of Lev Grossman’s fantasy novel trilogy that begins with the book “The Magicians.” Therefore, the show is indeed based on a book.

Around the release of their 2017 album “Wake Up Call,” the Canadian rock band Theory of a Deadman announced that they would market themselves simply as “Theory.” Band members said the change was meant to be a streamlined re-branding rather than a legal name change; they still acknowledge the full name but use “Theory” in most current promotion and artwork.
Answer: They have shortened their public/branding name to “Theory,” though the legal name Theory of a Deadman has not been completely abandoned.

Reasoning: Besides delivering checkmate, a player can also win if the opponent resigns, runs out of time, is defaulted/forfeited, or in some rule-sets makes an illegal move that ends the game. Therefore checkmate is not the sole path to victory.

Old Navy is a brand that was launched by and remains a subsidiary of Gap Inc., the same parent company that operates the Gap brand. Therefore, both Old Navy and Gap are owned by the same corporate entity.

A dairy cow begins to lactate only after giving birth to a calf. She produces milk for roughly 10 months (the lactation period) and is then ‘dried off’ for about 2 months before the next calving. Therefore, milk production is cyclic, not continuous throughout the cow’s life.

Drag is the resistive force an object experiences when moving through any fluid (liquid or gas). Air resistance is a particular form of drag that occurs when the fluid is specifically air. Thus, while air resistance is a drag force, the term “drag force” is broader and can also refer to resistance in water or other fluids, so they are not strictly the same.

Since February 2017, New Hampshire has been a constitutional-carry state. Anyone who is legally allowed to possess a firearm may carry it, openly or concealed, without first obtaining a state-issued license. (Permits are still available on a voluntary basis for reciprocity with other states.) Therefore, a license is not required to carry within New Hampshire itself.

Ritz-Carlton is a luxury hotel brand owned by Marriott International, while Four Seasons is an independent Canadian hotel management company (major shareholders include Cascade Investment and Kingdom Holding). They are separate corporate entities with no ownership or management relationship.

Electrons possess a non-zero rest mass. According to special relativity, any particle with rest mass would require infinite energy to be accelerated to the speed of light in vacuum (c). Therefore, while electrons can be accelerated to speeds arbitrarily close to c, they can never actually reach or exceed it.

Kentucky’s self-defense statute (KRS § 503.050) explicitly states that a person who is not engaged in unlawful activity and is in a place where he or she has a right to be ‘has no duty to retreat’ before using force, including deadly force, if the statutory conditions for self-defense are met. This language fits the common definition of a “stand-your-ground” law. The statute was enacted in 2006 as part of a broader castle-doctrine/stand-your-ground bill and remains in effect.

Rick Riordan followed the original five-book Percy Jackson & the Olympians series with another five-book series, The Heroes of Olympus, which continues events in the same world and features many of the same characters. Therefore, a sequel series does exist.

Most casino games are designed with a built-in house edge, but skilled or advantage play can occasionally reverse this. Examples include card counting and shuffle-tracking in blackjack, playing only ‘full-pay’ video-poker machines with perfect strategy, exploiting generous promotions or match-play coupons, and poker where players compete against each other rather than the house. These situations are rare and require skill, discipline, or favorable conditions, but they prove that a player can sometimes gain a positive expected value.

A hole-in-one on a par-5 is called a “condor.” While it has never happened in top-level professional play, a handful of verified instances are on record in casual or club play. Examples include Larry Bruce’s ace on a 480-yard par-5 in Hope, Arkansas (1962), Shaun Lynch’s 496-yard ace at Teign Valley, England (1995), and Mike Crean’s 517-yard ace at Green Valley Ranch, Colorado (2002). Therefore, yes—although extraordinarily rare—people have recorded holes-in-one on par-5 holes.

The two terms are often used interchangeably in popular speech, but in psychology they describe different (and unequally supported) phenomena. Eidetic memory refers to a short-lived, vivid after-image that some people—mostly children—can voluntarily inspect for seconds to minutes after the stimulus is removed. ‘Photographic memory,’ on the other hand, is popularly supposed to be a permanent, unlimited, exact visual recall; no scientific evidence has verified that such an ability exists. Because they describe abilities with different durations, mechanisms, and levels of scientific support, they are not the same.

New York and New Jersey are two separate, neighboring states in the United States. They have different governments, boundaries, and capitals (Albany for New York and Trenton for New Jersey). Therefore, they are not the same state.

The Dominican Republic is an independent nation that occupies the eastern portion of the island of Hispaniola in the Caribbean. Mexico is a separate sovereign country located in North America, thousands of kilometers away. The Dominican Republic has never been politically or territorially part of Mexico.

Middle-earth: Shadow of Mordor is set in the years between The Hobbit and The Lord of the Rings, i.e., before the main events of LOTR begin. Therefore, the game’s storyline takes place prior to the events of The Lord of the Rings.

New Line Cinema originally planned to adapt the remaining books in Philip Pullman’s ‘His Dark Materials’ trilogy after releasing ‘The Golden Compass’ in 2007. However, because the film under-performed at the U.S. box office and drew controversy, the studio cancelled those plans. No follow-up film was ever produced or released, so the 2007 movie has no cinematic sequel.

By definition, a square is a quadrilateral that has both four equal sides and four right angles. If a figure with four equal sides lacked right angles, it would instead be a rhombus, not a square. Therefore, having right angles is a necessary property of a square.

Both algorithms have an O(n²) worst-case time complexity, but insertion sort is adaptive: if the input is already partially ordered it can run much faster (as good as O(n) for nearly-sorted data). Selection sort, in contrast, always performs the same Θ(n²) comparisons and is not adaptive. In practice, insertion sort also makes at most n-1 swaps, while selection sort makes n−1 swaps plus the full set of comparisons, so insertion sort is generally regarded as the more efficient of the two.

In U.S. butchery, the section of ribs cut from the upper portion of a pig’s ribcage (next to the loin) is officially called “loin back ribs” or simply “back ribs.” When these ribs come from younger, smaller hogs they are marketed as “baby back ribs,” but they are the same anatomical cut; only the size differs. Therefore, in common usage, ‘back ribs’ and ‘baby back ribs’ refer to the same rib section.
The Showtime historical drama "The Tudors" officially ran for four seasons between 2007 and 2010 and concluded with the death of Henry VIII. No additional, fifth season was produced or released.

In the 2011 film "A Little Bit of Heaven," the main character, Marley Corbett (played by Kate Hudson), is diagnosed with terminal cancer early in the story. The narrative follows her coming to terms with her illness and saying goodbye to loved ones. In the film’s final act, Marley ultimately succumbs to her cancer, and her death is depicted on screen. Therefore, Marley does die in the movie.
Canada competes in international men’s association football; the squad is officially known as the Canada men’s national soccer team and is governed by Canada Soccer. Therefore, such a team exists.

The statutory ‘Right to Buy’ that guaranteed council tenants the ability to purchase their home at a discount was only created by the Housing Act 1980, which came into force after the 1979 general election. Although a handful of local authorities chose to sell small numbers of properties earlier, there was no general right for tenants to buy their council house before 1979, so for most tenants the answer would have been no.

A postal code is a generic term for the series of letters and/or numbers used by a country’s postal service to identify delivery areas. “ZIP code” (Zone Improvement Plan) is the specific name given to the United States postal code system. Therefore, while every ZIP code is a postal code, not every postal code is a ZIP code, so the two terms are not strictly interchangeable.

The Tour de France is an annual cycling Grand Tour. While the race always lasts about three weeks in July and finishes in Paris, the detailed route—cities visited, sequence and profile of stages, mountain climbs, and time trials—is redesigned each year. Therefore each edition is different in its stages and course, even though the overall format remains consistent.

A solar cell is a single photovoltaic device that converts sunlight into electricity. A solar panel (or module) is an assembly of many solar cells wired together and encapsulated in a protective frame to generate higher power. Thus, while related, they are not the same thing.

In Andy Weir’s novel and the film adaptation “The Martian,” astronaut Mark Watney is stranded on Mars but is ultimately rescued by the Hermes crew and shown back on Earth afterward, indicating he does indeed make it home.

Traditionally, the New York City subway operates all day and night, offering service 24 hours every day, although frequencies are lower late at night. (There was a temporary overnight shutdown during part of the COVID-19 pandemic, but regular 24-hour service has since resumed.)

By definition an adiabatic process involves no heat exchange (Q = 0). The first-law relation then reduces to ΔU = −W, so any change in internal energy must come from work done by or on the system. Therefore, work can indeed be done during an adiabatic process; the absence of heat transfer does not forbid work.

The Dulles Toll Road (VA-267) toll plazas accept E-ZPass transponders and cash (coins/bills) in staffed or exact-change lanes. They do not have credit/debit card readers at the plazas, so motorists cannot pay with a credit card on the road itself.

The 2011 film "We Bought a Zoo" is adapted from Benjamin Mee’s memoir detailing his real-life purchase and restoration of what became Dartmoor Zoological Park in Devon, England. Although the movie changes some details (e.g., setting it in the United States and adding fictionalized drama), its core premise is drawn from Mee’s true experience, so it is fundamentally based on a true story.

Because the equator is aligned roughly perpendicular to Earth’s axis of rotation, the Sun’s apparent path crosses close to straight overhead year-round. Consequently the interval between sunrise and sunset stays very close to 12 hours every day, varying by only a few minutes through the seasons, unlike the large seasonal swings in daylight seen at higher latitudes.

Keyless entry lets you lock/unlock the vehicle without inserting a physical key, usually via a fob or keypad. Remote start is a separate feature that allows you to start the engine from a distance so the car can warm up or cool down before you get in. Because they perform different functions, they are not the same feature.

The Czech Republic’s official currency is the Czech koruna (CZK). The euro is not legal tender there; while certain tourist-oriented businesses near borders or in major cities might accept euros, it is not generally usable for everyday transactions and change is usually given in koruna. Therefore, as a rule you cannot rely on using the euro in the Czech Republic.

In clinical practice, the term “normal saline” refers specifically to an isotonic solution containing 0.9 % (w/v) sodium chloride in water (9 g of NaCl per liter). Therefore, when someone says 0.9 % sodium chloride solution, they are describing the same formulation as normal saline.

Mickey’s and Minnie’s houses were part of Mickey’s Toontown Fair in the Magic Kingdom. That land closed permanently in 2011 and was rethemed into Storybook Circus as part of the New Fantasyland expansion. The houses were removed and are no longer present in the park.

In the Australian federal system, the six states (New South Wales, Victoria, Queensland, South Australia, Western Australia and Tasmania) all retained their colonial constitutions at Federation in 1901. These constitutions now operate as Acts passed by, and amendable by, each state’s own parliament. Territories instead have self-government statutes enacted by the Commonwealth, not constitutions in the same sense.

Doctor Doctor, the Australian drama series (titled The Heart Guy in some regions), was renewed beyond its third season. Season 4 was produced in 2019 and aired on the Nine Network beginning in February 2020, so a fourth season does exist.

Observations with the Hubble Space Telescope show that the Andromeda galaxy (M31) is moving toward the Milky Way at roughly 110 km/s. Dynamical models that include the measured transverse motion predict that the two galaxies will merge in about 4–5 billion years, making a collision essentially inevitable barring unforeseen gravitational perturbations. Other smaller galaxies (e.g., the Large and Small Magellanic Clouds) are also on interacting trajectories, but the Andromeda encounter is the major future collision event.

“Cruel Intentions” (1999) is a standalone feature film set in an elite New York prep school and follows step-siblings Kathryn and Sebastian in a story loosely based on “Les Liaisons dangereuses.” “Cruel Intentions 2” (2000), also called “Manchester Prep,” is a direct-to-video prequel assembled from episodes of an unrealized TV series and shows the characters’ earlier days. The two movies were produced and released separately, have different casts for several roles, and tell different, sequential stories. Therefore they are not the same film.

During World War I, the U.S. Army and other branches maintained racially segregated units. African-American troops were organized into separate divisions such as the 92nd and 93rd, usually led by white officers, and faced unequal treatment and restrictions on combat roles. Full racial integration of the U.S. armed forces did not begin until President Truman’s Executive Order 9981 in 1948, well after WWI.

According to the game’s lore and the dates given via Phone Guy’s calls and other clues, the events of Five Nights at Freddy’s 2 take place in 1987, whereas the original Five Nights at Freddy’s is set in the early 1990s. Therefore, although FNaF 2 was released later, its story occurs earlier, making it a prequel.

Although Ireland is a member of the EU, it is not part of the Schengen Area. Entry to Schengen countries and entry to Ireland are governed by separate visa regimes. Therefore a visa issued under the Schengen Agreement does not grant permission to enter Ireland; travelers who need a visa generally must obtain an Irish visa (unless they qualify under a specific program such as the British-Irish Visa Scheme or have another form of permission).

The U.S. Navy’s Blue Angels flight demonstration squadron has existed since 1946, and over the decades there have been several mishaps, including fatal crashes during practices and air-shows (e.g., crashes in 1952, 1999, 2007, 2016, etc.). Therefore, accidents have indeed occurred.

The United Kingdom held a referendum in 2016 in which a majority voted to leave the European Union. Following negotiations and the ratification of the Withdrawal Agreement, the UK formally exited the EU on 31 January 2020.

In biological classification, the common house mouse (genus Mus) and the common rats (genus Rattus) are both placed within the family Muridae (subfamily Murinae). Therefore, they do share the same family, even though they belong to different genera.

“Fifty Shades Darker” (2017) is the second film in the Fifty Shades trilogy. The third installment, “Fifty Shades Freed,” was released in 2018, so there is indeed another movie that follows “Fifty Shades Darker.”

The Sears Tower (now called Willis Tower) was the world’s tallest building from 1973 until 1998. It has since been surpassed by numerous taller skyscrapers such as the Burj Khalifa, Shanghai Tower, Abraj Al-Bait Clock Tower, and others. Therefore, it is no longer the tallest building in the world.

In building‐materials terminology, “hydrated lime” (also called non-hydraulic or air lime) is calcium hydroxide produced by slaking quicklime; it hardens only by reacting with carbon dioxide in air. “Hydraulic lime” is produced from limestone containing clay/silica; the resulting lime contains calcium silicates/aluminates that let it set in the presence of water. Because their compositions and setting mechanisms differ, they are not the same material.

Halo 2 was released for the original Xbox, and when played on an Xbox 360 through backward compatibility it retains its original feature set. Achievements were introduced with Xbox 360 titles and were never retrofitted to original Xbox games. Therefore, Halo 2 does not have achievements on Xbox 360 (though later versions such as Halo 2 Vista or Halo 2 Anniversary in the Master Chief Collection do).

U.S. marriage law is governed primarily by state statutes, all of which prohibit polygamy (being simultaneously married to more than one person). Entering a second legal marriage while still married to someone else constitutes bigamy, which is a criminal offense in every state and is not recognized as valid. Therefore, a person cannot legally marry more than one spouse at the same time in the United States.

The television series Marvel’s Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D. continued after season 5, receiving renewals for season 6 and a final season 7, which concluded the show in 2020. Therefore, season 5 was not the last season.
“Here Comes the Sun” was written by George Harrison and released by The Beatles on their 1969 album Abbey Road, so it is indeed a Beatles song.

The prostate is a male reproductive gland whose secretions enter the urethra via ducts, making it an exocrine (ducted) gland. It is classified as part of the male reproductive system, not the endocrine system, which is composed of ductless glands that release hormones directly into the bloodstream.

In most U.S. jurisdictions, a moving violation is an offense that relates to the way the vehicle is operated while it is in motion (e.g., speeding, running a red light). A citation for driving without proof of insurance—or for failing to carry insurance—is generally classified as an administrative or equipment-related offense. It does not involve the manner in which the vehicle was being driven, so it is usually categorized as a non-moving violation, even though it can carry significant fines and penalties.

In Canadian banking a complete routing number is made up of two parts: a 5-digit transit (branch) number and a 3-digit institution (bank) number. The transit number identifies the specific branch, while the institution number identifies the financial institution as a whole. Therefore, a transit number is not the same as an institution number—they are different identifiers that are merely used together.

The usual intent of the question is whether any World War I veterans are still alive. The last verified WWI service member, Florence Green (UK), died in 2012, and the last combat veteran, Claude Choules (Australia/UK), died in 2011. While a few non-veteran super-centenarians who were born during the WWI years are still alive, no one who actually served in the war survives.
"I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings" is Maya Angelou’s first of a series of autobiographical works. It recounts her childhood and early teenage years, making it an autobiographical memoir.

Motherhood Maternity is one of the clothing brands (and store chains) owned by Destination Maternity Corporation. Destination Maternity was the parent company and also used its own “Destination Maternity” super-store format that carried several of its brands, including Motherhood Maternity and A Pea in the Pod. Therefore the two names are related but not identical: Destination Maternity is/was the corporate and umbrella store name, while Motherhood Maternity is a specific brand operated by that company.

Edinburgh City Council has a local by-law that prohibits the consumption of alcohol in public places (streets, parks, etc.) unless a specific licence or exemption is in force (for example during certain organised events). Police can confiscate the alcohol and issue a fixed-penalty notice. Therefore, as a general rule, it is not legal to drink alcohol in public in Edinburgh.

A single transverse palmar (simian) crease is a common minor physical feature in Down syndrome, but it is not universal. Studies show it occurs in roughly 40-60 % of individuals with trisomy 21, so many affected babies do not have it.

In the original 1960s TV series “Lost in Space,” the B-9 Robot frequently speaks, delivering memorable lines such as “Danger, Will Robinson!” The robot also talks in later adaptations, including the 1998 film and the recent Netflix series. Therefore, the robot in Lost in Space does indeed talk.

Palm kernel oil is extracted from the seed (kernel) of the oil-palm fruit (Elaeis guineensis), whereas coconut oil comes from the meat of coconuts (Cocos nucifera). Although both are ‘lauric’ oils with similar fatty-acid profiles and can sometimes be substituted in recipes or industry, they originate from different plants and differ in flavor, aroma, and some physical properties. Therefore, they are not the same oil.

The original 1965 television series “Lost in Space,” created by Irwin Allen, was not a straight adaptation of a single novel, but its premise was explicitly inspired by Johann David Wyss’s 1812 novel “The Swiss Family Robinson” (and also resembles the earlier ‘Space Family Robinson’ comic). Because of this acknowledged inspiration, it can be said that the concept is loosely based on a book, though not formally adapted from one specific text word-for-word.

Ross-on-Wye once had a railway station, but it was closed in the 1960s (Beeching cuts). No National Rail services stop in the town today; the nearest open stations are in Hereford and Gloucester. Therefore, Ross-on-Wye does not currently have an operational train station.

The eye is a complex structure composed of multiple tissues that work together to enable vision. In anatomy and physiology, it is classified as one of the body’s sensory organs (specifically, a sense organ for sight). Therefore, eyes are indeed organs of the human body.

The Kentucky Derby is scheduled for the first Saturday in May each year, so the exact calendar date changes. When the first Saturday happens to fall on May 5, the Derby is on May 5, but in most years it falls on another date (e.g., May 1, May 2, May 6, etc.). Therefore, it is not always on May 5.

Submarine fiber-optic cables have been laid across the Atlantic since the 19th-century telegraph era and today carry the vast majority of trans-Atlantic internet traffic. Therefore, such cables unquestionably exist under the Atlantic Ocean.

Although extremely rare, a woman can release two eggs during the same menstrual cycle and then have intercourse with two different men in a short time window. Each egg can be fertilized by sperm from a different man, resulting in twins who are half-siblings genetically rather than full siblings. This phenomenon is called heteropaternal superfecundation and has been documented in genetic testing and medical literature.

Pet Supplies Plus is a national pet-supply chain that markets itself as pet-friendly and even offers in-store grooming and self-wash stations. The company’s policy is that customers may bring their pets into the store as long as the animals are leashed, safely restrained, and well-behaved. Individual locations could have minor variations (e.g., local health ordinances), but in general the answer is yes.

In kinship terminology, a parent’s half-brother (they share only one parent) is distinguished from a full brother. That man is still your uncle, but more precisely your half-uncle. The term is used in genealogy even if it is not common in everyday speech.

WSL comes in two major versions. WSL 1 runs Linux user-mode binaries as ‘pico-processes’ that call into a Windows translation layer; no full Linux kernel or hypervisor-backed VM is involved, so it is not a virtual machine. WSL 2, on the other hand, does run an actual Linux kernel inside a small, managed Hyper-V virtual machine. Because the original/overall feature is often referred to generically as WSL and many users still run or think of WSL 1, the blanket statement that “WSL is a virtual machine” is at best only partially correct. Given an unqualified yes/no question, the more accurate single answer is “False,” while noting the nuance that WSL 2 does employ virtualization.
Carmelo Anthony’s Denver Nuggets advanced to the 2009 NBA Western Conference Finals, where they played the Los Angeles Lakers. Therefore, he has indeed appeared in a Western Conference Finals series.

Astronauts on the International Space Station have conducted many experiments in plant biology—such as the Veggie system, Advanced Plant Habitat, and earlier Lada and Biomass Production experiments—to study how plants grow in microgravity and to supplement crew diets with fresh produce. Therefore, plants are actively cultivated on the ISS.

The Try Guys began as a BuzzFeed video series in 2014 but announced their departure from BuzzFeed in mid-2018 to form their own independent production company, 2nd Try LLC. Since then they have produced content entirely outside of BuzzFeed. Therefore, they no longer work for BuzzFeed.

For events where the President, Vice-President and other top officials gather (e.g., State of the Union, presidential inaugurations), one Cabinet-level official is deliberately kept at a secure, undisclosed location so that the constitutional line of succession is preserved in the event of a catastrophe. This practice, informally called having a “designated survivor,” has been in place for decades and is publicly acknowledged by the U.S. government.

The black and yellow garden spider (Argiope aurantia) does have venom it uses to subdue its insect prey, but that venom is not medically significant to people. Bites are rare and, when they occur, usually result in no more than mild, transient pain and swelling similar to a bee sting. Therefore, it is not considered poisonous or dangerous to humans in the normal sense of the word.

The BBC period drama “The Paradise” aired only two series (2012–2013). In early 2014 the BBC confirmed it had been cancelled and no renewal or revival has since been announced. Therefore, a third season is not planned.
The leafy tops of beet plants, often called beet greens, are commonly cooked or eaten raw in salads and are known to be nutritious. They are not poisonous and are widely recognized as edible.

In DC Comics canon, particularly since the 2011 New 52 relaunch and in various animated films and the live-action Justice League movie, Victor Stone (Cyborg) is depicted as an official, core member of the Justice League.
Scotiabank is the trading name used by The Bank of Nova Scotia; they refer to the same financial institution incorporated as The Bank of Nova Scotia and branded globally as Scotiabank.

The Tower of Pisa was designed in the 12th century as a vertical freestanding bell tower for the cathedral of Pisa. Its tilt began during construction due to an inadequate foundation and soft sub-soil, not by design. Historical records show builders attempted various corrections to reduce or stop the tilt, confirming it was unintended.
Mount Fuji’s elevation is 3,776 m, whereas the tallest mountain in the world above sea level is Mount Everest at 8,848 m. Therefore, Mount Fuji is not the tallest.

Yes. According to Brønsted–Lowry or Lewis definitions, some substances can donate a proton (act as an acid) in one reaction and accept a proton (act as a base) in another. Such substances are called amphoteric. A classic example is water (H₂O), which can donate H⁺ to become OH⁻ or accept H⁺ to become H₃O⁺. Other examples include bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻), amino acids, and Al(OH)₃. Therefore, a single compound can exhibit both acidic and basic behavior depending on its reaction partner and conditions.

CBS officially renewed Criminal Minds for a 13th season on May 6, 2016, and the season subsequently premiered in September 2017. Therefore, the answer to whether there is (or will be) a season 13 is yes.

In the 1997 film Mortal Kombat: Annihilation, Johnny Cage is killed very early in the story by Shao Kahn after being taken hostage; his neck is snapped on-screen. Therefore, yes, he dies in that movie.

The sirloin primal is divided into ‘top sirloin’ (the upper, more tender portion) and ‘bottom sirloin’ (which includes tri-tip, ball-tip, flap, etc.). A steak labeled simply “sirloin” could come from either part, often the less-tender bottom portion, whereas a “top sirloin steak” must come from the top section. Therefore they are related but not automatically identical cuts.

When a reactor core overheats, any residual or re-introduced coolant water can flash to steam almost instantaneously. The sudden, extremely rapid volume expansion of steam can create high pressures capable of causing an explosive event (a ‘steam explosion’ or ‘steam-water interaction’). Such phenomena have occurred or been considered credible in severe nuclear accidents (e.g., Chernobyl, Fukushima analyses). Therefore, there is indeed a danger of a steam explosion if the reactor core becomes overheated.

The 1994 film 'Pulp Fiction' is an original, nonlinear crime story written by Quentin Tarantino and Roger Avary. It is a work of fiction that pays homage to pulp magazines and crime films; it is not drawn from or intended to depict real historical events or true stories.

In the standard family of Rummy games, a player’s turn begins by taking one card either from the face-down stock or the face-up discard pile. Only the top (most recently discarded) card can be taken, but this is allowed in virtually all common variants (Gin Rummy, 500 Rummy, Basic Rummy, etc.). A few house rules or uncommon variants might restrict this, yet the generally accepted rules permit drawing from the discard pile.

All Intel Core 2 processors (including the Core 2 Duo line) implement Intel 64 (EM64T) instruction set extensions, allowing them to run 64-bit operating systems and applications. Earlier ‘Core Duo’ mobile chips were 32-bit, but every ‘Core 2 Duo’ model is 64-bit capable.

Shadowhunters is an American TV series adapted from Cassandra Clare’s young-adult fantasy novels collectively known as “The Mortal Instruments.” Because the show’s storyline and characters originate from those books, it is indeed based on a book series.

answer: Usually no, except for salaries that represent direct production labor, which are included in COGS.
Reasoning: Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) includes only costs that are directly tied to producing or acquiring the goods that were sold. Direct labor—wages or salaries paid to workers who actually manufacture the product—does belong in COGS. However, most other salaries (administrative, sales, executive, etc.) are period expenses recorded as SG&A, not COGS. Therefore, ‘salary’ in general is not automatically part of COGS; only the portion that is direct production labor is included.
Answer: Usually no, except for salaries that represent direct production labor, which are included in COGS.

Reasoning: Pennsylvania state liquor stores were once closed on Sundays, but laws have changed (e.g., Act 39 of 2016). Now many Fine Wine & Good Spirits stores have Sunday hours (typically 11 a.m.–7 p.m.), so purchasing liquor on Sunday is allowed, though not every store is open and hours are limited.

While hundreds of distinct sign languages exist worldwide, they do not map one-to-one with political borders. Some sign languages are used across several countries (e.g., American Sign Language in the U.S. and English-speaking parts of Canada; French Sign Language varieties in parts of Europe and Africa). A few small or recently established countries have no indigenous sign language and primarily use one imported from elsewhere. Therefore the statement that every country has its own sign language is not correct.

Domesticated skunks are kept as pets in some jurisdictions, provided they are captive-bred, descented, and the owner obtains any required wildlife or exotic-animal permits. However, many states, provinces, and countries ban private ownership outright or impose strict regulations. So in principle it is possible to have a skunk as a pet, but only where local law allows and with proper permits and care expertise.

In UK law there is no specific offence that expressly forbids motorists from flashing their headlights to warn other drivers of a speed-trap or police presence. The Highway Code (rule 110) says headlights should be flashed only to warn others of your presence, so using them for any other purpose is technically a breach of the Code, but the Code itself is not law. Prosecutions have occasionally been attempted under the wider offence of ‘obstructing a constable in the execution of his duty’ (Police Act 1996, s.89), yet courts have generally been reluctant to convict unless the prosecution can show the flashing actually hindered a specific police operation. Therefore, while it could potentially lead to an obstruction charge in particular circumstances, simply flashing headlights to warn of police is not automatically or categorically illegal in the UK.

Both the original 1996 Fargo film and the later television series begin with a title card claiming that the events depicted are true. However, the creators (the Coen Brothers for the film and Noah Hawley for the series) have stated in interviews that the stories and characters are entirely fictional; the “true story” claim is only used as a stylistic device. Therefore, the TV show is not actually based on real events.

answer: No, attending The Citadel does not obligate you to enter the military (unless you have a specific scholarship/contract).
Reasoning: The Citadel is a senior military college with mandatory participation in the Corps of Cadets and ROTC classes, but commissioning into the armed forces is voluntary unless a student has accepted an ROTC scholarship or other military contract. Many graduates pursue civilian careers.
Answer: No, attending The Citadel does not obligate you to enter the military (unless you have a specific scholarship/contract).

Reasoning: In statistics, variance measures the average of the squared deviations from the mean, while the standard deviation is the square root of the variance. Because one is the square of the other, they are related but not the same quantity.

Botanically, both peach (Prunus persica) and almond (Prunus dulcis) are members of the genus Prunus within the rose family, Rosaceae (sometimes informally called the “almond family” in casual language). Therefore, peaches are indeed in the same taxonomic family as almonds.
Honey bees (genus Apis) and bumble bees (genus Bombus) are distinct types of bees. They differ in taxonomy, appearance, life cycle, colony size, and behavior—so they are not the same insect.
Lions belong to the biological family Felidae (the cat family), whereas dogs belong to the family Canidae. Since they are classified under different families, a lion is not part of the dog family.

The 1st-generation iPad mini is built on the 32-bit Apple A5 chip. Apple ended 32-bit device support with iOS 10, and official documentation lists the iPad mini (1st gen) as being limited to iOS 9.3.5/9.3.6. Therefore it cannot be updated to iOS 10.

The 2006 animated film “The Girl Who Leapt Through Time” was produced by the studio Madhouse and directed by Mamoru Hosoda. Studio Ghibli had no involvement in its production. Earlier live-action versions were likewise produced by other companies, not Ghibli.

Marvel originally planned Infinity War as a two-part story. Although the second film’s title was later changed, the direct continuation was released as “Avengers: Endgame.” Therefore, a ‘second part’ to Infinity War does (and did) exist.

Ross Dress for Less is an off-price retailer that sells new, overstock, or closeout merchandise from manufacturers and other retailers at discounted prices. Thrift stores, by contrast, typically sell second-hand or donated items. Therefore, Ross is not classified as a thrift store.

In everyday usage, the terms “flash drive,” “USB flash drive,” “thumb drive,” and “USB stick” all refer to the same portable storage device that plugs into a computer’s USB port and uses flash memory to store data. Although the word “flash drive” can theoretically describe any storage device based on flash memory (e.g., SSDs, SD cards), in common conversation it specifically denotes the small USB-connected stick. Therefore, for typical practical purposes, a flash drive and a USB stick are the same thing.

Traditional angel food cake is a type of foam cake made almost entirely from whipped egg whites (along with sugar and a small amount of flour). The egg whites are essential for the cake’s structure and airy texture, so eggs are definitely an ingredient.

In culinary and botanical terms, “sweet pepper” is a broad category that includes any Capsicum variety with little or no heat (e.g., banana peppers, cubanelles, pimentos). A bell pepper is just one specific type within that broader sweet-pepper group. Because bell peppers are the most common sweet pepper sold in many supermarkets, the two names are sometimes used interchangeably in casual conversation, but technically they are not identical: every bell pepper is a sweet pepper, but not every sweet pepper is a bell pepper.

The AMC series 'Hell on Wheels' was officially concluded with its fifth season, which aired in two parts in 2015–2016. AMC announced at the time that Season 5 would be the final season, and there have been no credible announcements or plans for a sixth season since then.
Timor-Leste is the Portuguese name of the country whose English name is East Timor; both refer to the same sovereign state occupying the eastern half of the island of Timor.

The iPhone 6 was released on September 19, 2014. The first-generation iPhone SE was announced in March 2016 and released later that month. Therefore, the iPhone 6 indeed came out before the iPhone SE.

Texas A&M’s athletic programs have claimed national titles, most notably in football (e.g., the 1939 AP national championship) as well as in several other sports. Therefore the school has indeed won at least one national championship.

Disney’s monorail systems (at Walt Disney World and formerly at Disneyland) are conventional straddle-beam monorails that ride on concrete guideways using rubber tires and electric traction motors. Maglev trains, by contrast, are levitated and propelled by magnetic forces with no physical wheels in contact with the guideway. Because Disney’s monorails rely on tires and do not use magnetic levitation, they are not maglev trains.

In typical AC power systems the neutral conductor is intentionally bonded to the grounding conductor at a single point—the main service disconnect or transformer. This bond establishes a reference to earth and provides a return path for fault current. Beyond that single bonding point, neutral and ground must be kept separate; tying them together elsewhere can create parallel paths for current and safety hazards. Hence, a neutral can be connected to ground, but only at the designated bonding point, not throughout the rest of the wiring.

In denim terminology the rise is the distance from the crotch seam to the top of the waistband. When that rise is long enough to sit above or at the natural waist (typically about 11" or more), brands describe the jean as either “high-rise” or “high-waisted.” Although a few marketers may draw subtle distinctions, in common retail usage the two terms are used interchangeably to describe the same fit.

Yes. Throughout U.S. history several justices first joined the Court through presidential recess appointments—for example, John Rutledge (1795), Earl Warren (1953), William J. Brennan (1956), and Potter Stewart (1958).

Washington, D.C. is designated in the U.S. Constitution as a federal district under the direct authority of Congress. It was created specifically to be independent of any individual state, so it is not contained within the borders or jurisdiction of any U.S. state.

Richard W. Sears’s first business venture (1886) was reselling a shipment of pocket-watches to other railroad agents. That success led him to found the R. W. Sears Watch Company in Minneapolis, then to bring in watch-repairman Alvah C. Roebuck as a partner. Sears, Roebuck & Co. grew out of this watch-selling enterprise before expanding its catalog to many other goods. Therefore the company did indeed start by selling watches.

In Euclidean geometry, an isosceles triangle is defined as a triangle with at least two congruent sides. The theorem associated with such triangles states that the angles opposite the equal sides (the base angles) are also congruent. This is a well-established and fundamental result in elementary geometry.

Scientifically, a kilocalorie (kcal) is 1,000 small-“c” calories, so they are different units. However, on food labels the term “Calorie” (with an uppercase C, often written simply as “calorie”) is shorthand for a kilocalorie. Thus, in everyday nutritional contexts they are treated as the same, but strictly speaking a kcal ≠ a (small-c) calorie.

Tonsil stones (tonsilloliths) develop in the crypts of the tonsils from trapped food debris, bacteria, and dead cells that calcify. Salivary stones (sialoliths) form inside the ducts of the major salivary glands—most often the submandibular gland—from precipitated calcium salts. Because they arise in different anatomical sites, have different compositions and risk factors, and are managed differently, they are not the same entity.
“Bennie and the Jets” is an Elton John song whose lyrics describe a fictional glam-rock group. There was never an actual performing band by that name; it exists only within the narrative of the song.

Under Article II, Section 2 of the U.S. Constitution, the president’s pardon power extends only to “Offences against the United States,” i.e., federal crimes. Crimes prosecuted under state law are not “offences against the United States”; authority to pardon those lies with state governors or clemency boards. Therefore, the president cannot pardon someone for a purely state crime.

William Shakespeare classed 'A Midsummer Night’s Dream' among his comedies; it features the typical comic structure of romantic misunderstandings, magical interventions, and a happy ending with multiple marriages.

The United States permits its citizens to acquire or keep another nationality; it does not require formal renunciation when a U.S. citizen naturalizes elsewhere. Since 1 January 2014, the Czech Republic also allows its citizens to hold multiple nationalities and does not require renunciation of Czech citizenship when another is obtained (nor vice-versa). Therefore, nothing in either country’s law prevents a person from holding both U.S. and Czech citizenship simultaneously, assuming all ordinary requirements for acquisition of each citizenship are met.

In Nicholas Sparks’s novel (and the 2002 film adaptation) “A Walk to Remember,” the main female character, Jamie Sullivan, is diagnosed with terminal leukemia. The story ends with her husband Landon reflecting on their brief time together after her death (the movie softens it slightly, but it is still clear she dies shortly afterward). Therefore, the girl does die.

The deepest known point in the oceans is the Challenger Deep in the Mariana Trench. Human-occupied submersibles such as the bathyscaphe Trieste (1960), DSV Deepsea Challenger (2012), and the Limiting Factor (multiple dives since 2019) have successfully descended to this point. Therefore, humans have indeed reached the bottom of the Mariana Trench.

Multiple people have captured the WSOP Main Event title more than once—e.g., Doyle Brunson (1976, 1977), Johnny Chan (1987, 1988), Stu Ungar (1980, 1981, 1997) and Johnny Moss (1970, 1971, 1974). Therefore the answer to whether anyone has ever won it twice is yes.

Vegetable oil is a broad category that includes oils extracted from plant sources such as seeds, fruits, nuts, and grains. Sunflower oil is produced by pressing the seeds of the sunflower plant, so it falls under this category and is commonly labeled and used as a vegetable oil.

In common cocktail and bar terminology, “sweet vermouth” refers to the reddish-brown, sweeter style of vermouth that originated in Italy. This style is labeled “rosso” (Italian for “red”). Although there are niche sweet white vermouths, in nearly all recipes and retail contexts, rosso vermouth is what is meant by sweet vermouth.

Reese's Pieces are candy-coated bites filled with a peanut-butter center. Unlike Reese’s Peanut Butter Cups, they do not contain cocoa solids or any form of chocolate in their ingredient list, so the product has no chocolate content.

George A. Romero’s 1978 film "Dawn of the Dead" is itself the second entry in his Dead series (after "Night of the Living Dead"). The follow-up to that film is titled "Day of the Dead" (1985); later installments include "Land of the Dead," "Diary of the Dead," etc. None of the official sequels is called "Dawn of the Dead 2," and the 2004 Zack Snyder remake likewise never received an official sequel with that title ("Army of the Dead" is only a thematic successor). Therefore, there is no movie actually titled "Dawn of the Dead 2."

Stephen (Steph) Curry’s younger brother, Seth Curry, is also a professional basketball player who has played for multiple NBA teams (e.g., Dallas Mavericks, Philadelphia 76ers, Brooklyn Nets). Therefore, Steph Curry does have a brother in the NBA.

California Screamin’ was the original name of the launched steel roller-coaster at Disney California Adventure. In 2018 the track and ride system remained essentially unchanged, but it was re-themed to Pixar’s The Incredibles and renamed the Incredicoaster. Therefore, it is the same physical coaster, just with new story elements, décor, and audio.

A multicolored arc that is concave-up (so it looks ‘upside-down’ compared with a normal rainbow) does exist. It is usually produced not by raindrops but by sunlight refracted through horizontally oriented ice crystals in high clouds; the phenomenon is called a circumzenithal arc. Although it is technically an ice-halo effect rather than a true rain-drop rainbow, people commonly refer to it as an upside-down rainbow, so the answer to whether such a thing exists is effectively yes.

The 1996 film “Sling Blade,” written and directed by Billy Bob Thornton, is a work of fiction. The characters and events—including Karl Childers’ story—were created for the short film “Some Folks Call It a Sling Blade” and later expanded into the feature film. There is no historical individual or real-life event on which the plot is based.

Insurgent is the second film in The Divergent Series. Lionsgate released the follow-up (Allegiant) in 2016 and originally planned a fourth film (Ascendant), but that project was cancelled and no new theatrical or streaming film has been put into development since. The studio and the cast have indicated that the series is effectively finished, so another ‘Insurgent’/Divergent movie is not expected.

Oslo Airport (Oslo Lufthavn, Gardermoen) has an underground railway station—Oslo Airport Station—directly beneath the terminal. It is served by the Flytoget Airport Express as well as regional and intercity trains, so travelers can board trains at the airport itself.

answer: True – a conditional discharge does result in a criminal record (though it later becomes spent).
Reasoning: In order for a court to impose a conditional discharge it must first find the defendant guilty, so a conviction is formally recorded. That conviction is entered on the Police National Computer and will show up on standard or enhanced criminal-record (DBS) checks while it is unspent. Once the discharge period ends (and, for most purposes, one further year has passed), the conviction becomes "spent" and generally no longer needs to be disclosed, but the fact remains that a criminal record was created in the first place.
Answer: True – a conditional discharge does result in a criminal record (though it later becomes spent).

Reasoning: The most recent FIFA World Cup was the men’s tournament held in November–December 2022 in Qatar, and the United States men’s national team did qualify and compete (finishing second in Group B and reaching the Round of 16). Therefore, if the question refers to the latest World Cup held ‘this year,’ the answer is yes.

The Kissing Booth is a Netflix original film that premiered on the platform in 2018 and remains part of Netflix’s catalog. Therefore, it is available on Netflix (barring regional licensing anomalies).
Hawaii was admitted to the Union on August 21, 1959, becoming the 50th U.S. state. Therefore, it is indeed one of the states of the United States of America.

The last remaining reactor at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (Unit 3) was shut down in December 2000. Since then, no reactors have produced power there. The site is now in the process of decommissioning and containment, not electricity generation.

International law recognises the possibility of statelessness—people who are not considered nationals by any state under the operation of its laws. Such individuals, called stateless persons, can arise through gaps or conflicts in nationality laws, state succession, discrimination, or loss/renunciation of citizenship without acquiring another. Therefore, it is indeed possible for someone to have no citizenship.

JPMorgan Chase & Co. is the parent holding company. Its retail and commercial banking operations are branded simply as “Chase Bank.” In everyday usage people treat them interchangeably because Chase Bank is the banking arm of JPMorgan Chase, so they refer to the same overall financial institution.

The International Journal of Nursing Studies is published by Elsevier and is recognized in academic databases (e.g., PubMed, Scopus). Major scholarly journals from such publishers and with indexing in these databases require peer review before publication. The journal’s author guidelines and website explicitly state that submitted manuscripts undergo a peer-review process.
Modern Olympic ‘gold’ medals are composed primarily of sterling silver and are merely plated with a thin layer (about 6 g) of pure gold, so they are not made entirely of gold.

Jamaica is a sovereign island nation in the Caribbean and a member of the Commonwealth realm. It was formerly a British colony and gained independence in 1962. It is neither a U.S. state nor an unincorporated U.S. territory, so it is not considered part of the United States.

Under Article II, §2, cl. 3 of the U.S. Constitution, the President may make ‘recess appointments’ to any office that normally requires Senate confirmation. The clause contains no exception for the Supreme Court, and historically several Justices—e.g., John Rutledge (1795) and Potter Stewart (1958)—first joined the Court via recess appointment. The appointment only lasts until the end of the Senate’s next session unless the Senate later confirms the nominee, but it is constitutionally permissible.

A liger is a real hybrid offspring produced by mating a male lion (Panthera leo) with a female tiger (Panthera tigris). Such hybrids have been bred in captivity and are documented in zoos and wildlife parks, so they do exist.

In the original Sin City graphic-novel story “The Hard Goodbye” (the first Sin City story) and in the 2005 film adaptation’s Marv segment, Marv is captured, put on trial, and executed in the electric chair at the end of the story. Later comics feature him only in tales set earlier in the timeline, but chronologically his fate in the first story is death.

The Schengen Area is a group of European countries that have abolished internal border controls. While most EU member states participate, the Republic of Ireland opted out and instead remains in the separate Common Travel Area with the United Kingdom. Therefore, a standard Schengen visa does not grant entry to Ireland, and Irish visas do not provide Schengen access.

The island of Ireland is split into two political entities: the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland (part of the United Kingdom). The line separating them is an international land border, even though there are currently no routine passport checks due to the Common Travel Area and the Good Friday Agreement.

The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) is the country’s monetary authority—India’s central bank in the technical sense. “Central Bank of India,” however, is the name of a public-sector commercial bank that operates like any other retail/wholesale bank. Because they are separate legal entities with different mandates and functions, they are not the same institution.

A small percentage of people are born with intersex conditions—variations in sex development in which the external genitalia have both typically male and typically female characteristics (or are ambiguous). While it is virtually unheard-of to have two fully developed, fully functional sets of genitalia, it is medically documented that individuals can present with a combination of male- and female-typical genital structures.

The commonly used scientific name Aloe barbadensis Miller refers to the same plant that is popularly called aloe vera. They are taxonomic synonyms for the same species, widely recognized in botanical literature and commerce.

Disney and producer Jerry Bruckheimer have publicly stated on multiple occasions (most recently in 2023) that a sixth Pirates of the Caribbean film is in active development. Writers (Ted Elliott and Craig Mazin) have turned in a draft script and the studio is exploring casting and creative direction, even though no final green-light, filming start date, or released cast has been announced. While plans can always change until cameras roll, the current evidence points to the project moving forward rather than being cancelled.

North Korea’s men’s national football team has qualified for the FIFA World Cup on two occasions: famously in 1966 in England, where they reached the quarter-finals, and later in 2010 in South Africa. Therefore, they have indeed made it to the World Cup.

Cows, like all mammals, initiate lactation only after giving birth. Following calving, a cow will produce milk for several months, but output naturally tapers off. To maintain year-round commercial milk production, dairy farmers therefore re-impregnate cows on a roughly yearly cycle so each new birth restarts peak lactation.
Croatia reached the final of the 2018 FIFA World Cup in Russia, where they played against and lost to France. Therefore, Croatia has indeed appeared in a World Cup final.

The Isle of Man and the Channel Islands (Jersey, Guernsey, etc.) are both Crown dependencies of the UK, but they are geographically distinct. The Isle of Man lies in the Irish Sea between Great Britain and Ireland, whereas the Channel Islands are located in the English Channel near the French coast. Therefore, the Isle of Man is not part of the Channel Islands.
The Nissan Titan is marketed and classified by Nissan—and the automotive industry—as its full-size pickup, competing with other full-size models like the Ford F-150 and Chevrolet Silverado.

In vehicle size classifications, the typical progression is compact < midsize < full-size. Therefore a midsize car is smaller, not bigger, than a full-size car. The statement that a midsize car is bigger than a full size is incorrect.

An acre is defined as 43,560 square feet. A standard American football field (excluding the end zones) measures 100 yards by 53⅓ yards, or 300 ft × 160 ft = 48,000 square feet—already a bit larger than an acre (≈1.10 acres). Including the end zones it is 57,600 square feet (≈1.32 acres). Therefore a football field is larger than, and not exactly equal to, an acre.

In most empirical studies, higher levels of income, productive employment, and overall economic growth are accompanied by improvements in literacy, life expectancy, health outcomes, and other social indicators; likewise, social progress such as better education, gender equality, and strong institutions feeds back into sustained economic performance. While the relationship is not perfectly linear or guaranteed (some countries achieve growth without broad social gains and vice-versa), the evidence supports the existence of a fundamental, mutually reinforcing linkage between the two spheres. Hence a ‘direct link’—though complex and bidirectional—does exist.

LLB (LL.B.) is the Latin abbreviation for Legum Baccalaureus, which translates to Bachelor of Laws in English. They refer to the same undergraduate law degree; one is simply the full English name and the other its traditional abbreviation.

Google Voice consumer accounts are provided free of charge by Google; you can obtain and keep a number without paying a recurring subscription. Costs can occur for international calling or if using Google Voice through certain paid Google Workspace plans, but there is no standard monthly fee for ordinary personal use.

The FN Five-seveN sold on the commercial market is a semi-automatic handgun. Under U.S. federal law, semi-automatic handguns are legal for civilians to purchase provided they meet age, background-check, and other standard requirements. While some U.S. states or localities may restrict magazine capacity or the 5.7×28 mm cartridge, there is no blanket federal prohibition. Therefore, in the majority of jurisdictions a civilian can legally own an FN Five-seveN.

Horses (Equus caballus) and the various zebra species (genus Equus) are close relatives within the equid family. Like horses and donkeys (which produce mules), they have compatible enough genetics to mate and produce hybrid offspring commonly called zorses or zebroids. These hybrids are generally viable but usually sterile, reflecting the chromosomal differences between the parent species. Therefore, interbreeding is biologically possible even if the offspring cannot typically reproduce.

The U.S. Constitution requires a president to be a “natural-born citizen,” which means someone who is a U.S. citizen from birth. While most natural-born citizens are born on U.S. soil, someone born abroad to at least one U.S.-citizen parent is also considered a natural-born citizen under current law and longstanding interpretation. Therefore, being physically born in the United States is not strictly required to become president.

Gear oil and motor (engine) oil serve different purposes and are formulated differently. Gear oil is designed for gearboxes and differentials, typically has a much higher viscosity, and contains extreme-pressure (EP) additives to protect sliding gear surfaces. Motor oil is formulated for internal combustion engines, has lower viscosity grades (e.g., 5W-30), and contains detergents and dispersants suited for engine conditions. Because their compositions and intended uses differ, they are not the same.

Chicken tikka consists of marinated pieces of chicken that are skewered and roasted/grilled in a tandoor (or oven) and typically served dry or with minimal garnish. Chicken tikka masala, on the other hand, starts with the same roasted chicken tikka pieces but then adds them to a creamy, tomato-based spiced gravy (masala). Because one is a dry grilled preparation and the other is a sauced curry, there is indeed a clear difference between the two dishes.

In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, some Americans poured milk or cream and sweeteners over popped corn and ate it from a bowl, treating it much like other breakfast cereals of the time. Contemporary newspaper articles and cookbooks document this practice, indicating that popcorn was indeed consumed as a breakfast cereal for a period.

Pasadena sits on the northern edge of the San Gabriel Valley, east of downtown Los Angeles. The San Fernando Valley is a separate valley northwest of downtown L.A. Therefore, Pasadena is not located in the San Fernando Valley.

The anime adaptation of “Your Lie in April” (Shigatsu wa Kimi no Uso) ran from October 2014 to March 2015 and completely adapted the manga’s storyline in its single 22-episode run (plus an OVA). Since then, there has been no official announcement, production, or release of a second season. The series is considered finished.

In Major League Baseball, the rare feat of hitting two grand slams in a single inning has occurred once: Fernando Tatís (St. Louis Cardinals) accomplished it on April 23, 1999, hitting both grand slams off Chan Ho Park. Therefore, it is indeed possible and has happened.

Both U.S. FMVSS 108 and the equivalent UN/ECE regulations specify that front-facing turn-signal lamps must emit an amber (yellow) light. Other colors are not permitted (rear signals may be red or amber, but the front must be amber). Therefore, by regulation, front turn signals do indeed have to be amber.
The Athletics franchise has won the World Series several times (nine total, four since moving to Oakland in 1968). Therefore, the answer to whether they have ever won a World Series is yes.

During World War II many male professional baseball players were serving in the military, so in 1943 Philip K. Wrigley founded the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League in the United States. The league operated throughout the war (and continued afterward until 1954). Therefore, a women’s professional baseball league did indeed exist during WWII.

In the series finale of How I Met Your Mother it is revealed that the Mother, Tracy McConnell, dies from an illness several years before Ted begins telling the story to his children, confirming that she is deceased within the show’s timeline.

Margaret Mitchell never wrote a sequel to her 1936 novel, and the 1939 film was never followed by an official cinematic sequel. Decades later the Mitchell estate authorized follow-up novels (e.g., “Scarlett,” 1991), but these are not considered second installments by the original creator. Therefore the straightforward answer to whether there is a second “Gone with the Wind” is No.

Although both animals share the word “panda,” modern genetic and morphological studies place the giant panda in the bear family (Ursidae) and the red panda in its own separate family (Ailuridae) within the musteloid branch of Carnivora. They are therefore only very distantly related, no more closely than any two carnivores in different families.
Netflix officially announced Black Mirror Season 6 in 2022 and released those new episodes in June 2023, confirming that new installments of the series were produced and made available.

The only Super Bowl meeting between the Denver Broncos and the Seattle Seahawks was Super Bowl XLVIII in February 2014. In that game, the Seahawks won decisively, 43–8. Therefore, the Broncos did not beat the Seahawks in any Super Bowl.

“Film Stars Don’t Die in Liverpool” adapts Peter Turner’s memoir recounting his real-life romantic relationship with Oscar-winning actress Gloria Grahame during the final years of her life. Because the film is drawn directly from Turner’s autobiographical book and portrays actual events and people, it is considered a true story (a biographical drama, though naturally dramatized).

The Open Championship winner is presented with the original Claret Jug and may keep it for the year of his reign. Before the next Open, the champion must return the original trophy to the R&A. At that time the player receives a replica Claret Jug that he can keep permanently. Therefore the winner does not keep the actual jug forever.

The ‘Midtown Tunnel’ most commonly refers to the Queens-Midtown Tunnel connecting Manhattan and Queens in New York City. This tunnel is operated by MTA Bridges and Tunnels and all vehicular traffic is subject to a toll (now collected electronically via E-ZPass or Tolls by Mail). Therefore, yes—drivers must pay to use it.

The novel 'Fifty Shades of Grey' is the first book in a trilogy by E. L. James, followed by 'Fifty Shades Darker' and 'Fifty Shades Freed.' Both books were also adapted into film sequels. Therefore, a sequel exists.

The original series concluded in 2009 with the televised movie “Ed, Edd n Eddy’s Big Picture Show.” Since then neither Cartoon Network nor creator Danny Antonucci has announced a revival, sequel, reboot, or any new officially sanctioned project. Occasional rumors circulate among fans, but there is no credible information from the network, production studios, or Antonucci indicating that new episodes or a reboot are in development. Therefore, based on all publicly available information, it is unlikely that a new installment is currently planned.

Batman Returns (1992) was the second film in the original Warner Bros. Batman series that began with Batman (1989). Batman Forever (1995) was produced as the third installment in that same series, continuing after the events of Batman Returns (though with a new director and cast changes). Therefore, Batman Forever is considered the sequel to Batman Returns.

Scientifically, the turkey vulture (Cathartes aura) is a New World vulture. The word “buzzard,” however, refers to two different things depending on region. In Europe and much of the world, a buzzard is a Buteo hawk (e.g., the common buzzard, Buteo buteo) and is not a vulture at all. In North America, people often use the nickname “buzzard” for the turkey vulture, but that is a colloquial usage, not a taxonomic equivalence. Therefore, strictly speaking, a turkey vulture and a (true) buzzard are not the same, even though the terms are sometimes used interchangeably in North America.

Me to We is the for-profit social enterprise arm of the WE movement (formerly known as Free the Children/WE Charity). It is structured as a corporation, not as a registered charity or non-profit organization, even though it donates part of its profits to WE Charity and reinvests in social programs.

Mahi-mahi is the common name for the dolphinfish (Coryphaena hippurus), while “ahi” refers to yellowfin tuna (and sometimes bigeye tuna) in Hawaiian terminology. They belong to different families, look different, and have distinct culinary and ecological characteristics. Thus they are not the same fish.

Lisa Edelstein, who played Cuddy, left the series after Season 7, so the character does not appear in Season 8. Consequently, there is no opportunity for House and Cuddy to reconcile, and they never resume their relationship in the final season.

The brand Canada Dry was created in Canada, but today the product is owned by Keurig Dr Pepper and most commercial production for the U.S. market occurs in American bottling plants. While some Canada Dry sold within Canada is bottled there under licence, the ginger ale found in many places—especially in the United States—is not made in Canada. Therefore, the statement that Canada Dry Ginger Ale is made in Canada (implying it is generally or exclusively produced there) is inaccurate.

The Georgia Aquarium’s signature Ocean Voyager exhibit remains one of the very few places outside Asia that houses whale sharks. Although the individual animals have changed over the years (some have died and additional juveniles were added), the aquarium still maintains multiple whale sharks on exhibit today, according to recent (2023-24) reports and the aquarium’s own website.

Although both snacks are made from corn, tortilla chips are produced by first making nixtamalized corn tortillas, which are then cut and fried or baked. Corn chips, on the other hand, are made from a thicker masa or cornmeal dough that is extruded or molded and then fried. The processes, textures, shapes, and flavors differ, so they are considered two separate products rather than the same thing.

An airline ticket (or e-ticket) is proof that you have paid for and reserved transportation on a specific flight, whereas a boarding pass is issued after you check in and is the document that grants you access through security and onto the aircraft. Because they serve different purposes and are issued at different stages of travel, they are not the same thing.

American Sign Language (ASL) originated largely from French Sign Language and has its own grammar and vocabulary. Australian Sign Language (Auslan) evolved from British Sign Language and also has distinct grammar and lexicon. Because they come from different historical roots, ASL and Auslan are not mutually intelligible and are treated as separate languages.

The question appears to ask whether the United States (“us”) fields a national team in the (soccer) World Cup. The United States has both men’s and women’s national soccer teams that participate in FIFA World Cup tournaments whenever they qualify. The men’s team played in the 2022 World Cup, and the women’s team regularly competes (and has won multiple titles). Therefore, the U.S. does have a team in the World Cup context.

Germany is recorded as having won the Eurovision Song Contest twice—first in 1982 with Nicole’s “Ein bißchen Frieden” and again in 2010 with Lena’s “Satellite.” Therefore, the statement that Germany has ever won is correct.

In the United States the Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf chain’s beverages (coffee, espresso drinks, teas, powders, etc.) and most baked goods are certified by Kosher Supervision of America (KSA), and stores display that certification. Some international or franchise locations may stock items without certification, but as a brand in its core markets it is regarded as a kosher coffee chain.

Global biodiversity is not evenly distributed; it follows a well-known latitudinal gradient in which species richness is greatest in the tropics and declines toward the poles. A country located at low (tropical) latitudes is therefore expected to possess higher diversity of life forms compared with countries situated farther from the equator. Hence, latitude and biodiversity are indeed related.

In California, passing the Reading Instruction Competence Assessment (RICA) is a legal requirement only for candidates seeking a Multiple Subject (elementary) credential or an Education Specialist (special-education) credential. It is not required for Single Subject (secondary) credential candidates, career-technical teachers, administrators, or teachers in states other than California. Therefore, ‘all teachers’ do not have to take the RICA—only those pursuing the specific credentials that mandate it.

The gallbladder is divided into fundus (distal rounded end), body, and neck. The cystic duct is continuous with the neck, not the fundus. Therefore, the fundus is anatomically distant from the cystic duct.

The 2017 film 'Lady Bird,' written and directed by Greta Gerwig, centers on a high-school senior named Christine “Lady Bird” McPherson and her coming-of-age experiences in Sacramento. It has no connection to Claudia Alta “Lady Bird” Johnson, the former First Lady of the United States.
The reality series ‘Total Bellas’ was renewed for and aired a fourth season, which premiered on January 13, 2019. Therefore, a Season 4 does (or did) indeed exist.

In the FIFA World Cup (the tournament most people refer to when they say "the World Cup"), the two losing semi-finalists play a dedicated ‘third-place play-off’ match. The winner of that match is officially awarded third place in the tournament, so a third-place team is recognized.

Under U.S. regulations, bourbon must be produced anywhere in the United States, meet certain mash-bill, aging, and proof requirements, but there is no requirement that it be distilled in Bourbon County, Kentucky. Many bourbons are produced elsewhere in Kentucky and in other states.

Students at the U.S. Naval Academy are appointed to the rank of Midshipman in the U.S. Navy or Marine Corps. They are on active duty status, receive pay, and are subject to the Uniform Code of Military Justice. Therefore, by attending the Naval Academy, you are officially a member of the Navy (or Marine Corps) as a Midshipman.

Spider silk can indeed be woven into fabric, and a few demonstration garments (e.g., the golden orb-weaver spider silk cape displayed in 2012) have proven it is possible. The main hurdle is not feasibility but scale: spiders are territorial and cannibalistic, making large-scale farming difficult, so spider-silk textiles are rare and expensive. Nevertheless, technically you can make clothes from spider silk, either by painstakingly collecting natural spider silk or by using bio-engineered organisms that produce spider-silk proteins.

In the context of computer networking, the term “physical address” is commonly used to refer to the hardware (Media Access Control, or MAC) address that uniquely identifies a network interface card. Although the phrase “physical address” can mean something different in other domains (e.g., memory addressing), in standard network terminology physical address = MAC address.

Honey bees (genus Apis, e.g., Apis mellifera) and bumble bees (genus Bombus) are distinct groups of social bees. They differ in taxonomy, appearance, nesting habits, colony size, and life cycles, so they are not the same.

The television series "El Chapo" (a co-production of Univision and Netflix) has already released three seasons. Season 3 premiered in 2018, concluding the series. Therefore, the answer to whether there will be a Season 3 is effectively “yes” (it already exists).

The UK’s Data Protection Act 1998 was repealed and replaced by the Data Protection Act 2018, which incorporates and supplements the EU GDPR framework. Therefore, the 1998 Act is no longer the current legislation and has been superseded.

Both devices use flash memory technology, but they differ in form factor, interface, and typical usage.
